    'Submerged beds of [Ruppia maritima], including [Ruppia maritima] ssp. [rostellata], or [Ruppia cirrhosa] ([Ruppia drepanensis], [Ruppia spiralis]) and of [Chara spp.] of sea inlets, estuaries, permanent pools of mud or sand flats and coastal lagoons of Mediterranean coasts and of thermo-Atlantic coasts of southwestern Iberia, of norhwestern Africa, south to 27øN, and of the Macaronesian islands.', '(Holmboe, 1914: 206; Wolff, 1968; Knapp, 1973: 502; Zohary, 1973; Heywood, 1978: 276; Verhoeven, 1980; Babalonas, 1980: 625; Morgan, 1982; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Lanfranco, 1989: 37; Britton and Crivelli, 1993: 156; Hohenester and Welss, 1993: 13; Trpin and Vres, 1995: 79; Lorenzoni and Paradis, 1996: 157-159, 168, 173; Hoda y al., 1998: 3).');
    'Submerged beds of [Ruppia maritima] or [Ruppia cirrhosa], accompanied by [Zannichellia palustris], [Potamogeton pectinatus] and [Chara spp.]  of sea inlets, estuaries, permanent pools of mud or sand flats, and coastal lagoons of the Black Sea.', '(Walter, 1974: 200; Heywood, 1978: 276; Andreev y al., 1992: 716; Coldea, 1997: 34-35).');
    'Submerged beds of [Ruppia maritima] or [Ruppia cirrhosa] and of [Chara spp.]  of sea inlets, estuaries, permanent pools of mud or sand flats, and coastal lagoons of the desert coasts of the North Atlantic, between 27øN and 18øN, and of the Indian Ocean and its connected seas.', '(Zohary, 1973; Heywood, 1978: 276). ');
    'Submerged beds of [Ruppia spp.] and [Chara spp.]  of sea inlets, estuaries, permanent pools of mud or sand flats, and coastal lagoons of the boreal, temperate and subtropical western Pacific and its connected seas, distributed along all coasts, north to the northern coasts of the sea of Okhotsk and northern Kamtchatka in the Bering Sea.', '(Heywood, 1978: 276).');
    'Submerged beds of [Ruppia spp.] and [Chara spp.]  of sea inlets, estuaries, permanent pools of mud or sand flats, and coastal lagoons of tropical coasts of west Africa and of the Indo-Pacific.', '(Heywood, 1978: 276).');
    'Emergent [Eleocharis parvula] or [Eleocharis acicularis] formations of brackish seas, sea inlets, estuaries, permanent pools of mud or sand flats, and coastal lagoons, occurring in the open sea only in the Baltic, limited to coastal waterbodies elsewhere, and very rare.', '(Géhu, 1984a; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 4.2.2.1, 4.2.2.2; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 39; Pott, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994: units 4.3.2.1, 4.3.2.2).');
    'Emergent [Eleocharis parvula]-dominated formations of brackish seas, sea inlets, estuaries, permanent pools of mud or sand flats, and coastal lagoons. They occur in the open sea only in the inner Baltic, in particular in middle Sweden, southern Finland and Estonia; they are very rare elsewhere, noted in particular on a few points of the coasts of Norway and in closed limans of the northern Black Sea and Azov Sea coasts, probably extinct in France and Germany.', '(Walter, 1974: 200; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 4.2.2.1; Korotkov y al., 1991: 39; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.3.2.1; Mossberg y al., 1995: 606).');
    'Emergent [Eleocharis acicularis]-dominated formations of the open Baltic in the Gulf of Bothnia (Bothnia Sea, Bothnia Bay) and the Gulf of Finland.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 4.2.2.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.3.2.2).');
    '[Ranunculus spp.]-dominated communities developed in shallow-waters of very low salinity of coastal lagoons, coastal basins and coastal waters of the Palaearctic region, including the Atlantic, North Sea, Baltic Sea, Mediterranean Sea and Black Sea. The most widespread characteristic species is [Ranunculus baudotii]. Locally, other crowfoots may be typical, as, in particular, in the Gulf of Bothnia, [Ranunculus trichophyllus] ([Ranunculus confervoides]).', '(Holmboe, 1914: 80, 206; Wolff, 1968; Knapp, 1973: 502; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 4.2.2.2 [p.]; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Pott, 1992: 63; Britton and Crivelli, 1993: 156; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.3.2.2 [p.]; Mossberg y al., 1995: 138).');
    'Ice formations floating on sea water, usually constituting an incomplete cover, variable in form and structure, unstable and dynamic under the influence of surface air and water currents.', '(Armstrong and Roberts, 1956; Hood, 1983; Kullenberg, 1983; John, 1983). ');
    'Semicontinuous ice sheets covering the sea throughout the year, limited to the Arctic Ocean. ', '(Armstrong and Roberts, 1956; Hood, 1983; John, 1983: 76-80; Weslawski and Stempniewicz, 1995: 39-40). ');
    'Semicontinuous ice sheets forming on the sea for part of the year, characteristic of the Arctic Ocean, Baffin Bay, Davis Strait, the Greenland Sea, the Denmark Strait, the Norwegian Sea, the Barents Sea, the Kara Sea, the Laptev Sea, the East Siberian Sea, the Chukchi Sea, Bothnia Bay, the Bothnia Sea, and coastal areas of the Aland Sea, the Gulf of Finland and the Gulf of Riga, exceptional in other areas. ', '(Armstrong and Roberts, 1956; Hood, 1983; Kullenberg, 1983: 321; Lacombe, 1983: 110-111; John, 1983: 76-80; Weslawski and Stempniewicz, 1995: 39-40).');
    'Discontinuous formations of floating ice blocks, rafts and hummocks detached from the sea pack, remaining after the break-up of seasonal ice packs or drifting to more southern regions. ', '(Armstrong and Roberts, 1956; Hood, 1983; Lacombe, 1983: 112-113; John, 1983: 80-85; Munda, 1991; Weslawski and Stempniewicz, 1995: 39-40). ');
    'Floating and drifting blocks of ice detached from coastal glaciers (unit 63.3).', '(Armstrong and Roberts, 1956; Hood, 1983; Lacombe, 1983: 112-113; John, 1983: 80-85; Weslawski and Stempniewicz, 1995: 39-40).');
    'Bays and narrow channels of the oceans and their connected seas, including sea lochs or loughs, fiords or fiards, rias and straits but excluding estuaries and lagoons. Detailed habitats can be coded by combining subdivisions of unit 11 with the relevant physiographic subdivisions of unit 12. ', '(Wood, 1988). ');
    'More or less straight coasts, devoid of deep indentations, characteristic of concordant coasts, of soft-sediment coastlines, and of the contour of isolated promontories.', '(Clark, 1990).');
    'Coastlines of wide, curved indentations of the sea into the land, with a wide or fairly wide opening, including bays and gulfs.  ', '(Clark, 1990).');
    'More or less narrow stretches of water connecting two larger bodies of water; channels between islands and the mainland.', '(Sorokin, 1983; Clark, 1990).');
    'Bodies of water, such as coves, communicating with the sea by a relatively narrow but unobstructed opening.', '(Sorokin, 1983; Clark, 1990).');
    'Sea inlets dug by glacial action, usually characterized by the presence of an entrance moraine. ', '(Wood, 1988; Clark, 1990).');
    'Deep, long, narrow inlets in the coast, with high, rocky, parallel sides, smoothed by ice action, and a rocky floor often deeper than the sea floor and separated from it by a sill near the entrance, formed by the submergence of glacial valleys.   ', '(Wood, 1988; Clark, 1990).');
    'Irregular, often branched or islet-studded, shallow or deep, inlets in the coast, with low banks and a usually narrow entrance.', '(Wood, 1988; Clark, 1990).');
    'Sea inlets of glacial origin, communicating more broadly with the sea than fiords or fiards and lacking a shallow entrance sill. ', '(Ketchum, 1983; Wood, 1988).');
    'Funnel-shaped sea inlets formed, in particular, by drowned river valleys, particularly along discordant coasts, as a result of a rise in sea-level. ', '(Wood, 1988; Clark, 1990; Lovric, 1993a; Lovric, 1993b; Magri, 1999).');
    'Caves situated under the sea or opened to it, at least at high tide. Their marine part harbours benthic communities of units 11.26 and 11.294. They may be connected to terrestrial cave systems (unit 65) or to the underground water network through anchihaline environments (unit 65.451).', '(Augier, 1982, 1985; Harmelin y al., 1987; Fiala-Médione y al., 1987; Barnes and Hughes, 1988; Iliffe, 1992; Boury-Esnoult y al., 1993; Lovric, 1993a; Waugh, 1995: 136, 150).');
    'Sea-caves situated entirely below low-tide level.', '(Augier, 1982, 1985; Harmelin y al., 1987; Fiala-Médione y al., 1987; Barnes and Hughes, 1988; Boury-Esnoult y al., 1993; Lovric, 1993a; Waugh, 1995).');
    'Sea-caves situated in part above low-tide level, comprising mediolittoral (unit 11.294), and, in some cases, supralittoral (units 12.72 x 11.296, 12.72 x 11.297), communities; they may be in contact with, or grade into, terrestrial caves (unit 65), and contain sand or pebble beaches (units 12.72 x 16.1, 12.72 x 17).', '(Augier, 1982, 1985; Harmelin y al., 1987; Fiala-Médione y al., 1987; Barnes and Hughes, 1988; Boury-Esnoult y al., 1993; Lovric, 1993a; Waugh, 1995).');
    'Broadening of rivers entering the oceans or their connected seas and river channels below the tidal limit. Included are all marine or marine-related pelagic and benthic communities, which can be specified by use of subdivisions of unit 11, and all river course and riverbed communities, which can be specified by subdivisions of unit 24. The belts of fringing vegetation are excluded and indicated separately by use of units 53, 44, 15 and their subdivisions.', '(Ketchum, 1983; Summerfield, 1991: 331-339).');
    'Portions of rivers subject to the tide, upstream from the estuary. Their banks may be colonized by communities of units 24.52, 37.71, 44.12, 53.1, in particular of units 37.711, 37.712, 44.121, 53.114, 53.13, 53.16, 53.17.', '(Géhu and Géhu, 1976; Ellenberg, 1988: 305-307; Pott, 1992: 124; Pott, 1996: 98, 263-274).');
    'Brackish portions of rivers subject to the tide, upstream from the estuary. ', '(Ellenberg, 1988: 305-307). ');
    'Freshwater sections of rivers subject to the tide. ', '(Ellenberg, 1988: 305-307; Pott, 1996: 263-274).');
    'Broadening of rivers entering the sea. Detailed habitats can be coded by combining subdivisions of prefix 11 with the relevant physiographic subdivisions of unit 13.2. ', '(Ketchum, 1983; Dijkema y al., 1984; Britton and Morton, 1989; Summerfield, 1991: 331-339; Lovric, 1993a; Lovric, 1993b; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996; Gastescu and Oltean, 1997).');
    'River-dominated, allochthonous deltaic estuaries formed by rivers accumulating sediments beyond the river mouth, often complex and constituted by many channels, with a salt wedge in the main channel; they are characteristic of microtidal shorelines. ', '(Ketchum, 1983; Dijkema y al., 1984; Summerfield, 1991: 331-339; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Wave- and current-dominated autochthonous estuarine systems constituted by shallow, often extensive, embayments separated from the sea by offshore bars of current-transported sand and with a very reduced tidal range; they are characteristic of mesotidal shorelines.', '(Ketchum, 1983; Dijkema y al., 1984; Summerfield, 1991: 331-339; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Composite river- and sea-dominated estuarine systems, including estuaries of macrotidal shorelines, subjected to tide-currents, devoid of protective littoral bars, and often accompanied by very developed tidal flats.', '(Ketchum, 1983; Dijkema y al., 1984; Summerfield, 1991: 331-339; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Extensive, flat or nearly flat, surfaces of sands, muds or rocks of the coasts of the oceans, their connected seas and associated lagoons, submerged for part of every tide or for part of the annual cycle, devoid of terrestrial vascular plants. They are of particular importance as feeding grounds for wildfowl and waders. The diverse intertidal communities of invertebrates and algae that occupy them can be precised by use of the subdivisions of units 11.27 to 11.2A, phanerogamic marine vegetation communities that may be exposed for a few hours in the course of every tide by use of those of unit 11.3, brackish water vegetation of permanent pools by use of those of unit 11.4.', '(Fuller, 1982; Soper, 1989; Morrison, 1989; Hollis and Jones, 1991; Summerfield, 1991: 331; Britton and Crivelli, 1993).');
    'Sands and muds of the coasts of the oceans, their connected seas and associated lagoons, submerged for part of every tide or for part of the annual cycle, devoid of terrestrial vascular plants, but usually coated by blue algae and diatoms. They are particularly well developed in the Wadden Sea, in the large bays of the North Sea, Atlantic and Channel coasts, in estuaries, in the Mediterranean Gulf of Gabes and along some subtropical coasts, among others, those of Mauritania.', '(Fuller, 1982: 21-35; Eisma and Fey, 1982: 13, 43-50; Soper, 1989; Morrison, 1989: 197-201; Hollis and Jones, 1991; Britton and Crivelli, 1993: 134, 144-145). ');
    'Bedrock platforms or terraces washed by the tides, broad wave-cut rock platforms situated in the intertidal zone, but nearer low tide, with a more or less plane surface, rough in detail, dotted by tidepools.', '(Soper, 1989).');
    'Communities of phanerogamic plants, for the most part halophytes, colonizing sites submerged by high tides at some stage of the annual tidal cycle of oceans and their connected seas. Similar halophyte communities colonizing the fringes and emersed beds of inland permanent or temporary saline, hypersaline or brackish waterbodies, including inland closed seas, lakes, pools, sebkhas, rivers, springs, seeps. By extension, azonal, strongly differentiated, communities developing on habitually dry, alkali, chlorid or gypseous soils of the nemoral, middle Eurasian steppe, Irano-Anatolian, Mediterranean, Saharo-Mediterranean and Macaronesian zones. Zonal communities of the desert and semidesert areas, composed, to varying degrees, of halophytes or gypsophytes, are listed under 7. Some saline communities with strong physionognimic similarity to fresh water ones into which they may merge, have been listed in other sections, together with their freshwater counterparts; it is the case in particular of saline tamarisk stands (44.83 ff.) and of tall helophyte beds (53). More generally, halophile forests and their related thickets have been listed with other forests under 4; in particular mangrove forests and thickets are in 4C.', '(Chapman, 1975, 1977a, 1977b; Steers, 1977; Walter, 1977; Phleger, 1977; Daiber, 1977; Beeftink, 1977; Zahran, 1977; Hosokawa y al., 1977; Daubenmire, 1978; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991b, 1991c; Adam, 1990; Denny, 1993a; Britton and Crivelli, 1993; Glooschenko y al., 1993; Bliss, 1993; Cramer, 1993; Pott, 1996).');
    'Formations composed mostly or prominently of annuals, in particular Chenopodiaceae of genus [Salicornia] or grasses, colonizing periodically inundated muds and sands of marine or interior saltmarshes of the Palaearctic.', '(Oberdorfer, 1952, 1990; Duvigneaud, 1967; Holub y al., 1967; Wolff, 1968; Ganchev y al., 1971; Zohary, 1973; Vicherek, 1973; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Castroviejo and Porta, 1975; Rivas-Martinez and Costa, 1975; Géhu, Caron and Bon, 1975; Chapman, 1977a: 4; Parent and Burny, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Géhu, 1984a, 1984b, 1984c; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Géhu y al., 1984b; Ladero y al., 1984; Peinado Lorca y al., 1984; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Dijkema y al., 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Moravec, 1986; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Korotkov y al., 1991; Elias y al., 1991; Pott, 1992; Mucina, 1993d; Julve, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Müller, 1998: Annex 5).');
    'Annual glasswort ([Salicornia spp.], [Microcnemum coralloides]), seablite ([Suaeda spp.]), or sometimes saltwort ([Salsola spp.]), formations colonizing periodically inundated muds of coastal saltmarshes and inland salt-basins of the Palaearctic.', '(Oberdorfer, 1952, 1990; Duvigneaud, 1967; Holub y al., 1967; Wolff, 1968; Ganchev y al., 1971; Zohary, 1973;  Vicherek, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Castroviejo and Porta, 1975; Rivas-Martinez and Costa, 1975; Géhu, Caron and Bon, 1975; Chapman, 1977a; Parent and Burny, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Géhu, 1984a, 1984b, 1984c; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Géhu y al., 1984b; Ladero y al., 1984; Peinado Lorca y al., 1984; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Dijkema y al., 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; LahondŠre, 1985, 1994; Géhu, 1986; Moravec, 1986; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Korotkov y al., 1991; Elias y al., 1991; Pott, 1992; Mucina, 1993d; Julve, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Swards of annual [Salicornia spp.] and [Suaeda maritima] of the coastal saltmarshes of the North Sea, the Baltic, the northern Atlantic and the western Eurasian polar basin.  ', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Géhu, Caron and Bon, 1975; Parent and Burny, 1981; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Dijkema y al., 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 4.1.5.2; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; LahondŠre, 1985, 1994; Géhu, 1986: 184; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 44; Pott, 1992; Julve, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.2.5.2; Mossberg y al., 1995: 89).');
    'Colonies of nonreddening tetraploid glassworts [Salicornia dolichostachya], [Salicornia fragilis], [Salicornia decumbens] and of [Suaeda maritima] ssp. [flexilis], occupying the lowest, dampest areas of northern and western European coastal flats.  ', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Géhu, Caron and Bon, 1975; Parent and Burny, 1981; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Géhu and Rivas-Martinez, 1984; Dijkema y al., 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 4.2.3.1; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; LahondŠre, 1985: 95-101; Géhu, 1986: 184; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992; Julve, 1993: 39-40; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.2.3.3; Mossberg y al., 1995: 89).');
    'Colonies of often much-branched, diploid glassworts [Salicornia ramosissima], [Salicornia europaea], [Salicornia obscura] [i.a.] and/or of [Suaeda maritima], occupying higher, drier areas of European coastal flats.  ', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Géhu, Caron and Bon, 1975; Hanso, 1975: 97; Parent and Burny, 1981; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Dijkema y al., 1984; Géhu and Rivas-Martinez, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 4.1.5.2 [p.]; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; LahondŠre, 1985: 106-117; Géhu, 1986: 184; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992; Julve, 1993: 40; LahondŠre, 1994: 41, 43-44; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.2.5.2; Mossberg y al., 1995: 89).');
    'Swards of annual [Salicornia spp.] of the coastal saltmarshes of the western Eurasian polar basin, in particular, [Salicornia dolichostachya] ssp. [pojarkovae] swards of northern Norway and northern Russia.', '(Dijkema, 1984a: 70; Géhu and Rivas-Martinez, 1984: 37; Mossberg y al., 1995: 89).');
    'Glasswort formations of inland saltmarshes of nemoral middle Europe, in particular of Germany, Poland, France and England (unit 15.4). ', '(Duvigneaud, 1967; Géhu, 1984a; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Dijkema y al., 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992; Julve, 1993).');
    'Formations of halonitrophilous annuals ([Frankenia pulverulenta], [Suaeda confusa], [Salsola acutifolia], [Parapholis incurva], [Hordeum marinum], [Cressa cretica]) colonizing solonchak salt muds susceptible to temporary inundation and extreme drying, caracteristic of lagoon systems of the western Black Sea coast and of the Danube Delta, somewhat similar ecologically and in species composition to the Mediterranean formations of the [Frankenietea pulverulentae].', '(Ganchev y al., 1971; Sanda y al., 1980; Popescu and Sanda, 1981).');
    'Formations of halonitrophilous annuals dominated by [Frankenia pulverulenta] colonizing salt muds susceptible to temporary inundation and extreme drying in openings within [Artemisio austriacae-Poetum bulbosae] or [Obionetum pedunculatae] communities of lagoon systems of the Black Sea, the Azov Sea and the Danube Delta.', '(Walter, 1974: 197; Popescu and Sanda, 1981).');
    'Saltmarsh formations constituted by [Cressa cretica], often accompanied by [Crypsis spp.], [Puccinellia festuciformis] ssp. [convoluta], [Aster tripolium], [Salicornia spp.] of western Black Sea coastal areas.', '(Ganchev y al., 1971).');
    'Closed halonitrophilous annual communities dominated by [Hordeum marinum], with [Plantago coronopus], [Lotus tenuis], [Juncus gerardi], [Lepidium latifolium], [Spergularia media], [Puccinellia distans], colonizing moderately salted muds of the western Black Sea coast and the Danube delta, susceptible to heavy autumn and spring inundation. ', '(Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a; Popescu and Sanda, 1992).');
    'Formations of small annual caryophyllid pioneers, in particular [Sagina maritima] and [Cerastium spp.], notably [Cerastium gracile] ([Cerastium ramosissimum]) or [Cerastium dubium] ([Cerastium anomalum]), of the western Black Sea coast and the Danube delta, developed on sands subject to variable salinity and humidity, in particular in the zone of contact between dune and saltmarsh.', '(Serbanescu, 1965; Chifu y al., 1991).');
    'Perennial pioneer grasslands of coastal salt muds of the Palaearctic, formed by [Spartina spp.] or similar grasses.  ', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Chapman, 1977a; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Parent and Burny, 1981; Pignatti, 1982; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Géhu, 1984b; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Dijkema y al., 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Diaz Gonzales and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Alcaraz Ariza and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1987; Pott, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Perennial pioneer grasslands of coastal salt muds dominated by flat-leaved [Spartina maritima] ([Spartina stricta]), [Spartina townsendii], [Spartina anglica], [Spartina alterniflora], distributed along Atlantic and North Sea coasts of middle Europe north to Denmark and south to northwestern Iberia, with outposts on the Atlantic coast of Africa around Tangier, Rabat and Cap Blanc, extending east to the Danish archipelago and with isolated areas of occurrence in the Mediterranean basin, located in the northern Adriatic, in the Venice Lagoon and nearby coasts, from the mouth of the Po to Trieste and Slovenia, and in estuaries of the coasts of northwestern Africa.', '(Knapp, 1973: 501; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Chapman, 1977a: 7, 9-10; Chapman, 1977b: 233; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980: 42; Parent and Burny, 1981; Pignatti, 1982: 590; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Géhu, 1984b; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Dijkema y al., 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 4.1.3.2; Diaz Gonzales and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 86; Pott, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.2.3.2; Mossberg y al., 1995: 591; Trpin and Vres, 1995: 87).');
    'Perennial pioneer grasslands of southern Iberian coastal salt muds, dominated by the junciform-leaved [Spartina densiflora].  ', '(Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980: 42-43; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1987: 226).');
