    'Garrigues occupying gypsum-rich soils of mediterranean North Africa, floristically characterised by the presence of numerous gypsophilous species.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Le Houérou, 1969; Herbauts, 1973; Knapp, 1973).');
    'Salt steppes and their associated saltmarsh herbaceous, suffrutescent or frutescent communities developed in the middle Eurasian steppe, the Irano-Anatolian and the Saharo-Mediterranean zones, under continental or mediterraneo-continental climatic regimes; they share a contingent of species of Irano-Turanian affinities. Communities of the saltmarshes of continental waterbodies of the middle Eurasian steppe, the central Eurasian desert, the Irano-Anatolian and the Saharo-Mediterranean zones. Salt steppes and saltmarshes of areas of extreme continentality within the boreal zone.', '(Zohary, 1973; Walter, 1974; Chapman, 1977a; Soo, 1980; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Korotkov y al., 1991: 46-451, 52-53, 55-58, 60-64, 65-66, 66-73, 73-75, 75-79, 80-84, 97, 131, 139, 157-158, 194-195; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Salt steppes and saltmarsh meadows of the Pannonic plain and its satellite basins. Large expanses of salt steppe form an open landscape of short-grass swards on slightly elevated ground (unit 15.A11) and of rills (units 15.A13, 15.A14), eroded shallow depressions with bare or sparsely vegetated saline soils, dry or moist in spring and prone to white salt efflorescences. Deeper rills, with less ephemeral water, support medium-tall saline meadows (unit 15.A12). Waterholes that dot the surface harbour brackish aquatic vegetation (unit 23.23) and are fringed by tall emergents (unit 53, in particular halophile communities of 53.17); their drying muds, subjected to prolonged immersion, are colonized by pioneer formations of Chenopodiaceae (unit 15.1151) or crypsoid grasses (unit 15.14). These ensembles of communities are mainly represented in the central Pannonic plain, east of the Tisza, in the Danube lowlands of the Tisza-Danube interfluve and in the Neusiedler See (Lake Ferto) basin. Smaller relics persist in the Danube lowlands of Slovakia, in the eastern Pannonic plain and Transsylvanian basin of Romania, in the Voivodina and have survived until recently in Moravia, where they may now be extinct. Outside of the Pannonic basin, western outposts of the continental salt steppes and saltmarshes (unit 15.A) are also known from the Bohemian basin and from isolated intermontane basins of the southwestern Balkan peninsula; the Bohemian communities have long been extinct; the extremely localized Balkanic ones, although equally related to the Pannonic and Pontic formations, have, for convenience, been included in this ensemble of units with which they share their extreme western location within the Eurasian salt steppe complex.', '(Topa, 1939; Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Holub y al., 1967; Vicherek, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1982, 1986; Szujko-Lacza y al., 1982; Komaromy, 1982; Moravec y al., 1983; Moravec, 1986; Elias y al., 1991; Mucina, 1993d).');
    '[Festuca pseudovina] swards of the slightly elevated natron shoulders and low benches of the Pannonic puszta, on saline but permanently dry soils with a thin humic layer. Together with the low-lying rills that score them, they constitute the main landscape of the saline Pannonian steppes; the formations of unit 15.A111 constitute the center group of communities, those of unit 15.A113 mostly compose intermediate belts between these and the bare or sparsely vegetated rills, those of units 15.A112 and 15.A114 are edaphically or geographically limited variants, that of unit 15.A116 is both transitional to rill vegetation and geographically limited. The communities of unit 15.A115 comprise the transitions between the saline pusztas and saline steppe-forests.', '(Topa, 1939; Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Holub y al., 1967; Vicherek, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1982, 1986; Szujko-Lacza y al., 1982; Komaromy, 1982; Moravec y al., 1983; Moravec, 1986; Elias y al., 1991; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Dominant salt-steppe communities of dry soils of the Pannonic plain, capable of covering vast surfaces, with [Festuca pseudovina], [Achillea collina], [Achillea setacea], [Trifolium subterraneum], [Trifolium pallidum], [Trifolium strictum], [Trifolium retusum], [Lotus tenuis], [Centaurea pannonica], [Scilla autumnalis]. ', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1982, 1986; Szujko-Lacza y al., 1982; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Salt-steppe communities of the northern and central parts of the Pannonian basin.  ', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1982, 1986; Szujko-Lacza y al., 1982).');
    'Salt-steppe communities of the southern parts of the Pannonian basin, with [Trifolium subterraneum], [Scilla autumnalis].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1982, 1986; Szujko-Lacza y al., 1982).');
    'Rare local salt-steppe formation of the Hortobagy, invaded by the tall, physiognomically dominant [Elymus elongatus] ssp. [ponticus] ([Agropyron ruthenicum]). ', '(Patkai and Molnar, pers. comm., 1992).');
    'Salt-steppe communities developed on sandy soils of the Pannonic plain, usually occupying much smaller surfaces than those of 15.A11, with [Festuca pseudovina], [Achillea collina] and [Achillea asplenifolia]. They are locally a refuge for tall grass loess-steppe and sand-steppe species such as [Astragalus varius], [Astragalus austriacus], [Astragalus aster], [Orchis ustulata], [Iris pumila]. ', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1982, 1986; Szujko-Lacza y al., 1982; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Saline steppe communities of the Pannonic plain, of strong middle Asian affinities, developed on more low-lying surfaces than those of unit 15.A111, often on the periphery of rills, usually inundated in early spring, dominated by sward-forming [Festuca pseudovina] with a variable admixture of emergent [Artemisia], often physiognomically dominant, and patchy mass-occurrences of [Limonium]. Characteristic species include [Artemisia santonicum] ssp. [santonicum], [Artemisia maritima] ssp. [maritima], [Festuca pseudovina], [Limonium gmelinii], [Trifolium retusum] ([Trifolium parviflorum]), [Sedum caespitosum], [Taraxacum bessarabicum] and the endemic [Plantago schwarzenbergiana].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1982, 1986; Szujko-Lacza y al., 1982; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Salt steppes or semideserts of the Transsylvanian basin, with [Festuca pseudovina], [Achillea collina] and species of Pontic and middle Asian affinities, such as [Artemisia santonicum] ssp. [patens], [Goniolimon tataricum], [Petrosimonia triandra]. 
', '(Todor, 1948; Soo, 1957a: 373; Sanda y al., 1980).');
    'Medium tall meadow communities of the Pannonic basin characteristic, in particular, of clearings and edges of oak forests on saline soils covered by water in early spring, species-rich and with an admixture of species of mesophile grasslands, dry grasslands and salt steppes, in particular, [Peucedanum officinale], [Peucedanum alsaticum], [Scutellaria galericulata], [Vicia narbonensis] var. [serratifolia], [Aster sedifolius] ([Aster punctatus]), [Aster linosyris], [Artemisia pontica], [Dianthus pontederae], [Rumex pseudonatronatus], [Iris spuria], [Orchis morio], [Festuca pseudovina], [Alopecurus pratensis], [Agrostis stolonifera].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Fekete y al., 1992).');
    'Communities dominated by [Limonium gmelinii] and [Artemisia santonicum], with [Aster tripolium], [Spergularia media], [Hordeum hystrix], [Gypsophila muralis] var. [stepposa], of the Transylvanian basin of eastern Pannonia, transitional to formations of the [Puccinellion limosae] (unit 15.A13).
', '(Sanda y al., 1980; So¢, 1957a, 1980).');
    'Salt-meadow communities of medium tall often tussock-forming grasses, developed on summer-dry carbonate-poor clay soils ([Beckmannion] communities) or on carbonate-rich or sandy soils ([Scorzonero-Juncion gerardii] communities) of the Pannonic plain. The [Scorzonero-Juncion gerardii] formations are well represented in particular in western Pannonia, in the Neusiedler See (Lake Ferto) basin and in the Danube-Tisza interfluvial region.   ', '(Topa, 1939; Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Holub y al., 1967; Vicherek, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986; Moravec y al., 1983; Moravec, 1986; Elias y al., 1991; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Medium-tall saline meadow communities of the central and eastern Pannonic plain, developed on less alkaline soils, poor in halophytic species, with [Agrostis stolonifera], [Alopecurus pratensis], [Glyceria fluitans] ssp. [poiformis], [Lysimachia nummularia], [Lythrum hyssopifolia], [Sium sisaroideum] and the Pannonic endemic [Cirsium brachycephalum].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986).');
    'Medium tall salt-meadow communities of the central and eastern Pannonic plain and the Transylvanian basin, developed on more alkaline soils, richer in halophytic species but poorer in overall species richness than the communities of unit 15.A121, with [Agrostis stolonifera], [Beckmannia eruciformis], [Bupleurum tenuissimum], [Pholiurus pannonicus], [Puccinellia limosa].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986).');
    'Medium-short salt-meadow communities of the central and eastern Pannonic plain and the Transylvanian basin, developed on silt accumulations, in particular of drift lines of larger marshes and along rills, with [Agrostis stolonifera], [Eleocharis palustris], [Eleocharis uniglumis], [Myosotis palustris], [Aster tripolium] ssp. [pannonicus], [Alopecurus geniculatus].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986).');
    'Pannonic salt-meadow communities of tussock-forming species installed on higher ground and less alkaline soils, subject to brief periods of water cover, with [Scorzonera parviflora], [Juncus gerardi], [Agrostis stolonifera], [Carex distans], [Taraxacum bessarabicum]; [Lotus tenuis], [Tetragonolobus maritimus], [Blackstonia serotina] are characteristic. They also harbour [Plantago maxima], [Ophrys scolopax], [Iris spuria].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Vicherek, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986; Moravec y al., 1983; Moravec, 1986; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Salt-meadow communities of the Pannonic basin, mostly developed on the margin of depressions, subject to brief periods of water cover, with [Scorzonera parviflora], [Juncus gerardi], [Agrostis stolonifera], [Triglochin maritima], [Eleocharis uniglumis] and the moss [Drepanocladus polycarpus], sometimes harbouring [Orchis palustris]. ', '(Soo, 1957a, 1980; Serbanescu, 1965; Vicherek, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986; Moravec y al., 1983; Moravec, 1986; Mucina, 1993d).');
    'Tragacanthic communities of the Taurus, the Antitaurus, the Amanus, the Aegean ranges of western Anatolia, the Lebanon mountains, Mount Hermon, the Jebel Druz and the mountains of northern Sinai, with rich communities dominated by numerous species of genera [Astragalus] and [Acantholimon], acccompanied by, among others, [Berberis cretica], [Daphne oleoides].', '(Zohary, 1973: 492-496; Ozenda, 1975: 26; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    'Tragacanthic communities of the Taurus and the Antitaurus, dominated by several species of genus [Acantholimon] and by [Astragalus angustifolius] and [Astragalus pannosus], among others.', '(Zohary, 1973: 495).');
    'Tragacanthic communities of the Aegean ranges of western Anatolia, dominated by species of genera [Astragalus] and [Acantholimon], acccompanied by, among others, [Daphne oleoides].', '(Zohary, 1973: 495-496).');
    'Tragacanthic communities of the Amanus, extremely rich in species, in particular of genus [Astragalus].', '(Zohary, 1973: 496).');
    'Tragacanthic communities of the Lebanon mountains, Mount Hermon, the Jebel Druz, dominated by over 15 species of genus [Astragalus], several species of genus [Acantholimon] and by [Berberis cretica].', '(Zohary, 1973: 494).');
    'Tragacanthic communities of the mountains of northern Sinai, dominated by a very limited number of species of genus [Astragalus].', '(Zohary, 1973: 493).');
    'Hedgehog-heaths of hills, plateaux and mountains of the steppe and substeppe zones of western central Eurasia, west to eastern Bulgaria and central Anatolia.', '(Schweinfurth, 1957; Zohary, 1973; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1987; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c).');
    'Open, herb-rich, snowbed communities of the middle to high alpine level of the boreal and southern arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia, developed on level or gently sloping moist calcareous ground with solifluction tongues separated by gravelly expanses with a thin but prolonged snow cover, dominated by [Luzula arctica]. [Luzula confusa], [Ranunculus glacialis], [Ranunculus sulphureus], [Cerastium spp.] and [Draba crassifolia] are characteristic of the species cortŠge.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.3.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.3.1).');
    'Herb-rich and often mosaic patterned snow-patch or near snow-patch communities of alpine levels of boreal and arctic Scandinavia, of the lower alpine belt of Iceland, of the Scottish Highlands and of the English Lake District, with many moss species and few lichens, occurring on calcareous, nutrient-rich, humid substrates. Characteristic species include [Ranunculus acris], [Poa alpina], [Poa arctica], [Saxifraga oppositifolia], [Silene acaulis], [Oxyria digyna], [Potentilla crantzii], [Cerastium alpinum], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Saussurea alpina], [Primula stricta], [Viola biflora], [Carex norvegica], [Minuartia biflora], [Thalictrum alpinum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 1.3.4.1, 1.3.4.3, 1.3.4.4; Rodwell, 1992: units CG12, U15; Påhlsson, 1994: units 1.2.4.1, 1.2.4.3, 1.2.4.4).');
    'Extremely herb-rich moderately chionophilous communities of the low and middle alpine levels of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia and of the lower alpine belt of Iceland, developed on calcareous, nutrient-rich, humid substrates, with a ground layer formed by many moss species and few lichens, and a mosaic-like vascular plant dominance in which a few species characterize smaller patches in different microtopic sites. These dominants include [Potentilla crantzii], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Silene acaulis], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Cerastium alpinum] and, in Scandinavia, [Poa alpina], [Poa arctica], [Saussurea alpina], or, in Iceland, [Alchemilla vulgaris] [s.l.], [Bartsia alpina], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Ranunculus acris], [Rumex acetosa], [Rhodiola rosea] ([Sedum roseum]), [Taraxacum spp.] These communities constitute an important habitat for [Nigritella nigra] [s.s.], [Primula stricta], [Armeria maritima] ssp. [labradorica]. [Drepanocladus uncinatus] is often the dominant bryophyte.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.4.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.4.1).');
    'Moderately chionophilous communities of higher altitudes of the Highlands of Scotland, forming, over calcareous bedrocks, short, often fairly open, species-rich swards of grasses, forbs and bryophytes among which [Silene acaulis], [Minuartia sedoides], [Sibbaldia procumbens], [Alchemilla alpina], [Thymus praecox], [Festuca ovina], [Festuca vivipara], [Agrostis capillaris], [Nardus stricta], [Deschampsia cespitosa] are prominent. The species cortŠge, rich in arctoalpine species, some of them of locally very restricted distribution, includes [Luzula spicata], [Saxifraga oppositifolia], [Polygonum viviparum], [Sagina saginoides], [Cerastium alpinum], [Antennaria dioica], [Saxlix herbacea], [Omalotheca supina], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Juncus trifidus], [Euphrasia frigida], [Alchemilla filicaulis] ssp. [filicaulis], [Myosotis alpestris], [Veronica alpina], [Poa alpina], [Draba norvegica], [Potentilla crantzii]. These communities are similar to the Fennoscandian communities of unit 36.12361; they are related also to the more acidocline communities of unit 36.11241.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: units D3a [p.], D3b; Rodwell, 1992: unit CG12).');
    'Herb-rich, moderately chionophilous, closed communities of the low and middle alpine levels of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia, developed over calcareous substrates with near-surface or subsurface seeping water, usually with deep soils that may be superficially decalcified, sometimes with lithosoils, with few dominants, mostly [Ranunculus acris] and [Poa alpina], sometimes [Petasites frigidus], and a mosaic of multispecific plant assemblies that include [Alchemilla glomerulans], [Arabis alpina], [Bartsia alpina], [Equisetum arvense], [Oxyria digyna], [Pedicularis hirsuta], [Pedicularis oederi], [Ranunculus nivalis], [Ranunculus pygmaeus], [Salix polaris], [Saussurea alpina], [Saxifraga cernua], [Saxifraga cespitosa], [Taraxacum croceum], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Trollius europaeus], [Veronica alpina], [Viola biflora], [Selaginella selaginoides]. These communities often occupy an intermediate position, in particular along streams, or at the bottom of hollows, between small herb communities of unit 36.12361 and tall herb communities of unit 37.8, dominated by [Trollius europaeus].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.4.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.4.3).');
    'Chionophilous, patchy communities of the low and middle alpine levels of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia, developed over calcareous substrates on moist, sometimes porous and unstable, mineral soils, dominated by [Saxifraga oppositifolia], accompanied by [Oxyria digyna], with a locally variable set of accompanying species and an often broken ground layer generally rich in marchantiaceid liverworts. The species cortŠge includes [Arabis alpina], [Cerastium alpinum], [Draba crassifolia], [Omalotheca supina], [Ranunculus pygmaeus], [Rumex acetosa], [Sagina saginoides], [Salix herbacea], [Saxifraga cernua], [Saxifraga tenuis], [Taraxacum croceum], [Veronica alpina], [Poa alpina], [Poa arctica], [Poa stricta].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.4.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.4.4).');
    'Almost pure banks of [Saxifraga aizoides] growing on continuously irrigated steep, calcareous cliff faces and earth banks of the Scottish Highlands and the Lake District; the species cortŠge includes [Saxifraga oppositifolia], [Alchemilla glabra], [Deschampsia cespitosa], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Selaginella selaginoides], [Blindia acuta], [Orthothecium rufescens]. This community is related to the Fennoscandian communities of unit 36.12364.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit D5; Rodwell, 1992: unit U15).');
    'Chionophilous communities of stony and gravelly ground of the islands of the polar basin developed in conditions of shorter snow cover than the polar willow communities, with a species cortŠge that includes [Trisetum spicatum], [Ranunculus nivalis], [Ranunculus pygmaeus], [Oxyria dygina], [Lidia biflora], [Poa arctica], [Potentilla hyparctica], [Carex lachenalii].', '(Hadac, 1989: 147-151).');
    'Snow-patch communities of high mountains of the Pontic Range and of the Caucasus.  ', '(Zohary, 1973: 498). ');
    'Snow-patch communities of high mountains of the Tien-Shan and Altai systems.', '(Walter, 1974: 261-261).');
    'Snow-patch communities of high mountains of the Himalayan system.', NULL);
    'Snow-patch communities of high mountains of boreonemoral, nemoral, warm-temperate and subtropical eastern Asia.', NULL);
    'Stonecrop and houseleak pioneer communities colonizing small surfaces on shallow soils of mostly siliceous rocky outcrops in the subalpine, alpine or montane levels of higher mountains of sub-Atlantic to Atlantic climates, in particular, of the Alps, the Pyrenees, the Cantabrians and associated northwestern Iberian ranges, the Black Forest and the Slovakian Carpathians.   The communities are dominated by succulent [Sempervivum arachnoideum] ssp. [arachnoideum], [Sempervivum arachnoideum] ssp. [tomentosum], [Sempervivum montanum] ssp. [montanum], [Sempervivum montanum] ssp. [stiriacum], [Sempervivum wulfenii], [Jovibarba arenaria], [Sedum montanum], [Sedum anglicum] ssp. [pyrenaicum], [Sedum sexangulare], [Sedum album], [Sedum annuum], [Saxifraga aspera], accompanied by [Silene rupestris], [Scleranthus polycarpos], [Veronica fruticans], [Thymus praecox] ssp. [polytrichus], [Viola tricolor] ssp. [saxatilis], by small crucifers, lichens and mosses.', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1955a; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Dupias, 1985; Ellenberg, 1988: 484; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a, 1994; Pott, 1992; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993b).');
    'Alpine and subalpine grasslands developed over crystalline rocks and other lime-deficient substrates or on decalcified soils of the boreal mountains, including the Caledonian mountains of Scotland, and of the western Alpids and their satellite Hercynian ranges, with [Armeria alpina], [Armeria alliacea] ([Armeria montana]), [Euphrasia minima], [Gentiana alpina], [Geum montanum], [Juncus trifidus], [Lychnis alpina], [Pedicularis pyrenaica], [Phyteuma hemisphaericum], [Pulsatilla alpina] ssp. [sulphurea], [Ranunculus pyrenaeus], [Sempervivum montanum], [Botrychium lunaria].', '(Ellenberg, 1963; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Ozenda, 1985; Jonglet, 1990; Grabherr, 1993c). ');
    'Halophile solonchak or solonetz-solonchak formations of western Black Sea coastal saltmarshes and of the lower Danube plain of Muntenia constituted by [Petrosimonia triandra] or [Petrosimonia brachiata], often with [Salsola soda], [Suaeda maritima], [Bassia hirsuta], [Puccinellia festuciformis] ssp. [convoluta], [Puccinellia distans], [Artemisia santonicum], [Artemisia austriaca].', '(Serbanescu, 1965; Ganchev y al., 1971; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    '[Frankenia hirsuta] halophilous meadows on solonchaks of the western Pontic region.', '(Walter, 1974; Chifu y al., 1991).');
    'Sea lavender-dominated moderately saline steppes of the lower Danube basin, including [Limonium latifolium]-dominated formations of the Studena river valley of northern Bulgaria and [Limonium vulgare]-dominated formations of Muntenia.', '(Ganchev y al., 1971; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda and Popescu 1990).');
    '[Camphorosma monspeliaca]-dominated formations of sulphate-rich saline flats of Northern Thrace, in particular in the basins of the middle Maritsa and Tundza and, locally, of the Black Sea plain and lower Danube plain of Oltenia, Muntenia and northern Bulgaria, with [Poa bulbosa], [Hordeum hystrix], [Gypsophila muralis], and in some local variants, [Artemisia santonicum] or [Genista sessilifolia] ([Genista trifoliolata]).', '(Serbanescu, 1965; Ganchev y al., 1971; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    '[Halimione pedunculata]-dominated formations of the lower Danube plain of eastern Muntenia, with [Puccinellia distans], [Spergularia media], [Salicornia europaea], [Juncus gerardi].', '(Serbanescu, 1965; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    'Formations of [Aeluropus littoralis], [Puccinellia festuciformis] ssp. [convoluta], [Puccinellia distans] ssp. [limosa], [Puccinellia distans] ssp. [distans] of western Black Sea coastal saltmarshes and adjacent inland areas.', '(Ganchev y al., 1971; Sanda y al., 1980).');
    'Formations of [Aeluropus littoralis], often accompanied by [Puccinellia festuciformis] ssp. [convoluta], [Puccinellia distans] ssp. [limosa], [Crypsis aculeata], [Salicornia europaea], [Suaeda maritima], [Spergularia spp.], [Juncus gerardi], [Cirsium alatum], [Taraxacum bessarabicum], [Plantago maritima] of sandy, strongly saline solonchaks or solonetz-solonchaks of western Black Sea coastal saltmarshes and of the Braila plain.', '(Krausch, 1965; Ganchev y al., 1971; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    'Formations of [Aeluropus littoralis] and [Puccinellia distans] ssp. [limosa] of very damp saline sands of the western Black Sea coast, with [Limonium gmelinii], [Limonium bellidifolium], [Plantago maritima], [Salicornia europaea], [Spergularia media], [Rumex maritimus].', '(Ganchev y al., 1971; Sanda y al., 1980; Popescu y al., 1987; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    '[Puccinellia festuciformis] ssp. [convoluta] meadows of western Black Sea coastal areas, with [Puccinellia distans], [Crypsis alopecuroides], [Crypsis aculeata], [Salicornia europaea], [Suaeda maritima], [Spergularia marina], [Spergularia media].', '(Ganchev y al., 1971).');
    'Scrubby formations of [Halimione verrucifera], [Halocnemum strobilaceum] and [Nitraria schoberi], accompanied by [Artemisia spp.], [Limonium spp.], [Petrosimonia spp.], colonizing saltmarshes and salt basins of western Black Sea coastal areas and of the lower Danube valley.', '(Sanda y al., 1980).');
    'Salt scrubs of Muntenia, Moldavia and the Dobrogea, dominated by [Halimione verrucifera], with [Artemisia santonicum], [Artemisia maritima], [Lotus angustissimus], [Puccinellia limosa], [Carex distans], [Camphorosma annua], [Plantago cornuti], [Taraxacum bessarabicum], [Suaeda maritima], [Salicornia europaea], [Limonium gmelinii].', '(Sanda y al., 1980; Mititelu y al., 1982; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    'Subarbustive halophile formations of the western Black Sea coastal lagoons, in particular of the Sinoe, Golovita, Razelm and Smeica lagoons of the Dobrogea, dominated by [Halocnemum strobilaceum], with [Halimione verrucifera], [Petrosimonia oppositifolia], [Limonium bellidifolium], [Lotus tenuis], [Plantago maritima].

', '(Topa, 1939; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    'Very local, more or less mesophile saline shrubby steppe of the vicinity of the mud volcanos of the Muntenian foothills of the extreme southeastern Carpathians, at Policiori-P¿clele (Buzau), formed by the spiny zygophyllaceous shrub [Nitraria schoberi], at the westernmost limit of its range, with [Halimione verrucifera], [Artemisia maritima], [Camphorosma monspeliaca].', '(Serbanescu, 1960; Sanda y al., 1980; Mititelu y al., 1982; Sanda and Popescu, 1990a).');
    'Salt steppes and saltmarshes of the southern edge and valleys of the Podolian, Central Russian and Volga plateaux, north of the Pontic and Caspian plains, associated with the steppes of unit 34.922; they extend west to the upper Prut basin of Romanian Moldavia and east to the Volga-Kama trough. They are developed, in particular, on the left bank of the Dniepr between the Oster and the Supoy, on the right bank of the Dniepr in the Bila Tserkva area south of Kiev, in the Bela region of the Bug-Dniestr interfluve, on the middle Don and in the Oka-Don plain.  ', '(Topa, 1939; Ravarut y al., 1968; Walter, 1974: 163, units 2a, 2b, [p.], 193-194, section a; Tolmachev, 1980: 36-37; Sanda y al., 1980; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Communities dominated by low tufted grasses and subshrubs, in particular [Festuca pseudovina] and [Artemisia spp.], occupying higher, drier solonetz ground in salt steppes of the southern periphery of the Podolian plateau, of the Central Russian and the Volga plateaux, north of the Pontic and Caspian plains, west to the upper Prut basin and east to the Volga-Kama.', '(Sanda y al., 1980; Popescu y al., 1984; Korotkov y al., 1991: 77).');
    'Halophilous communities of shady slopes of the Sarmatic steppe region composed of [Artemisia santonicum] ssp. [patens], with [Halimione pedunculata], [Aster tripolium], [Bassia sedoides], [Puccinellia distans]. 

', '(Popescu y al., 1984).');
    'Salt steppes of the Sarmatic region, west to Romanian Moldavia, with [Festuca pseudovina], [Achillea collina], [Artemisia santonicum] ssp. [patens], [Goniolimon tataricum], [Petrosimonia oppositifolia]. 
', '(Sanda y al., 1980).');
    '[Festuca pseudodalmatica], [Festuca pseudovina] and [Limonium tomentellum] saline steppes formed on deeply columnar solonetz of loess river terraces of the Ukrainian forest-steppe and steppe zones.', '(Korotkov y al., 1991: 77).');
