    'Formations of the coasts of the Palaearctic region, composed mostly of a few annual species, occupying accumulations of drift material and sands rich in nitrogenous organic matter, usually comprising [Cakile maritima], [Salsola kali], [Atriplex spp.], [Polygonum spp.]', '(Oberdorfer, 1952: 330-331; Lavrentiades, 1963; Wolff, 1968; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Géhu, 1984a, 1985; Ellenberg, 1988; Kolbek y al., 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992; Miyawaki and Suzuki, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Annual communities of sand beaches of the low Arctic and high Arctic oceanic zones of the Palaearctic Atlantic, Pacific and Arctic oceans, with [Cakile edentula] ssp. [islandica] ([Cakile arctica]), [Atriplex lapponica].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 4.1.1.5 [p.], 4.1.1.6 [p.]; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu, 1985: 39; van der Maarel, 1993c; Påhlsson, 1994: units 4.2.1.6, 4.2.1.4 [p.]).');
    'Annual communities of sand beaches of the Polar Basin coasts of continental Eurasia, from Finnmark eastwards, with [Atriplex lapponica] ([Atriplex longipes] ssp. [praecox] [p.]), [Polygonum norvegicum] and [Cakile edentula] ssp. [islandica] ([Cakile arctica]).', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 4.1.1.5 [p.], 4.1.1.6 [p.]; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu, 1985: 39, 49; van der Maarel, 1993c: 489; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.2.1.4 [p.]; Mossberg y al., 1995: 86, 180).');
    'Annual communities of Icelandic sand beaches, on fine sands, with [Cakile edentula] ssp. [islandica] ([Cakile arctica]) and [Atriplex glabriuscula]. Outlying stations occur within the boreal zone in southern Iceland and the Faeroe Islands.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 86; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 4.1.1.6 [p.]; Géhu, 1984a; Géhu, 1985: 39, 49; van der Maarel, 1993c: 490; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.2.1.6; Mossberg y al., 1995: 180).');
    'Annual halonitrophilous communities of the sand beaches of the temperate North Atlantic, the North Sea, the English Channel, the Irish Sea and the Baltic, with [Suaeda maritima], [Bassia hirsuta], [Cakile maritima], [Salsola kali], [Beta maritima], [Atriplex spp.], [Glaucium flavum], [Polygonum spp.], [Mertensia maratima].', '(Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; LahondŠre, 1980; Parent and Burny, 1981; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 4.1.1.5 [p.], 4.1.1.6 [p.]; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Géhu, 1984a, 1985; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994: units 4.2.1.4 [p.], 4.2.1.5).');
    'Fixed dunes of the mediterranean Maghreb and northern Atlantic Morocco with [Crucianella maritima], [Teucrium polium] var. [maritimum], [Artemisia campestris], [Calendula suffruticosa], [Lotus creticus].', '(Knapp, 1973: 496-497).');
    'Coastal dune communities of the Adriatic, the Ionian, the Aegean and the eastern Mediterranean, dominated by dwarf shrubs and subshrubs of genera [Ephedra], [Ononis], [Artemisia], and, very locally, [Crucianella], by tall canes or by succulents; they are usually rich in species of genus [Silene].', '(Oberdorfer, 1952: 333-334; Lavrentiades, 1963; Knapp, 1973: 495-497; Zohary, 1973: 446-450; Horvat y al., 1974; Vanden Berghen, 1978b; Géhu y al., 1984b: 421; Géhu, 1985: 41, 58-60; Zahran and Willis, 1992: 26; Pignatti, 1993: 387; Lavrentiades, 1993: 436-437; Lovric and Uslu, 1993: 453; Randall, 1993: 466-469; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1993: 6; Géhu and Biondi, 1996: 188; Hoda y al., 1998: 4).');
    'Fixed dune communities of the Adriatic coasts of Italy, Istria and Dalmatia, generally without [Crucianella maritima]. Dunal systems are mostly limited to the northeastern Adriatic coasts of Italy, from Ravenna to the northern Gulf of Trieste, with more isolated occurrences in the Otanto, on the north coast of Gargano, around Pescara and Conero, on the island of Rab, around Split, Kastel-Novi, the Neretva estuary and on the Montenegrine coast. Grey dune communities appear to be lacking or poorly developed in most of them, absent, in particular, in the Dalmatian ones. Italian communities, in particular northeastern Italian ones, are dominated by the ligneous, much branched biennial [Scabiosa argentea] var. [alba], with [Euphorbia paralias], [Phleum arenarium], [Silene conica] ssp. [conica], [Silene vulgaris] ssp. [angustifolia] and a more developed bryophyte cover, with [Tortula ruraliformis], then other mediterranean dunes.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 149; Pignatti, 1982: 673; Géhu y al., 1984b: 415-416, 421; Pignatti, 1993: 380, 384-387).');
    'Coastal dune communities of the southern Adriatic and Ionian coasts of Albania, of the Ionian coasts of the Hellenic peninsula, of the western Peloponnese, of the Ionian archipelago, dominated by [Ephedra distachya], [Euphorbia terracina], and the otherwise mostly west-Mediterranean [Silene nicaeensis].', '(Lavrentiades, 1963; Horvat y al., 1974: 123-124; Géhu, 1985: 41, 58-60; Lavrentiades, 1993: 436-437; Hoda y al., 1998: 4).');
    'Coastal dune communities of the Aegean coasts of continental Greece, Turkey and the archipelagoes, dominated by [Ephedra distachya], [Euphorbia terracina], [Silene conica] ssp. [subconica].', '(Oberdorfer, 1952: 333-334; Horvat y al., 1974: 123-124; Géhu, 1985: 41, 58-60; Lavrentiades, 1993: 436-437).');
    'Coastal dune communities of Anatolian, Levantine, Cyprian and North African coasts of the eastern Mediterranean, west to arid Tunisia, dominated by dwarf shrubs and subshrubs of genera [Ononis], [Artemisia], locally associated with [Crucianella], by tall canes or by succulents.', '(Knapp, 1973: 495-497; Zohary, 1973: 446-450; Vanden Berghen, 1978b; Zahran and Willis, 1992: 26; Lovric and Uslu, 1993: 453; Randall, 1993: 466-469; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1993: 6; Géhu and Biondi, 1996: 188).');
    'Coastal dune communities of Anatolian, Levantine, Cyprian and North African coasts of the eastern Mediterranean, west to arid Tunisia, dominated by dwarf shrubs of genus [Ononis], in particular, [Ononis natrix] ssp. [hispanica] in southern Anatolia, [Ononis vaginalis] between the Nile and north-east Lybia, [Ononis angustissima] in Tunisia, associated with [Lotus creticus], [Euphorbia paralias], and with canes of unit 16.22443, or, locally, in particular in the Levantine area and Egypt, with [Crucianella maritima].

', '(Holmboe, 1914: 103, 260; Knapp, 1973: 496-497; Vanden Berghen, 1978b: 227-236; Zahran and Willis, 1992: 26; Lovric and Uslu, 1993: 453, 457; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1993: 6).');
    'Coastal rear dune communities of Levantine and northeastern African coasts of the eastern Mediterranean dominated by [Artemisia monosperma], with [Cyperus capitatus].', '(Knapp, 1973: 497; Zohary, 1973: 447; Randall, 1993: 466-469).');
    'Coastal dune communities of North African coasts of the eastern Mediterranean, west to arid Tunisia, dominated by [Imperata cylindrica], associated with elements of unit 16.22441 and sometimes with desert grasses of genus [Stipagrostis] ([Aristida]), in particular, [Stipagrostis pungens], [Stipagrostis coerulescens], [Stipagrostis scoparia].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 255; Knapp, 1973: 496; Vanden Berghen, 1978b: 227-236).');
    'Semi-fixed dunes of arid or subdesert coasts of central and eastern North Africa, between Tunisia and Egypt, dominated by the chenopodid [Nitraria retusa].', '(Géhu and Biondi, 1996: 188).');
    'Dunal grasslands, in particular of northern Brittany, rich in species characteristic of dry calcareous grasslands (unit 34.32).', '(Géhu, 1985: 42).');
    '[Geranium sanguineum]-rich forb and grass communities, related to hem formations of unit 34.4, developed within grey dune systems of western Ireland, southwestern England, Wales, Brittany and southwestern Norway. ', '(Géhu, 1985: 42, 51; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.1.4.2 [p.]).');
