    'Coastal sand dune communities of the desert coasts of the Nile delta, dominated by Elymus farctus] or by [Silene succulenta], or by both in association.', '(Zahran and Willis, 1992: 318, 320).');
    'Coastal sand dune communities of the desert coasts of the African Atlantic.', '(Knapp, 1973).');
    'Coastal sand dune communities of the desert coasts of the Red Sea, of the Arabian Sea and of the Persian Gulf.', '(Knapp, 1973; Zahran, 1993; Shuaib, 1995).');
    'Dune communities of tropical coasts of the Palaearctic region.', '(Schnell, 1971b). ');
    'Humid depressions of the coastal dunal systems of the Palaearctic region. The most important habitats are included in the subordinate units. If the divisions proposed are not sufficient, appropriate codes from units 22.4, 22.3, 54.2, 54.4, 53 can be used in conjunction with them. Humid dune-slacks are extremely rich and specialized habitats, very threatened by the lowering of water tables. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Lebrun y al., 1949; Morariu, 1957; Herbauts, 1971; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; LahondŠre, 1980; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994; Müller, 1998: Annex 5).');
    'Fresh-water aquatic communities (cf. unit 22.4) of permanent dune-slack water bodies of the Palaearctic region. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; LahondŠre, 1980; Popescu y al., 1980; Stewart and Church, 1992: 24, 36).');
    'Pioneer formations of humid sands and dune pool fringes of the Palaearctic region, on soils with low salinity; communities can be specified by use of codes from unit 22.3, in particular unit 22.322 and unit 22.3132. 

', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Lebrun y al., 1949; Pignatti, 1959; Horvatic, 1954; Morariu, 1957; Herbauts, 1971; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Géhu and Foucault, 1977; LahondŠre, 1980; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1984a; Oberdorfer, 1990).');
    'Calcareous and, occasionally, acidic fen formations of coastal dune-slacks of the Palaearctic region (cf. units 54.2, 54.4, in particular units 54.21, 54.2H, 54.49), often invaded by creeping willow, occupying the wettest parts of dune-slacks. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Provost, 1975; LahondŠre, 1980; Oberdorfer, 1990).');
    'Humid grasslands and rushbeds (units 37.218, 37.21F, 37.31, 37.4 [i.a.]), wet heaths and swamp-heaths (unit 31.112 [i.a.]) of dune-slacks of the Palaearctic region, also often with creeping willows ([Salix rosmarinifolia], [Salix arenaria]).', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Dihoru and Negrean, 1976; LahondŠre, 1980).');
    'Reedbeds, tall-sedge communities and canebeds (cf. units 53.1, 53.2, 53.3, 53.6) of dune-slacks of the Palaearctic region. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; LahondŠre, 1980; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994).');
    'Beaches of the oceans, of their connected seas and of their associated coastal lagoons, covered by pebbles, or sometimes boulders, usually formed by wave action. ', '(Vanden Berghen, 1964; Zohary, 1973; Augier, 1982; Géhu, 1985; van der Maarel, 1993b: 13).');
    'Shingle beaches devoid of phanerogamic vegetation of the Palaearctic region. Codes of mediolittoral (intertidal) and supralittoral invertebrate communities listed under unit 11.28 can be combined with code 17.1 to record detailed habitats. ', '(Augier, 1982; Lovric, 1993a; Viney, 1994: xv). ');
