    'Humid meadows of Atlantic and sub-Atlantic Europe dominated by, or rich in, [Juncus acutiflorus]. They are floristically and phytosociologically very varied and many are as related to the oligotrophic [Molinion] communities of unit 37.3 as to the more eutrophic [Calthion] ones of unit 37.2. Sharp-flowered rush meadows are particularly characteristic of the oceanic and suboceanic regions of the western seaboard of Europe from northwestern Iberia to the Low Countries, extending locally in Hercynian ranges to the Harz and the Bohemian Quadrangle and in small sub-Atlantic enclaves of the Germano-Baltic plains to eastern Germany and Poland.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 122; Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958: 132-136; Sougnez and Limbourg, 1963; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 577; Braun-Blanquet, 1967a; Archiloque y al., 1969; Thoen and Bracke, 1971: 233-234; Noirfalise and Dethioux, 1972; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 180; Delpech, 1976; O''Sullivan, 1976a: 260-262; Schumacker, 1976: 254-257; Duvigneaud, 1976; Frileux, 1976; Sissingh, 1976; Bournérias y al., 1976; Delpech and Frileux, 1976; Wattez, 1976; Rose, 1976; De Sloover and Lebrun, 1976; Brasseur y al., 1978; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1980, 1985; De Sloover y al., 1980: 51-53; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Vanden Berghen and Peeters, 1982: 195-197; Gorissen y al., 1983; Moravec y al., 1983: 51; Dethioux y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 85; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b: 135-137, 216, 232; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Ladero Alvarez, 1987; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M23; Trautmann, 1991: 44; Pott, 1992: 234; Julve, 1993: 69-70; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 381-385; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 323; Robbe, 1993: 50; Schubert y al., 1995: 296; Frankard y al., 1998: 38).');
    'Meadows of the valleys of great rivers of continental or subcontinental climate regions of Central Europe, submitted to repeated inundation periods in the year, characteristic of the Elbe, the Saale, the Main valleys of Germany, of Bohemia, Moravia, Austria and northeastern Croatia, with a disjunct outpost in the arid Rhine graben; they are usually dominated by [Deschampsia cespitosa]; characteristic species include [Cnidium dubium] ([Cnidium venosum]), [Viola persicifolia], [Allium angulosum], [Iris sibirica], [Oenanthe lachenalii], [Oenanthe silaifolia], [Gratiola officinalis], [Juncus atratus], [Leucojum aestivum], [Carex praecox] var. [suzae], [Lythrum virgatum]. Because of universal river control schemes, these communities, dependent on natural or near natural flow regemes, are extremely threatened.', '(Balatova-Tulackova, 1965, 1976; Horvat y al., 1974: 401-403, 493; Moravec y al., 1983: 52-53, 54; Ellenberg, 1988; Zimmermann y al., 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Pott, 1992: 234, 237, 238; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 309-311, 331-336; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 372-375, 398-403; Julve, 1993: 90; Schubert y al., 1995: 301-303; Ilijanic, 1996: 107; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
