    'Wet heaths of the northern Atlantic and sub-Atlantic domaine and of boreal enclaves in the southern Atlantic and sub-Atlantic domaine. They mostly comprise wet and humid heaths of anmoors, gleypodzols and thin peats of the British Isles, the Germano-Baltic plains and neighbouring Hercynian hills, northern and northwestern France, southern Scandinavia, dominated by [Erica tetralix] or [Calluna vulgaris], sometimes in association with [Scirpus cespitosus] or [Molinia caerulea], usually accompanied by nonpeatbuilding sphagna, in particular, [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum molle], [Sphagnum tenellum]. They also include peaty heaths of more southern regions, in western France, the periphery of the Paris Basin and northwestern Iberia, mostly developed in the central, most humid, part of depressions, often in contact with somewhat less humid formations of unit 31.12.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: 163-164; Corillion, 1962: 103-105; Corillion, 1963: 16; Ellenberg, 1963; Depasse y al., 1970: 14-17; Géhu, 1973: 362-368, 373-374, 375; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 213-214, 215-216; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; De Sloover y al., 1978: 122-126; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 26, 34, 84; Gimingham y al., 1979: 385; Bournérias, 1979; Noirfalise y al., 1980: 25; Ratcliffe, 1980: 3, 7; de Smidt, 1981: 46-47, 48, 49-55; Pi¿rart and Duvigneaud, 1982: 24; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.1.2.1, 5.1.1.5b; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 93, 184; Bournérias, 1984: 316-318; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b: 185; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 97; Ellenberg, 1988: 510-512, 667; Oberdorfer, 1990: 43; Rodwell, 1991b: units M15, M16, H5, M14 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 194-195; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 273-280, 280-282; Julve, 1993: 104, 108; Robbe, 1993: 51; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.2.1, 5.1.1.5b, 5.1.1.5c [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.7; Riecken y al., 1994: 143, 93; Schubert y al., 1995: 143-144; Romao, 1996: 46; Opermanis y al., 1997: 56).');
    'Wet heaths and humid heaths of the British Isles, the Germano-Baltic plains and northern France, with principal areas of occurrence in the drier, eastern, lowlands of Britain and in the North Sea plain between northern Belgium and Schleswig-Holstein, extending to southwestern Belgium and northwestern France, to the confines of Normandy, to the montane level of the western Hercynian hills, in particular, the Ardennes, and, in the northeast, to the Prignitz, the Lausitz and western Poland, always rich in, and generally dominated by, [Erica tetralix], sometimes by [Calluna vulgaris], often in association with [Molinia caerulea], accompanied by nonpeat-building sphagna, in particular, [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum molle], [Sphagnum tenellum], and by [Zygogonium ericetorum]; the cortŠge may include [Gentiana pneumonanthe], [Juncus squarrosus], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Scirpus cespitosus] ssp. [germanicus], [Carex panicea], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Dicranum scoparium].', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 120; Ellenberg, 1963; Depasse y al., 1970: 14-17; Géhu, 1973: 362-368, 373-374, 375; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 213-214, 215-216; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; De Sloover y al., 1978: 122-126; Gimingham y al., 1979: 385; Bournérias, 1979; Noirfalise y al., 1980: 25; de Smidt, 1981: 48, 49-55; Pi¿rart and Duvigneaud, 1982: 24; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.1.2.1, 5.1.1.5b; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 93, 184; Bournérias, 1984: 316-318; Ellenberg, 1988: 510-512, 667; Oberdorfer, 1990: 43; Rodwell, 1991b: units M16, M14 [p.]; Lambert y al., 1991: 66-68; Pott, 1992: 195; Julve, 1993: 104; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.2.1, 5.1.1.5b, 5.1.1.5c [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.7.1; Riecken y al., 1994: 143; Schubert y al., 1995: 144; Frankard y al., 1998: 39).');
    'Wet heaths or swamp-heaths of wet depressions of the acidified coastal dunes of the Wadden Sea islands of the Netherlands, Lower Saxony and Schleswig-Holstein, and of the southern Baltic coasts, east to eastern Germany, dominated by [Erica tetralix], accompanied by [Empetrum nigrum], [Salix repens], [Calluna vulgaris], [Carex trinervis], [Juncus balticus] ([Juncus arcticus] ssp. [balticus]), [Juncus anceps] ([Juncus alpinoarticulatus] ssp. [atricapillus]), [Calamagrostis epigeios], [Vaccinium macrocarpum] ([Oxycoccus macrocarpus]), [Drosera rotundifolia], [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum molle].', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 216; Gimingham y al., 1979: 385; de Smidt, 1981: 46-47, 48; Ellenberg, 1988: 290, 512; Westhoff and van Oosten, 1991: 142-147; Pott, 1992: 195; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 3.11.3 [p.]; Schubert y al., 1995: 143).');
    'Wet heaths of Ireland, western and northern Britain, western Norway, southern Norway and Sweden, western, northern and northeastern Jutland, mostly developed on shallow peats, sometimes on peaty mineral soils, under highly oceanic climates, dominated by [Erica tetralix] and/or [Calluna vulgaris], in association with [Scirpus cespitosus] or [Molinia caerulea], accompanied by, in particular, [Potentilla erecta], [Polygala serpyllifollia], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Carex panicea], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Myrica gale], [Cornus svecica], [Sphagnum palustre], [Sphagnum capillifolium], [Sphagnum subnitens], [Dicranum scoparium], [Hypnum jutlandicum], [Leucobryum glaucum], [Cladonia spp.].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.1.2.1, 5.1.1.5b; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M15; Pott, 1992: 195-196; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.2.1, 5.1.1.5b, 5.1.1.5c [p.]).');
    'Wet and humid heaths of anmoors of middle European Hercynian hills and their periphery, in particular, of the Black Forest and the Vosges, at the continental limit of the range of the Western European wet heaths, dominated by [Calluna vulgaris] in association with [Scirpus cespitosus] ssp. [germanicus] accompanied by [Juncus squarrosus], [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum tenellum], [Leucobryum glaucum], [Scirpus cespitosus] ssp. [cespitosus], [Molinia caerulea]. Facies may be dominated by [Scirpus cespitosus] with little or no [Calluna vulgaris] and constitute oligotrophic humid grasslands included in unit 37.32.', '(Parent, 1973: 55; Oberdorfer, 1990: 43; Pott, 1992: 195-196; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 273-280, 280-282).');
    'Tall heaths of moist, shallow depressions of the Lizard in Cornwall, dominated by [Erica vagans] and [Schoenus nigricans] with [Erica tetralix], [Molinia caerulea], [Serratula tinctoria] and often [Ulex gallii].', '(Rodwell, 1991b: unit H5).');
    'Peaty heaths of western France, the periphery of the Paris Basin and northwestern Iberia, mostly developed in the central, most humid, part of depressions, often in contact with somewhat less humid formations of unit 31.12.', '(Corillion, 1962: 103-105; Corillion, 1963: 16; Géhu, 1973: 373; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 26, 34, 84; Gimingham y al., 1979: 385; Bournérias, 1979; Bournérias, 1984: 316-318; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b: 185; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 97; Julve, 1993: 108; Robbe, 1993: 51; Romao, 1996: 46).');
    'Humid and meso-hygrophile heaths of gley-podzols and semipeaty soils of the northwestern Iberian peninsula, Atlantic France, the Paris Basin and its periphery, extreme southern England, dominated by [Erica tetralix] or [Erica ciliaris], with [Erica scoparia], [Erica ciliaris], [Calluna vulgaris], [Ulex minor], [Ulex gallii] or [Genista anglica]. They may, in particular, form transition belts between peaty heaths of unit 31.11 and dry heaths of unit 31.2.', '(Corillion, 1962: 103-105; Corillion, 1963: 16-17; Géhu, 1973: 362-368, 371-374, 375; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 26, 30-36, 78, 82-84; Gimingham y al., 1979: 385; Rodwell, 1991b: units H3 [p.], H4 [p.], M16 [p.]; Julve, 1993: 104; Robbe, 1993: 100-101; Romao, 1996: 46).');
    'Beaches of inland seas and of large saline lakes, formed by wind or wave action.', '(Jung, 1990; Hollis and Jones, 1991; Scott, 1991; Britton and Crivelli, 1993).');
    'Estuaries formed by rivers emptying into inland seas and large saline lakes.', '(Jung, 1990; Hollis and Jones, 1991; Scott, 1991; Britton and Crivelli, 1993).');
    'All rivers and streams, permanent or temporary, fresh or saline, including rivers, streams, brooks, rivulets, rills, torrents, wadis or oueds, waterfalls, cascades and rapids.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Whitten and Brooks, 1972; Lelek, 1980; Haslam and Wolseley, 1981; Holmes, 1983; Haslam, 1987; Clark, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Summerfield, 1991; Leser, 1994; Einarsson, 1994; Waugh, 1995; Cummins y al., 1995; Petersen y al., 1995; Ladle and Westlake, 1995; Billen y al., 1995; Sabater y al., 1995; Statzner and Kohmann, 1995; Cattaneo y al., 1995; Bogatov y al., 1995; Dudgeon, 1995; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Flowing water courses of the Palaearctic region, permanent or temporary, and their associated animal and microscopic algae pelagic and benthic communities. Rivers, streams, brooks, rivulets, rills, torrents, wadis or oueds, waterfalls, cascades and rapids are included. The macrophytic, euhydrophytic communities that colonize them are separately listed under unit 24.4. Features of the river bed, uncovered by low water or permanently emerging, such as gravel, sand, mud or rock islands and bars are listed under units 24.2, 24.3, 24.5 and 24.6. The macrophytic amphibious communities and the terrestrial communities that may develop on them are listed under the relevant sections when specific to watercourses, are otherwise indicated by codes from units 15, 22.3, 3 or 4. The fringing belts of tall or short emergent vegetation are listed under unit 53, the spring vegetation under unit 54.1, the riverside veils of tall herbs and lianas under unit 37.71, riverine arbustive and arborescent vegetation under unit 44. The subdivisions of this unit are based on slope, width and water temperature, according to usual ichthyological practice. Classifications based on flora, such as that of Holmes (1983) for British streams, give broadly similar results. For each of the divisions below, subdivisions can be introduced to take into account regional characteristics, as well as the morphodynamics of the stream, as proposed, for instance, by Malavoi (1989).', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Whitten and Brooks, 1972; Lelek, 1980; Haslam and Wolseley, 1981; Philippart and Vranken, 1983; Holmes, 1983, 1992; Haslam, 1987; Malavoi, 1989; Clark, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Summerfield, 1991; Leser, 1994: 141-142; Einarsson, 1994; Waugh, 1995: 50-89; Cummins y al., 1995; Petersen y al., 1995; Ladle and Westlake, 1995; Billen y al., 1995; Sabater y al., 1995; Statzner and Kohmann, 1995; Cattaneo y al., 1995; Bogatov y al., 1995; Dudgeon, 1995; Mrakovcic, 1996; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Gushing springs (rheocrenes), spring basins (limnocrenes), seepages (helocrenes) and crenal streams, rivulets formed in and near the source area of streams, characterized by high stability of temperature, near the annual average of the ground water, best developed in mountain situations. The presence of specialized vegetation associated with the spring is indicated by use of divisions of unit 54.1.', '(Holmboe, 1914: 4; Schembri, 1989: 76; Schubert, 1991; Leser, 1994: 261; Demetropoulos, 1996).');
    'Upper and middle reaches of Palaearctic mountain streams ("Gebirgsbach", "alpine", "mountain" and "upland" streams), characterized by turbulent, irregular flow, by diurnal and annual temperature variations higher than in the crenon, and, by aquatic biocoenoses largely dominated by Turbellaria, Ephemeroptera, Plecoptera, Trichoptera, Diptera, by Bryophyta and epilithic Bacillariophyta, Cyanophycaea, Rhodophyta and Chlorophyta algae, with few, specialized, immerged macrophytes (unit 24.3). The unit corresponds to the "Trout zone" or "Salmonid zone" of western European ichthyological classifications.', '(Lelek, 1980; Haslam and Wolseley, 1981; Philippart and Vranken, 1983; Holmes, 1983; Haslam, 1987; Schubert, 1991; Leser, 1994: 459; Glazovskij, 1995: 27-28). ');
    'Lower reaches of Palaearctic mountain streams ("Gebirgsbach", "alpine", "mountain" and "upland" streams), often representing the middle course of rivers. The unit corresponds to the "Grayling zone" of western European ichthyological classifications.', '(Lelek, 1980; Haslam and Wolseley, 1981; Philippart and Vranken, 1983; Holmes, 1983; Haslam, 1987; Schubert, 1991; Leser, 1994: 459). ');
    'Upper reaches of Palaearctic lowland streams ("Niederungsbach", "lowland" and "plain" streams), characterized by calmer flow, higher annual temperature variation and aquatic biocoenoses comprising more standing water species, among them immerged macrophytes (unit 24.3). The unit corresponds to the "Barbel zone" of western European ichthyological classifications.', '(Lelek, 1980; Haslam and Wolseley, 1981; Philippart and Vranken, 1983; Holmes, 1983; Haslam, 1987; Schubert, 1991; Leser, 1994: 419-420). ');
    'Middle and lower reaches of Palaearctic lowland streams ("Niederungsbach", "lowland" and "plain" streams), with aquatic biocoenoses very similar to those of standing water. The unit corresponds to the "Bream zone" of western European ichthyological classifications.', '(Lelek, 1980; Haslam and Wolseley, 1981; Philippart and Vranken, 1983; Holmes, 1983; Haslam, 1987; Schubert, 1991; Leser, 1994: 419-420). ');
    'Palaearctic watercourses of which the flow is interrupted for part of the year, leaving a dry bed or pools; conditions during the period of flow can be indicated by one of the previous codes.', '(Holmboe, 1914: 4; Whitten and Brooks, 1972; Clark, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Einarsson, 1994: 143; Lanfranco, 1999a, 1999b; Schembri, 1999b, 1999c).');
    'More or less vertical descent of a water course over irregularities of the streambed. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 247; Whitten and Brooks, 1972; Horvat y al., 1974: 492-494; Clark, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Waugh, 1995: 70; Einarsson, 1994: 146-152; Mohorovicic, 1996; Bralic, 1996; Bozicevic, 1996; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Deposit beds of Palaearctic streams formed of pebbles, gravels, boulders or a mixture of gravels and finer sediments, with the communities that occupy them.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Braun-Blanquet, 1973b; Vanden Berghen, 1982; Géhu, 1984a; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Clark, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Summerfield, 1991; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Leser, 1994; Einarsson, 1994; Waugh, 1995; Cummins y al., 1995; Petersen y al., 1995; Ladle and Westlake, 1995; Billen y al., 1995; Sabater y al., 1995; Statzner and Kohmann, 1995; Cattaneo y al., 1995; Bogatov y al., 1995; Dudgeon, 1995; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Deposit beds of Palaearctic streams formed of pebbles, gravels, boulders or a mixture of gravels and finer sediments, occupying the edges of the stream, forming islands in the channel or supporting the arms and rivulets constituting the stream, together with their associated animal communities. The presence of vascular vegetation is indicated by use of the appropriate code from unit 24.22. Water-fringing communities, in particular of units 53, 37.7, 37.8, 37.9, may contribute to the colonisation of the deposits. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Vanden Berghen, 1982; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Clark, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Summerfield, 1991: 199-204, 284-287; Leser, 1994; Einarsson, 1994: 146-154, 169-170; Waugh, 1995: 50-89; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 23-29).');
    'Deposit beds of Palaearctic streams formed of pebbles, gravels, boulders or a mixture of gravels and finer sediments strewn along the sides of the stream or constituting islands in its channel.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Vanden Berghen, 1982; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Clark, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Summerfield, 1991: 199-204, 284-287; Leser, 1994: 141-142; Einarsson, 1994: 146-154, 169-170; Waugh, 1995: 50-89; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 23-29).');
    'Large beds of gravels, pebbles, boulders or mixed coarse and fine sediments constituting outwash fans, alluvial fans, sandar (sandur), deposited and criss-crossed by braided rivers of the Palaearctic region, characteristic, in particular, of boreal and arctic lands with intense fluvio-glacial deposition.', '(Whitten and Brooks, 1972: 62; Whittow, 1984: 71-72, 467; Clark, 1990: 279; Schubert, 1991; Summerfield, 1991: 210-211, 222-223, 284-287; Mayhew and Penny, 1992: 169, 201; Leser, 1994; Einarsson, 1994: 154, 169-170; Waugh, 1995: 72, 107; Glazovskij, 1995: 27; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 26; Gudjonsson and Gislason, 1998).');
    'Vascular plant communities occupying gravel deposits of Palaearctic rivers, including pioneer vegetation and subsequent stages in the colonization sequence. Early-stage communities of Alpide, boreal and Mediterranean watercourses are specialized, those of nemoral lowlands and hills are related to other formations, in particular those of unit 37.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Holub y al., 1967; Archiloque y al., 1969; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Braun-Blanquet, 1973b; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Vanden Berghen, 1982; Géhu, 1984a; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Open assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants, rich in alpine species, colonizing gravel beds of Palaearctic streams with an alpine, summer-high, flow regime, formed in northern boreal and lower arctic mountains, hills and sometimes lowlands, as well as in the alpine and subalpine zones of higher, glaciated, mountains of more southern regions, sometimes with abyssal stations at lower altitudes.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Holub y al., 1967; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Braun-Blanquet, 1973b; Vanden Berghen, 1982; Géhu, 1984a; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Open assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants colonizing  alluvial and glacial gravels and sands inundated by rivulets and streams of the alpine and subalpine levels of the Alps. Characteristic plants include [Epilobium fleischeri], [Saxifraga bryoides], [Gypsophila repens], [Rumex cutatus], [Trifolium pallescens], [Astragalus sempervirens], [Rhacomitrium canescens].  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Holub y al., 1967; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Braun-Blanquet, 1973b; Vanden Berghen, 1982; Géhu, 1984a; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993).');
    'Open assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants colonizing gravel beds of streams of northern boreal and lower arctic Eurasian mountains, hills and sometimes lowlands.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Low open assemblies of grasses and herbs colonising the lower parts of stony, boulder-strewn shingle banks of rivers in the mountains of boreal and arctic Scandinavia and in Iceland dominated by [Oxyria digyna] and [Cerastium alpinum] or by [Calamagrostis stricta], [Deschampsia cespitosa] and [Oxyria digyna]. There are very few lichens and mosses present, except in the [Calamagrostis] communities, in which [Hypnum lindbergii] may be abundant, and in the Norwegian and Icelandic representatives of the [Cerastium] communities, in which they play an important part, in particular the mosses [Rhacomitrium canescens] and [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.5.1.1; Påhlsson, 1994: units 7.2.1.1, 7.2.1.1a).');
    'Often sparse and lacunar assemblies of herbaceous plants dominated by the spectacular, low-growing, [Epilobium latifolium], a species restricted in the Palaearctic to Iceland, Greenland and Siberia, variously accompanied by [Silene uniflora], [Festuca richardsoni], colonizing shingle, gravel and sand deposits of river beds of lowlands and lower mountains of Iceland.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.5.1.1a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.1.1b).');
    'Extremely dry, level, gravelly and stony terraces situated above the water line of rivers of Iceland and of the alpine and arcto-alpine regions of Scandinavia, colonized by a continuous moss and lichen cover dominated by [Rhacomitrium canescens], [Stereocaulon spp.], and, in Iceland, [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], with few vascular plants.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.5.1.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.1.4).');
    'Open assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants colonizing  alluvial and glacial gravels and sands inundated by rivulets and streams of the alpine and subalpine levels of central Eurasian mountains.', NULL);
    'Open assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants colonizing  alluvial and glacial gravels and sands inundated by rivulets and streams of the alpine and subalpine levels of mountains of eastern Eurasia.', NULL);
    'Open or closed assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants, colonizing, within the montane or submontane levels, gravel beds of streams with an alpine, summer-high, flow regime, born in high mountains of the Alpine system.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Braun-Blanquet, 1973b; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Open and often unstable assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants, rich in casual immigrants from higher altitudes, colonizing gravel beds of the montane reaches of unregulated Alpine streams, with [Chondrilla chondrilloides], often accompanied by [Erucastrum nasturtiifolium], [Gypsophila repens], [Dryas octopetala], [Aethionema saxatile], [Epilobium dodonaei], [Erigeron acer], [Leontodon berinii], [Buphthalmum salicifolium], [Euphorbia cyparissias], [Fumana procumbens], [Agrostis gigantea], [Anthyllis vulneraria] ssp. [alpestris], [Campanula cochlearifolia], [Hieracium piloselloides], [Calamagrostis pseudophragmites], [Conyza canadensis], [Pritzelago alpina], and seedlings of [Salix elaeagnos], [Salix purpurea], [Salix daphnoides] and [Myricaria germanica].  Because of widespread interference with natural flow regimes, these formations are gravely endangered.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Braun-Blanquet, 1973b; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Closed or lacunar assemblies of often large herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants colonizing montane and submontane gravel beds loaded with finer sands or silts of unregulated streams of the Alpine system and its vicinity.  [Calamagrostis pseudophragmites] is usually dominant, seedlings of montane and dealpine willows, characteristic of 24.2221, often absent.  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 117-118).');
    '[Calamagrostis pseudophragmites]-dominated communities of rivers originating  in the Alpine and Carpathian arcs complex. Characteristic plants include [Epilobium dodonaei], [Agrostis gigantea], [Phalaris arundinacea], [Tussilago farfara]. Like those of unit 24.2221, these communities are gravely threatened by widespread watercourse alterations affecting natural flow regimes.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Sanda y al., 1980; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 117-118).');
    'Assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants colonizing gravel beds of streams with an alpine, summer-high, flow regime in the montane zone of the Pyrenees and the Cantabrian chain, with [Calamagrostis pseudophragmites] and [Erucastrum nasturtiifolium].
', '(Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b).');
    'Thermophile pioneer communities of river gravels, mostly characteristic of the upper Rhine, with [Scrophularia canina], [Epilobium dodonaei], [Hieracium piloselloides], [Silene prostrata], [Inula conyza], [Centaurea stoebe] ssp. [stoebe], [Arenaria serpyllifolia], [Echium vulgare], [Salix elaeagnos] seedlings.  ', '(Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Pott, 1992).');
    'Open or closed assemblies of herbaceous or suffrutescent pioneering plants, colonizing, within the montane or submontane levels, gravel beds of streams with an alpine, summer-high, flow regime, born in the high Ponto-Caucasian mountains.', NULL);
    'Communities of low shrubby pioneers invading the herbaceous formations of units 24.221 and 24.222 on gravel deposits rich in fine silt of mountain and northern boreal Palaearctic streams with an alpine, summer-high, flow regime. [Myricaria germanica] and [Salix spp.] are characteristic. Precise communities can be indicated by use of codes from unit 44, in particular unit 44.11.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Påhlsson, 1994; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Thickets or woods of, among others, [Salix spp.], [Hippophae rhamnoides], [Alnus spp.], [Betula spp.], on stream gravels of mountain and northern boreal Palaearctic streams with an alpine, summer-high, flow regime. Precise communities can be indicated by use of codes from unit 44, in particular unit 44.11.', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Heaths rich in gorse ([Ulex spp.]) of the Atlantic margins of Europe.', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Corillion, 1962, 1963; Dendaletche, 1973; Géhu, 1973: 365-375; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Ratcliffe, 1977b, 1977c; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Rivas-Martinez, 1979; Géhu, 1984a; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Webb, 1986; Izco, 1987; Rodwell, 1991b: units H2, H3 [p.], H4 [p.], H6, H7 [p.], H8; Julve, 1993; Romao, 1996: 47).');
    'Wind-swept heaths with prostrate, cushiony gorse or broom ([Ulex europaeus] f. [maritimus], [Ulex gallii] f. [humilis], [Cytisus scoparius] ssp. [maritimus]), [Erica vagans], [Erica cinerea], [Calluna vulgaris], and numerous other maritime ecotypes, of cliff tops of promontories and islands of Brittany, Cotentin, southern Ireland, Cornwall, Wales, the Cantabrian coast and Galicia.', '(Corillion, 1963: 15; Géhu, 1973: 368-369; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 38-43; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H7 [p.]; Julve, 1993: 104-105).');
    'Oceanic heaths of Ireland, Wales, the Isle of Man, the South-West Peninsula and, locally, the Pennines and the coasts of East Anglia, dominated by [Ulex gallii], [Calluna vulgaris] and [Erica cinerea]. Basicline heaths, somewhat homologous to the continental formations of unit 31.22B, may form in zones of transition between some communities of this unit and calcareous grasslands of unit 34.', '(Géhu, 1973: 365-375; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Rivas-Martinez, 1979; Webb, 1986: 84; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H8).');
    'Western Irish heaths comprising the northern, isolated, populations of [Erica mackaiana].  ', '(Géhu, 1973: 365-375; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Rivas-Martinez, 1979; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 59; Webb, 1986: 120).');
    'Heaths of well drained soils of the coasts and offshore islands of Ireland, Cornwall and Brittany, other than cushiony maritime formations, dominated by or rich in [Erica vagans], constituting isolated northern outposts of occurrence of the species.', '(Corillion, 1963: 15-16, 26; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Webb, 1986: 56, 80, 84; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H6; Romao, 1996: 48).');
    'Heaths of well drained soils of the coasts and offshore islands of Brittany, other than cushiony maritime formations, dominated by or rich in the uncommon and local [Erica vagans], almost limited to the islands of Belle-Ile and Groix.', '(Corillion, 1963: 15-16, 26; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383).');
    'Heaths of well drained soils of the Lizard, in Cornwall, with a mixed canopy usually formed by [Erica vagans], [Ulex europaeus], [Erica cinerea], [Ulex gallii], with [Carex flacca], [Viola riviniana], [Filipendula vulgaris], [Agrostis canina], [Stachys officinalis] ([Stachys betonica], [Betonica officinalis]), [Hypochoeris radicata], [Polygala vulgaris], [Potentilla erecta], [Dactylis glomerata], [Scilla verna].', '(Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Webb, 1986: 56, 80, 84; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H6).');
    'Heaths of well drained soils of Brittany, the Cotentin peninsula, the South-Western Peninsula and the south coast of Wales, dominated by [Ulex gallii], [Erica cinerea] and [Calluna vulgaris], often rich in grasses, in particular, [Agrostis curtisii].', '(Corillion, 1963: 15; Géhu, 1973: 370; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Webb, 1986: 84; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H4 [p.]; Julve, 1993: 104).');
    'Heaths with [Ulex gallii], [Erica mackaiana], [Erica cinerea], [Daboecia cantabrica] of well drained soils of the beech level of the Pyrenees and the Cantabrian chain and, very locally, of Galicia.', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 27, 30-34; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984a: 125-126; Izco, 1987: 409).');
    'Heaths with [Ulex gallii], [Erica vagans], [Erica cinerea], sometimes [Erica aragonensis], and [Pseudarrhenatherum longifolium] of the French and Spanish Basque coast and of the beech level of the Atlantic Pyrenees and of the Cantabrian chain, mostly on mildly acid or sightly calcareous soils.', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Dendaletche, 1973: 134; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383-385; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 30; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 102, 103, 105; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987: 136; Izco, 1987: 410, 411; Julve, 1993: 104).');
    'Heaths of sub-Atlantic France and of southern and southeastern England formed by [Ulex minor], [Erica cinerea], [Calluna vulgaris] and [Ulex europaeus].', '(Corillion, 1962, 1963; Géhu, 1973: 371; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 385; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Webb, 1986; Rodwell, 1991b: units H2, H3c).');
    'Heaths of well drained soils of interior and oriental Brittany, the Perche, Normandy, the Paris Basin, the Sologne, the southern Morvan, dominated by [Erica cinerea], [Ulex minor], [Calluna vulgaris] and [Ulex europaeus].', '(Corillion, 1962: 106; Corillion, 1963: 18; Géhu, 1973: 371; Gimingham y al., 1979: 385; Bournérias, 1979; Bournérias, 1984: 319-320; Robbe, 1993: 100-101; Julve, 1993: 104).');
    'Heaths of southern and southeastern England, from east Dorset to Kent, dominated by [Calluna vulgaris] and [Ulex minor], accompanied by [Erica cinerea] and usually by [Deschampsia flexuosa], sometimes by [Vaccinium myrtillus] or [Molinia caerulea]; [Ulex europaeus] and [Agrostis curtisii] are uncommon.', '(Géhu, 1973: 371; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Webb, 1986: 83; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H2).');
    'Heants of Dorset and Hampshire dominated by [Ulex minor], [Erica cinerea] and [Agrostis curtisii], on relatively well drained soils; [Calluna vulgaris] is usually of low abundance, [Ulex europaeus] is usually present. They constitute an important habitat of [Viola lactea].', '(Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Webb, 1986: 83; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H3c).');
    'Heaths of well drained soils of Aquitaine, Saintonge, Poitou, Sologne and the Loire region formed by [Ulex minor] and [Erica cinerea], sometimes with [Erica scoparia].', '(Géhu, 1973: 370-371; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 25).');
    'Aquitanian heaths with rock-roses. Iberian heaths with numerous species of heathers (notably [Erica umbellata], [Erica aragonensis]) and brooms, rock-roses and often [Daboecia]. When the rock-roses and other Mediterranean shrubs become dominant they should be classified under sclerophyllous scrubs (unit 32).', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Géhu, 1973: 363-365, 375; Polunin and Smythies, 1973; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Gimingham y al., 1979: 383-385; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 16-22; Penas and Diaz Gonzalez, 1985; Izco, 1987; Bayer and Lopez Gonzalez, 1989; Julve, 1993; Romao, 1996: 47).');
    'Coastal and collinar [Erica]-[Ulex]-[Cistus] heaths of the periphery of the Bay of Biscay and of the slopes of the Garonne Gap. ', '(Géhu, 1973: 369-370; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 25-26, 28-30; Julve, 1993: 104).');
    '[Erica cinerea] and [Cistus salvifolius] heaths of the Aquitanian coast, with irradiations in the Landes and to the Montagne noire and Minervois.  ', '(Géhu, 1973: 369-370; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 25; Julve, 1993: 104).');
    'Arid [Erica cinerea] heaths of interior sandy hills and dunes of the Landes of Gascony and of Sologne gravels, with [Halimium alyssoides].  ', '(Géhu, 1973: 370; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 25-26; Julve, 1993: 104).');
    'Tall, dense heaths of the coasts, hills and lower montane areas of the Atlantic slope of Cantabria, the Asturias and Galicia, formed by [Erica vagans] and [Ulex europaeus], with [Erica cinerea], [Calluna vulgaris] and [Daboecia cantabrica]. ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 28-30).');
    'Atlantic Galician and Portuguese [Erica cinerea], [Erica umbellata] and [Ulex europaeus] heaths.  ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 36-38, 38-39, 43; Izco, 1987: 408-409, 411).');
    'Coastal and collinar, thermo-Atlantic Galician and northern Portuguese heaths with [Erica cinerea], [Erica umbellata], [Ulex minor], [Ulex europaeus], [Ulex micranthus], [Cistus salvifolius] and [Halimium alyssoides]. ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 36-38, 38-39; Izco, 1987: 408-409, 411).');
    'Cushiony heaths with [Ulex europaeus] ssp. [latebracteatus] f. [humilis] and [Erica cinerea] of cliff tops of Galicia, north and central Portugal (southern vicariant of unit 31.231).  ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 43).');
    'Low [Calluna vulgaris]-rich heaths of interior northwestern mountains, limited to the Sierra de la Cabrera and the neighbouring Sierra Segundera, Pena Trevinca and Sierra del Teleno.  ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 68-70, 78-79; Izco, 1987: 411-412).');
    'Open, cushiony formations of [Calluna vulgaris], [Erica umbellata], [Genista sanabrensis], [Halimium umbellatum], [Halimium alyssoides] occupying dry, superficial soils.  ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 68-70; Izco, 1987: 411-412).');
    'Formations of [Calluna vulgaris], [Genista carpetana], [Genista anglica], [Genista micrantha] and [Thymelaea coridifolia] ([Thymelaea dendryobryum]) of wetter stations. ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 78-79).');
    '[Erica aragonensis] or [Erica umbellata] heaths of the interior slopes of the Cordillera Cantabrica, of interior Galicia and of the Leonese mountains.  ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 52-54, 61-64; Izco, 1987: 410-412; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987: 135-142).');
    'Supra-Mediterranean [Erica aragonensis] heaths with [Chamaespartium tridentatum], [Calluna vulgaris], [Halimium alyssoides] of the interior slopes of the Cantabrian Cordillera, eastern Galician ranges, Leon mountains and the Sierra de Cabrera.  ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 61-64; Izco, 1987: 410-411).');
    'Lower altitude heaths on the confines of Galicia and Leon dominated by [Erica umbellata] accompanied by [Erica cinerea], [Calluna vulgaris], [Chamaespartium tridentatum], [Halimium alyssoides], [Genista triacanthos], [Lavandula stoechas] ssp. [luisieri].', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 52-54; Izco, 1987: 410-411).');
    'Lower altitude heaths on the confines of Galicia and Leon, characteristic of slightly more uniform and humid climates than those of unit 31.2442, dominated by [Erica cinerea], accompanied by [Calluna vulgaris], [Chamaespartium tridentatum], [Erica umbellata], [Halimium umbellatum] and Mediterranean elements such as [Lavandula stoechas] ssp. [pedunculata], [Thymus mastichina].  ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 54; Izco, 1987: 411-412).');
    'Wet heaths and humid heaths of the northwestern Iberian peninsula, in the Atlantic and Carpetano-Iberico-Leonese provinces and, very locally, in the Luso-Extremadurian province, particularly characteristic of the beech and deciduous oak levels of the Cantabrian chain and Galicia, dominated by [Erica tetralix], [Erica ciliaris] or [Erica mackaiana] with [Genista anglica], [Genista micrantha], [Ulex gallii], [Calluna vulgaris], [Erica cinerea], [Daboecia cantabrica], [Juncus squarrosus], [Cirsium filipendulum], and sometimes [Euphorbia polygafolia].', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 30-36, 78, 82-84; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984a: 125-126; Loidi Arregui, 1987: 68; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 99, 102, 103, 105; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987: 136; Izco, 1987: 409).');
    'Humid and meso-hygrophile heaths of gley-podzols with hydromor of Aquitanian and Ligerian France north to Brenne and the Le Mans region, dominated by [Erica tetralix], [Erica scoparia] or [Erica ciliaris], with [Molinia caerulea], [Scorzonera humilis], [Carum verticillatum], [Ulex minor], [Genista anglica], [Pseudarrhenatherum longifolium] ([Arrhenatherum thorei]).', '(Géhu, 1973: 362-368, 371-374, 375; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 26).');
    'Humid and meso-hygrophile heaths of semipeaty gley podzols of eastern Britanny, Normandy, the southern Paris Basin, the Morvan, extending very locally to England in southern Dorset, dominated by [Erica tetralix] or [Erica ciliaris], generally with [Ulex minor], accompanied by [Calluna vulgaris], [Genista anglica], [Salix repens], [Ulex europaeus], [Molinia caerulea], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Danthonia decumbens], [Carex panicea], [Polygala serpyllifolia], [Potentilla erecta], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Lobelia urens], [Carum verticillatum], [Scorzonera humilis], [Pedicularis sylvatica], [Ajuga occidentalis], [Sphagnum compactum], [Cladonia spp.]', '(Corillion, 1962: 103-106; Corillion, 1963: 16-18; Géhu, 1973: 362-368, 373-374, 375; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 26; Bournérias, 1979: 319-320; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H3a, H3b; Julve, 1993: 104; Robbe, 1993: 100-101; Romao, 1996: 46).');
    'Humid and meso-hygrophile heaths of semipeaty gley podzols of hyper-Atlantic lower Brittany, Cornwall and Devon, dominated by [Erica tetralix] or [Erica ciliaris], generally with [Ulex gallii], accompanied by [Genista anglica], [Salix repens], [Molinia caerulea], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Juncus squarrosus], [Potentilla erecta], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Pinguicula lusitanica], [Viola palustris], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Lobelia urens], [Wahlenbergia hederacea], [Anagallis tenella], [Hydrocotyle vulgaris], [Cirsium dissectum] ([Cirsium anglicum]), [Carum verticillatum], [Dactylorhiza ericetorum] ([Dactylorhiza maculata] ssp. [ericetorum]), [Sphagnum spp.] and sometimes [Myrica gale].', '(Corillion, 1963: 16-18; Géhu, 1973: 362-368, 372-374, 375; Rivas-Martinez, 1979: 26; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H4c; Julve, 1993: 104; Romao, 1996: 46).');
    'Degraded facies of wet heaths, humid heaths and swamp-heaths of the Atlantic and sub-Atlantic domaines of the western Palaearctic region, dominated by [Molinia caerulea].', '(Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Bournérias, 1979, 1984: 314, 316; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.2.2 [p.]; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M16 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.5c [p.], 5.1.2.2 [p.]; Schubert y al., 1995: 144; Opermanis y al., 1997: 56).');
    'Xerophile or meso-xerophile heaths on siliceous, podsolic soils in moist Atlantic and sub-Atlantic climates of the plains and low mountains of Western and Central Europe. ', '(Gimingham, 1972; Géhu, 1973: 375; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Specht, 1979a; Gimingham y al., 1979; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Rivas-Martinez, 1979; Noirfalise y al., 1980; Ratcliffe, 1980; De Smidt, 1981; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Webb, 1986; Oberdorfer, 1990: 43; Rodwell, 1991b: 347-356; Pott, 1992; Ellmauer, 1993: 402-405; Oberdorfer, 1993a; Julve, 1993: 103-106; Påhlsson, 1994; Schubert y al., 1995: 137-143; Romao, 1996: 47; Loidi y al., 1997; Müller, 1998: Annex 5).');
    'Submontane, or sometimes lowland or coastal, heaths rich in [Vaccinium spp.], usually with [Calluna vulgaris], of the northern and western British Isles, of the North Atlantic islands, of Fennoscandia, of the Hercynian ranges and the lower levels of the Alps, the Carpathians, the Pyrenees and the Cordillera Cantabrica.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Ellenberg, 1963; Géhu, 1973: 363-365, 375; Schumacker, 1973; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 225; Noirfalise and Vanesse, 1976; Ratcliffe, 1977b, 1977c, 1980; De Sloover y al., 1978; Rivas-Martinez, 1979; Gimingham y al., 1979: 381-382; Noirfalise y al., 1980; De Smidt, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Webb, 1986; Noirfalise, 1987; Hejny and Slavik, 1988; Salomez, 1990; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a: 243; Coldea, 1991; Rodwell, 1991b: H12, H16, H18, H21; Pott, 1992: 319; Ellmauer, 1993: 407-408; Julve, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Schubert y al., 1995: 140-143; Romao, 1996: 47).');
    'Low altitude heaths of boreomontane affinities developed under euoceanic climates along the coasts of low Arctic and northern temperate North Atlantic islands and of boreal and arctic Scandinavia, generally characterized by the prominence of [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Vaccinium uliginosum] or [Vaccinium vitis-idaea].', '(Ratcliffe, 1977b: 325; Ratcliffe, 1977c: 285-286, 297; Nordiska Ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.1.1; Webb, 1986: 80; Rodwell, 1991b: units H14, H17, [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: 5.1.1.1).');
    'Low altitude heaths of boreomontane affinities of the Faeroe, Shetland and Orkney islands, mostly characteristic of exposed headlands under euoceanic conditions, with [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Calluna vulgaris], [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Arctostaphylos alpinus], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum]. They are floristically closely related to montane heaths of unit 31.45, in particular, the Scottish Highland heaths of units 31.451 and 31.452.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977b: 325; Ratcliffe, 1977c: 285-286, 297; Webb, 1986: 80; Rodwell, 1991b: units H14, H17, [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.1.1 [p.]).');
    'Low altitude prostrate, open, moss-rich heaths of boreomontane affinities of the coasts and islands of oceanic southern boreal, oceanic middle boreal and arcto-alpine Norway, dominated by [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Vaccinium uliginosum] and [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], accompanied by [Calluna vulgaris], [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Arctostaphylos alpinus], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Cladonia spp.], [Sphagnum spp.]', '(Nordiska Ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.1.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.1.1 [p.]).');
    'Moss-rich, closed [Vaccinium uliginosum]-[Vaccinium myrtillus]-[Empetrum hermaphroditum] heaths of Iceland, of boreomontane affinities, developed under humid euoceanic climate conditions at mostly low altitudes, typically from sealevel to 460 m. The three erico¿d shrubs dominate in any combination and may be accompanied by [Calluna vulgaris] or [Loiseleuria procumbens]. Common nonerico¿d vascular plants include [Alchemilla alpina], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Salix herbacea], [Viola palustris], [Galium boreale], [Galium normanii], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Carex bigelowii], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Avenella flexuosa]. Orchids include [Dactylorhiza islandica], [Coeloglossum viride], [Listera cordata]. The moss layer is very developed, with a cover of 20% to 70%, and a rich and diverse bryophyte and lichen cortŠge in which [Rhacomitrium canescens], [Drepanocladus uncinatus], [Rhytidiadelphus squarrosus], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus], [Hylocomium splendens], [Dicranum scoparium], [Polytrichum alpinum] may be particularly prominent.', '(Steindorsson, 1965: 79-86, 120, tables XI, XII; Hadac, 1972: 367-371; Hadac, 1985a: 135-137; Nordiska Ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.1.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.1.1 [p.]).');
    '[Vaccinium]-dominated, [Vaccinium]-rich and [Empetrum]-rich heaths of boreomontane affinities characteristic of northern and western uplands of Britain and of western and southern Scandinavia, with extensions in the Germano-Baltic plain, particularly in Jutland, Poland, southern Finland and the Baltic States. [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Empetrum nigrum], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Pleurozium schreberi] and [Hylocomium splendens] are strongly represented among the associates of [Calluna vulgaris].', '(Gimingham y al., 1979: 381-383; Ratcliffe, 1980: 3, 9; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.1.1.5, 5.1.1.5a; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 94, 191; Rodwell, 1991b: H12, H16, H18, H21; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.3, 5.1.1.3a, 5.1.1.5, 5.1.1.5a, 5.1.1.5d, 5.1.1.6, 5.1.1.6a).');
    'Usually low, relatively open submontane or subboreal heaths of the uplands of northern and western Britain, of southern Fennoscandia and Denmark, usually dominated by [Vaccinium myrtillus], in association with [Empetrum nigrum], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Calluna vulgaris], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea] or [Vaccinium uliginosum] and with a moss-rich or grass-rich cortŠge.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: 3, 9; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H18; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.6, 5.1.1.6a).');
    'Usually low, relatively open submontane heaths of the uplands of northern and western Britain, particularly widespread in the central and eastern Highlands, usually dominated by [Vaccinium myrtillus], often in association with [Empetrum nigrum] or [Empetrum hermaphroditum], variously accompanied by [Calluna vulgaris], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Vaccinium uliginosum] and with a generally moss-rich or grass-rich cortŠge that includes, in particular, [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Festuca ovina], [Agrostis capillaris], [Nardus stricta], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Danthonia decumbens].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: 3, 9; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H18).');
    '[Vaccinium myrtillus] heaths of the Highlands, with outposts in the Southern Uplands, the Lake District, and northern Wales, with abundant [Empetrum hermaphroditum] and bryophytes, mostly associated with large shallow snow beds at relatively high altitudes.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B3e [p.], B3b [p.]; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H18a).');
    '[Vaccinium myrtillus] heaths of the western and central Highlands, with outliers in the Southern Uplands and Wales, with [Alchemilla alpina] and abundant grasses, characteristic of lower altitudes, sunnier stations and lesser snow cover than those of unit 31.21211.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B3c; Rodwell, 1991b: unit 18b).');
    '[Vaccinium myrtillus]-[Empetrum spp.] heaths of the southern Highlands, the Southern Uplands, the Lake District, the Bowland Fells, the Pennines, Wales and Dartmoor, with [Cladonia] lichens, [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Galium saxatile], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Festuca ovina], [Carex bigelowii].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B3e [p.]; Rodwell, 1991b: unit 18c).');
    'Usually low, relatively open, subboreal heaths of southern Fennoscandia and Denmark, usually dominated by [Vaccinium myrtillus] and [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], in association with [Calluna vulgaris] and mosses or with [Deschampsia flexuosa].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.6, 5.1.1.6a).');
    'Open [Vaccinium myrtillus]-[Vaccinium vitis-ideae]-[Calluna vulgaris] heaths characteristic of southern Scandinavia, distributed in Denmark, along the coast of Norway, north to central Norway, and in southwestern Sweden, developed under somewhat humid, mild-winter climates, with a field layer species cortŠge comprising [Galium saxatile], [Maianthemum bifolium], [Potentilla erecta], [Trientalis europaea], [Danthonia decumbens], [Deschampsia flexuosa], and a ground layer dominated by [Pleurozium schreberi] accompanied by [Dicranum polysetum], [Hypnum cupressiforme], [Hylocomium splendens], [Rhytidiadelphus triquetum] and lichens of genus [Cladonia]; [Juniperus communis] may be present; [Blechnum spicant] and [Rhytidiadelphus loreus] may be the important constituents of communities of oceanic Norway.', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.1.6).');
    'Grass-rich [Vaccinium myrtillus]-[Vaccinium vitis-ideae] heaths of central Sweden and southwestern Finland, with a species cortŠge comprising [Deschampsia flexuosa], which may codominate with the ericoid shrubs, [Calamagrostis arundinacea], [Luzula pilosa], [Lathyrus linifolius], [Melampyrum spp.], [Viola riviniana], occupying dry, lightly grazed patches within birch-oak pastures often on boulder-strewn moraine land.', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.1.6a).');
    'Subboreal and upland [Calluna vulgaris]-dominated heaths of northern and western Britain, southern Scandinavia and Denmark, more or less rich in [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea] or [Empetrum nigrum] and sometimes with [Erica cinerea], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], grasses or lichens.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: 3, 9; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.1.5; Rodwell, 1991b: H12; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.3, 5.1.1.3a, 5.1.1.5, 5.1.1.5d).');
    'Subboreal, upland, [Calluna vulgaris]-dominated heaths of northern and western Britain, more or less rich in [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Erica cinerea] or [Empetrum nigrum], accompanied by grasses or by pleurocarps and lichens.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: 3, 9; Rodwell, 1991b: H12).');
    'Submontane and collinar heaths of the Highlands, the Southern Uplands, Orkney, Shetland, the Lake District, the Pennines, the North York Moors, Wales, the South-West Peninsula dominated by [Calluna vulgaris] associated with [Vaccinium myrtillus], which may sometimes be codominant, accompanied by [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Empetrum nigrum] and, sometimes, [Erica cinerea], and often by pleurocarps and lichens.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: units B3a, B3g, B1a [p.]; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H12a, H12b [p.]).');
    'Grassy submontane and collinar heaths of the eastern Highlands, the Southern Uplands, Orkney, the Lake District, Wales, the South-West Peninsula dominated by [Calluna vulgaris] associated with [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Festuca ovina], [Festuca rubra], [Nardus stricta], [Anthoxanthum odoratum] and with [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Empetrum nigrum], [Erica cinerea]. Grassy [Calluna]-[Vaccinium] heaths, in particular, those rich in [Nardus stricta] and associated grasses, or in [Juncus squarrosus], include communities transitional to grasslands of units 35 and 37.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B3d; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H12c, 497, units U6 [p.], U7 [p.]).');
    'Subboreal [Calluna vulgaris]-dominated heaths of southern Scandinavia and Denmark, rich in [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea] or [Empetrum nigrum], in mosses and lichens, and sometimes grasses.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.1.5; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.3, 5.1.1.3a, 5.1.1.5, 5.1.1.5d).');
    'Very open heaths of Denmark, southern Sweden, southern Norway and, very locally, southwestern Finland, developed on podzols in humid, mild-winter climates, dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum nigrum] and [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], with a rich moss and lichen cortŠge usually dominated by [Pleurozium schreberi], sometimes with a prominent occurrence of [Molinia caerulea].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.3, 5.1.1.3a).');
    'Open heaths of western and northern Jutland, northern Zealand, Scania, the coasts and near-coastal hills of southern Sweden and southern Norway, of oceanic Norway north to the oceanic middle boreal zone, dominated by [Calluna vulgaris] accompanied by [Vaccinium vitis-idaea] and/or [Vaccinium myrtillus], and with [Pleurozium schreberi] usually dominant in the moss layer; [Blechnum spicant] may be the main accompanier of [Calluna vulgaris] in some communities of the oceanic southern boreal zone of Norway.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.1.5; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.1.5, 5.1.1.5d).');
