    'Pioneer communities colonizing thin debris soils and cracks of rocks, cliffs and rock pavements of xerothermic enclaves of the boreonemoral and southern boreal zones of Norway, Sweden and Finland, mostly limited to coastal regions, southern slopes and alvars. Some of the communities share physiognomic and ecological characteristics with the Central European communities of unit 34.35.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.1.5.1, 5.2.1.1; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.1.5.1, 5.2.1.1, 5.2.1.1a, 5.2.1.1b, 385).');
    'Open swards of lowland and hill calcareous rock debris of boreonemoral Europe, limited to alvar limestone outcroppings of ¿land, Gotland, V¿sterg¿tland, the ?land archipelago and extreme southern Finland; they are very low [Sedum album] and [Tortella spp.]-dominated herb and moss communities  occupying open, level limestone pavements almost totally lacking in soil, surrounded by a system of fissures, under semiarid climatic conditions. [Tortella inclinata] and [Tortella tortuosa] dominate among the mosses and lichens; the species cortŠge also includes, among others, [Allium schoenoprasum], [Androsace septentrionale], [Arenaria serpyllifolia], [Apera interrupta], [Cerastium pumilum], [Geranium lucidum], [Linum catharticus], [Saxifraga tridactylites], [Sedum acre], [Melica ciliata], [Tortella rigens], [Tortella caeruleonigricans], [Barbula spp.], [Cladonia symphycarpia], [Collema spp.] They are associated with rock fissure communities of unit 62.1B1 and rock lichen communities of unit 62.4121.', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1963: 31; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.5.1; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993b: 513; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.5.1).');
    'Sparse communities of small annuals, short grasses and succulents colonizing thin soils covering acid or basic rocks, or forming in small cracks under extremely dry local climates in xerothermic enclaves of Scandinavia, north to the southern boreal zone, mostly in coastal areas and on south-facing slopes. They are a refuge for species of low competition potential and are often dominated by one or two species, in particular, [Sedum acre], [Aira praecox], [Viola tricolor], [Rumex tenuifolius]. Their species cortŠge includes [Arabidopsis thaliana], [Bromus mollis], [Geranium pusillum], [Jasione montana], [Lychnis viscaria], [Satureja acinos], [Saxifraga granulata], [Saxifraga tridactylites], [Scleranthus annuus], [Scleranthus perennis], [Sedum album], [Sedum telephium], [Trifolium arvense], [Veronica arvensis], [Veronica spicata], [Veronica verna], [Viola rupestris], [Ceratodon purpureus], [Rhytidium rugosum], [Thuidium abietinum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.2.1.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.2.1.1).');
    'Rock swards of the Atlantic coast of Norway developed in thermic enclaves on south-facing slopes under oceanic climates, richer in grass and poorer in xerophile species than the communities of unit 34.1152, with a species cortŠge that includes [Plantago lanceolata], often dominant, [Festuca vivipara], [Viola tricolor], [Alchemilla alpina], [Allium oleraceum], [Arabidopsis thaliana], [Conopodium majus], [Galium saxatile], [Hieracium pilosella], [Potentilla argentea], [Veronica officinalis], [Luzula campestris], [Orchis mascula].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.2.1.1a).');
    'Rock swards of Tr¿ndelag and northern Norway with [Astragalus alpinus], [Campanula rotundifolia], [Draba incana], [Erigeron borealis], [Gentiana nivalis], [Gentianella campestris], [Lotus corniculatus], [Poa alpina], [Potentilla crantzii], [Primula scandinavica].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.2.1.1b).');
    'Open grasslands of strongly to slightly calcareous inland sands of Western Europe and of western and northern Central Europe, locally to Lithuania, Latvia and Belarus, with [Helichrysum arenarium], [Silene otites], [Silene chlorantha], [Dianthus deltoides], [Dianthus arenarius], [Gypsophila fastigiata] ssp. [arenaria], [Astragalus arenarius], [Androsace septentrionalis], [Onosma arenaria], [Jurinea cyanoides], [Koeleria glauca], [Festuca psammophila], [Festuca polesica], [Festuca duvalii] and the Brandenburg endemic [Stipa borysthenica] ssp. [germanica], sometimes interspersed with annual formations with [Cerastium semidecandrum], [Vicia lathyroides], [Silene conica], [Phleum arenarium], [Petrorhagia prolifera], [Arenaria serpyllifolia], [Sedum acre]. Dunal formations can be characterized by conjunction of this code with those of unit 64.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 91, 92, 93; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 151-153; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.4.2, 383; Duvigneaud, 1985; Parent, 1986; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 201; Julve, 1993: 26-27; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.4.1; Opermanis y al., 1997: 56).');
