    'Low to medium-tall shrub formations of the mediterranean zone of North Africa, characteristic of coastal and near-coastal regions of Morocco, Algeria, Tunisia, Cyrenaica, and of the lower slopes of near-Mediterranean North African mountains, within the potential range of lowland evergreen oak forests. Mostly developed on limestones and akin, in their species composition, to western Mediterranean mesomediterranean garrigues of unit 32.4, they can also colonize other substrates, and often comprise, even on limestones, a number of species typical, on the north side of the Mediterranean, of siliceous terrain as well as a proeminent admixture of thermomediterranean elements. [Rosmarinus officinalis] is the most common dominant; other dominants include [Globularia alypum], [Chamaerops humilis] (unit 32.24), [Teucrium polium]. Often conspicuous elements comprise [Lavandula dentata], [Lavandula multifida], [Asparagus spp.], [Calycotome intermedia], [Cistus clusii], [Ephedra spp.], [Helianthemum spp.], [Micromeria nervosa], [Helichrysum rupestre], [Osyris alba], [Thymelaea spp.], [Ebenus pinnata]. Some communities of the shores of the Sea of Alboran are related to the Iberian communities of unit 32.28.', '(Knapp, 1973: 485-486; Zohary, 1973: 85; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 92). ');
