    'Dwarf heaths dominated by [Empetrum hermaphroditum] and [Vaccinium uliginosum], with [Arctostaphylos alpinus], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], lycopodes ([Huperzia selago], [Diphasiastrum alpinum]), mosses ([Barbilophozia lycopodioides], [Hylocomium splendens], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Rhythidiadelphus triquetrus]) and lichens ([Cetraria islandica], [Cladonia arbuscula], [Cladonia rangiferina], [Cladonia stellaris], [Cladonia gracilis], [Peltigera aphthosa]) of the subalpine belt of the Alps, the Carpathians, the Dinarides, the Pyrenees, the Central Massif, the Sudeten, the Jura, the Northern Apennines, characteristic of relatively windswept, snow-free stations, in frost-exposure situations that are, however, less extreme than those prevailing where communities of unit 31.41 dominate. Unlike the formations of 31.41, those of 31.44 are clearly two-layered.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974: 590; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 76-80; Gruber, 1978; Gimingham y al., 1979; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 102, 209; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992b; Pott, 1992: 329; Coldea, 1991: 384; Grabherr, 1993d: 454-456; Wojtun y al., 1998).');
    'Alpine and high-montane heaths of the highlands and islands of Scotland and, very locally, of the Lake District and of Ireland, alpine and lowland boreal heaths of Iceland, alpine heaths of boreal mountains, in particular of the mountains of Scandinavia, of the Urals, of the mountains of Siberia, alpine heaths of Far Eastern mountains at, or just south of, the limits of the boreal zone, with [Juniperus nana], [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Arctostaphylos alpinus], [Phyllodoce caerulea], [Betula nana] and elements of alpine flora.', '(Steindorsson, 1966; Hadac, 1972, 1985a; Ratcliffe, 1977a, 1977b, 1977c, 1980; Gimingham y al., 1979; Bliss, 1979; Specht, 1979d; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Noirfalise, 1987; Lancaster, 1989; Rodwell, 1991b; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Prostrate alpine and high-montane [Calluna vulgaris] or [Vaccinium myrtillus] heaths of windswept summits and ridges, with little snow cover, of the Highlands, the Inner Hebrides and, very locally, of the uplands of Ireland, England and Wales, with [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Arctostaphylos alpinus].', '(Rodwell, 1991b: units H13, H14, H17, H20). ');
    'Dwarf, prostrate, matted, wind-clipped, low-alpine [Calluna vulgaris] heaths, often with lichen mats, of windswept summits, ridges and mountain passes exposed to cold, continental climates, in the Highlands of Scotland, particularly the east-central Highlands, with very few fragmentary outposts in isolated upland areas of England and Wales, with [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Empetrum hermaphroditum].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: units B2a, B2b, B2c; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H13).');
    'Prostrate, wind-clipped, open, low-alpine [Calluna vulgaris] heaths of moderate to fairly high altitude windswept plateaux and ridges of the northwest Highlands of Scotland, with outposts in the Grampians, descending locally to lower altitudes on Skye, with an abundance of [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], and with [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Arctostaphylos alpinus],
[Arctostaphylos uva-ursi].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B2d [p.]; Noirfalise, 1987; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H14).');
    'Prostrate, open, low-alpine [Calluna vulgaris]  heaths of windswept ridges and crests of the northwest Highlands of Scotland, generally at slightly higher altitudes than those of unit 31.4512, though also extending locally to low altitudes, in particular, along the northern Scottish coast, with [Arctostaphylos alpinus], [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], 
[Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Empetrum nigrum], [Erica cinerea], sometimes [Salix herbacea]; lichens are often prominent.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B2d [p.]; Noirfalise, 1987; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H17).');
    'Oro-Mediterranean and montane hedgehog-heaths of other Iberian ranges and of southern France. ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Archiloque y al., 1969; Polunin and Smythies, 1973; Ozenda, 1975, 1985; Girerd, 1978; Ozenda y al., 1979; Izco, 1979; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Quézel, 1981b; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Dupias, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
