    '[Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [phoenicea]-dominated formations occupying steep rocky slopes of the meso-Mediterranean and, locally, thermo-Mediterranean or lower supra-Mediterranean zones, particularly developed on crests and spurs of the mountains bordering the Ebro depression, in calcareous mountains of Valencia, in the southwestern Alps and Provence, in Sardinia, in Sicily, in Puglia, in southern Greece, in North Africa. Remarkable, generally uncommon, stands of old, tall trees may take on an almost woodland appearance.  ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 278, 285-289; Rechinger, 1951; Bolos and Molinier, 1958; Bolos y al., 1970; Horvat y al., 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1974a; Quézel, 1981b; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Tomaselli, 1981b; Chiappini, 1985a, 1985b; Gamisans, 1985; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Viney, 1994: 8; Prpic, 1996: 67; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 80).');
    '[Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [lycia]-dominated formations of coastal sands, alluvions and abrupt shores. Many are dunal and can be coded under unit 16.27. ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Bolos and Molinier, 1958; Bolos y al., 1970; Horvat y al., 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1974a; Quézel, 1981b; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Tomaselli, 1981b; Chiappini, 1985a, 1985b; Gamisans, 1985; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 80, 92).');
    'Low shrub formations with pronounced Mediterranean affinities formed as a degradation stage of thermophile deciduous forests ([Quercion pubescentis], [Ostryo-Carpinion]) or sometimes of [Quercus rotundifolia] forests in the supra-Mediterranean belt of the Mediterranean basin. Included here are only those formations that are characteristic of the supra-Mediterranean level; formations, particularly of the lower supra-Mediterranean, that are closely related to meso-Mediterranean communities have been included under units 32.4 and 32.5. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1953; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Archiloque y al., 1969; Braun-Blanquet and Braun-Blanquet, 1971; Bonin, 1971; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Ozenda, 1975, 1981, 1985; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Dupias, 1985; Fernandez Gonzalez, 1986).');
    'Montane formations dominated by [Lavandula angustifolia] ("[Lavandula vera]") with [Genista cinerea] ssp. [cinerea], [Buxus sempervirens] (both sometimes co-dominant), [Astragalus purpureus], [Onobrychis supina], [Satureja montana], [Artemisia alba], [Catananche caerulea], [Aphyllanthes monspeliensis], [Thymus vulgaris] characteristic of great surfaces of the supra-Mediterranean level of southwestern Alps of France, also occurring on the southern flanks of the Pyrenees in northern Spain. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1953; Archiloque y al., 1969; Braun-Blanquet and Braun-Blanquet, 1971; Bonin, 1971; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Dupias, 1985).');
    'Supra-Mediterranean garrigues or grasslands of the southwestern Alps, Haute Provence, the southern Central Massif, the CorbiŠres and the eastern Pyrenees dominated by [Genista cinerea] ssp. [cinerea], including the broom-rich facies of the French lavender garrigues and the White Quercy broom-fields.  ', '(Duvigneaud, 1953; Archiloque y al., 1969; Braun-Blanquet and Braun-Blanquet, 1971; Bonin, 1971; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Becker y al., 1982; Dupias, 1985).');
    'Low frutescent or suffrutescent formations of the supra-Mediterranean levels of the Iberian Meseta and its surrounding mountains and of northern Spain and southern France, rich in small labiate shrubs of genera [Thymus], [Teucrium], [Salvia], [Satureja], [Sideritis], [Lavandula], accompanied by leguminous shrubs ([Genista scorpius], [Genista pilosa], [Genista pseudopilosa], [Genista cinerea] ssp. [speciosa], [Coronilla minima], [Dorycnium pentaphyllum] ssp. [pentaphyllum]) and various grasses ([Stipa spp.], [Brachypodium spp.]). In the north they often have an important, sometimes predominant, grass element and their impoverished shrub component is sometimes reduced to an almost monospecific [Thymus] formation; southwards, they become progressively more dominated by a richer constellation of shrub species. ', '(Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Dupias, 1985). ');
    'Supra-Mediterranean dwarf-shrub formations of the Iberian Meseta, its surrounding mountains, northern Spain and southern France, dominated by labiate shrubs or subshrubs of genera [Thymus] ([Thymus serpolifolium], [Thymus vulgaris], [Thymus loscosii], [Thymus mastigophorus]), [Teucrium] ([Teucrium aureum], [Teucrium aragonense], [Teucrium gnaphalodes], [Teucrium polium]), [Salvia] ([Salvia lavandulifolia], [Salvia phlomoides]), [Satureja] ([Satureja montana]), [Sideritis] ([Sideritis incana]), [Lavandula] ([Lavandula angustifolia], [Lavandula lanata], [Lavandula latifolia]), often constituting a species-rich assemblage, but, mostly in the north, sometimes limited to one or a few species of [Thymus]; associated shrubs often include greenweeds ([Genista spp.]).', '(Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Dupias, 1985; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Loidi Arregui, 1987). ');
