    'Prostrate [Vaccinium myrtillus]-[Empetrum hermaphroditum] heaths, with abundant [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], of fairly exposed slopes and summits at moderate to high altitudes of the northwestern Highlands of Scotland, with scattered representatives in the Grampians, and lower altitude occurrences along the west coast of Scotland and on Skye, with [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Alchemilla alpina], [Carex bigelowii].', '(Rodwell, 1991b: unit H20). ');
    'Subboreal [Calluna vulgaris]-[Vaccinium myrtillus] heaths of windswept summits and ridges of Ireland, with [Empetrum nigrum], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] and sometimes [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Salix herbacea], [Diphasiastrum alpinum] ([Lycopodium alpinum]); they are limited to small surfaces, mostly above 800 metres, with areas of concentrated occurrence in Munster and in Connemarra.', '(Bohn and Cross, 1992).');
    'Low- to very low-growing low alpine and subalpine [Vaccinium myrtillus] heaths of the Highlands of Scotland, Skye, and, locally, the Southern Uplands and northern England, characteristic of somewhat more protected stations with longer snow cover than those of unit 31.451, with [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Cornus suecica], [Carex bigelowii], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum].', '(Rodwell, 1991b: units H19, H22). ');
    'Very low, matted, low alpine heaths of moderately sheltered and snowbound slopes of the Grampians and, more locally, of the northwestern Highlands, with fragmentary outposts in the Southern Uplands and the Lake District, formed by [Vaccinium myrtillus] with [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Empetrum hermaphroditum] and abundant lichens, in particular, [Cladonia arbuscula], [Cladonia uncialis], [Cetraria islandica]. [Carex bigelowii], [Deschampsia flexuosa] and [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] are often abundant.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B3f; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H19).');
    'Low, subalpine heaths of the central and northwestern Highlands, with outposts in the Moffat-Tweedsmuir hills and in the Cheviots, within the Southern Uplands, developed on peaty ground under oceanic climates with prolonged snow cover, formed by [Vaccinium myrtillus] with [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], and sometimes [Vaccinium uliginosum], associated with a moist carpet of bryophytes. [Rubus chamaemorus], [Cornus suecica] and [Carex bigelowii] are characteristic of the species cortŠge.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B3b [p.]; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H22).');
    'Prostrate [Juniperus nana] mats of the Highlands of Scotland, restricted to a limited number of stations on the west side of mountains in the northwest Highlands and on Skye, with [Calluna vulgaris], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Arctostapylos alpina], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Cladonia uncialis], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] and oceanic hepatics.', '(McVean, 1964a: 162-163; McVean, 1964b: 481-482; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit B2d [p.]; Noirfalise, 1987; Rodwell, 1991b: unit H15).');
    'Alpine heaths of the boreal mountains of Scandinavia, with [Juniperus nana], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Vaccinium spp.], [Arctostaphylos alpinus], dwarf [Salix spp.], [Betula nana] and elements of alpine flora.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Open, scattered heaths of the mountains of Fennoscandia with [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Diapensia lapponica], [Arctostaphylos alpinus] and many lichens, occurring in variable species dominance, installed on patches in snow fields swept bare by the wind in winter, often on dry gravel, sometimes on solifluction, and with high insolation. Maritime and continental types can be identified by the lichen cover.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.1.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.1 [p.]).');
    'Heaths of the alpine belt of Fennoscandia, dominated by [Betula nana] and [Empetrum hermaphroditum], with [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Arctostaphylos alpina], [Salix glauca], [Salix lapponum] and a ground layer often rich in lichens, growing on poor, gravelly and sandy soils, with a low pH.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.1.2 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.4 [p.]).');
    'Xerophilous low heaths of the subalpine and lower alpine levels of Fennoscandia dominated by [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Arctostaphylos alpinus], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Betula nana], with a richly developed lichen layer and few vascular plants. [Juncus trifidus] and [Luzula spicata] are also characteristic. There is little or no snow cover.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.1.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.2).');
    'Subalpine and alpine heaths of the mountains of Fennoscandia under rather continental climate, composed of thick (up to 20 cm) lichen carpets, dominated by [Cladonia alpestris]. During periods of drought, lichen carpet often cracks into polygons and mosses and scattered vascular plants appear. Lichen heaths can carpet large areas in lower situations; higher, they are restricted to narrow zones between wind-heaths and snowpatch vegetation. They grow on sand, gravel and stone, under a thin, early thawing snow cover.
', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.1.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.3).');
    'Formations of the 1300-1900 m altitudinal range in the Sierra de Gador, often with [Erinacea anthyllis] or [Ulex parviflorus].  ', '(Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Formations developed in the 800-1400 m altitudinal range of other Baetic and sub-Baetic ranges, often, in the higher mountains, immediately below [Erinacetalia] communities.  ', '(Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Unommon hedgehog-heaths with [Erinacea anthyllis] and [Anthyllis montana], and related cushion plant formations, colonizing windswept stations with skeletal soil of the Mediterranean mountains of northeastern Spain (Montsant, Llaveria, Cardo, Maestrazgo septentrional, Beceite; Montserrat; Bergueda, Solsones).  ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Polunin and Smythies, 1973; Ozenda, 1975, 1985; Ozenda y al., 1979; Izco, 1979; Quézel, 1981b; Noirfalise, 1987; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Mostly supra-Mediterranean hedgehog garrigues and heaths physiognomically dominated by small, hemispherical [Genista spp.].  ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Archiloque y al., 1969; Polunin and Smythies, 1973; Ozenda, 1975, 1985; Girerd, 1978; Ozenda y al., 1979; Izco, 1979; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Quézel, 1981b; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Dupias, 1985; Noirfalise, 1987; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Cushion-heaths dominated by [Genista hispanica] ssp. [occidentalis] or [Genista hystrix] ssp. [legionensis], often with [Erica vagans], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi] ssp. [crassifolia] or [Lithodora diffusa], characteristic of the Pyreneen-Cantabrian system, where they may occur from the collinar to the subalpine level. ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Ozenda, 1975, 1985; Izco, 1979; Quézel, 1981b; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Dupias, 1985; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Heaths dominated by the cushions of [Genista sanabrensis], with [Erica umbellata] and [Calluna vulgaris], occupying crests of southern Galicio-Leonese mountains at about 1800 m (cf. 31.2431).  ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Cushion heaths dominated by [Genista pumila] ssp. [pumila] of windswept plateaux and crests of the Meseta and of the northern and southern Iberian Range.  ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Meseta hedgehog-heaths with [Genista scorpius], rich in cushion-forming small shrubs.  ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Unarmed [Genista pseudopilosa]-dominated hedgehog-heaths with [Erinacea anthyllis] and other cushion plants of the sierras de Alcaraz and Segura.', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    '[Genista lobelii] and [Genista pulchella] hedgehog-heaths of windswept hilltops of southeastern France.', '(Archiloque y al., 1969; Ozenda, 1975, 1985; Girerd, 1978; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Quézel, 1981b).');
    'Local meso- and supra-Mediterranean [Astragalus] formations of the Spanish Meseta.  ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Polunin and Smythies, 1973; Ozenda, 1975, 1985; Ozenda y al., 1979; Izco, 1979; Quézel, 1981b; Noirfalise, 1987; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Supra-Mediterranean [Astragalus granatensis] ssp. [granatensis] ([Astragalus boissieri]) formations of pastoral runs of the left bank of the middle Duero (Soria, Segovia) and of the highlands of Atienza (Guadalajara).  ', '(Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Meso- and supra-Mediterranean hedgehog-heaths with [Astragalus clusii] ([Astragalus tumidus]) of the southern Meseta, from La Mancha to the Baetic hills of eastern Andalusia (Orce, Sagra, Baza, Maria), with [Paronychia aretioides], [Genista pumila] ssp. [mugronensis], [Genista scorpius]. ', '(Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Izco, 1979; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987).');
    'Cushion-forming communities of high altitudes and wind-exposed plateaux of the Balearics, dominated by [Teucrium subspinosum]. ', '(Bolos and Molinier, 1958; Meusel, 1973: 215-218; Rivas-Martinez and Costa, 1987: 496, 499-500, 507; Straka y al., 1987: 1).');
    'Arborescent matorrals of Greece, Anatolia and the Near East, dominated by [Juniperus excelsa] or [Juniperus foetidissima].  ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974; Quézel, 1981b; Tomaselli, 1981b).');
    'Arborescent matorrals of Greece, Anatolia and the Near East, dominated by [Juniperus excelsa], derived from unit 42.A3. ', NULL);
    'Arborescent matorrals of Greece, Anatolia and the Near East, dominated by [Juniperus foetidissima], derived from unit 42.A4. ', NULL);
    'Mediterranean formations dominated by [Juniperus communis].  ', '(Horvat y al., 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1974a; Quézel, 1981b; Tomaselli, 1981b).');
    'Arborescent matorral dominated by [Juniperus drupacea], limited to the Peloponnese and Asia Minor, derived from forests of unit 42.A5. ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973; Polunin, 1980; Sfikas, 1984)');
    'Rare, calciphile [Erica manipuliflora] formations of Puglia and Sicily.  ', NULL);
    '[Erica manipuliflora] formations of Greece and its archipelagoes, Mediterranean Anatolia, Cyprus.  ', '(Sfikas, 1992: 224-227; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 19).');
    'Noncushion formations dominated by [Sarcopoterium spinosum] of the eastern Mediterranean.  ', '(Turland y al., 1993: 7; Viney, 1994: xiii; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 18-19).');
    '[Pistacia lentiscus] -dominated or -rich formations, widespread and abundant in thermo-Mediterranean and coastal meso-Mediterranean zones of the entire Mediterranean basin; locally, similar formations may appear in warm inland meso-Mediterranean areas. Often low and sometimes very open, the lentisc brush can in favourable situations reach a height of several metres, grading into arborescent matorral (unit 32.123). ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 278, 280-285; Knapp, 1973: 484; Gamisans, 1991: 115-119; Turland y al., 1993: 7; Paradis and Piazza, 1993: 243; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 16; Lanfranco, 1999a; Schembri, 1999b).');
    'Thermo-mediterranean formations physiognomically dominated by the brilliantly flowering [Calicotome villosa] or [Calicotome spinosa], widespread in European thermo-mediterranean regions, in the Levant, in particular on sandy plains and in presteppic areas, and in North Africa, notably in semi-arid areas of northeastern Tunisia and northeastern Libya.', '(Zohary, 1973: 153, 540; Knapp, 1973: 486-487; Horvat y al., 1974; Turland y al., 1993: 7; Viney, 1994: xiii).');
    '[Laurus nobilis] thickets of humid or fresh stations of thermo-mediterranean regions, low-growing facies of unit 32.18, noted in particular in Sardinia, Sicily, the Maltese Islands, Campania and Crete.', '(Turland y al., 1993: 7; Lanfranco, 1989: 15; Sfikas, 1992: 272; Lanfranco, 1999a).');
    'Low formations of [Helichrysum] ([Helichrysum italicum] ssp. [microphyllum], [Helichrysum italicum] ssp. [italicum]) with spurges ([Euphorbia pithyusa], [i.a.]), [Pistacia lentiscus], [Camphorosma monspeliaca], [Artemisia densiflora] or [Thymelaea passerina], [Thymelaea hirsuta], [Thymelaea tartonraira] of the immediate vicinity of sea cliffs, forming the transition between cliff vegetations or clifftop phryganas and thermo-Mediterranean brushes; they are particularly characteristic of the large Mediterranean islands.  ', '(Paradis and Piazza, 1993: 238, 243).');
    '[Myrtus communis]-dominated brush. Particularly noteworthy formations occur in the Balearics ([Clematidi-Myrtetum]), in southern Iberia, in Sardinia, in the Aegean, in the eastern Mediterranean coastal regions, in North Africa. Myrtle thickets can in favourable situations reach a height of a few metres, grading into arborescent matorral (unit 32.124). ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 134, 217; Knapp, 1973: 487; Lanfranco, 1989: 24; Turland y al., 1993: 7; Paradis and Piazza, 1993: 243; Viney, 1994: xiii; Hoda y al., 1998: 13).');
    '[Quercus coccifera] thickets of the Mediterranean basin rich in thermo-Mediterranean elements, in particular, [Pistacia lentiscus], [Chamaerops humilis], [Rhamnus lycioides] ssp. [lycioides], [Rhamnus lycioides] ssp. [oleoides], [Asparagus albus], [Asparagus acutifolius], [Bupleurum gibraltarium]. ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Bolos y al., 1970).');
    'Formations of [Quercus coccifera] of southern Portugal, southern and eastern Spain and the Ebro basin.  ', NULL);
    'Rare [Quercus coccifera] formations of Liguria, Corsica, Sardinia and Sicily.  ', NULL);
    'Formations of [Quercus coccifera] of the thermo-Mediterranean zone of Greece and its archipelagoes.', '(Turland y al., 1993: 7).');
    'Formations of [Quercus coccifera] of the thermo-Mediterranean zone of the periphery of the Anatolian plateau. ', '(Zohary, 1973).');
    'Formations of [Quercus coccifera] of the thermo-Mediterranean zone of Cyprus. ', '(Zohary, 1973; Meikle, 1977: 1; Viney, 1994: xiii).');
    'Formations of [Quercus coccifera] of the thermo-Mediterranean zone of the eastern Mediterranean coastal fringe. ', '(Zohary, 1973).');
    'Characteristically supramediterranean garrigues of Italy and the large central Mediterranean islands. In the supra-Mediterranean level of Italy and the large central Mediterranean islands, the substitution stages of the thermophile deciduous forests are mostly grasslands or shrubby grasslands, hedgehog heaths, deciduous shrubs, semimaquis or occasionally embryonic garrigues that differ little from those of the mesomediterranean level. A few formations, in particular with labiates of genera [Thymus], [Teucrium], [Salvia], [Lavandula] and others, with [Helichrysum spp.] or with [Euphorbia spp.], may warrant separate listing under this heading.', '(Pignatti, 1982; Ozenda, 1985). ');
    'Formations of the supramediterranean level and submediterranean areas of the Balkan peninsula dominated by sclerophyllous shrubs or subshrubs.', '(Horvat y al., 1974).');
    'Formations of the supramediterranean level and submediterranean areas of the Balkan peninsula dominated by sclerophyllous shrubs, impoverished irradiations of the communities of units 32.32 and 32.5, in particular unit 32.51. Included are, notably, the [Phillyrea latifolia] and [Quercus coccifera] thickets or scrubs of the middle Struma-Strimon and Mesta-Nestos valleys of Bulgaria, when monodominated by these species, as well as some [Buxus sempervirens]- or [Juniperus oxycedrus]-dominated formations of the supramediterranean [Ostryo-Carpinion aegeicum] region of northern Greece, southern Albania and the southern F.Y.R. of Macedonia; most of the communities that include them also comprise, however, a substantial admixture of deciduous species and thus belong to unit 32.7.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 175; Qosja and Puto, 1985; Bondev, 1991; Vangjeli, 1999).');
    'Formations of the supramediterranean [Ostryo-Carpinion aegeicum] zone of the southern Balkan peninsula, in particular, of northern Greece and the southern  F.Y.R. of Macedonia, dominated by subshrubs associated with supramediterranean dry grassland elements and generally forming a mosa¿c with such grasslands; they include, notably [Satureja montana] grassy, stony scrubs and [Genista nissana] heaths.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 176-177, 265).');
