    'Stands of [Euphorbia dendroides], remarkable tertiary relict of Macaronesian origin; they occur as a facies of the thermo-Mediterranean brushes of the Balearics, Corsica, Sardinia, Sicily, Islas Eolie, Egadi, Pelagi, Pantelleria, Crete, and, very locally, of those of the coasts of northern Catalonia, southeastern France, peninsular Italy and its islands, central Greece, notably on slopes facing the gulf of Corinth, the Peloponnese, the Aegean archipelagoes, Albania and enclaves of the Mediterranean periphery of Anatolia and the Levant. Particularly extensive and robust stands occur in Sicily, Sardinia and Crete where they may extend to relatively high altitudes. Very local formations in Mediterranean North Africa occupy the steep rocky slopes of some coastal capes and isolated inland sites, in Cyrenaica, northern Tunisia (Ichkeul), and in a narrow coastal strip in northern Algeria.', '(Rechinger, 1951; Quézel and Santa, 1963; Bolos y al., 1970; Pignatti, 1972; Zohary, 1973; Knapp, 1973: 487-488; Horvat y al., 1974; Brullo y al., 1977; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Ozenda, 1981; Becker y al., 1982; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Gamisans, 1985; Chiappini, 1985b; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 18; Hoda y al., 1998: 13; Lanfranco, 1999a).');
    'Garrigues invaded and dominated by the high tussocks of [Ampelodesmos mauritanica]; typically thermo-Mediterranean, they also occur extensively in the meso-Mediterranean zone. They are most prevalent on the Tyrrhenian coast of central and southern Italy, in Sicily, in the Mediterranean zone and the less arid parts of the Saharo-Mediterranean transition zone of North Africa. ', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Pignatti and Pedrotti, 1962; Reisigl y al., 1980; Pignatti, 1982; White, 1983).');
    '[Chamaerops humilis]-dominated formations; other thermo-Mediterranean brushes or garrigues rich in the physiognomically important palmetto can be identified by a combination of this code and that of the other appropriate subdivision of unit 32.2. Palmetto brushes are best represented in the coastal areas of southwestern, southern and eastern Iberia, the Balearics, Sicily and its satellite islands and Mediterranean North Africa, with more sporadic occurrences in the Guadalquivir basin, Sardinia, and the Tyrrhenian coasts and islands of peninsular Italy. They are apparently extinct in the wild in the Maltese Islands.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Fenaroli, 1970; Knapp, 1973: 485; Ozenda y al., 1979; Reisigl y al., 1980; Tomaselli, 1981a, 1981b; Chiappini, 1985b; Noirfalise, 1986; Lanfranco, 1989: 45).');
    'Shrub formations constituting, with the halonitrophilous scrubs (unit 15.724) and the localized gypsum scrubs (unit 15.93), much of the natural and seminatural vegetation of the arid zone of southeastern Spain (Almeria, Murcia, Alicante), a highly distinctive region of unique climatological, biological and landscape character within Europe, extremely rich in African and endemic species. Several of the most remarkable formations remain in only a few undisturbed localities and are gravely at risk. Similar formations occur in the upper arid (Mediterranean arid) zone of North Africa; they are included in unit 32.D11. Outposts of these communities also exist in Sicily, the Egadi islands, the Pelagie islands, the Maltese Islands and Pantelleria.', '(Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Brullo y al., 1977; Freitag, 1971; Rivas-Martinez, 1974a; Ozenda y al., 1979; Quézel, 1981a: 89; Pignatti, 1982; Ferre Bueno y al., 1985; Noirfalise, 1986; Le Houérou, 1986; Alcaraz Ariza and Peinado Lorca, 1987).');
    'Communities dominated by hummocks of the lotus tree [Ziziphus lotus], usually with [Lycium intricatum], [Withania frutescens], [Asparagus albus], [Asparagus stipularis], [Rhamnus lycioides], of the arid Iberian Southeast. Very tall stands can be coded as unit 32.17.  ', '(Freitag, 1971; Rivas-Martinez, 1974a; Quézel, 1981b; Alcaraz Ariza and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1993: 364-367).');
    '[Ziziphus lotus] formations of western Sicily.  ', '(Pignatti, 1982). ');
    'Xerophytic scrubs and thickets of the Cape Verde Islands dominated by succulents, in particular the candalabra-shaped pachycaul dendroid [Euphorbia tuckeyana], accompanied by the pachycaul candelabra bugloss [Echium hypertropicum], and the small tree or shrub [Sideroxylon marmulano], with the lianas [Periploca laevigata] and [Sarcostema daltonii]. The three arborescent componants are in severe regression or in danger of extinction.', '(Grandvaux Barbosa, 1968a: 95; Knapp, 1973: 581; White, 1983: 251).');
    'Communities of the western Mediterraneo-Saharan transition zone, under strong Atlantic influence, dominated by tall cactiform or pachycaul dendroid spurges of genus [Euphorbia].', '(Gaussen y al., 1969: 19, 26; Herbauts, 1973: 328-329; Knapp, 1973: 409, 487; White, 1983: 228-229; Ozenda, 1991: 82-83, 332, 563-565).');
    'Communities of the mediterraneo-Saharan transition steppes and semideserts zone of northwestern Morocco dominated by the cactiform spurge [Euphorbia resinifera], often alone or with very scattered participation of larger woody plants, such as [Acacia gummifera], [Ceratonia siliqua], [Chamaerops humulis], [Olea europea], [Pistachia lentiscus], [Tetraclinis articulata], [Ziziphus lotus], with a cortŠge of smaller species composed typically of Mediterranean genera, located on shallow, often calcareous lithosols in areas north of the Great Atlas, mainly on the lower slopes of the western Middle Atlas.', '(Knapp, 1973: 487; White, 1983: 228; Ozenda, 1991: 563).');
    'Communities of the mediterraneo-Saharan transition steppes and semideserts zone of northwestern Morocco dominated by the cactiform spurge [Euphorbia officinarum] var. [beaumierana], distributed mostly in the coastal [Argania] woodland zone, extending from 100 km south of Essaouira to the Souss, slightly south of Agadir, typically occupying steep, rocky slopes leading to the sea, or windswept, stony cliff tops, often with a few scattered, low, shrubby, windclipped woody species, in particular, [Acacia gummifera], [Argania spinosa], [Ceratonia siliqua], [Maytenis senegalensis], [Olea europea], [Phillyrea angustifolia], [Pistachia lentiscus], and sometimes the 2-metre tall soft-stemmed pachycaulous [Aeolium arboreum] and [Sonchus pinnatifidus], as well as climbers, [Periploca laevigata], succulent-stemmed [Senecio anteuphorbium], and small shrubs, [Helianthemum canariense], [Lavandula dentata], [Lavandula maroccana], [Lavandula multifida], [Withania fruticans].', '(Knapp, 1973: 409; White, 1983: 228; Ozenda, 1991: 563; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 87-88).');
    'Communities of cliffs and ravines of the southern Moroccan coasts dominated by the pachycaul tree spurge [Euphorbia obtusifolia] ssp. [regis-jubae], characteristic of the zone of transition between mediterranean formations and coastal desert communities of the Atlantic Sahara, distributed between Safi and the western Anti-Atlas.', '(Knapp, 1973: 409; White, 1983: 228; Ozenda, 1991: 564-565, Plate 18).');
    'Communities of the mediterraneo-Saharan transition steppes and semideserts zone of northwestern Morocco dominated by the cactiform spurge [Euphorbia echinus], mostly distributed in the coastlands, rarer in the interior, characteristic of the southern part of the mediterraneo-Saharan transition region, south of the Oued Souss, extending far south in the coastal desert belt, south to Cap Blanc in Mauritania, most common between the Oued Noun and the Oued Dra, occupying rocky hillsides and pebbly or gravelly lower slopes, on permeable soils.', '(Knapp, 1973: 409, 487; White, 1983: 228-229; Ozenda, 1991: 332, 563, Plate 18).');
    'Communities of forbs, grasses and shrubs resulting from over-browsing and over-grazing of garrigues and consisting of unpalatable plants, in particular Liliaceae ([Asphodelus], [Urginea]), thistles ([Carthamus], [Carlina], [Centaurea], [Onopordum]), [Phlomis], [Ferula], especially characteristic of the more arid areas of the Mediterranean basin.  ', '(Le Houérou, 1986; Horvat y al., 1974; Lanfranco, 1999a; Schembri, 1999b).');
    'Communities of degraded terrains of the Mediterranean basin overwhelmingly dominated by facies-forming Liliaceae of genus [Asphodelus].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 45; Horvat y al., 1974: 97; Sfikas, 1992: 308; Hoda y al., 1998: 11; Lanfranco, 1999a; Schembri, 1999b).');
    'Communities of degraded terrains of the Mediterranean basin overwhelmingly dominated by facies-forming thistles, notably of genera [Carthamus], [Carlina], [Centaurea], [Onopordum], [Notobasis], [Galactites].', '(Le Houérou, 1986; Lanfranco, 1999a; Schembri, 1999b).');
    'Communities of degraded terrains of the Mediterranean basin overwhelmingly dominated by facies-forming tall labiates of genus [Phlomis].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 156; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 19; Hoda y al., 1998: 11).');
    'Communities of degraded terrains of the Mediterranean basin dominated by facies-forming tall, robust umbellifers of genus [Ferula].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 140).');
    'Thickets and brushes of Spanish broom, [Spartium junceum], widespread in mediterranean and sub-mediterranean areas of the Mediterranean basin, particularly in western Mediterranean Europe and North Africa.', '(Knapp, 1973: 486-487).');
    'Shrubby formations, often low, of the meso- and occasionally supra-Mediterranean zones of the Adriatic lowlands of the Balkan peninsula from Istria to southern Albania. Included here are all sclerophyllous formations, regardless of substrate, except high maquis with [Erica arborea] and [Arbutus spp.], listed in unit 32.3. The subdivisions proposed are based on the physiognomically most significant dominants; codominance can be indicated by use of multiple codes.  ', '(Horvat y al., 1974; Reisigl y al., 1980; Hoda y al., 1998: 13-14).');
    'Heaths of Iceland dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], usually associated with [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Salix herbacea], [Rubus saxatilis], [Polygonum viviparum], [Galium boreale], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Carex bigelowii], [Luzula multiflora], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Equisetum pratense] and, often, with [Thymus praecox] ssp. [arcticus], [Galium normanii], [Platanthera hyperborea], [Dactylorhiza islandica], [Festuca vivipara], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Agrostis tenuis]. The mucinal layer is poorly to moderately developed, with a total cover ranging between 0 and 40%. [Rhacomitrium canescens], [Lophozia sudetica], [Ptilidium ciliare], [Drepanocladus uncinatus], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Rhytidiadelphus squarrosus], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus] are the most common species. They are mostly limited to the lowlands, best developed in the central northern lowlands, apparently absent from parts of the northwestern peninsula, often developed on loess deposits.', '(Steindorsson, 1966: 61-62, 93, table XX; Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 65; Hadac, 1972: 361-365; Hadac, 1985a: 132-133; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.1.3a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.2b).');
    'Heaths of Spitzbergen dominated by [Cassiope tetragona], with [Dryas octopetala] var. [minor], [Carex rupestris], [Silene acaulis] var. [arctica], [Drepanocladus uncinatus].', '(Hadac, 1989: 164-165).');
    'Heaths of Greenland dominated by [Cassiope tetragona], with [Dryas octopetala], [Carex bigelowii], [Silene acaulis], [Vaccinium uliginosum] ssp. [microphyllum], [Phyllodoce caerulea], [Drepanocladus uncinatus].', '(Hadac, 1989: 165; Gensbol, 1996).');
    'Formations of [Bruckenthalia spiculifolia], often accompanied by [Juniperus nana], [Vaccinium myrtillus] and herbaceous alpine grassland species, occupying damp, noncalcareous substrates of high mountains of the Balkan peninsula and northern Anatolia.', '(Horvat y al., 1974; Davis, 1978; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Strid, 1989; Sanda and Popescu, 1991; Bondev, 1991).');
    '[Bruckenthalia spiculifolia] heaths of the alpine and subalpine belts of the Vitosha, the Rila, the Pirin, the Slovianka, the Rhodopes, the Vrondous, the Menikion and the Pangeon.', '(Strid, 1989; Bondev, 1991).');
    '[Bruckenthalia spiculifolia] formations of the subalpine, alpine and  locally, montane, belts of the Pelagonian mountains, south to the Varnous, the Vitsi, the Piperitsa, the Voras, the Pinovon, the Tzena, of the Moeso-Macedonian mountains south to the Kerkini (Belles range), and of the Pieria in the northern Thessalian mountains.

', '(Horvat y al., 1974; Strid, 1989; Bondev, 1991).');
