    'Low, open, heaths of the western and northern coasts of arctic Scandinavia developed on sandy, calcareous soils in exposed coastal climates, dominated by [Dryas octopetala] and [Empetrum hermaphroditum], accompanied by short sedges and grasses, usually without a mucinal layer.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 1.2.3.2a; Påhlsson, 1994: 4.1.4.4).');
    '[Dryas octopetala]-dominated heaths of Iceland. [Empetrum hermaphroditum] often dominates with the [Dryas]. Other accompaniers may include [Calluna vulgaris], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Salix callicarpaea] ([Salix arctica]), [Thymus arcticus], [Silene acaulis], [Armeria maritima], [Cerastium alpinum], [Draba incana], [Rhinanthus minor], [Euphrasia frigida], [Parnassia palustris], [Tofieldia pusilla], [Kobresia myosuroides], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex capillaris], [Carex glacialis], [Carex rupestris], [Carex vaginata], [Festuca vivipara], [Festuca richardsonii], [Luzula multiflora], [Luzula spicata], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Botrychium lunaria], [Equisetum pratense], [Equisetum boreale]. The moss layer can be variously developed and include, in particular, [Rhacomitrium canescens], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Drepanocladus uncinatus]. [Dryas] heaths occupy a variety of substrates, in particular, loess deposits, gravels, moraines, sands, in mostly somewhat wind-exposed situations.', '(Steindorsson, 1966: 60-61, 63-64, tables XXII, XXVII; Steindorsson, 1967: 76, table XXXVII; Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 67, 68-79, 71; Hadac, 1985a: 139-141; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.3.2b [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.3.2a).');
    'Widespread neutrophilous to calciphilous, species-rich thorny scrub and seminatural hedge communities of the British Isles, with [Crataegus monogyna], [Hedera helix], [Rubus spp.], [Prunus spinosa], [Fraxinus excelsior].  Included are the [Hedera helix]-[Urtica dioica], [Mercurialis perennis] and [Brachypodium sylvaticum] subcommunities of the [Crataegus monogyna]-[Hedera helix] scrub.', '(Rodwell, 1991a: units W21a, W21b, W21c).');
    'Species-rich communities mostly of southeastern England, characterized by the abundance of [Viburnum lantana], [Ligustrum vulgare], [Cornus sanguinea], [Tamus communis] and [Clematis vitalba], the frequency of [Taxus baccata] saplings and [Juniperus communis].', '(Rodwell, 1991a: unit W21d).');
