    'Retama fields formed in coastal regions of Egypt, and on maritime sands of Tunisia, Algeria and Morocco, by [Lygos raetam] ssp. [duraiei], distributed from Egypt to Algeria. Fields of [Lygos raetam] ssp. [raetam] of the deserts, subdeserts and mediterraneo-Saharan steppes of North Africa are in units 71 and 32.D.', '(Knapp, 1973: 497; Zohary, 1973: 328, 393; Foucault, 1993b: 270-271; Pignatti, 1993: 387; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 92).');
    'Retama fields formed on stabilized dunes and in thermo-mediterranean bathas of  the Levant by [Lygos raetam] ssp. [sarcocarpa]. Fields of [Lygos raetam] ssp. [raetam] of transition zone bathas, subdesert steppes and deserts of the same regions are in units 32.D and 71.', '(Zohary, 1973: 328, 393, 447, 538; Randall, 1993: 468). ');
    'Thermomediterranean formations of volcanic rocks and sands of Stromboli and Vulcano dominated by the very tall Eolian endemic broom [Cytisus aeolicus], with the Tyrrhenian insular endemic [Centaurea aeolica]. ', '(Pignatti, 1982: 632). ');
    'Thermomediterranean formations dominated by the Tyrrhenian endemic [Genista ephedroidres], often on steep rocky substrates, restricted to a few localities on western and northern Sardinian headlands, on the island of Zannone, Circeo National Park (Latium), on the north coast of Sicily, on the Eolian and Ponsian islands and along the Cilento coast (Campania).', '(Pignatti, 1982: 640, 643; Padula, 1985: 99). ');
