    'Western Mediterranean formations, for the most part limited to the lower meso-mediterranean and thermo-mediterranean zones of the western Iberian peninsula, with outposts in western Morocco, dominated by gorse ([Ulex spp.], [Stauracanthus spp.]) of thermo-Mediterranean affinities, or by the spiny, globular broom [Genista hirsuta], accompanied by a cortŠge of plants characteristic of the meso- and thermo-mediterranean cistus maquis (32.33), thermo-mediterranean brushes (32.21) or, occasionally, meso-mediterranean garrigues (32.4). Other thermo-mediterranean gorse formations will be found among the more specialized extreme southern Iberian endemic communities listed under 32.25, 32.28, 32.29, 32.2A, 32.2B and 32.2C. ', '(Braun-Blanquet y al., 1956; Braun-Blanquet y al., 1964a; Rivas Goday and Rivas-Martinez, 1968; Rivas-Martinez, 1979).');
    '[Ulex argenteus] ssp. [argenteus]-dominated or -rich formations of low slopes of the Serra da Monchique and neighbouring areas of Algarve and southwest Alentejo, usually with [Cistus ladanifer]. The gorse is endemic to the area; the communities inhabited by its two equally restricted relatives, [Ulex argenteus] ssp. [subsericeus] and [Ulex argenteus] ssp. [erinaceus] are listed under units 32.2A3, 32.2B4 and 32.2563. ', NULL);
    'Cushion-heaths of [Ulex densus] formed in substitution stages of the [Melico-Cocciferetum] on dry, calcareous coastal hills of the Tejo and Estremadura regions of central-western Portugal; the gorse is endemic to the area. ', NULL);
    'Formations of the western Sierra Morena (Sierra de Aracena, Badajos region, southeastern Portugal) dominated by [Ulex eriocladus], developed mostly in the meso-Mediterranean zone and locally in contact with [Erica umbellata] heaths; the gorse is endemic to the area.  ', NULL);
    '[Ulex parviflorus] ssp. [parviflorus]-dominated formations of central-western Portugal, southern and eastern Spain and southern France and coastal North Africa, locally distributed on calcareous or siliceous substrates of the thermo-Mediterranean and lower meso-Mediterranean zones, occasionally ascending to higher elevations. Communities including the related [Ulex parviflorus] ssp. [willkommii], [Ulex baeticus] and [Ulex australis] are listed under units 32.28, 32.2A and 32.2C, clearly meso-Mediterranean formations under unit 32.4H.', NULL);
    '[Stauracanthus genistoides] ssp. [spectabilis]-dominated formations; the gorse has a very restricted distribution on the coast of Alentejo and in Morocco. ', NULL);
    '[Stauracanthus genistoides] ssp. [spectabilis]-dominated formations of the coast of Alentejo, limited to a very few stations. ', NULL);
    '[Stauracanthus genistoides] ssp. [spectabilis]-dominated formations of northwestern Morocco, with [Teline linifolia], limited to the region of Rabat on dry decalcified sands, in association with open [Quercus suber] woods.', '(Knapp, 1973: 485)');
    '[Astragalus thracicus] phryganas of the Thracian steppe zone of northeastern Greece and Turkey-in-Europe, with local representatives in the xerothermic oak belt of the hills and rim of the Northern Thracian plain (East Rumelian plain) of southeastern Bulgaria, in particular, in the Bakadzicita hills of the Yambol Tundzja basin and in the foothills of the eastern Rhodopes.', '(Stojanov, 1936; Ozenda, 1954; Horvat y al., 1974: 119, 351; Strid, 1989: 466; Bondev, 1991: unit 125t; Meshinev y al., 1993: 129).');
    'Cushion-forming thermo-Mediterranean summer-deciduous, often thorny, sclerophyllous formations of Mediterranean areas of the Levant, north and west to the Gulf of Alexandrette, with local outposts in the Gulf of Antalaya and in Cyprus; they occupy large areas in the lowlands, ascending locally into the hills and, in Lebanon, to 1300 m in the mountains.', '(Zohary, 1973: 28, 532-541; Meikle, 1977: 4; Quézel, 1981b: 116).');
    'Cushion-forming thermo-mediterranean summer-deciduous, often thorny, sclerophyllous formations of Cyprus, mostly characteristic of the central plains, of semisteppic batha appearance, outpost of the continental formations of units 33.C2 to 33.C5, and like them of Irano-Turanian affinities, formed by [Sarcopoterium spinosum], [Thymus capitatus] ([Coridothymus capitatus]), [Lithodora hispidula] ([Lithospermum hispidulum]), [Onosma fruticosum], [Galium suberosum].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 274-277; Zohary, 1973: 28, 153-154, 537, 538; Meikle, 1977: 4; Sfikas, 1992: 240; Viney, 1994: xiii).');
    'Phryganas or bathas of Cyprus dominated by [Sarcopoterium spinosum], variously accompanied by [Thymus capitatus] ([Coridothymus capitatus]), [Lithodora hispidula] ([Lithospermum hispidulum]), [Galium suberosum], [Noaea mucronata], [Cistus salviifolius], [Cistus creticus], [Fumana thymifolia], [Salvia verbenacea], [Helichrysum rupicolum], [Pistacia lentiscus].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 274-277; Zohary, 1973: 154, 537; Meikle, 1977: 4; Viney, 1994: xiii).');
    'Phryganas or bathas of Cyprus dominated by cushions of [Thymus capitatus] ([Coridothymus capitatus]), accompanied by [Sarcopoterium spinosum], [Galium suberosum], [Noaea mucronata], [Fumana thymifolia], [Asphodelus microcarpus], [Hyparrhenia hirta].', '(Zohary, 1973: 154, 538; Meikle, 1977: 4).');
    'Phryganas or bathas of Cyprus dominated by Boraginaceae, in particular, [Lithodora hispidula] ([Lithospermum hispidulum]) or [Onosma fruticosum].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 274).');
    'Thorny cushion formations of the Levant and southern Anatolia dominated by [Sarcopoterium spinosum] on calcareous substrates, including terra rossa, rendzina or sand, typically on hills near the coast; there is often a significant participation of annuals.', '(Zohary, 1973: 534-537).');
    'Cushion formations of the Levant and southern Anatolia dominated by [Thymus capitatus] ([Coridothymus capitatus]), typically forming a sparse plant cover poor in annuals, on calcareous substrates.', '(Zohary, 1973: 153, 537-538).');
    'Cushion formations of the Levant dominated by labiates, in particular, [Salvia triloba] or [Satureja thymbra], typically developed on calcareous rocky substrates and red soils.', '(Zohary, 1973: 540-541).');
    '[Lithospermum hispidulum]-dominated phryganas of southeastern Anatolia and the Levant.  ', NULL);
    'Thermo-mediterranean summer-deciduous, mostly thorny cushion formations of North Africa, scattered in the semiarid and arid zones, particularly on the margins of the Sahara, mostly dominated by [Sarcopoterium spinosum]. They are prevalent, in particular, in Cyrenaica, with [Sarcopoterium spinosum], [Thymus capitatus] ([Coridothymus capitatus]), [Genista acanthoclada], [Phlomis floccosa], [Ballota pseudo-dictamnus].', '(Quézel, 1967b; Knapp, 1973: 486; Quézel, 1981b: 115; White, 1983: 159).');
    'Primary and secondary steppes, formations dominated by medium or tall perennnial tuft-forming grasses or suffrutescents, with lacunar ground cover, together with their associated therophyte communities; typical formations, with two periods of dormancy, in large part climactic, are characteristic of a steppe belt in continental Central Eurasia and on the western Asian plateaux, with irradiations in the nemoral zone; physiognomically similar formations, although perhaps largely anthropogenic, and mostly with a single period of dormancy, are widespread in the transition zone between the Mediterranean and Saharo-Sindian domaines and occur locally in the Mediterranean zone. By extension, 34 also includes dry thermophilous, mostly zoogenous, grasslands and thermophile forest fringe formations of the lowland, hill and montane altitudinal levels of the nemoral and Mediterranean zones, on mostly calcareous soils, sands, and decomposed rock surfaces.', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Zohary, 1973; Knapp, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Walter, 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1977a; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Brullo, 1985; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Le Houérou, 1986; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Rieley and Page, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Ripley, 1992a).');
    'Semiclosed sand steppes of the Deliblat steppe of the Vojvodina, developed on highly calcareous sands as a transition stage between the [Alysso-Festucetum vaginataea] and the [Chrysopogonetum pannonicum], dominated by the endemic [Festuca wagneri s.s.], with [Festuca rupicola], [Stipa capillata], [Poa bulbosa], [Peucedanum arenarium], [Potentilla cinerea], [Verbascum lychnitis], [Silene otites], [Scabiosa ochroleuca].', '(Soo, 1959: 496; Horvat y al., 1974: 261-264, 298, 300, 302; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a).');
    'Relatively closed, primary or secondary, fescue or feathergrass swards of basophilous, humus- and nutrient-rich, sandy or mixed sand-loessy soils of the Pannonic basin of Hungary, eastern Austria, southern Slovakia and Transylvania, of relatively rare and sporadic occurrence, dominated by [Festuca rupicola], [Stipa joannis], [Stipa pulcherrima], [Carex humilis], [Stipa capillata], [Koeleria macrantha], [Dichanthium ischaemum], or, in some facies, [Chrysopogon gryllus], with [Carex liparocarpos], [Festuca vaginata], [Festuca wagneri] [s.l.], [Agropyron cristatum] ssp. [pectinatum], [Achillea ochroleuca], [Astragalus asper], [Astragalus onobrychis], [Astragalus exscapus], [Astragalus austriacus], [Oxytropis pilosa], [Potentilla cinerea], [Potentilla arenaria], [Linum austriacum], [Salvia nemorosa], [Alyssum tortuosum], [Alyssum montanum] ssp. [gmelinii], [Silene parviflora], [Silene viscosa], [Dianthus giganteiformis] ssp. [pontederae], [Asperula cynanchica], [Galium glaucum], [Galium verum],  [Pulsatilla grandis], [Pulsatilla nigricans], [Lotus corniculatus], [Onosma arenaria] ssp. [pseudoarenaria], [Euphorbia cyparissias], [Euphorbia nicaeensis] ssp. [glareosa] ([Euphorbia glareosa], [Euphorbia pannonica]), [Artemisia alba], [Artemisia campestris], [Artemisia laciniata], [Artemisia pancicii], [Thymus glabrescens], [Daphne cneorum], [Cytisus ratisbonensis], [Muscari botryoides], [Muscari comosum], [Iris variegata], [Iris humilis] ssp. [arenaria], [Colchicum arenarium], [Ophrys sphegodes], [Anacamptis pyramidalis], [Botrychium lunaria].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1959, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szabo y al., 1985; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 438-440; Kovacs-Lang y al., 1995).');
    'Fescue pastures of sandy alluvial soils of the Pannonic basin, distributed in the Austrian Seewinkel, the Hungarian plains, the Banat, the Crisana and Transylvania, forming a mosaic with saline pusztas (unit 15.A11) and water-edge vegetation to constitute the puszta landscape, formed by [Festuca pseudovina], [Potentilla arenaria], [Cynodon dactylon], [Carex stenophylla] and, in some stands, [Festuca valesiaca], with [Fragaria viridis], [Cerastium semidecandrum], [Euphorbia seguierana], [Eryngium campestre], [Thymus glabrescens], [Poa bulbosa].', '(Soo, 1957a, 1959, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szabo y al., 1985; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a; Kovacs-Lang y al., 1995).');
    'Formations dominated by medium or tall perennnial tuft-forming grasses or suffrutescents, with lacunar ground cover, together with their associated therophyte communities developed on moving or fixed sands within the range of the Ponto-Sarmatic steppes (unit 34.92) and the regions of influence of their communities. Most of these formations are associated with inland dune systems and define subdivisions of habitats listed under units 64.72 and 64.73.

', '(Vicherek, 1972; Walter, 1974: 185-186; Horvat y al., 1974: 344-345; Boscaiu, 1975; Sanda y al., 1980; Bondev, 1991: unit 147 [p.]; Donita, 1992: units 35 L12, L12a; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 70-71; Donita and Ivan, 1992a, 1992b: 96-98; Sanda y al., 1992: 131; Hanganu y al., 1994: 34-35).');
    'Sand steppes of the plains of the western Black Sea, west of the Dniester, and of the basin of the lower Danube. Most of the formations listed are associated with inland dune systems and define subdivisions of habitats listed under unit 64.72. Within the steppe region, differences between inland and coastal sand communities are attenuated, so that some of the formations listed here may also occur in coastal grey dunes; communities that are specific to these have, however, not been included in this unit, but only in unit 16.22B.   ', '(Vicherek, 1972; Walter, 1974: 185-186; Horvat y al., 1974: 344-345; Boscaiu, 1975; Sanda y al., 1980; Bondev, 1991: unit 147 [p.]; Donita, 1992: units 35 L12, L12a; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 70-71; Donita and Ivan, 1992a, 1992b: 96-98; Sanda y al., 1992: 131; Hanganu y al., 1994: 34-35).');
    'Therophyte-dominated stages of the first succession phase in the colonisation of western Pontic sands, with a thin, low cover of mostly ephemereal, early-blooming annuals of small stature.', '(Popescu and Sanda, 1976; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda y al., 1987; Bondev, 1991: unit 147 [p.]; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 71; Donita and Ivan, 1992b: 96-98).');
    'Therophyte stages of the first succession phase in the colonisation of western Pontic sands, dominated by annual grasses, [Bromus tectorum], [Apera spica-venti] ([Apera maritima]), [Secale sylvestre], with [Cynodon dactylon], [Polygonum arenarium], [Euphorbia seguierana], [Centaurea arenaria], [Alyssum desertorum], [Silene conica], [Syrenia montana], [Convolvulus persicus], [Koeleria glauca], [Scabiosa argentea].', '(Paun y al., 1972; Mititelu y al., 1973; Popescu and Sanda, 1976; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda y al., 1987; Bondev, 1991: unit 147 [p.]; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 71; Donita and Ivan, 1992b: 96-98; Hanganu y al., 1994).');
    'Therophyte stages of the first succession phase in the colonisation of western Pontic sands, dominated by annual forbs, [Plantago arenaria] ([Plantago indica]), [Mollugo cerviana], with [Polygonum arenarium], [Viola kitaibeliana], [Viola hymettia], [Centaurea arenaria], [Achillea ochroleuca], [Syrenia cana], [Silene conica], [Bromus tectorum], [Apera spica-venti].', '(Buia and Paun, 1964; Popescu and Sanda, 1976, 1987; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda y al., 1987; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 71; Sanda y al., 1992: 131).');
    'Communities of the Scottish Central Highlands, extensive in the Cairngorms where they are often at the upper limit of vegetation, of the Scandinavian mountains and of lowland and lower alpine areas of Iceland, occupying porous substrates, dominated by [Juncus trifidus], and [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], which often forms extensive carpets among the [Juncus] tufts; [Carex bigelowii] is generally present and there is a lichen-rich species cortŠge that includes, in particular, [Cetraria islandica], [Cladonia sylvatica], [Cladonia uncialis], [Cladonia gracilis], [Cladonia arbuscula].', '(McVean, 1964c: 507-508; Hadac, 1972: 353; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit C7; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.1.5; Rodwell, 1992: unit U9a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.5).');
    '[Juncus trifidus] and [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum]-dominated communities, rich in [Carex bigelowii] and with a participation of [Salix herbacea], of the Scottish Highlands and the mountains of Scandinavia, occupying mostly south-facing slopes, typically on sandy-humus soil over gravel, sand or stoney substrates in areas of high snowfall and spring flooding.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit E1e; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.1.5; Rodwell, 1992: unit U9b; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.1.5).');
    '[Nardus stricta] communities developed in areas of prolonged snow cover in the Scandinavian mountains, Iceland, the Faeroe Islands, Scotland, Cumbria, the northern Pennines and northern Wales, with [Carex bigelowii], [Alchemilla alpina], [Agrostis borealis], mosses and lichens.', '(Hadac, 1972: 372-379; Ratcliffe, 1977a, 1980: unit C2b; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.1.2; Hadac, 1985a: 141-143; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Hill, 1990; Rodwell, 1992: unit U7; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.1.2).');
    '[Nardus stricta] communities developed in areas of prolonged snow cover in Scotland, Cumbria, the northern Pennines and northern Wales, with [Carex bigelowii], [Galium saxatile], [Potentilla erecta], [Alchemilla alpina], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Agrostis capillaris], [Festuca ovina], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Diphasiastrum alpinum], [Cladonia uncialis], [Cetraria islandica].', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a, 1980: unit C2b; Hill, 1990; Rodwell, 1992: unit U7).');
    '[Nardus stricta] grasslands developed in areas of prolonged snow cover in the Scandinavian mountains, mostly on relatively acid sandy substrates and in hollows, moist in spring and dessicated in summer, formed by dense or scattered tussocks of matgrass, with an often species-rich cortŠge that includes [Carex bigelowii], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Deschampsia cespitosa], [Agrostis borealis], [Sibbaldia procumbens], [Omalotheca supina] ([Gnaphalium supinum]), [Diphasiastrum alpinum], [Drepanocladus uncinatus], [Polytrichum commune].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.1.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.1.2).');
    '[Nardus stricta] grasslands of Iceland, with [Polygonum viviparum], [Viola palustris], [Alchemilla alpina], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Agrostis capillaris], [Rhacomitrium canescans], [Drepanocladus uncinatus], [Rhytidiadelphus squarrosus].', '(Hadac, 1972: 372-379; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.1.2; Hadac, 1985a: 141-143; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.1.2).');
    '[Nardus stricta] grasslands of boreal affinities of the Faeroe Islands, with [Carex bigelowii] and [Polytrichum norvegicum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.1.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.1.2).');
    'Dense, closed grasslands of the low and middle alpine levels of the Scandinavian mountains dominated by patchy tussocks of [Festuca ovina] or, on the maritime fa¿ade of Norway, of [Festuca vivipara], in alternation with lichen carpets, accompanied by [Juncus trifidus], occupying dry, acid (pH 4-5.5) soils over nutrient-poor bedrock in areas generally without snow cover or flowing groundwater, under relatively cool and dry climates. The species cortŠge includes [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Luzula spicata], [Agrostis mertensi], [Antennaria alpina], [Antennaria dioica], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex rupestris], [Luzula confusa], [Trisetum spicatum], [Silene acaulis], [Solidago virgaurea].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.2.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.2.1).');
    'Grassland communities of the lowlands and lower alpine levels of Iceland and the Faeroe Islands, similar to the fescue grasslands of unit 36.325, with [Festuca vivipara] and [Festuca richardsonii], but without [Festuca ovina] and an accompanying species cortŠge that differs somewhat, including [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Luzula spicata], [Juncus trifidus], [Agrostis canina], [Agrostis capillaris], [Luzula multiflora], [Equisetum pratense], and, in Iceland, [Kobresia myosuroides], [Trisetum spicatum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.2.1a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.2.1a).');
    'Low growing heath grasslands of relatively poor, stoney, porous substrates of the subalpine and low alpine levels of Iceland, dominated by [Kobresia myosuroides], with [Juncus trifidus], [Agrostis vinealis], [Agrostis capillaris], [Festuca richardsonii], [Thymus arcticus], [Stereocaulon spp].

 ', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 66-67; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.1.5a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.5a).');
    'Grasslands of the extrasylvatic and upper sylvatic levels of the Urals, developed on high plateaux with deep soils and relatively high precipitations, particularly in the subalpine level of the southern Urals, or as substitution stages of grazed montane tundra.', '(Walter, 1974: 338-339).');
    'Species-rich humid grasslands of oligotrophic calcareous or calcicline soils of Central Europe, northeast to eastern Germany, Poland, Lithuania and Latvia, east to the Bohemian basin, Slovakia and the Ukraine, southeast to Austria, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with [Selinum carvifolia], [Succisa pratensis], [Galium uliginosum], [Serratula tinctoria], [Gentiana pneumonanthe], [Stachys officinalis] ([Betonica officinalis]), [Sanguisorba officinalis], [Laserpitium prutenicum], [Carex panicea], [Euphrasia rostkoviana], [Prunella vulgaris], [Ranunculus acris], [Silaum silaus], [Cirsium tuberosum], [Carex tomentosa], [Tetragonolobus maritimus], [Inula salicina], [Dianthus superbus], [Epipactis palustris], [Ophioglossum vulgatum], [Iris sibirica].', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Sanda y al., 1980: 55; Moravec y al., 1983: 53-54; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 85; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989; Korotkov y al., 1991: 151; Coldea, 1991: 460-462, 464; Pott, 1992: 236-237; Ruzickova y al., 1992: 76; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 386-390; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 303-305; Julve, 1993: 73-74; Oberdorfer, 1994: 39; Schubert y al., 1995: 300; Opermanis y al., 1997: 56; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Species-rich humid grasslands of oligotrophic calcareous or calcicline soils of the calcareous northern pre-Alps, the eastern Alps, the Jura, the Baar plateau, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with a species cortŠge characterized by the prominence of [Trollius europaeus], [Gentiana asclepiadea] or [Allium suaveolens].', '(Ernst, 1965: 40; de Foucault, 1976: 246-247; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989; Pott, 1992: 236; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 386-390, 395-398; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 306-307; Julve, 1993: 74; Oberdorfer, 1994: 39).');
    'Species-rich humid grasslands of oligotrophic calcareous or calcicline soils of the eastern Alps and neighbouring regions, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with [Allium suaveolens], [Allium angulosum].', '(Pott, 1992: 236; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 395-398; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 307; Oberdorfer, 1994: 39).');
    'Species-rich humid grasslands of oligotrophic calcareous or calcicline soils of the calcareous northern pre-Alps, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with a species cortŠge characterized by the prominence of [Gentiana asclepiadea].', '(Pott, 1992: 236; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 386-390, 395-398; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 306-307; Oberdorfer, 1994: 39).');
    'Species-rich humid grasslands of oligotrophic calcareous or calcicline soils of the Jura and the Baar plateau, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with a species cortŠge characterized by the prominence of [Trollius europaeus].', '(de Foucault, 1976: 246-247; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 386-390; Julve, 1993: 74; Oberdorfer, 1994: 39).');
    'Wet grasslands of the banks of the Loisach dominated by [Molinia caerulea] accompanied by fragmentary heavy metal communities comprising [Minuartia verna] var. [hercynica], [Silene vulgaris] var. [humilis] and [Cardaminopsis halleri], with [Cladonia spp.]', '(Ernst, 1965: 40). ');
    'Species-rich humid grasslands of oligotrophic calcareous and often alkaline soils of the Pannonic basin, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with [Lathyrus pannonicus], [Adenophora lilifolia], [Centaurea jacea], [Lotus maritimus], [Cirsium canum], [Inula britannica], [Succisa pratensis], [Serratula tinctoria], [Sanguisorba officinalis], [Silaum silaus], [Carex distans], [Carex flacca], [Carex hostiana], [Juncus subnodulosus], [Sesleria uliginosa]. These grasslands have become extremely rare in Austria.', '(Soo, 1980: 527; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 299-308, 309-310).');
    'Species-rich humid [Molinia] or [Molinia]-[Sesleria] grasslands of the northern and western periphery of the range of the typical Central European communities of units 37.3111 and 37.3112, with a species cortŠge tending somewhat towards that of the sympatric, Atlantic or sub-Atlantic, acidocline communities of unit 37.32.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 124 [p.]; Sougnez and Limbourg, 1963: 383-387; Noirfalise y al., 1980, 1985: unit Hme; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.2.3.4; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M26).');
    'Submontane humid grasslands of the northern Pennines and the Lake District developed on moist moderately base-rich and calcareous peats and peaty mineral soils dominated by [Molinia caerulea] with [Carex nigra], [Carex panicea], with [Crepis paludosa], [Succisa pratensis], [Valeriana dioica], [Potentilla erecta], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Angelica sylvestris], [Sanguisorba officinalis], [Trollius europaeus], [Ranunculus acris], [Serratula tinctoria], [Carex pulicaris], [Carex flacca], [Carex hostiana], [Juncus acutiflorus], [Festuca rubra], [Briza media], [Equisetum palustre], [Calliergon cuspidatum].', '(Rodwell, 1991b: unit M26).');
    'Closed, perennial communities of moderately calcareous stabilized sands of northern and western Central Europe and northern Eastern Europe, with [Armeria elongata], [Festuca trachyphylla], [Dianthus carthusianorum], [Silene otites], [Phleum boehmeri], [Koeleria gracilis], [Centaurea rhenana], [Chondrilla juncea], [Asperula cynanchica], [Eryngium campestre], [Sedum sexangulare], [Helichrysum arenarium].', '(Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 202; Pott, 1992).');
    'Closed, perennial communities of acidocline stabilized sands of northern and western Central Europe and northern Eastern Europe, with [Armeria elongata], [Festuca trachyphylla], [Dianthus deltoides], [Helichrysum arenarium], [Vicia lathyroides], [Chondrilla juncea], [Hieracium pilosella].', '(Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 202; Pott, 1992).');
    'Moderately closed, perennial communities of loose slightly calcareous sands of northern and western Central Europe and northern Eastern Europe, with [Corynephorus canescens], [Silene tatarica], [Petasites spurius], [Plantago indica].', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Korotkov y al., 1991: 201; Oberdorfer, 1993a: 155-156).');
    'Subcontinental xeric, thermophile grasslands of middle European collinar rock ledges, mostly dominated by the strong tufts of the glaucous [Festuca pallens] and [Festuca pannonica] and of the green [Sesleria albicans], and with [Dianthus gratianopolitanus], [Melica ciliata], [Aster alpinus], [Artemisia campestris] ssp. [lednicensis], [Hieracium spp.], [Biscutella laevigata] ssp. [varia], [Teucrium botrys], [Allium strictum], locally distributed in the Rhenish Schist Massif, the Pf¿lzerwald, the Rhine-Nahe-Mainz valleys, the Rh¿n, the Harz and its periphery, the southern Saxony hills, the Black Forest foothills, the French, Swabian and Franconian Juras, the Cracow-Czestochowa Jura, the western Pieniny, the Klippe Range of Nowy Targ and Spisz, the Mur Valley of Styria and, with possibly the greatest frequency and diversity, in the hills of the Bohemian hasin, in the Bohemio-Moravian hills, the southern Moravian hills, the sub-Pannonic foothills of the Carpathian and Alpine systems, the Middle Hungarian Ranges. The communities of the [Festucion pallescentis] often occupy isolated stations and include rare or relictual species which impart to many of them a distinctive biogeographical and physiognomic individuality. In particular, rare and highly disjunct western outposts occur in the Meuse basin of the Belgian and French Ardennes, harbouring, among others, very isolated populations of [Draba aizoides] var. [montana], [Artemisia alba] ssp. [saxatilis] and [Hieracium vogesiacum].', '(Wendelberger, 1954; Schumacher, 1977; Soo, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Duvigneaud, 1982c, 1985; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Parent, 1986; Ellenberg, 1988; Zimmermann y al., 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992: 251; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 459-460; Schubert y al., 1995: 268-272).');
    'Central European calcicolous subcontinental rock-ledge grasslands of orogenous affinities, montane or submontane with a strong representation of species characteristic of higher-altitude communities, often occupying stations of comparatively cool microclimate.', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Moravec y al., 1983: 63-64; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 460).');
    'Calciphile rock ledge grasslands rich in dealpine species of northern exposures in the collinar and submontane levels of the eastern and southern periphery of the Alps and the Carpathians, with relict occurrences in the Bohemian basin, southern Moravia and the Central Hungarian Range.', '(Soo, 1959, 1980: unit 43 [p.]; Moravec y al., 1983: 63-64; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 460-471).');
    'Calciphile rock ledge grasslands of the eastern Alpine periphery dominated by [Stipa eriocaulis].', '(Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 462-464, 470).');
    'Calciphile rock ledge grasslands of the eastern Alpine periphery and inner valleys, dominated by [Sesleria albicans] ([Sesleria calcarea]), [Festuca pallens], [Festuca rupicola], [Koeleria pyramidata], [Brachypodium rupestre], [Carex humilis], [Seseli austriacum], [Teucrium montanum].', '(Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 466-471).');
    'Calciphile rock ledge grasslands rich in dealpine species of northern exposures in the collinar and submontane levels of the southern spurs of the Northwestern Carpathians of Moravia and southern Slovakia, of the Pavlov Hills of southern Moravia and the northern Weinviertel of Austria.', '(Soo, 1959: 488 6; Moravec y al., 1983: 63-64; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 460-471).');
    'Relict primary calciphile closed rock grasslands of northern exposures of dolomite hills of the central part of the Hungarian Central Range and of the Austrian Hainburger Bergen, developed on shallow rendzinas, dominated by [Sesleria sadleriana] ssp. [sadleriana], endemic to the region, with [Carex humilis], [Genista pilosa], [Hieracium danubiale], [Asplenium ruta-muraria], [Draba lasiocarpa], [Poa badensis], [Alyssum saxatile], [Dianthus lumnitzeri], [Thalictrum foetidum], [Sempervivum schlehanii], [Saxifraga aizoon], [Ceterach officinarum], [Homalothecium lutescens], [Rhytidiadelphus triquetrus].', '(Zolyomi, 1936, 1958; Soo, 1980; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 465-466; Kovacs-Lang y al., 1995).');
    'North-facing slope rock-ledge grasslands of the Bohemian basin, in particular, of the Bohemian Karst and the Bohemian Central Range, with [Sesleria albicans], [Anthyllis vulneraria], [Vincetoxicum hirundinaria], [Primula veris], [Scabiosa columbaria], [Carex digitata], [Lembotropis nigricans].', '(Moravec y al., 1983: 63-64; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 467).');
    'More or less open grasslands constituting the second stage of succession in the colonisation of western Pontic sands, dominated by perennial grasses.', '(Vicherek, 1972; Horvat y al., 1974: 345-346; Sanda y al., 1980; Bondev, 1991: unit 147 [p.]; Donita, 1992: unit 35 L12, L12a; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 70-71; Donita and Ivan, 1992a, 1992b: 96-98; Sanda y al., 1992: 131; Hanganu y al., 1994: 34-35).');
    'Open perennial grasslands colonizing sands of Oltenia, Muntenia and southern Moldavia, dominated by [Festuca vaginata] with [Koeleria glauca], [Euphorbia seguierana], [Polygonum anarium], [Kochia laniflora], [Gypsophila paniculata], [Astragalus virgatus], [Astragalus varius], [Onosma arenaria], [Centaurea arenaria], [Tragopogon floccosus], [Echinops ruthenicus] and, in Oltenia, [Corispermum nitidum], [Teucrium polium], [Viola kitaibeliana], [Asperula tenella].', '(Sanda y al., 1980; Donita, 1992: unit 35 L12; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 70-71; Sanda y al., 1992: 131).');
    'Open perennial grasslands of the inland sands of the Danube Delta and the northern Dobrogea, characterized by [Festuca arenicola] ([Festuca beckeri]), [Stipa borysthenica], [Scabiosa argentea], [Syrenia montana] and with [Koeleria glauca], [Carex ligerica], [Fumana procumbens], [Minuartia setacea], [Ephedra distachya].', '(Simon, 1960; Krausch, 1965; Vicherek, 1972; Horvat y al., 1974: 345-346; Popescu and Sanda, 1976; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda y al., 1987; Bondev, 1991: unit 147 [p.]; Donita, 1992: unit 35 L12a; Donita and Ivan, 1992a, 1992b: 96-98; Hanganu y al., 1994: 34-35).');
