    'Species-rich calcicolous wet grasslands of Scandinavia dominated by [Sesleria caerulea], [Molinia caerulea], [Carex panicea] and [Linum catharticum] with a ground layer dominated by [Campylium stellatum] and [Ctenidum molluscum]. They are distributed in the Danish archipelago, in extreme southern Scania, ¿land and Gotland, coastal Estonia, along the coasts of the Skagerrak, the Kattegatt, and the Oslo Fjord, along the Atlantic coast of Norway north to the middle boreal zone, in west G¿tland and east G¿tland, in Södermanland and Uppland, in central J¿mtland on moist gley-calcareous soils with a relatively thick, peaty sod, under humid to semiarid nemoral, boreonemoral, southern boreal, middle boreal and oceanic climate conditions. [Carex flacca] and [Primula farinosa] are characteristic of their species cortŠge which also includes [Carex flava], [Carex lepidocarpa], [Carex pulicaria], [Carex hostiana], [Carex nigra], [Cirsium acaule], [Parnassia palustre], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Polygala amarella], [Potentilla erecta], [Primula vulgaris], [Scorzonera humilis], [Succisa pratensis], [Festuca rubra], [Hierochloe odorata], [Briza media] and many orchid species. These grasslands have affinities with the moister variants of unit 34.32, in particular the British [Sesleria] grasslands of unit 34.32142 and the moist Mesobromions of unit 34.324.', '(Hanso, 1975: 99; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.2.3.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.2.3.4).');
