    'Acidocline oligotrophic humid grasslands of Fennoscandia, north to the southern boreal zone and to the oceanic middle boreal zone of Norway, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with [Succisa pratensis], [Potentilla erecta], [Cirsium palustre]. Wetter, highly oligotrophic, communities, developed on permanently wet peaty ground, typically have a fairly tall sward, in which [Molinia caerulea] is the single dominant and a species cortŠge that includes [Juncus conglomeratus], [Juncus effusus], [Pinguicula vulgaris]; somewhat drier and more mesotrophic communities, occupying moist gley soils, often with stagnant water and peat formation, are short, grass and sedge dominated in which the dominance is shared between [Molinia caerulea], [Carex nigra] and [Carex panicea], with a species cortŠge of variable richness, transitional between the species-poor communities of unit 37.32 and the species-rich calcicline meadows of unit 37.311, often fairly similar to the latter, including [Filipendula ulmaria], [Galium palustre], [Geum rivale], [Juncus filiformis], [Viola palustris], and, on the continent, but absent in the Faeroes, [Platanthera bifolia]; communities of western Norway are distinct, comprising a number of species of Atlantic affinities.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.2.3.3, 5.2.3.5a; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.2.3.3, 5.2.3.5a).');
    'Acidocline [Molinia caerulea]-dominated oligotrophic humid grasslands of Central Europe, distributed from Germany to Poland and Lithuania and from eastern France to Austria, of limited occurrence within the area of prevalence of the more continental, basicline communities of unit 37.311; their species cortŠge includes [Succisa pratensis], [Potentilla erecta], [Cirsium palustre], [Juncus conglomeratus] ([Juncus subuliflorus]), [Juncus effusus], [Juncus acutiflorus], [Agrostis capillaris], [Viola persicifolia] ([Viola stagnina]), [Inula britannica], [Achillea ptarmica], [Hydrocotyle vulgaris], [Deschampsia cespitosa].', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; O''Sullivan, 1976b: 300; Moravec y al., 1983: 54; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 85; Korotkov y al., 1991: 151; Trautmann, 1991: 43, Table 11a; Lekavicius, 1992: 199-200; Pott, 1992: 235-236; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 308-311; Oberdorfer, 1993b: 385; Julve, 1993: 70; Schubert y al., 1995: 300-301; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
