    '[Sesleria albicans] grasslands of Carboniferous sugar limestones of upper Teesdale, with [Koeleria macrantha], [Festuca ovina], [Carex flacca], [Carex panicea], [Carex capillaris], [Kobresia simpliciuscula], and a highly distinctive species cortŠge that includes many regionally rare species, in particular, [Carex ericetorum], [Gentiana verna], [Viola rupestris], [Helianthemum canum], as well as species of northern montane affinities, such as [Polygonum viviparum], [Antennaria dioica], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Selaginella selaginoides]. The substrates contain high quantities of lead and these communities could be included within unit 34.2.', '(Bradshaw, 1985; Rodwell, 1992: unit CG9d).');
    'Dry calcicolous grasslands of Carboniferous Limestone outcrops of Wales and the Mendips, extending locally to hard Chalk formations of the Isle of Wight and of the neighbouring southern English mainland, with [Festuca ovina], [Koeleria macrantha], [Carex flacca], [Briza media], [Avenula pubescens], [Avenula pratensis], [Festuca rubra], [Carlina vulgaris], [Sanguisorba minor], [Thymus praecox], [Hieracium pilosella], [Lotus corniculatus], [Plantago lanceolata], [Helianthemum nummularium], [Helianthemum canum], [Scilla verna].', '(Summerhayes, 1976; Rodwell, 1992: units CG1d, CG1e, CG1f).');
    'Grasslands of the chalk downs and mainly Jurassic calcareous hills of southern Britain, mostly of southern and eastern England, with [Bromus erectus] and [Brachypodium pinnatum], or [Festuca spp.] and [Avenula spp.], often very rich in orchids.', '(Summerhayes, 1976; Rivas-Martinez, 1977a; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Rodwell, 1992). ');
    'Grasslands of the chalk downs and calcareous hills of southern and eastern England, and locally of Wales, dominated by tall grasses, generally [Bromus erectus] and/or [Brachypodium pinnatum], occasionally, in somewhat marginal situations, [Avenula spp.] and [Festuca rubra].', '(Summerhayes, 1976; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Polunin and Walters, 1985;  Rodwell, 1992: units CG3, CG5, CG6).');
    'Supra- and upper meso-Mediterranean grasslands, often on compact calcareous marls, dominated by, or rich in, the rush-like lily [Aphyllanthes monspeliensis] and with [Catananche caerulea], [Linum suffruticosum] ssp. [suffruticosum] and [Linum suffruticosum] ssp. [salsoloides], [Linum narbonense], [Linum strictum], [Linum campanulatum], [Linum tenuifolium], [Dorycnium suffruticosum], [Staehelina dubia], [Lavandula latifolia], [Potentilla crantzii], [Stipa offneri], [Stipa iberica], [Koeleria vallesiana], [Brachypodium phoenicoides], [Carex humilis] of southern France, northern and northeastern Spain, and Liguria.', NULL);
    'Steppe-like [Stipa]-dominated supra-Mediterranean garrigues and hedgehog-heaths of the mountains and plateaux of eastern Spain; [Stipa]-dominated facies of [Aphyllanthes] grasslands.  ', NULL);
    'Supra-Mediterranean and montane psychroxerophile, open perennial grasslands of the Cantabrian and Iberian ranges particularly characteristic of frost-fashioned, snow-free, superficial soils of the [Juniperus thurifera] and [Juniperus sabina] environments, rich in [Festuca hystrix], [Festuca burnatii], [Poa ligulata] and with, among others, [Armeria bigerrensis] ssp. [legionensis], [Arenaria aggregata] ssp. [cantabrica], [Centaurea janeri] ssp. [babiana], [Draba cantabrica], [Saxifraga conifera], [Ononis striata], [Ononis cristata], [Ononis pusilla], [Coronilla minima], [Paronychia kapela] ssp. [serpyllifolia], [Helianthemum canum], [Carex humilis]. They ascend to the oromediterranean level and extend southeast to the eastern Baetic chains. ', '(Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Martinez Parras and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Costa, 1987).');
    'Open grasslands of calcareous substrates of the middle and southern Apennines, southern vicariant of the [Xerobromion], with [Bromus erectus], [Sideritis syriaca] and many Apennine endemics or subendemics such as [Crepis lacera], [Centaurea rupestris] ssp. [ceratophylla], [Phleum ambiguum], [Carex macrolepis]. Many distinctive communities exist in this unit, some still covering vast expanses of land of exceptional biological significance such as Campo Imperatore in the Gran Sasso range; a few examples are cited below, others may be added.  ', '(Bonin, 1971; Biondi and Blasi, 1982; Biondi y al., 1985).');
    'Grasslands of the 350-1350 m range of the central Apennines with [Asperula purpurea], [Eryngium amethystinum], [Crepis lacera], [Allium sphaerocephalon], [Teucrium montanum].  ', NULL);
    'Grasslands of the lower sectors of the central Apennines (average 800 m) developed on well-exposed surfaces and somewhat marly calcareous soils with [Trigonella monspeliaca], [Trigonella gladiata], [Sideritis syriaca], [Ononis variegata]. ', NULL);
    'Chamaephyte-rich grasslands of the central-southern and southern Apennines, generally below the level of 34.744, with [Satureja montana], [Sideritis syriaca], [Plantago sempervirens], [Globularia punctata], [Chamaecytisus spinescens], [Chamaecytisus hirsutus], [Scabiosa crenata], [Helichrysum italicum], [Lavandula angustifolia], [Teucrium montanum], [Asphodeline lutea], [Stipa pennata], [Bromus erectus], [Bromus caprinus], [Avenula pretutiana].  ', NULL);
    'Grasslands of high montane zones (upper fringe of the beech zone, average 1250 m) of the central and southern Apennines, transitional towards alpine grasslands (36), with [Sesleria nitida], [Sesleria tenuifolia], [Festuca dimorpha], [Potentilla cinerea], [Carex macrolepis], [Chamaecytisus polytrichus].  ', NULL);
    'Xeric grasslands of the sub-Mediterranean zones of Trieste, Istria, the Balkan peninsula and of the [Ostryo-Carpinion] zone of Greece, where they coexist with steppic grasslands of the [Festucetalia valesiacae] (unit 34.311), developing in areas of lesser continentality than the latter, and incorporating a greater Mediterranean element than they do; like the steppic grasslands, however, they are often dominated by [Carex humilis] or [Festuca rupicola]. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 176-178, 212-213, 267, 484-485).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the warmer lowlands and hills of the Balkan and northern Hellenic peninsulas, within the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis aegeicum] and [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] zones. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 176-178, 208-211, 212-213; Hoda y al., 1998: 11).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis aegeicum] zone of northern Greece, the southern F.Y.R. of Macedonia and southwestern Albania, on the northwestern spurs of the Pindus system.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 176-178; Hoda y al., 1998: 11).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis aegeicum] zone of northern Greece, the southern F.Y.R. of Macedonia and southern Albania dominated by grasses of genera [Festuca] and [Koeleria], most widespread submediterranean dry grasslands within the area.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 176-178).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of limestones and marbles of the oak level of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis aegeicum] zone of northern Greece, the southern F.Y.R. of Macedonia and southern Albania rich in therophytes and with a strong representation of [Carex humilis].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 176-178).');
    'Species-poor pioneer submediterranean xeric grasslands of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis aegeicum] zone of northern Greece, the southern F.Y.R. of Macedonia and southern Albania dominated by the robust [Achnatherum calamagrostis].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 176-178).');
    'Snow-patch communities of arctic and boreal mountains of Fennoscandia, the Scottish Highlands, Iceland, Greenland and other islands of the Norwegian and Greenland seas, formed of mats of mosses and lichens.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Hadac, 1989; Rodwell, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Moss snow-patch communities of the Scottish Highlands and the mountains of western Norway formed of mats of bryophytes dominated by [Kiaeria starkei] ([Dicranum starkei]) and [Polytrichum sexangulare] ([Polytrichum norvegicum]), with [Kiaeria falcata], [Polytrichum alpinum], [Oligotrichum hercynicum], [Pohlia ludwigii], [Pleurocladula albescens], [Barbilophozia floerkii]. ', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit E3 [p.]; Rodwell, 1992: unit U11; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.1.1a [p.]).');
    'Snow-patch communities of the alpine levels of Scandinavian and Icelandic mountains formed of mats of bryophytes of varied species composition, usually dominated by [Polytrichum sexangulare] ([Polytrichum norvegicum]), characteristically accompanied by, notably, [Andraea spp.], ([Andraea blittii], [Andraea obovata]) and [Anthelia juratzkana]. Solitary vascular plants, including [Salix herbacea], [Cerastium cerastoides], [Omalotheca supina] ([Gnaphalium supinum]), [Saxifraga stellaris], [Carex lachenalii], [Deschampsia alpina], and lichens occur scattered at few metre intervals. [Polytrichum] communities are physiognomically variable, depending on the nutrient deficient substrate, which varies from fine material to rough boulders or solifluction, and may be dry to moist during the growing season. They appear as thin crusts on stones in hollows, as dense moss carpets on fine soils, as patches on coarser material, alternating with bare stones and gravel, or in boulder fields as fragments between boulders.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.1.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.1.1a [p.]).');
    'Snow-patch moss communities of alpine levels of Iceland, Spitzbergen, Jan Mayen and Greenland formed by often continuous mats of the blue hepatica [Anthelia juratzkana], hardening and becoming crusty in summer.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 94-95; Hadac, 1971b: 115-117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.1.4a; Hadac, 1985a: 122-123; Hadac, 1989: 156-157; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.1.1b).');
    'Acidophilous snow-patch communities of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia, Iceland and the Scottish Highlands dominated by dwarf willows embedded in dense bryophyte carpets.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rodwell, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Moss and dwarf willow snow-patch communities of the Scottish Highlands, with fragmentary outposts in the Southern Uplands, with [Salix herbacea], [Saxifraga stellaris], [Silene acaulis], [Omalotheca supina], [Luzula spicata] and mosses [Rhacomitrium heterostictum], [Rhacomitrium fasciculare], [Gymnomitrium concinnatum], [Polytrichum norvegicum], [Oligotrichum hercynicum], [Nardia scalaris].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit E3 [p.]; Rodwell, 1992: unit U12).');
COMMIT;
    'Moss and dwarf-willow snow-patch communities of the alpine level of boreal and arcto-alpine Scandinavian mountains and of Iceland, dominated by [Salix herbacea], alone or with [Cassiope hypnoides], [Omalotheca supina] ([Gnaphalium supinum]), [Ranunculus glacialis], frequently rich in small liver-mosses and lichens. Formations of high alpine and upper middle alpine levels are characteristically with [Poa flexuosa], [Luzula confusa], [Cardamine bellidifolia], [Ranunculus glacialis], of lower alpine levels with [Omalotheca supina], [Sibbaldia procumbens] and [Veronica alpina].', '(Steindorsson, 1965: 100-113, 120, tables XV-XVIII; Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 94-95; Hadac, 1971b: 117-121; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.1.1; Hadac, 1985a: 123-125; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.1.1).');
    'Acidophilous snow-patch communities of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia, Iceland and the Scottish Highlands dominated by coarse tussocky grasses, in particular, [Deschampsia cespitosa], sometimes associated with large hypnaceous mosses.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rodwell, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Snow-patch communities of the western and central Highlands, with outposts in the Southern Uplands, dominated by [Deschampsia cespitosa] or by [Rhytidiadelphus loreus] associated with [Deschampsia cespitosa] and often with [Hylocomium splendens] or [Pleurozium schreberi], with [Rhytidiadelphus squarrosus], [Rhytidiadelphus triquetrus], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Carex bigelowii], [Galium saxatile], [Alchemilla alpina].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit E2; Rodwell, 1992: unit U13).');
    'Snow-patch communities of the low and middle alpine levels of Scandinavian mountains and of the lowland to low alpine levels of Iceland dominated by [Deschampsia flexuosa] and [Anthoxanthum odoratum] on poor, nonflooded, substrates, with [Omalotheca norvegica] ([Gnaphalium norvegicum]), [Omalotheca supina] ([Gnaphalium supinum]), [Diphasiastrum alpinum], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex brunnescens].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.1.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.1.4).');
    'Acidophilous or acidocline snow-patch communities of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia, Iceland, the Faeroes and the Scottish Highlands forming a low, often open, turf of mat- and cushion-forming herbs, short tufted grasses and bryophyte patches.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rodwell, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Calcicolous open grasslands of the northwestern Carpathians dominated by [Festuca versicolor].', NULL);
    'Tall open grasslands of limestone bedrock in the alpine level of the Tatras formed by [Sesleria tatrae] and [Festuca versicolor], with [Androsace chamaejasme], [Astragalus frigidus], [Cerastium alpinum] ssp. [lanatum], [Hedysarum obscurum], [Oxytropis halleri], [Saussurea alpina] var. [borbasii], [Selaginella selaginoides], [Senecio capitatus].', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984).');
    'Local basiphile open grasslands of calcareous sandstones in steep slopes of the subalpine level of the Babia Gora, in the western Beskides, dominated by [Festuca versicolor], with [Saxifraga aizoon].', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984).');
    'Open grasslands of the Northwestern Carpathians and the Sudeten formed by [Agrostis alpina] and [Festuca versicolor], intermediate between calciphile and acidophile formations, and between grasslands and rock communities.', NULL);
    'Local open grasslands, transitional between basiphile and acidophile communities, developed on granites in the alpine level of the Tatras, formed by [Sesleria tatrae], [Festuca versicolor], [Agrostis alpina], with [Alchemilla flabellata], [Antennaria carpatica], [Callianthemum coriandrifolium], [Carex fuliginosa], [Lloydia serotina], [Pachypleurum simplex], [Pulsatilla vernalis], [Hieracium spp.]', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984).');
    'Open grasslands of the high Sudeten formed by [Agrostis alpina] or [Agrostis alpina] and [Festuca versicolor], with [Galium boreale], [Hieracium villosum], [Phyteuma orbiculare], [Saxifraga paniculata], [Scabiosa lucida], [Thymus praecox].', '(Jenik y al., 1980: 6; Moravec y al., 1983: 11; Kwiaitkowski, 1997: 283-286).');
    'Calcicolous open stepped grasslands of the montane level of the central Pienini, developed on steep slopes and rock banks, somewhat transitional between alpine grasslands and rock ledge swards of 34.351, constituted by [Sesleria albicans] ([Sesleria varia]), with [Helianthemum rupifragum], [Centaurea axillaris], [Erysimum witmannii] and the palaeo-endemic [Dendranthema zawadskii].', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984).');
    'Calcicolous, xero-thermophile, open, scraped, stepped and garland grasslands of the alpine and subalpine levels of the eastern Carpathians, on slopes with shallow limestone soils, dominated by, or rich in [Sesleria bielzii], [Sesleria rigida] ssp. [haynaldiana], [Festuca versicolor], [Festuca amethystina], [Festuca saxatilis], [Carex sempervirens].', '(Puscaru-Soroceanu y al., 1956, 1981; Boscaiu, 1971; Sanda y al., 1980; Coldea, 1984, 1991; Popescu and Sanda, 1989).');
    'Calcicolous open grasslands colonizing ledges, sills, crests of limestone rocks in the alpine and subalpine levels of the Eastern and the Southern Carpathians, formed by [Carex sempervirens] and [Sesleria] species, in particular, [Sesleria bielzii], [Sesleria rigida] ssp. [haynaldiana], [Sesleria heuflerana], or, at the contact with rock formations, by [Festuca saxatilis], [Sesleria spp.], [Carex sempervirens] and [Dianthus tenuifolius], accompanied by saxicolous species.', '(Popescu and Sanda, 1989; Coldea, 1991: 394-400).');
    'Calcicolous, xerothermophile, open grasslands of the alpine and subalpine levels of the southeastern Carpathians, on shallow rendzinas of crests, summits and ledges, dominated by [Festuca versicolor] and [Carex sempervirens], with [Sesleria rigida] ssp. [haynaldiana], [Cerastium transsilvanicum].', '(Puscaru, 1956; Beldie, 1967; Coldea, 1991: 399).');
    'Calcicolous open grasslands of the lower alpine and subalpine levels of the eastern Carpathians formed by [Festuca amethystina], with [Bellardiochloa violacea], [Carex sempervirens], [Allium ochroleucum], [Phyteuma orbiculare], [Biscutella laevigata], [Linum perenne] ssp. [extraaxillare] ([Linum extraaxillare]), [Festuca saxatilis].
', '(Puscaru, 1956; Beldie, 1967; Coldea, 1991: 395).');
    'Xero-mesophile open grasslands of sunny adrets of the Rodnei mountains in the Eastern Carpathians dominated by the southeastern Carpathian endemic [Festuca nitida] ssp. [flaccida] ([Festuca flaccida]), developed on rendzinas overlying limestone substrates, ecologically similar to the Alpine violet fescue grasslands of unit 36.414, though more open.', '(Coldea, 1991).');
    'Xerothermophile, open, sculptured, stepped or garland grasslands of the southwestern, central and northeastern Taurus. ', '(Géhu, 1984a; Noirfalise, 1987: unit Z).');
    'Xerothermophile, open, sculptured, stepped or garland grasslands of the Atlas ranges of North Africa.', '(Quézel, 1957, 1964: 323; White, 1983: 159).');
    'Enriched hay meadows and pastures of the subalpine and lower alpine levels of of the western Alpids and their satellite ranges. ', '(Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993). ');
    'Tall dry or mesophile grasslands of England and Wales dominated by [Bromus erectus], most characteristic of the Chalk of the North and South Downs, of Hampshire and Wiltshire and of the Chilterns, of the Oolite of the Cotswolds and of Northamptonshire, and of the Magnesian Limestone of West Yorkshire, with isolated occurrences in southern Wales.', '(Rodwell, 1992: unit CG3).');
    'Tall, dry or mesophile calcicolous grasslands of England, dominated by [Bromus erectus] and [Brachypodium pinnatum] in intimate mixture, or in coarser grain mosaics, most characteristic of the Oolite of the Cotswolds and of Northamptonshire-Lincolnshire, with outposts on the southern Chalk and the Magnesian Limestone of Derbyshire and West Yorkshire.', '(Rodwell, 1992: unit CG5).');
    'Tall calcicolous grasslands of England dominated by [Festuca rubra], [Avenula pubescens] and [Avenula pratensis], developing mostly as fringes near the bottom of valley-side slopes or on accumulations of colluvion, somewhat intermediate between [Mesobromion] grasslands of unit 34.32 and mesophile grasslands of unit 38.2.', '(Rodwell, 1992: unit CG6).');
    'Dry or mesophile calcicole grasslands of England dominated by [Brachypodium pinnatum], most characteristic of the northern Chalk of the Yorkshire Wolds, also widespread on the Oolite of the Cotswolds and Northamptonshire, local of the Chalk of the North and South Downs, and on the Chalk and Corallian Limestone of Dorset.', '(Summerhayes, 1976; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Rodwell, 1992: unit CG4).');
    'Short calcicolous turfs of England and Wales dominated by [Festuca ovina], with [Festuca rubra], [Koeleria macrantha], [Avenula pratensis] and a prominent admixture of perennial forbs or of therophytes, bryophytes and lichens.   ', '(Summerhayes, 1976; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Rodwell, 1992: units CG2, CG7).');
    'Usually short to very short forb-rich dry to mesophile calcicolous grasslands of England and Wales, most characteristic of the southern English Chalk, extending to Carboniferous Limestones of Wales, the Mendips, Derbyshire, the Isle of Man, Craven and Morecombe Bay, to the northern Chalk of the Yorkshire Wolds, the Corallian Limestone of the North York Moors, the Magnesian Limestone of Durham, formed by [Festuca ovina], [Festuca rubra], [Avenula pratensis], [Koeleria macrantha], [Briza media], with a prominent admixture of forbs, in particular, [Cirsium acaule], [Asperula cynanchica], [Onobrychis viciifolia], [Sanguisorba minor], [Plantago lanceolata], [Campanula rotundifolia], [Galium verum], [Primula veris], [Polygala vulgaris], [Viola hirta], and a few chamaephytes, notably, [Hippocrepis comosa], [Thymus praecox], [Helianthemum nummularium]. The large hemispherical hills of mound-building ants, in particular [Lasius flavus], are an important structural element of these grasslands.', '(Rodwell, 1992: unit CG2).');
    'Short, dry, open, or loosely closed, calcicolous grasslands of southern and eastern England, particularly of the Breckland and of the Chalk of southern England, with outposts on the Chalk of the Yorkshire Wolds and the Carboniferous Limestone of Derbyshire and the Mendips, dominated by [Festuca ovina], with a species cortŠge that includes [Koeleria macrantha], [Hieracium pilosella], [Leontodon hispidus], [Thymus praecox], [Thymus pulegeoides], [Hypnum cupressiforme], and in which therophytes, chamaephytes, bryophytes and lichens are often prominent; of subcontinental affinities, they show similarities with the steppe grasslands of unit 34.31 and with the [Xerobromion] communities of unit 34.33.', '(Rodwell, 1992: unit CG7).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] zone of Adriatic Croatia, in Istria and Dalmatia, western Bosnia-Herzegovina, western Montenegro, northwestern and western Albania south to the Vj¿s¿s lowlands.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 208-211, 212-213; Hoda y al., 1998: 11).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] zone of the western Balkan peninsula, with [Plantago holosteum] ssp. [depauperata], [Centaurea tommasinii], [Carlina lanata], [Koeleria splendens], [Festuca trachyphylla], [Festuca valesiaca], [Chrysopogon gryllus], [Stipa bromoides], [Bromus erectus].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 208-212).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of strongly eroded slopes of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] zone of Istria and Dalmatia, with [Salvia officinalis], [Campanula sibirica], [Stipa bromoides], [Bromus erectus].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 208-212).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the northern part of the transition zone between the mesomediterranean and [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] regions of Dalmatia, particularly well developed on the karst of the island of Pag, with [Asphodelus microcarpus], [Chamaecytisus spinescens], [Scutellaria orientalis] var. [pinnatifida], [Inula candida], [Cirsum acarna], [Chrysopogon gryllus], [Bromus erectus], [Melica ciliata]. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 208-213; Hoda y al., 1998: 11).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] zone of the Dalmatian archipelago, noted in particular from Pag, with [Armeria dalmatica], [Artemisia alba], [Alyssum montanum], [Helichrysum italicum].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 208-213).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the upper [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] zone of Dalmatia, with [Satureja montana], [Galium corrudifolium], [Aethionema saxatile], [Artemisia alba], [Melica ciliata], [Bothriochloa ischaemum], [Bromus erectus].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 208-213).');
    'Fairly dense, closed submediterranean xeric grasslands of the [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis adriaticum] zone of the western Balkan peninsula, developed on relatively fine-textured soils, with [Achillea nobilis], [Medicago prostrata], [Festuca valesiaca], [Koeleria splendens], [Bromus erectus], [Cladonia endiviaefolia]. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 208-212).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the submontane and montane levels of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, within the upper levels of the [Ostryo-Carpinion adriaticum] zone, reaching locally to the beech level, of more medio-European physiognomy than the formations of unit 34.751, and somewhat reminiscent of [Bromion erecti] grasslands. ', '(Ritter-Studnicka, 1973: 311; Horvat y al., 1974: 213-214, 484; Poldini, 1989: 149-187; Kaligaric, 1997: 40-66; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Submontane and montane submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula with [Carex humilis], [Bromus erectus], Centaurea rupestris], [Leucanthemum liburnicum], [Plantago argentea], [Jurinea mollis], [Iris cengialti], [Pulsatilla vulgaris] ssp. [grandis] and, in warmer stations, [Filipendula vulgaris], [Lotus corniculatus], [Leontodon hispidus], [Briza media], on exposed slopes, [Sesleria juncifolia], [Gentiana lutea], [Gentiana clusii], [Trinia glauca], in the most montane situations [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi]. They occur from Trieste to Montenegro, and in the Velebit, Dinara, Kamesnika, Prenj und Biokovo ranges, and are used as pastures or sometimes hay meadows.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 213, 484; Poldini, 1989: 161-175; Kaligaric, 1997: 46-63; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Low, mat-forming submontane and montane submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, occupying windswept hilltops, with [Satureja subspicata] with [Edraianthus tenuifolius], [Helianthemum oelandicum] ssp. [italicum], [Genista holopetala], [Crepis chondrilloides], distributed from the Orjen to the Obruc range.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 213; Poldini, 1989: 163, 166).');
    'Submontane and montane submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, replacing the grasslands of unit 34.7522 in the Obruc range and Gorsky Kotar on extremely wind-exposed domes with shallow dolomitic rendzinas, at an altitude of 800-1100 m, with [Carex mucronata], [Genista holopetala], [Euphorbia saxatilis], [Gentiana clusii], [Minuartia laricifolia], [Sesleria juncifolia].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 213, 484; Poldini, 1989: 175-176; Kaligaric, 1997: 44-46; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Lacunar, cespitose steppic grasslands of the northeastern Adriatic dominated by the tall andropogonid grasses [Chrysopogon gryllus] and [Dichanthium ischaemum], associated with [Cleistogenes serotina], and with [Carex humulis], [Anthyllis adriadica], [Asperula purpurea], the endemic [Centaurea cristata], [Artemisia alba], [Bupleurum veronense], [Petrorhagia saxifraga], [Argyrolobium zanonii], [Onosma javorkae], [Carlina corymbosa], [Gentiana tergestina]. They are characteristic of the Triestine karst, with uncommon occurrence in karstic Slovenia. These tall-grass steppic grasslands are intermediate between the more mediterranean andropogonid grass steppes of unit 34.6344 and the peri-Alpine [Chrysopogon] grasslands of unit 34.327. Related [Chrysopogon] grasslands also exist in units 34.751 and 34.753.', '(Poldini, 1989: 153-161; Kaligaric, 1997: 41-43, 109; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Species-rich, low and often somewhat open swards of the western and central Scottish Highlands characteristic of sheltered hollows and corries kept moist by snow-melt or snow-bed springs, often on podzolized soils over calcareous substrates, formed by [Alchemilla alpina], [Sibbaldia procumbens], [Thymus praecox], [Silene acaulis], [Nardus stricta], [Agrostis capillaris], [Festuca ovina], [Festuca vivipara], [Deschampsia cespitosa], [Omalotheca supina], [Galium saxatile].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit D3a [p.]; Rodwell, 1992: unit U14). ');
    'Herb-rich, well-developed, closed meadow communities of lower and middle alpine levels of Scandinavian mountains, in locations around snow patches on south-facing slopes with relatively early thaw, on stable, moist substrates with low pH, subject to periodic flooding, mainly in spring. The ground layer is dominated by mosses; dominant vascular species, depending on subtypes, are [Ranunculus acris], [Sibbaldia procumbens] or [Alchemilla glomerulans]; the cortŠge may include [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Cerastium cerastoides], [Epilobium angustifolium], [Rumex acetosa], [Taraxacum croceum], [Veronica alpina], [Oxyria digyna], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex lachenalii], [Calamagrostis neglecta], [Phleum alpinum], [Agrostis mertensii], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Equisetum arvense]; lime-loving species are absent.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.3.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.3.1).');
    'Species-rich, extremely patchy, communities of lower and middle alpine levels of Scandinavian mountains, of Iceland and the Faeroe Islands, forming on flooded, extremely moist, late thawing, poor substrates in heavy rainfall areas, dominated by [Oxyria digyna] and various species of saxifrages ([Saxifraga stellaris], [Saxifraga caespitosa], [Saxifraga hypnoides], [Saxifraga tenuis], [Saxifraga rivularis], [Saxifraga oppositifolia]) or by [Deschampsia alpina].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.3.3.2; Hadac, 1985b: 117-119; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.2.3.2).');
    'Acidophilous snow-bed communities of alpine and arcto-alpine levels of the Fennoscandian mountains, of Iceland and of the Scottish Highlands dominated by ferns, characteristic of screes with prolonged snow cover, related to the tall-herb communities of unit 37.8. [Cryptogramma crispa], [Athyrium distentifolium] ([Athyrium alpestre]), [Athyrium filix-femina], [Dryopteris expansa] ([Dryopteris assimilis]) or [Dryopteris filix-mas] can dominate the communities. [Galium saxatile], [Calamagrostis purpurea], [Barbilophozia floerkii], [Polytrichum alpinum] are among the associates. ', '(McVean, 1964d: 515-516; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit D2b; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 1.3.5.1, 1.3.5.2, 1.3.5.3 [p.]; Rodwell, 1992: unit U18; Påhlsson, 1994: units 1.2.5.1, 1.2.5.1a, 1.2.5.1b [p.]).');
    'Acidophilous snowbed communities of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains and subarctic lowlands of Scandinavia and Iceland, mostly developed in areas of long snowcover, dominated by Cyperaceae or Juncaceae, usually with a prominent bryophyte or lichen ground layer.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.1.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.1.2).');
    'Acidophilous snowbed communities of boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of  Scandinavia and Iceland forming on extremely wet sandy substrates, under prolonged snow cover and with near-surface water during the entire vegetation period, dominated by [Carex rufina], often in a single species situation, or with [Carex lachenalii], [Carex bigelowii], on a compact moss carpet dominated by [Calliergon cordifolium]. Occurs in western parts of mountain chains, under submaritime or maritime climates.', '(Steindorsson, 1965: 115; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.1.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.1.2).');
    'Mostly open snowbed communities of the alpine belt of boreal and arctic Scandinavia and Iceland, developed, on north- and northwest-facing slopes, in conjunction with snow fields that may thaw only in some years, on often very bare stony, gravellly or boulder-strewn acid, nutrient-poor soils, with high moisture content but susceptible to summer dessication, dominated by [Luzula arcuata] or, in Scandinavia only, [Luzula confusa], with a ground layer formed by hepatics, mosses or [Cetraria islandica]; the species cortŠge includes [Ranunculus glacialis] as well as, among others, [Ranunculus pygmaeus], [Cassiope hypnoides], [Silene acaulis], [Cardamine bellidifolia], [Saxifraga rivularis], [Carex lachenalii], [Poa flexuosa], and, in Iceland, [Poa alpina], [Phleum alpinum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.1.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.1.3).');
    'Snow-patch communities of the high altitudes of the Urals, devoid of [Salix herbacea]. [Lagotis uralensis], [Anemone biarmiensis], [Ranunculus borealis], [Ranunculus sulfphureus], [Alchemilla murbeckiana], [Rhodiola rosea] are charactermistic of distinctive associations.', '(Walter, 1974: 339).');
    'Snow-patch communities of high mountains of boreal eastern Asia, in particular, of Kamchatka and Amurland.', '(Saphronova, 1964c: unit 106 [p.]).');
    'Basiphile or basicline snow-patch or snowbed communities of the boreal and arcto-alpine mountains, including the Caledonian mountains of Scotland, and of the western Alpids, developed on calcareous substrates, on calcschists, or on base-rich soils.', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1954, 1975a; Rivas-Martinez, 1963, 1975c; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 626-628; Ozenda, 1975; Ratcliffe, 1980; Pignatti, 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 76; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Dupias, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Jonglet, 1990; Hill, 1990; Coldea, 1991: 376-379; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    '[Trisetum flavescens]-dominated grasslands of the subalpine level of the Alps, the Carpathians and the Jura. Yellow oatgrass hay meadows are typically montane and have been listed and described under unit 38.3; subalpine representatives may, however, be coded under this unit when useful to preserve the unity of subalpine habitat complexes.  ', '(Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 368-372; Seliskar, 1998: 17).');
    'Species-poor manured cattle pastures of the subalpine and lower alpine levels of the western Alpids and their satellite ranges, with [Agrostis alpina], [Phleum alpinum], [Poa alpina], [Cerastium fontanum], [Crepis aurea], [Leontodon hispidus], [Trifolium badium], [Trifolium thalii].  ', '(Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993: 372-379; Seliskar, 1998: 17).');
    'High-altitude grass and sedge dominated formations of the Caucasus, of the Pontic Range, of the Elburz and of the Crimean mountains.', '(Zohary, 1973: 498-499; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Noirfalise, 1987; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Grasslands of the humid alpine level of the eastern Pontic Range, with [Campanula tridentata], [Alchemilla vulgaris], [Poa alpina], [Festuca "ovina"], and of the humid subalpine level, occupied by pastures of [Festuca spp.], with [Luzula spicata], [Carex tristis], [Lotus corniculatus].', '(Gaussen y al., 1969: units 40, 42; Zohary, 1973: 498; Noirfalise, 1987: unit W).');
    'Grass and sedge dominated formations of alpine and subalpine meadows of the high Caucasus, with a considerable variety of associations.', '(Gaussen y al., 1969: units 40, 42; Walter, 1974: 388-393; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Korotkov y al., 1991: 247-248, 249-250).');
    'Grass and sedge dominated formations of alpine and subalpine meadows of Crimea.', '(Walter, 1974: 356-360; Walter and Breckle, 1986).');
    'Extrasylvatic grasslands of the Elburz range of northern Iran, of limited extent and insularized, developed under humid alpine conditions, with [Dactylis glomerata], [Alopecurus spp.], [Sesleria phleoides], [Trifolium spp.], [Lotus corniculatus], [Polygonum bistorta], [Primula auriculata], [Pedicularis comosa].', '(Gaussen y al., 1969: unit 40; Zohary, 1973: 499; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c: 242).');
    'High altitude grass and sedge dominated communities of eastern Anatolian, Irano-Afghan and Central Asian mountains.', '(Noirfalise, 1987).');
    'High altitude grass and sedge communities of the Altai and other central and eastern Asian boreal mountain ranges.', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c).');
    'High altitude grass and sedge dominated communities of the Himalayan system, developed at the 3800 or 4200 to 4800 or 5500 m level in the main ranges and at the 4000-5100 m level on the dry Tibetan plateau.', '(Schweinfurth, 1957; Gaussen y al., 1969: units 40, 41; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 47; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 208-212, 220-226).');
    'High altitude grass and sedge dominated communities of the high mountains of the Far East.', '(Walter and Breckle, 1991c).');
    'Unimproved or lightly improved wet meadows and tall herb communities of the boreal, nemoral, warm-temperate humid, steppic and mediterranean zones of the Palaearctic. ', '(Soo, 1961, 1980; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Korotkov y al., 1991; Oberdorfer, 1993b; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993).');
    'Dense stands of tall or medium-tall hygrophile herbs developed in strips on fertile alluvial stream banks of the boreal, nemoral and steppe zone lowlands, and, by extension, tall herb stands colonizing humid hay meadows and pastures after more or less long discontinuation of mowing or grazing. Higher altitude formations, most characteristic of the subalpine zone of mountains, are listed under unit 37.8; the highly distinctive, lowland and montane, very tall herb formations of the Pacific Far East are individualized under unit 37.9. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Noirfalise y al., 1980; Soo, 1980; Wheeler, 1980c; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Walter and Breckle, 1991c; Pott, 1992; Rodwell, 1991b; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'River bank, humid depression and abandoned meadow tall herb communities of the western deciduous forest region and its zones of influence, characteristically dominated by [Filipendula ulmaria].', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Noirfalise y al., 1980; Soo, 1980; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Pott, 1992; Rodwell, 1992; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Mesophile and mesoxerophile calcareous grasslands of the sub-Atlantic domaine in the Low Countries, Germany, the Czech Republic, Switzerland, northern, central and western France and northwestern Spain. They are faunistically and floristically rich and the highly discontinuous nature of their distribution gives rise to a considerable geographical variation in the composition of plant and animal communities, marked by the occurrence of numerous species of local or disjunct occurrence in addition to the basic cortŠge common to most of them. Besides this geographical variation, the nature of these grasslands also depends, to a great extent, on hydric regime, substrate characteristics and agropastoral treatment, notably on whether they are mowed or grazed and how intensively. In particular, the relative abundance of the main constituent grass species, [Bromus erectus], [Brachypodium pinnatum] [s. l.], [Sesleria albicans] and [Koeleria pyramidata], varies both geographically with climatic conditions and locally with topography and agropastoral regime. Thus, although separate geographical entities may differ in that relative abundance, similarly differing facies may also coexist locally, producing sharply distinct habitats. To accomodate for these concurrent axes of variation, formations dominated by [Brachypodium] or by [Sesleria], as well as all semidamp formations, are removed from this division and placed in units 34.323, 34.324 and 34.325. Geographical subdivisions, most apt at identifying distinctive plant and animal communities, may be used in the four sections by addition of a fourth decimal digit common to all of them. The regions encompassed by the geographical subdivisions corresponding to each value of this fourth digit are in all cases described under this section although in some of them, or in parts of some of them, there may be no grasslands belonging to unit 34.322, but only grasslands belonging to units 34.323, 34.324 or 34.325; these cases have, as much as possible, been identified under each of the subdivisions below.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Braun-Blanquet, 1976; Petit and Ramaut, 1970, 1985; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Lambinon, 1974; Schumacher, 1977; Rivas-Martinez, 1977a; Gruber, 1978; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Sipkes, 1980; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Ozenda, 1981; Noirfalise and Dethioux, 1982; Duvigneaud, 1982a, 1982b, 1983a, 1983b, 1985; Moravec y al., 1983; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Dupias, 1985; Bobbink and Willems, 1987; Loidi Arregui, 1987; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Vigo and Ninot, 1987; Chas, 1989; Zimmermann y al., 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a).');
    'Mesophile grasslands of the northwestern Hercynian periphery, on mostly Devonian or Carboniferous limestones or dolomitic limestones, occasionally on calcschists, in the Mosan district of Belgium and the French Meuse, with isolated stations in the Ardenne-Eifel of Luxembourg and Rhineland. ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 99, 100; Thill, 1964: 30-32, 39-44; Schumacher, 1977; Avril and Dethioux, 1980: 54-55; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Noirfalise and Dethioux, 1982; Duvigneaud, 1983b, 1985; Delescaille y al., 1990; Duvigneaud and Saintenoy-Simon, 1996; Duvigneaud and Saintenoy-Simon, 1997; Godefroid and Verhelpen, 1997).');
    'Chalk grasslands of the Belgian low Meuse, extreme southeastern Netherlands and Westphalia, generally without [Bromus erectus], and alluvial [Mesobromion] grasslands of adjacent regions (these to be listed under unit 34.324).', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 99; Petit and Ramaut, 1970, 1985; Sipkes, 1980; Noirfalise and Dethioux, 1982; Duvigneaud, 1983b, 1985; Bobbink and Willems, 1987).');
    'Closed mesophile grasslands, on substrates derived from Mesozoic limestones, of the periphery of the Harz in Saxony, Thuringe, Hesse and the hills of Lower Saxony. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a).');
    'Closed mesophile calcareous grasslands of the Oder basin in Brandenbourg and Mecklenburg. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a).
');
    'Mesophile grasslands of the Cretaceous northwestern and western periphery of the Paris basin, the valleys of the Seine, Bray and Somme and adjacent Jurassic areas of Basse Normandie and the Boulonnais. ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 99, 100, 106; Lambinon, 1974; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Noirfalise and Dethioux, 1982; Duvigneaud, 1983b).');
    'Mesophile calcareous grasslands of the Parisian Tertiary in the central Paris basin. ', '(Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981).');
    'Mesophile grasslands of the northeastern, eastern and southeastern Jurassic belt of the Paris basin and adjacent Cretaceous areas in Lorraine, Champagne, Haute-Marne, Burgundy, Haute-Sa¿ne. ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 99, 101, 103; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Noirfalise and Dethioux, 1982; Duvigneaud, 1982b, 1983a, 1983b).');
    'Closed mesophile calcareous grasslands of the Rhine, Mainz, Moselle, Neckar, Nahe and Lahn valleys in their crossing of the northern Hercynian ranges. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Sipkes, 1980; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a).');
    'Closed mesophile calcareous grasslands of the upper Rhine rift and adjacent hills, in Alsace, Baden-W?rttemberg and Switzerland. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a).');
    'Mesophile calcareous grasslands of the southern Black Forest. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Wolkinger and Plank, 1981; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a).');
    'Rock grasslands of steep slopes of the Triestine and Slovenian karst dominated by [Sesleria juncifolia], with [Carex humilis], [Allium ochroleucum], [Sempervivum tectorum], [Scorzonera austriaca] var. [platyphylla], [Athamanta turbith] and species of the [Sedo-Scleranthetea] and [Potentilletalia caulescentis] rock-debris and cliff cortŠges.', '(Poldini, 1989: 160-161; Kaligaric, 1997: 44-46, 109; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, within the [Ostryo-Carpinion adriaticum] zone, developed on deeper more acidified soils than the formations of units 34.751 and 34.752, over flysch or schists, or over loam or clay covered limestones.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 214-216, 485; Poldini, 1989: 147-149; Kaligaric, 1997: 27-40; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Deep soil, acidocline submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, distributed in Istria, northern coastal Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina, with [Danthonia provincialis], [Chrysopogon gryllus], [Bromus erectus], [Schoenus nigricans], [Dianthus ferrugineus] ssp. [liburnicus], [Ferulago campestris], [Scorzonera villosa].
', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 215, 485; Poldini, 1989: 147-149; Kaligaric, 1997: 27-40; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
    'Deep soil, acidocline submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, characteristic of the northern Quarnero-Istrian coastal area, with [Euphorbia nicaeensis], [Potentilla pedata], [Potentilla cinerea], [Dianthus carthusianorum]', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 214-216).');
    'Deep soil, acidocline submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, distributed the Quarnero Islands, in particular Rab, Pag and Muc, and in central and northern Dalmatia, with [Ononis spinosa] ssp. [antiquorum], [Astragalus monspessulanus] ssp. [illyricus], [Inula oculus-christi], [Onobrychis arenaria], [Scorpiurus subvillosus], [Leucanthemum croaticum], [Inula ensifolia].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 215).');
    'Deep soil, acidocline submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, limited to moutain slopes of Istria, up to the beech level, transitional to medio-European [Bromion erecti] grasslands, with [Bromus erectus], [Brachypodium pinnatum], [Festuca valesiaca], [Thalictrum aquilegifolium], [Lilium bulbiferum], [Gentianella germanica], [Primula veris], [Scorzonera villosa], [Hypochoeris maculata]. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 214-216, 485).');
    'Deep soil, acidocline submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, characteristic of clearings of the submontane hop-hornbeam beech woods with [Hypochoeris maculata], [Pedicularis acaulis], [Linum narbonense], [Carex montana], and a number of acidophilous species, such as [Calluna vulgaris].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 216).');
    'Open acidocline submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula, characteristic of fallow, superficially eroded fields of the Croatian coastal region, with [Poa bulbosa], [Seseli montanum] ssp. [tommasinii], [Trifolium incarnatum] ssp. [molinerii], [Ophrys bertolonii], [Salvia bertolonii], [Thymus longicaulis], [Sanguisorba minor] ssp. [muricata], [Silene vulgaris], [Festuca pseudovina], [Bromus erectus].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 216).');
    'Postcultural acidocline submediterranean xeric grasslands of the Adriatic fa¿ade of the Balkan peninsula dominated by [Cleistogenes serotina] ([Diplachne serotina], [Leptochloa serotina]).', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 216).');
    'Submediterranean xeric grasslands of dolomitic rendzinas of Bosnia-Herzegovina, with [Peucedanum arenarium] ssp. [neumayerii], [Euphorbia barrelieri], [Reichardia macrophylla], [Silene reichenbachii], [Saponaria bellidifolia], [Haplophyllum patavium].', '(Ritter-Studnicka, 1959; Ritter-Studnicka, 1968; Horvat y al., 1974: 484).');
    'Formations composed mostly of annuals, in particular, grasses of genera [Bromus], [Aegilops], [Avena], [Vulpia], crucifers and leguminous plants, that occupy considerable expanses of the western, central and eastern meso- and thermo-Mediterranean zones on soils slightly enriched in nitrates. These communities develop as pioneers of bare soils slightly nitrified by aeration or organic addition, along roads, on land-fills and in interstitial spaces of cultivation. They also replace the oligotrophic annual communities included in the Mediterranean xeric grasslands (units 34.51, 34.53) under the influence of pastoral activities. They are widespread as postcultural formations. They evolve through intensive grazing into perennial pastures of the [Poetalia bulbosae] and related communities (unit 34.52), through increased nitrification into ruderal formations (unit 87), through an increase in edaphic humidity into amphibious communities (unit 22.3) and perennial andropogonid steppes (unit 34.634) or Phoenician torgrass swards (unit 34.36). Ligneous recolonization may lead either to halonitrophilous scrubs of the [Salsolo-Peganetalia] (unit 15.17), or to maquis and garrigues of the [Rosmarinetalia], [Lavanduletalia] or [Gypsophiletalia] (units 32, 15.19).', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1975c; Izco, 1977; Peinado Lorca y al., 1984; Herranz Sanz and Gomez Campo, 1986; Ladero Alvarez, 1987; Rivas-Martinez and Costa, 1987; Aparicio Martinez and Silvestre Domingo, 1987; Martinez Parras y al., 1987).');
    'Herbaceous snow-patch swards of the Alpids, characteristic of carbonated soils under snow for long periods, with [Arabis caerulea], [Carex atrata], [Ranunculus alpestris], [Saxifraga androsacea].', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1954, 1975a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 626-628; Ozenda, 1975; Pignatti, 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 76; Dupias, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Jonglet, 1990; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Herbaceous snow-patch swards of humid, carbonated soils, of the Alps and the Pyrenees, under snow for long periods, with [Ranunculus alpestris], [Arabis caerulea], [Omalotheca hoppeana] ([Gnaphalium hoppeanum]), [Hutchinsia alpina], [Potentilla brauniana] ([Potentilla minima]), [Soldanella alpina]. ', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1954, 1975a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Ozenda, 1975; Dupias, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Jonglet, 1990; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Endemic snow patch community of the high Tatras and nearby Carpathian ranges, characteristic of sites with very long snow cover, with the western Carpathian endemic [Saxifraga wahlenbergii] ([Saxifraga perdurans]), [Hutchinsia alpina], [Bucegia romanica].', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 76).');
    'Uncommon, isolated herbaceous snow-patch swards of the southern Dinarides and the Pelagonides, on carbonated soils under snow for long periods, generally associated with dolines.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 626-628; Hoda y al., 1998: 21).');
    'Espalier willow communities of calcareous stone fields submitted to relatively long snow-cover of the Alpids and the boreal mountains, with [Salix reticulata], [Salix retusa].', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1954, 1975a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 626-628; Ozenda, 1975; Pignatti, 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 76; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Dupias, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Jonglet, 1990; Coldea, 1991: 376-379; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Espalier willow communities of snow-bound calcareous stone fields of the Alpids, with the net-leaved willow, [Salix reticulata], and the retuse-leaved willow, [Salix retusa], or with [Salix kitaibeliana].  ', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1954, 1975a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 626-628; Ozenda, 1975; Pignatti, 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 76; Dupias, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1992a; Jonglet, 1990; Coldea, 1991: 376-379; Pott, 1992; Englisch y al., 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
