    'Primary and secondary steppes, formations dominated by medium or tall perennnial tuft-forming grasses or suffrutescents, with lacunar ground cover and associated therophyte communities, with two periods of dormancy, in large part climactic, accompanied by an Irano-Turanian cortŠge, of continental Central Eurasia and the Western Asian plateaux. The formations of the transition zone between the Mediterranean and Saharo-Sindian domaines, similar in appearance and floristically related to a varying degree, have been included in the Mediterranean steppes of unit 34.6. Sand steppes and salt steppes occurring within the range of the continental steppes of unit 34.9 are listed separately under units 34.A and 15.A, respectively.', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Saphronova, 1964a; Saphronova, 1964b; Saphronova, 1964c; Zohary, 1973; Walter, 1974; Horvat y al., 1974: 297; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Grassland communities of the Pannonic region, rich in herbaceous dicotyledonous species including, among others, [Salvia nemorosa], [Salvia austriaca], [Filipendula vulgaris], [Astragalus austriacus], [Astragalus exscapus], [Galium verum], [Ajuga genevensis], [Dianthus pontederae], [Thymus glabrescens], and grasses, [Festuca rupicola], [Koeleria macrantha], installed on, notably, loess ridges formed by fluviatile erosion and accumulation. These communities are sensitive to grazing and trampling and have been extensively transformed into other grassland types.  ', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Schneider-Binder, 1967; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986; Fekete y al., 1992; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a).');
    'Primary species-rich, relatively closed, multi-strata steppic grasslands, on deep chernozems, the main Pannonic representative of the steppes of Central Eurasia, composed mainly of [Festuca rupicola], [Stipa capillata], [Koeleria cristata], [Poa angustifolia], [Bromus inermis], [Elymus hispidus], [Achillea pannonica], [Taraxacum serotinum], [Viola ambigua], [Astragalus onobrychis], [Chamaecytisus austriacus], [Chamaecytisus supinus], [Adonis vernalis], [Veronica austriaca], [Veronica prostrata], [Vinca herbacea], [Asperula glauca], [Allium paniculatum], with [Nepeta parviflora], [Silene longiflora], [Ajuga laxmannii], [Astragalus dasyanthus], [Astragalus vesicarius], [Astragalus exscapus], [Astragalus austriacus], [Salvia nemorosa], [Salvia nutans], [Echium maculatum]. Originally widely distributed throughout the loess plateau of the Pannonic basin and at the foot of the Hungarian Central Range, but now reduced only to small fragments because of intensive agricultural activity. This habitat is of major conservation importance and harbours numerous rare and threatened taxa, including, among flowering plants, [Crambe tataria], [Adonis transsylvanica], [Thlaspi jankae], [Brassica elongata].', '(Soo, 1959: unit 14; Soo, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974: 261-264, 297-299; Moravec y al., 1983; Zolyomi, 1985; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a: 443-445; Kovacs-Lang y al., 1995).');
    'Snowbed communities of the boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia, characteristic of the edges of snowfields on calcareous often stone-littered soils with near-surface ground water or moisture in early spring and little or no solifluction, constituted by dense carpets of mosses and forbs in which [Salix polaris] dominates, often totally; the species cortŠge includes [Salix reticulata], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Erigeron uniflora], [Omalotheca supina] ([Gnaphalium supinum]), [Minuartia biflora], [Ranunculus pygmaeus], [Saxifraga aizoides], [Saxifraga cernua], [Saxifraga stellaris], [Saxifraga tenuis], [Silene acaulis], [Taraxacum croceum], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Tofieldia pusilla], [Veronica alpina], [Viola biflora], [Carex lachenalii], [Poa alpina] f. [vivipara] and mosses.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.2.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.2.1).');
    'Snowbed communities of islands of the polar basin, in particular, of Spitzbergen with [Salix polaris], [Luzula confusa], [Pedicularis hirsuta], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Cerastium arcticum], [Dricranum elongatum], [Drepanocladus uncinatus], [Gymnomitrion coralloides], [Anthelia juratzkana], [Cetraria delisei], [Sterocolon alpinum].', '(Hadac, 1989: 135, 150-158).');
    'Moss dominated snowbed communities of calcareous gravel and stonefields, or moraine, of Scandinavian mountains, with, in particular, [Distichium capillaceum], [Pohlia albicans], [Pohlia drummondii], often pioneering on "new ground". Individual vascular plants, growing widely separated, include, notably, [Cardamine pratense] f. [dentata], [Cerastium arcticum], [Cerastium cerastoides], [Saxifraga oppositifolia]. ', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.2.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.2.1a).');
    'Open snowbed communities of the alpine level of the boreal and arcto-alpine zones of Scandinavian mountains forming on level calcareous substrates often waterlogged the whole year, in the proximity of melting snow or cold springs,  on north-facing slopes, with prolonged snow-lie. Vascular plants are characteristically scattered, with great variation in the ground layer, with an often broken moss carpet, bare patches of gravel and stones. Characteristic species, often hygrophilous, include [Ranunculus nivalis], [Ranunculus sulphureus], [Salix herbacea], [Arabis alpina], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Cerastium cerastoides], [Minuartia biflora], [Oxyria digyna], [Taraxacum croceum], [Viola biflora], [Saxifraga oppositifolia], [Saxifraga rivularis], [Saxifraga nivalis], [Saxifraga tenuis], [Saussurea alpina], [Sibbaldia procumbens], [Juncus biglumis], [Poa alpina].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.2.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.2.2).');
    'Sparse communities of the alpine level of northern boreal and arcto-alpine mountains of Scandinavia and of Iceland dominated by the grass [Phippsia algida], with, notably, [Salix herbacea], [Cerastium arcticum], [Cerastium cerastoides], [Oxyria digyna], [Ranunculus glacialis], [Ranunculus nivalis], [Ranunculus pygmaeus], [Saxifraga cernua], [Saxifraga oppositifolia], [Saxifraga rivularis], [Saxifraga stellaris], [Saxifraga tenuis], [Carex lachenalii], [Juncus biglumis], [Poa alpina] f. [vivipara], [Deschampsia alpina], [Sagina saginoides], with a fragmentary moss cover and no lichens, located on gravelly, sandy, sometimes totally waterlogged soils, calcareous in Scandinavia, with prolonged snow-cover. Snow grass communities frequently occur as pioneer vegetation on small surfaces, very common in the central part of southern Norway and in Sweden from Jamtland northwards.', '(Steindorsson, 1965: 115-117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.4.2.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.3.2.3).');
    '[Nardus stricta] grasslands of the high altitudes of the Sudeten mountains (Krkonose, Hruby Jesenik), with [Carex bigelowii] ssp. [rigida] ([Carex rigida], [Carex fyllae]), [Hieracium alpinum], [Primula minima], [Potentilla aurea], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Lycopodium alpinum], and, in some formations, [Sphagnum nemoreum], [Sphagnum girgensohnii], [Polytrichum strictum].', '(Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 97-98, Table 13; Moravec y al., 1983: 55; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 94, 189; Krahulec y al., 1996: 67-69; Jenik and Jirasek, 1998: 228-232, 301-302).');
    'Flower-rich [Nardus stricta] grasslands of the high altitudes of the Sudeten mountains (Krkonose, Hruby Jesenik), with [Hieracium alpinum], [Campanula bohemica], [Viola sudetica], [Gentiana asclepiadea], [Homogyne alpina], [Potentilla aurea], [Pulsatilla alba], [Rhinanthus alpinus], [Solidago virgaurea], [Thesium alpinum], [Luzula sudetica].', '(Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 97-98, Table 13; Jenik y al., 1980: 9-10; Moravec y al., 1983: 55; Krahulec, 1990: 344; Krahulec y al., 1996: 63-66).');
    'Upper montane to low alpine [Nardus stricta] grasslands of the Sudeten mountains (Krkonose, Hruby Jesenik), developed at altitudes of 700-1100 m, comprising elements of high altitude [Nardion] grasslands, as well as of montane mesophile [Polygono-Trisetion] grasslands and collinar [Galio-Nardion] grasslands, with [Silene vulgaris], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Crepis succisifolia], [Silene dioica] ([Melandrium rubrum]), [Potentilla aurea], [Potentilla erecta], [Ranunculus acris], [Campanula bohemica], [Campanula rotundifolia], [Galium saxatile], [Hypericum maculatum], [Polygonum bistorta], [Leucanthemum vulgare], [Leontodon hispidus], [Hieracium lachenalii], [Gymnadenia conopsea], [Luzula luzuloides], [Luzula multiflora], [Carex pilulifera], [Agrostis capillaris], [Anthoxanthum odoratum].', '(Krahulec, 1990: 342; Krahulec y al., 1996: 57-61).');
    'Grasslands dominated by, or rich in, [Nardus stricta] of the Carpathian system.', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Coldea, 1987, 1991).');
    'Lightly managed hay meadows and pastures on both basicline and acidocline, nutrient-rich permanently or temporarily humid soils of middle European lowlands, hills and low mountains under Atlantic or sub-Atlantic climatic conditions, from the British Isles and northwestern Iberia east to Lithuania, in the Germano-Baltic plain, the Western and Central European Hercynian ranges, the Jura, the valleys and foothills of the Alps, the western Carpathians and the western Cantabro-Pyrenean range. Among the characteristic plant components of the highly diverse communities forming this unit are [Caltha palustris], [Cirsium palustre], [Cirsium rivulare], [Cirsium oleraceum], [Carduus personata], [Telekia speciosa], [Epilobium parviflorum], [Lychnis flos-cuculi], [Mentha aquatica], [Scirpus sylvaticus], [Stachys palustris], [Bromus racemosus], [Crepis paludosa], [Fritillaria meleagris], [Geum rivale], [Polygonum bistorta], [Senecio aquaticus], [Trollius europaeus], [Lotus uliginosus], [Trifolium dubium], [Equisetum palustre], [Equisetum telmateia], [Myosotis palustris], [Deschampsia cespitosa], [Angelica sylvestris], [Oenanthe silaifolia], [Gratiola officinalis], [Inula salicina], [Succisella inflexa], [Dactylorhiza majalis], [Ranunculus acris], [Rumex acetosa], [Holcus lanatus], [Alopecurus pratensis], [Festuca pratensis], [Festuca gigantea], [Juncus effusus], [Juncus filiformis]. ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Sougnez and Limbourg, 1963; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 572-594; Braun-Blanquet, 1967a; Archiloque y al., 1969; Noirfalise and Dethioux, 1972; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Balatova-Tulackova, 1975, 1983; Delpech, 1976; O''Sullivan, 1976a; Schumacker, 1976; Duvigneaud, 1976; Frileux, 1976; Sissingh, 1976; Bournérias y al., 1976; Delpech and Frileux, 1976; Wattez, 1976; Rose, 1976; De Sloover and Lebrun, 1976; Brasseur y al., 1978; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1980, 1985; De Sloover y al., 1980; Gorissen y al., 1983; Dethioux y al., 1983; Moravec y al., 1983; Kovar, 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b: 135-136, 216, 232; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993b; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Pott, 1992; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M22; Rodwell, 1992: units MG8, MG9, MG10; Julve, 1993; Ellmauer and Mucina, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Schubert y al., 1995; Seliskar, 1998: 16).');
