    'Steppes of the central and eastern Iranian Plateau, of the Kopet Dagh, the Pamir-Alai and the extreme western Tien-Shan, around the rim of the Ferghana basin and along the spur of the Karatau.', '(Saphronova, 1964b: unit 55; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 76; Walter, 1974: 256-283; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Steppes of the middle Lena basin of eastern Siberia, formed in regions of extreme continentality near the southern edge of the permafrost and the northern limit of the taiga belt.', '(Saphronova, 1964c: unit 33B [p.]; Walter, 1974; Grin y al., 1976: 25; Mirkin y al., 1985: 346, 354-371, 379-382; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Formations dominated by medium or tall perennnial tuft-forming grasses or suffrutescents, with lacunar ground cover, together with their associated therophyte communities developed on moving or fixed sands within the range of the continental Eurasian steppes (unit 34.9) and their areas of influence, or of the Mediterranean and sub-Mediterranean steppes of the zones of transition between the Mediterranean and southern Palaearctic desert zones. Most of these formations are associated with inland dune systems and define subdivisions of habitats listed under unit 64.7.', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974: 261-264, 297-302; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a, 1993b).');
    'Formations dominated by medium or tall perennnial tuft-forming grasses or suffrutescents, with lacunar ground cover, together with their associated therophyte communities developed on moving or fixed sands within the range of the Pannonic steppes (unit 34.91), thus in the Pannonic basin and the areas of preponderant influence of its communities. Most of these formations are associated with inland dune systems and define subdivisions of habitats listed under unit 64.71.', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974: 261-264, 297-302; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a, 1993b).');
    'Therophyte-dominated stages of the first succession phase in the colonisation of Pannonic sands, and in particular of Pannonic dunes (64.71), characterized by a very thin, low cover of mostly ephemereal, early-blooming annuals of small stature, among which [Bromus mollis], [Bromus tectorum], [Bromus squarrosus], [Medicago minima], [Cerastium brachypetalum], [Erophila verna], [Plantago indica], [Saxifraga tridactylites], [Poa annua], [Poa bulbosa], [Viola kitaibeliana], [Lithospermum arvense], [Corispermum nitidum], [Polygonum arenarium], with a few species of longer seasonal visibility, such as [Equisetum ramosissimum] var. [altissimum], [Alyssum tortuosum], [Sedum acre], [Cynodon dactylon].', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993b).');
    'Pioneer sand-swards of the northern Pannonic basin, dominated by [Bromus tectorum], with [Koeleria glauca], [Secale sylvestre], [Cynodon dactylon], [Polygonum arenarium], [Sedum urvillei], [Kochia laniflora], [Plantago arenaria], [Helichrysum arenarium], [Alyssum montanum] ssp. [gmelinii], [Alyssum alyssoides].
 ', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Resmerita y al., 1967;  Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szabo y al., 1985; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993b: 499-500).');
    'Pioneer sand-swards of the southern Pannonic basin, in particular of the Deliblat sand-steppe, dominated by [Corispermum nitidum] and [Polygonum arenarium]. ', '(Soo, 1959: 475 unit 1 [p.]; Horvat y al., 1974: 300-302).');
    'Pioneer sand-swards of the Pannonic basin, well characterized in the Seewinkel, dominated by [Equisetum ramosissimum], with [Scirpus holoschoenus] and small herbs. ', '(Soo, 1959: 475 unit 1a [p.]; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993b: 500-501).');
    'More or less open grasslands constituting the second stage of succession in the colonisation of Pannonic sands, in particular of Pannonic dunes (unit 64.71), best characterized in Hungary and the Vojvodina, with representatives in southern Slovakia, northeastern Austria and western Romania, dominated by the perennial grasses [Festuca vaginata], [Stipa capillata], [Stipa borysthenica], [Cleistogenes serotina], [Koeleria glauca], [Koeleria cristata], [Carex liparocarpos], accompanied by [Euphorbia seguierana], [Alkanna tinctoria], [Alyssum montanum] ssp. [gmelinii], [Dianthus serotinus], [Dianthus diutinus], [Gypsophila paniculata], [Scabiosa ochroleuca], [Astragalus austriacus], [Astragalus onobrychis], [Erysimum diffusum], [Fumana procumbens], [Minuartia glomerata], [Minuartia verna].', '(Soo, 1959, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Popescu and Sanda, 1987; Mucina and Kolbek, 1993a).');
    'Moss-heaths of Scandinavia, formed by carpets of [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] up to 10 cm thick, usually accompanied by lichens, mostly of genera [Cetraria], notably [Cetraria nivalis], and [Cladonia], and by scattered vascular plants, among which [Carex bigelowii], [Festuca vivipara], [Empetrum hermaphroditum] may be dominant or well represented. They are limited to the low alpine and middle alpine levels of mountains under maritime climates of southern and middle Scandinavia, developing on mixed sands and gravels with low lime content, pH in the order of 4.5 to 6.5, and a thin humus layer. They typically occupy small surfaces, of the order of 1-4 mý.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.2.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.1.2a).');
    'Carpets of [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] of the Scottish Highlands, most characteristic of the maritime western plateaux and the inner Hebrides, extending south, in the western British uplands, to the Southern Uplands, the Lake District and northern Wales, richer in grasses ([Festuca ovina], [Festuca vivipara], [Deschampsia flexuosa]) and with a less overwhelming dominance of [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] than in unit 36.32211, with a lesser abundance of lichens and a greater representation of subshrubs ([Vaccinium myrtillus], [Empetrum nigrum] ssp. [hermaphroditum]), characteristic of lower elevations and less exposed situations. Characteristic vascular plants include [Galium saxatile], [Potentilla erecta], [Carex pilulifera].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit E1c; Rodwell, 1992: unit U10a).');
    '[Rhacomitrium] moss-heaths of the northwest Scottish Highlands, of the Faeroe Islands and of Iceland, with outposts in the Central Highlands and the Southern Uplands, developed in conditions of high rainfall, early snow-thaw, prevalent cloudiness and harsh winds, with a sparse vascular cortŠge richer in cushion-herbs, poorer in [Carex bigelowii], grasses and lichens, than those of units 36.3221 and 36.3222.', '(Hadac, 1972: 350-357; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit E1b; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.2.4; Rodwell, 1992: unit U10c, 412-413; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.2.3).');
    '[Rhacomitrium] moss-heaths rich in cushion-herbs, often very open, with a fragmented moss carpet, a relative reduction of [Carex bigelowii] and few lichens, developed in conditions of high rainfall, early snow-thaw, prevalent cloudiness and harsh winds, most characteristic of the northwest Scottish Highlands, where they occupy exposed summits, ridges and spurs, also recorded in Ireland, with outposts in the Central Highlands and the Southern Uplands; [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] is the dominant moss; the characteristic cushion herbs and mat-formers include [Armeria maritima], [Silene acaulis], [Minuartia sedoides], [Thymus praecox] ssp. [arcticus], [Alchemilla alpina], [Salix herbacea]; other associates comprise [Carex bigelowii], [Juncus trifidus], [Polygonum viviparum], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus], [Aulacomnium turgidum], [Hypnum hamulosum].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit E1b; Rodwell, 1992: unit U10c, 412-413).');
    '[Rhacomitrium] moss-heaths of Iceland, where they colonize river gravels, stoney terrain and lava fields; [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] is the dominant moss in the heavy rainfall lowland areas, especially on lava fields, [Rhacomitrium canescens] in relatively lower rainfall areas of the highlands. Associated vascular plants may include [Armeria maritima], [Silene acaulis], [Thymus praecox] ssp. [arcticus], [Salix herbacea], [Cardaminopsis petraea], [Cerastium alpinum], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Galium normanii], [Polygonum viviparum], [Carex bigelowii], [Kobresia myosuroides], [Juncus trifidus], [Luzula spicata], [Festuca richardsonii], [Festuca vivipara], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Calluna vulgaris]. Lichens are not numerous, represented mostly by species of genera [Cetraria], [Cornicularia], [Cladonia], [Stereocaulon], [Peltigera], and by [Thamnolia vermicularis].', '(Hadac, 1972: 352-357; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.2.4; Bernhardt, 1986: 246-247; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.2.3).');
    '[Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] moss-heaths of the Faeroe Islands.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.2.2.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 1.1.2.3).');
    'Carpets of [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] of Greenland and Spitzbergen, developed under oceanic climates on well-stabilized noncalcareous stoney substrates, with an overwhelming dominance of mosses ([Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Dicranum elongatum], [Hylocomium alascanum]) and of lichens ([Thamnolia subuliformis], [Cladonia uncialis], [Cladonia gracilis], [Cetraria nivalis]), and few vascular plants, among which [Cardamine bellidifolia], [Luzula confusa], [Saxifraga cespitosa], [Salix polaris].', '(Trapnell, 1933; Hadac, 1989; Rodwell, 1992: 412-413).');
    'Lichen-rich communities of the Scottish Highlands, the Scandinavian mountains and Iceland, limited to stoney, acid substrates in exposed situations, such as granitic summital plateaux, summit detritus, steep screes, summit ridges, dominated by [Juncus trifidus] and [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] with [Carex bigelowii], [Salix herbacea], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Alchemilla alpina] and, sometimes, ericoid shrubs.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a, 1980: units C7, E1e; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 1.2.1.5, 1.3.1.5; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Hill, 1990; Rodwell, 1992: unit U9; Påhlsson, 1994: units 1.1.1.5, 1.2.1.5).');
    'Humid meadows of the Danube Delta, with [Molinia caerulea] ssp. [euxina], [Vicia biennis], [Cirsium alatum], [Erianthus adpressus], [Carex panicea], [Potentilla erecta], [Euphorbia lucida], [Symphytum officinale], [Pulicaria dysenterica], [Eleocharis palustris], [Orchis elegans] ([Orchis palustris] ssp. [elegans]).', '(Dihoru and Negrean, 1976; Sanda y al., 1980: 56; Sanda and Popescu, 1991).');
    'Humid formations of southern Moldavia, Oltenia and the Danube Delta, developed in broad interdunal depressions with an accumulation of calcic humus, dominated by [Scirpus holoschoenus] ([Holoschoenus vulgaris]), accompanied by a [Festucetalia vaginatae] cortŠge that includes [Plantago arenaria], [Anthemis ruthenica], [Euphorbia seguierana], [Dianthus polymorphus], [Carex ligerica], [Festuca arenicola], [Koeleria glauca], [Asperula setulosa], [Helianthemum nummularium], [Syrenia montana], [Minuartia setacea], [Salix rosmarinifolia].', '(Simon, 1960; Krausch, 1965; Dihoru and Negrean, 1976; Sanda y al., 1980: 79; Sanda y al., 1987; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 71; Donita and Ivan, 1992b: 96-97; Sanda y al., 1992: 131).');
    'Floodplain meadows of northern Russia, Bashkiria, Bielorussian Polesia.
', '(Korotkov y al., 1991: 153-157)');
    'Floodplain meadows of the semidesert regions of the Ponto-Caspian plains, in particular of the Don and Volga valleys.
', '(Golub and Mirkin, 1986; Korotkov y al., 1991: 151-153).');
