    'Cantabrian and peri-Cantabrian acidophilous [Quercus robur] or [Quercus petraea] forests, sometimes rich in [Betula celtiberica], [Quercus pyrenaica] or [Castanea sativa], with [Teucrium scorodonia], [Blechnum spicant], [Lonicera periclymenum], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Veronica officinalis], [Hypericum pulchrum], [Lathyrus montanus], [Melampyrum pratense], [Euphorbia dulcis], [Euphorbia amygdaloides], [Stellaria holostea], [Oxalis acetosella], [Pteridium aquilinum], [Dryopteris dilatata], [Dryopteris affinis], [Dryopteris aemula], [Oreopteris limbosperma], [Polypodium vulgare], [Ulex europaeus], [Ulex gallii], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Daboecia cantabrica], [Erica cinerea], [Erica vagans]. ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1974b; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Loidi Arregui, 1987; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987).');
    'Cantabro-Euskaldian collinar to montane [Quercus robur] forests. ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1974b; Loidi Arregui, 1987: 59; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 89).');
    'Continental xerophile woods of [Quercus robur] and [Acer tataricum] on leached chernozems of low hills of northeastern Romania, with [Acer campestre], [Pyrus pyraster], [Prunus avium] in the tree layer, [Prunus spinosa], [Euonymus europaeus], [Cornus sanguinea], [Prunus fruticosa], [Amygdalus nana] in the shrub layer and [Buglossoides purpurocaerulea] ([Lithospermum purpurocaeruleum]), [Viola hirta], [Vincetoxicum hirundinaria] ([Cynanchum vincetoxicum]), [Sedum maximum], [Fragaria viridis] in the herb layer.', '(Paschovschi and Donita, 1967; Ivan, 1992).');
    'Subcontinental forests of [Quercus robur], [Quercus petraea], [Acer tataricum] on grey soils of north-facing low hills of the wooded steppe region of northeastern Romania, with [Carpinus betulus], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Prunus avium], [Acer campestre], in the tree layer, [Cornus sanguinea], [Euonymus europaeus], [Rhamnus catharticus] in the shrub layer and [Carex pilosa], [Stellaria holostea], [Asarum europaeum], [Mercurialis perennis] in the herb layer.', '(Ivan, 1992). ');
    'Woods of [Quercus robur], [Tilia cordata], [Malus sylvestris], [Pyrus pyraster] with [Acer tataricum], [Prunus fruticosa], [Prunus spinosa], developed mostly on shady slopes and in humid gorges of the wooded steppe zone of the Ukraine and southern Russia, in particular in the Don region and the Busuluk depression east of the Volga, on marly and loess black earths (chernozems).', '(Walter, 1986: 32; Jahn, 1991: 453, 456). ');
    'Ultimate woodland representation at the southern edge of the wooded steppe zone, formed by low, crooked [Quercus robur] occasionally associated with [Acer campestre], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Ulmus minor], covered with lichens and interspersed with thorny bushes, [Prunus spinosa], [Crataegus monogyna], [Rhamnus catharticus], [Rosa spp].', '(Walter, 1986: 32; Jahn, 1991: 456). ');
    'Xero-thermophile oak woods of the pre-Carpathian hills fringing the lower Danube and Prut basins.', NULL);
    'Neutrophile [Quercus pubescens] woods of the sylvosteppic plains and low hills of southern Romania and the Moldova Republic, with [Buglossoides purpurocaerulea] ([Lithospermum purpurocaeruleum]), and other sub-Mediterranean species, including [Cotinus coggygria], [Achillea coarctata], [Asparagus verticillatus].

', '(Borza, 1966; Jakucs and Feckete, 1958). ');
    'Neutrophile [Quercus pubescens] woods of Muntenia, with [Prunus mahaleb], [Acer campestre] in the tree layer, [Cornus mas], [Crataegus monogyna], [Ligustrum vulgare] in the shrub layer, [Buglossoides purpurocaerulea] ([Lithospermum purpurocaeruleum]), [Vincetoxicum hirundinaria] ([Cynanchum vincetoxicum]), [Origanum vulgare], [Poa angustifolia] in the herb layer.
', '(Jakucs and Fekete, 1957; Sanda y al., 1980: 135; Popescu y al., 1984).');
    'Thermophilous oak woods of the wooded steppe zones of northern Crimea and the northern piedmont of the Caucasus, in the transition region from the Euro-Siberian steppes to the Euxinian montane vegetations.', '(Walter, 1974: 353-354, 372-376).');
    'Xero-thermophile oak woods of the Mediterraneo-steppic transition zone of central and eastern Anatolia and Iran. ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973; Noirfalise, 1987; Walter and Breckle, 1991c). ');
    'Steppe forests of Anatolia in which dominant trees of Mediterranean affinities are accompanied by mostly Irano-Turanian steppe elements. ', '(Zohary, 1973: 579-582; Noirfalise, 1987: units S13, S14).');
    '[Quercus anatolica]-dominated forests and woods of presteppic regions of Anatolia, under semiarid climate conditions of 300-600 mm annual precipitation, 3 dry months and 2-4 months of snow cover, usually occupying calcareous substrates between 800-900 m and 1100-1300 m; the species cortŠge is rich in leguminous plants, including [Vicia cracca] ssp. [stenophylla], [Trifolium panormitanum] ssp. [elongatum], [Coronilla varia], [Lathyrus digitalis], typically with [Pyrus elaeagnifolia], [Colutea cilicia], [Jasminum fruticans], [Paliurus australis], [Falcaria rivini], and frequently infiltrated by spiny [Astragalus] steppe elements; on compacted andesites, notably north and northeast of Ankara, the oaks are accompanied by [Viburnum lantana], [Trifolium medium], [Primula vulgaris], [Fragaria vesca].', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit S13). ');
    'Oak forests and woods of the presteppic periphery of the Anatolian plateau, mostly characteristic of the southern piedmont of the Anti-Taurus, with representatives in the central Pontic valleys, developed under semiarid climate conditions of 5-7 dry, cool or cold months, characterized by submediterranean elements, including [Quercus calliprinos], [Arbutus andrachne], [Rhamnus graecus], [Rhamnus alaternus], [Jasminum fruticans], [Rhus coraria], [Asparagus aphyllus], [Juniperus oxycedrus]; in the great interior valleys [Juniperus excelsa] and [Juniperus foetidissima] play an important role, associating with [Quercus syspirensis], [Pistacia atlantica], [Crataegus orientalis] in the interior valleys of the Pontic range, or with [Pinus brutia] in the Taurus.', '(Zohary, 1973: 500-532; Noirfalise, 1987: unit S14). ');
    'Humid beech forests of high, snowy dolomitic and calcareous sierras of Galicia (Ancares, Cebreiro, Caurel), somewhat intermediate between unit 41.12 and unit 41.13. ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Izco, 1987).');
    'Humid acidophilous beech forests of the Northern Iberian Range. ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987: 137).');
    'Hyper-humid acidophilous beech forests of the Northern Iberian Range. ', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987: 137-138).');
    'Relict acidophilous beech forests of the Sierra de Ayllon.', '(Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Peinado Lorca and Martinez Parras, 1987: 180, 188-189; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987: 438).');
    '[Fagus sylvatica] and, in higher mountains, [Fagus sylvatica]-[Abies alba] or [Fagus sylvatica]-[Abies alba]-[Picea abies] forests developed on neutral or near-neutral soils, with mild humus (mull), of the medio-European and Atlantic domaines of Western Europe and of central and northern Central Europe, characterized by a strong representation of species belonging to the ecological groups of [Anemone nemorosa], of [Lamium galeobdolon], of [Galium odoratum] and [Melica uniflora] and, in mountains, various [Dentaria spp.], forming a richer and more abundant herb layer than in the forests of units 41.11 and 41.12.', '(Vanden Berghen and Coûteaux, 1955; Dagnelie y al., 1960; Noirfalise, 1962, 1984, 1986, 1987; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1963; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Sougnez, 1967; Tanghe, 1967, 1968, 1970; Dethioux, 1969; Coûteaux, 1969; Renault, 1978; Rogister, 1978, 1981; Ozenda, 1979, 1982, 1985; Bournérias, 1979; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Ozenda y al., 1979; Soo, 1980; Timbal, 1981; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 112; Moravec y al., 1982; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Neutrocline or basicline [Fagus sylvatica] and [Fagus sylvatica]-[Quercus petraea]-[Quercus robur] forests of hills, low mountains and plateaux of the Hercynian arc and its peripheral regions, of the Jura, Lorraine, the Paris basin, Burgundy, the Alpine piedmont, the Carpathians and a few localities of the North Sea-Baltic plain.', '(Vanden Berghen and Coûteaux, 1955; Dagnelie y al., 1960; Noirfalise, 1962, 1984, 1986, 1987; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1963; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Sougnez, 1967; Tanghe, 1967, 1968, 1970; Dethioux, 1969; Coûteaux, 1969; Renault, 1978; Rogister, 1978, 1981; Ozenda, 1979, 1982, 1985; Bournérias, 1979; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Ozenda y al., 1979; Soo, 1980; Timbal, 1981; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Moravec y al., 1982; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994; Moravec, 1998a).');
    'Slightly moist [Fagus sylvatica] forests developed over calcareous bedrock on stony, neutral or weakly acid rendzina or similar humus-carbonate soils, with [Galium odoratum], [Melica uniflora], [Mercurialis perennis], [Lathyrus vernus], [Asarum europaeum], [Hordelymus europaeus], [Epipactis helleborine], [Epipactis leptochila], [Neottia nidus-avis], [Circaea lutetiana], [Viola reichenbachiana], distributed locally on the hills, low mountains and plateaux of the Hercynian arc and its peripheral regions, from the Ardenne-Eifel to Moravia, and north to Denmark and southern Sweden, in the entire Jura catena, in Lorraine and the eastern Paris basin, in Burgundy, in the Bavarian Alpine piedmont, the Vorarlberg limestone Alps, the Wienerwald. They include the Central European [Fagus]-[Mercurialis perennis] forests, as well as occasional stands exceptionally rich in spring-flowering geophytes, sometimes known as wild garlic-rich beech woods.', '(Thill, 1964: 32-34, 37; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 112; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.1.3, Moravec y al., 1982; Noirfalise, 1984: units IV.2.3.4, IV.2.3.5; Ellenberg, 1988: 74, 75, 76-86; Oberdorfer, 1992b, 1994; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.2.3; Moravec, 1998a: 130-133, unit 21).');
    '[Fagus sylvatica] forests of sub-Atlantic Western and Central Europe, north to Denmark, southern Norway, southern Sweden and Poland, developed on a more or less deep layer of brown loess-loam, less rich in calciphile plants and richer in acid- and drought-tolerant species; [Melica uniflora] (in northern formations) and [Galium odoratum] are usually well represented. ', '(Moravec y al., 1982;  Noirfalise, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 112; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.1.2; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1992b, 1994; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.2.2; Moravec, 1998a).');
    'Neutrocline [Fagus sylvatica] forests rich in [Melica uniflora] of the northern and northwestern part of the Hercynian and Germano-Baltic range of the medio-European woodruff beech forests, in particular, in the Ardennes, northern Germany and Denmark. ', '(Noirfalise, 1984: units IV.2.3.1, IV.2.3.2, IV.2.3.3; Ellenberg, 1988: 104). ');
    'Neutrocline [Fagus sylvatica] forests of the central and eastern part of the Hercynian, Jurassian and peri-Alpine range of the woodruff beech forests. ', '(Ellenberg, 1988: 104; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Moravec, 1998a: 116-119, unit 16).');
    'Neutrocline [Fagus sylvatica] forests of the southwestern part of the range of the Medio-European woodruff beech forests, rich in, and sometimes entirely dominated by, [Carex brizoides].', '(Ellenberg, 1988: 104). ');
    'Sub-Atlantic and medio-European forests of [Quercus robur] and [Quercus petraea], with [Carpinus betulus], developed on meso-oligotrophic soils, less hydromorphic than those occupied by the often sympatric forests of unit 41.23, characterized by the replacement of the groups of [Primula elatior] and [Lamium galeobdolon], well represented in the forests of unit 41.23, by those of [Deschampsia flexuosa] and of [Maianthemum bifolium], transgressives from the [Quercion]. They constitute the prevalent oak-hornbeam forests of the M?nster basin, the Rhenish and Mosan regions, the northwestern Hercynian lands, Lorraine and the eastern Paris basin, Burgundy.', '(Breton, 1957; Vanden Berghen and Mullenders, 1957b; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Tanghe, 1964b, 1967, 1968, 1970; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Sougnez, 1967; Noirfalise, 1968; Couteaux, 1969; Duvigneaud and Denayer-De Smet, 1970; Sougnez, 1973, 1978; Bugnon and Rameau, 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Ozenda y al., 1979; Rameau and Timbal, 1979; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984: 111-117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.2.2.2, 2.2.2.2a; Noirfalise, 1987: units D3 [p.], D4 [p.], D6 [p.], D7 [p.], F3 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 181; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 159-166; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.2.3.2, 2.2.3.2a; Schubert y al., 1995: 83).');
    'Typical sub-Atlantic [Quercus robur]-[Quercus petraea]-[Carpinus betulus] forests of northern Europe, north to southern Norway, southern Sweden and southern Finland, and of the eastern Paris basin and Lorraine, with [Stellaria holostea], [Carex brizoides], [Narcissus pseudonarcissus], [Polygonatum verticillatum], [Potentilla sterilis], [Ranunculus nemorosus], [Poa chaixii], [Luzula sylvatica], [Luzula luzuloides]. ', '(Noirfalise, 1984: units V.4.3.1, V.4.3.3 [p.]; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.2.2.2, 2.2.2.2a; Noirfalise, 1987: units D3 [p.], F3 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 181; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 159-166; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.2.3.2, 2.2.3.2a; Schubert y al., 1995: 83).');
    'Oak-hornbeam forests of Lorraine marls, with [Quercus robur], [Carpinus betulus], [Acer campestre], [Sorbus torminalis], [Lonicera xylosteum], [Galium odoratum], [Carex umbrosa], [Pulmonaria obscura] and [Ornithogalum pyrenaicum]. ', '(Noirfalise, 1984: unit V.4.3.3 [p.]; Noirfalise, 1987: units D4 [p.]).');
    '[Quercus robur]-[Quercus petraea]-[Carpinus betulus] forests of the mesozoic hills and plateaux of northwestern Burgundy (Nivernais, Langres plateau, Barrois, Morvan piedmont).', '(Noirfalise, 1987: units D6 [p.]).');
    '[Quercus robur]-[Quercus petraea]-[Carpinus betulus] forests of the Sa¿ne plain in southern Burgundy and Bresse, of the southern Lyonnais and of the Limagne basin, including the outstanding multicentury-old stands of CŒteaux and similar stations.', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit D7 [p.]).');
    'Sub-Atlantic forests of [Quercus robur] and [Quercus petraea], mostly low-canopied, with [Carpinus betulus], [Sorbus torminalis], [Betula pendula], [Populus tremula] in the subcanopy or the understorey, developed on soils with an alternating hydric regime, mostly clays derived from the alteration of Devonian schists, characterized by the abundance of [Carex flacca] and the coexistence of acidocline and calcicline species, typical of the sub-Hercynian Fagne-Famenne depression where they constitute a highly distinctive, almost continuous, forest-belt. ', '(Thill, 1964: 37-39; Noirfalise, 1968; Sougnez, 1978; Noirfalise, 1984: unit V.4.3.2; Duvigneaud and Saintenoy-Simon, 1987: 50).');
    '[Quercus robur] or [Quercus petraea] forests of eutrophic or mesotrophic soils of subcontinental and continental northern and central Central Europe and of Eastern Europe. [Carpinus betulus] is generally present in their western representatives, widespread in Central Europe and western Eastern Europe. They are richer in lime, [Tilia cordata], than the sub-Atlantic forests of units 41.23, 41.24 and 41.25. They are of more northern character in their area of mutual approach than the Balkanic forests of unit 41.2C. Their southern limit of occurrence follows the Carpathian arc, the northern rim of the Podolian plateaux, and, farther east, the southern limit of nemoral forests.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Noirfalise, 1968; Neuh¿usl and Neuh¿uslova-Novotna, 1973;  Richard, 1974; Ozenda and Wagner, 1975; Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Noirfalise, 1987: D5 [p.], D9 [p.]; Jahn, 1991: 418, 453 5b-6; Korotkov y al., 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 128-131).');
    '[Quercus petraea]-[Carpinus betulus] forests of regions with subcontinental climate within the central European range of [Fagus sylvatica], such as the Upper Rhine plain, the rain shadows of the Harz, Rh¿n and Spessart, the Swabian-Franconian basin, the Bavarian plateau and Thuringe, the Austrian northern pre-Alps and the Wienerwald, the Polish central lowlands and adjacent hills of Silesia, Great Poland and Kujawy, dominated by [Quercus petraea] and with [Sorbus torminalis], [Sorbus domestica], [Acer campestre], [Ligustrum vulgare], [Convallaria majalis], [Carex montana], [Carex umbrosa], [Festuca heterophylla]. ', '(Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 107; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 159-160, 166-171; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 131-133).');
    'Lime-oak forests of Central and Eastern Europe developed in regions of continental climate east of the range of [Fagus sylvatica], but within that of [Carpinus betulus], in Poland, Lithuania, Belarus, Ukraine and Russia, with [Quercus petraea], [Quercus robur], [Tilia cordata], [Acer platanoides], [Carpinus betulus].						', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988: 148-150; Korotkov y al., 1991: 298-299; Jahn, 1991: 403).');
    'Galicio-Asturian collinar to montane [Quercus robur] forests, richer in western Iberian species such as [Linaria triornitophora], [Omphalodes nitida], [Saxifraga spathularis], than the forests of unit 41.5621. ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1974b; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b: 89-92; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 89).');
    'Oro-Cantabrian montane [Quercus petraea] forests. ', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1974b; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 101).');
