    'Neutrophilous [Fagus sylvatica] or [Fagus moesiaca] and [Abies alba] forests of the higher altitudes of the montane level of the Pelagonids.', '(Horvat y al., 1974; Ozenda, 1975, 1979; Em, 1985; Hoda y al., 1998: 15).');
    'Neutrophilous [Fagus sylvatica] or [Fagus moesiaca] and [Carpinus betulus] forests of the Pelagonids.', '(Em, 1968).');
    'Forests of [Quercus petraea], [Quercus robur] and [Carpinus betulus] of low hills of the central Transylvanian plateau, with [Prunus avium], [Acer tataricum], [Acer campestre] in the tree layer, [Viburnum lantana], [Cornus sanguinea], [Ligustrum vulgare], [Staphylea pinnata] in the shrub layer, [Vincetoxicum hirundinaria] ([Cynanchum vincetoxicum]), [Melittis melissophyllum], [Stellaria holostea], [Ranunculus auricomus], [Asarum europaeum] in the herb layer.', '(Soo, 1951; Zolyomi, 1957; Borza, 1959; Donita, 1992: unit 21; Donita and Ivan, 1992a; Coldea, 1992: 151; Donita and Coldea, 1992; Ivan, 1992; Coldea and Chifu, 1994).
');
    'Forests of [Quercus petraea] [s.l.], [Quercus robur] and [Carpinus betulus], usually with [Tilia tomentosa], of the plateaux and eastern Carpathian foothills of Moldavia, of the Dobrojea plateau, of the plateaux, Southern Carpathian foothills and, locally, plains of Muntenia and Oltenia, west to the western Getic piedmont, characterized by a cortŠge richer in sub-Mediterranean or sub-Pontic species than that of the forests of unit 41.2C1.  ', '(Sanda y al., 1980; Donita, 1992; Coldea and Chifu, 1994).');
    'Forests of [Quercus robur] and [Carpinus betulus] of the plains, plateaux and foothills of Muntenia and, locally, of the hills and plateaux of Romanian Moldavia and the Moldova Republic, with [Tilia tomentosa], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Tilia cordata] in the tree layer and a cortŠge of [Carpinion] species, in particular, [Stellaria holostea], [Carex pilosa], [Ranunculus auricomus], accompanied by the thermophilous [Arum orientale], [Lathyrus venetus], [Scutellaria altissima], [Carpesium cernuum], [Potentilla micrantha], [Lychnis coronaria].', '(Geideman y al., 1964; Dobrescu and Kovacs, 1973; Donita, 1992: units 13, 18; Donita and Ivan, 1992a; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992; Sanda y al., 1992; Donita and Coldea, 1992; Coldea and Chifu, 1994).');
    'Forests of [Quercus petraea], [Carpinus betulus] and [Tilia tomentosa], of the plateaux and Carpathian foothills of Romanian Moldavia and the Moldova Republic, of the Dobrogea plateau and, locally, of the foothills of Muntenia, with [Quercus robur], [Quercus dalechampii], [Quercus polycarpa], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Fraxinus excelsior] ssp. [coriariifolia] ([Fraxinus coriariifolia]) in the tree layer, and with an herb layer comprised of [Carpinion] species, such as [Stellaria holostea], [Carex pilosa], together with thermophile species, including [Scutellaria altissima], [Carex brevicollis], [Carpesium cernuum], [Potentilla micrantha], [Buglossoides purpurocaerulea] ([Lithospermum purpurocaeruleum]).', '(Dihoru and Donita, 1970; Dobrescu and Kovacs, 1973; Geideman y al., 1964; Donita, 1992: units 14, 15, 16; Donita and Ivan, 1992a, 1992b; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992; Coldea and Chifu, 1994).');
    'Oak-hornbeam forests dominated by [Quercus petraea] [s.l.], [Quercus robur], [Quercus cerris], and sometimes [Quercus frainetto], of somewhat humid sites, shady slopes and narrow valleys of the [Quercion frainetto] zone of Serbia, Bulgaria and Romania; they are characterized by a distinctly middle European cortŠge comprising [Carpinus betulus], [Acer campestre], [Prunus avium], [Corylus avellana], [Euonymus europaeus], [Lonicera caprifolium], [Helleborus odorus], [Cruciata glabra] and [Ranunculus ficaria] to which are associated various sub-Mediterranean and Ponto-Pannonic elements.', '(Donita and Dihoru, 1970; Dobrescu and Kovacs, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 240-242, 248-251; Jahn, 1991; Bondev, 1991).');
    'Forests dominated by [Quercus dalechampii], accompanied by [Carpinus betulus], widespread in the xeromesophytic durmast oak-hornbeam, 600-1200 metre, belt of the Balkan Range and its northern and northwestern spurs and satellites of northwestern Bulgaria and eastern Serbia, the Anti-Balkan (Sredna Gora) and neighbouring hills, the southeastern Dinarides, the Moeso-Macedonian mountains, the Rhodopides and the Sakar range of central Thrace, more humid than the [Carpinus orientalis]-[Quercus dalechampii] forests of unit 41.76831, accompanied by a distinctly middle-European cortŠge, comprising as local characteristics, [Acer campestre], [Prunus avium], [Corylus avellana], [Crataegus monogyna], [Cornus sanguinea], [Helleborus odorus], [Stellaria holostea], [Cruciata glabra], [Melica uniflora], [Poa nemoralis], [Dactylis glomerata], [Festuca heterophylla].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 248-251; Bondev, 1991: unit 56).');
    'Oak-hornbeam forests dominated by [Quercus petraea] [s.l.], [Quercus cerris], and sometimes [Quercus frainetto], of the [Quercion frainetto] zone of Serbia, northern Bulgaria and the Southern Carpathian foothills and valleys of Romania, characterized by a strong representation of thermophile species, in particular, of species of the [Quercion frainetto] constellation, including [Tilia tomentosa], [Sorbus torminalis], [Pyrus pyraster], [Acer tataricum], [Cornus mas], [Nectaroscordum siculum], together with medio-European [Carpenion betuli] or [Fagetalia] species.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 240-242).');
    'Forests of [Quercus petraea] and [Carpinus betulus] of the Olt, Jiu and Cerna valleys of the Getic piedmont of the Southern Carpathians, developed on sunny, moderate slopes and slightly acid leached brown soils, with [Tilia tomentosa], [Tilia cordata] and [Fagus sylvatica] sporadically present in the tree layer, and with a cortŠge that includes the characteristic [Galium kitaibelianum], [Galium baillonii], [Veronica bachofenii], the acidophile [Luzula luzuloides], [Calamagrostis arundinacea], [Deschampsia flexuosa] and the thermophile [Primula columnae], [Potentilla micrantha], [Aremonia agrimonoides], [Lychnis coronaria].', '(Coldea and Chifu, 1994).');
    '[Quercus pyrenaica] formations of medio-European character, of the collinar and montane levels of the Cantabrian chain and its satellite ranges west to the Sierra de Picos de Ancares in Galicia, characteristic of areas with comparatively low precipitation, in the rain shadow of the coastward ranges or the interior oro-Cantabrian hills. ', '(Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Meson, 1982, 1983; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b: 92; Loidi Arregui, 1987: 61-62; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 91; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987: 138-139; Izco, 1987: 398).');
    '[Quercus pyrenaica] forests of the sub-Mediterranean siliceous enclaves of the Maestrazgo and eastern Catalonian ranges, reduced to a very few relicts in the Penagolosa and Prades massifs. ', '(Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Meson, 1982, 1983; Peinado Lorca and Martinez Parras, 1987: 180, 187; Costa, 1987: 303). ');
    '[Quercus pyrenaica] forests of siliceous supra-Mediterranean areas with sub-humid climate of the western Sierra Nevada, the Sierra de Alfacar, the northern flancs of the Sierra de Cazulas and the Sierra Tejeda; in more humid locations [Fraxinus angustifolius] and [Acer granatense] accompany [Quercus pyrenaica]. ', '(Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Meson, 1982, 1983; Martinez Parras and Peinado Lorca, 1987). ');
    '[Quercus pyrenaica] forests of southwestern France north to the Sologne where they constitute relatively estensive formations on poor soils, with [Betula pendula], [Lonicera periclymenum], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Holcus mollis], [Molinia caerulea], [Teucrium scorodonia].', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1967c). ');
    '[Quercus pyrenaica] forests of the western Rif and of the Tangier area, pure or mixed with [Quercus canariensis], [Quercus suber] or [Quercus ilex], mist-bound and rich in ferns, in particular, [Polystichum aculeatum], [Asplenium adiantum-nigrum], [Athyrium filix-femina], [Blechnum spicant], [Pteridium aquilinum].', '(Herbauts, 1973: 348-349; Knapp, 1973: 480; White, 1983: 157; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 41; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 83-84). ');
    'Forests or woods of submediterranean climate regions and supramediterranean altitudinal levels, and of western Eurasian steppe and substeppe zones, dominated by deciduous or semideciduous thermophilous [Quercus] species; they may, under local microclimatic or edaphic conditions, replace the evergreen oak forests in mesomediterranean or thermomediterranean areas, and irradiate far north into medio-European or sub-Atlantic regions. ', '(Oberdorfer, 1947; Duvigneaud, 1953; Jakucs, 1960; Horvat, 1962; Rey y al., 1963; Vanden Berghen, 1963; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Archiloque y al., 1970; Fenaroli, 1970; Debazac and Mavrommatis, 1971; Barbero y al., 1971; Tomaselli, 1973, 1981a; Tombal, 1974; Horvat y al., 1974; Tosco, 1975; Ozenda and Wagner, 1975; Ozenda, 1975; Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1984, 1986, 1987; Soo, 1980; Peinado-Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Chytry and Vicherek, 1995; Kolbek y al., 1997; Chytry, 1997; Chytry y al., 1998; Chytry, 1998; Chytry and Kolbek, 1998).');
    '[Quercus pubescens] forests and woods of the supra-Mediterranean zone of France, west of the Alpine arc, and of northeastern Spain, with irradiations to southern Germany and Belgium. Low medio-European forests of [Quercus petraea] or [Quercus robur] occupying warm exposures beyond the range of [Quercus pubescens] and linked to the [Quercion pubescenti-petraeae] by the presence of [Buxus sempervirens] or other thermophile calcicolous plants, including [Limodorum abortivum], [Melittis melissophyllum]. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1953; Rey y al., 1963; Vanden Berghen, 1963; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Archiloque y al., 1970; Barbero y al., 1971; Tomaselli, 1981a; Tombal, 1974; Ozenda and Wagner, 1975; Ozenda, 1975; Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1984, 1986, 1987; Loidi Arregui, 1987; Bolos y Capdevila, 1987; Vigo and Ninot, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Chytry, 1997; Chytry y al., 1998).');
    '[Quercus pubescens] ssp. [pubescens] forests and woods of sub- and supra-Mediterranean regions of France, and of thermal stations in more northerly locations of Western Europe. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1953; Rey y al., 1963; Vanden Berghen, 1963; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Archiloque y al., 1970; Barbero y al., 1971; Tomaselli, 1981a; Tombal, 1974; Ozenda and Wagner, 1975; Ozenda, 1975; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1984, 1986, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1992b).');
    '[Quercus pubescens] ssp. [pubescens] forests and woods of sub- and supra-Mediterranean regions of France. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1953; Rey y al., 1963; Vanden Berghen, 1963; Archiloque y al., 1970; Barbero y al., 1971; Tomaselli, 1981a; Ozenda and Wagner, 1975; Ozenda, 1975; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Oberdorfer, 1992b).');
    '[Quercus pubescens] ssp. [pubescens] forests and woods of thermal stations in the nemoral zone of France, Belgium, Luxemburg and western Germany. ', '(Thill, 1964: 17-20; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Tombal, 1974; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1984: unit VII.2; Ellenberg, 1988: 176; Oberdorfer, 1992b).');
    'Thermophilous [Quercus petraea] or [Quercus robur] and [Quercus pubescens] woods of the western and northern periphery of the Hercynian arc in Lorraine, the Ardenne periphery and southern Germany, northeast to extreme northwestern Poland, in the Oder Valley.', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 231, 108-109; Noirfalise, 1984: unit VII.3; Matuszkiewicz and Kozlowska, 1991: 203-256; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Pott, 1992: 387-388).');
    'Communities of the montane and subalpine levels of high and moderately high mountains of the Alpine system and neighbouring ranges, dominated by tall grasses of genus [Calamagrostis], accompanied by a species cortŠge similar to that of the subalpine tall-herb communities.', '(Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984; Sanda y al., 1980; Moravec y al., 1983; Ozenda, 1985; Ellenberg, 1988; Belohlovkova and Fiserova, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a; Coldea, 1991; Karner and Mucina, 1993).');
    'Thermophile, meso-xerophile species-rich, abundantly flowering, often primary   formations of steep adrets of the subalpine level of the Alps, the Jura, the great Hercynian ranges and the Central Massif, the Dinarides, the Pelagonides,  the Moeso-Macedonian mountains, the Rhodopides, the Balkan Range, mostly dominated by [Calamagrostis arundinacea], associated with plants such as [Senecio doronicum], [Digitalis grandiflora], [Hieracium aurantiacum], [Hieracium prenanthoides], [Aconitum vulparia], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Bupleurum longifolium], [Galium boreale], [Lilium martagon], [Pimpinella major], [Rosa pendulina], [Sorbus sudetica], [Sorbus aria], [Sorbus mougeotii], [Sorbus chamaemespilus].  ', '(Wendelberger, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974: 584; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 95-97; Jenik y al., 1980: 11-12; Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984; Moravec y al., 1983; Ozenda, 1985; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a; Karner and Mucina, 1993; Meshinev y al., 1995; Hoda y al., 1998: 20).');
    'Communities of the montane and subalpine levels of the Alps, the Sudeten, the Carpathians, the Rhodopes, dominated by [Calamagrostis villosa], accompanied by a tall-herb species cortŠge usually less rich in woodland edge and short grassland species than those of the [Calamagrostion arundinaceae]; characteristic species include [Adenostyles alliariae], [Peucedanum ostruthium], [Geum montanum], [Homogyne alpina], [Ligusticum mutellina], [Potentilla aurea], [Phleum rhaeticum], [Agrostis schraderana], [Dianthus superbus] ssp. [alpestris], [Hieracium prenanthoides], [Hieracium aureum], [Molinia caerulea], [Ranunculus platanifolius], [Silene vulgaris], [Solidago virgaurea] ssp. [minuta].', '(Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 94-95; Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984; Sanda y al., 1980; Jenik y al., 1980: 10-11; Moravec y al., 1983: 15-16; Ellenberg, 1988; Belohlovkova and Fiserova, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990, 1993a; Coldea, 1991: 445; Karner and Mucina, 1993; Meshinev y al., 1995).');
    'Communities of the montane and subalpine levels of the Carpathians dominated by tall fescues, accompanied by a species cortŠge similar to that of the subalpine tall-herb communities.', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984; Sanda y al., 1980; Belohlovkova and Fiserova, 1989; Coldea, 1991).');
    'Tall, two-layered, closed [Festuca carpatica]-dominated grasslands of the northwestern and eastern Carpathians, developed on shallow stony soils overlying basic rocks, on steep slopes subjected to long snow cover, in particular, in avalanche troughs, physiognomically and ecologically similar to small reed grasslands of the [Calamagrostion arundinaceae] [s.l.], but with a species cortŠge characteristic in part of the calciphile grasslands of the [Seslerion tatrae] and the [Festuco saxatilis-Seslerion bielzii].', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Belohlovkova and Fiserova, 1989; Coldea, 1991: 400-401). ');
    'Mesophile tall grass community of the subalpine and upper montane levels of the Romanian and Ukrainian Carpathians dominated by [Festuca porcii], with [Calamagrostis villosa], [Festuca picta], [Knautia longifolia] and regional species such as [Campanula patula] ssp. [abietina], [Hypericum richeri] ssp. [grisebachii], [Achillea distans], [Festuca pratensis] ssp. [apennina], [Scorzonera purpurea] ssp. [rosea] ([Scorzonera rosea]).', '(Sanda y al., 1980; Coldea, 1991: 446-447).');
    'Communities of the upper montane and subalpine levels of the Sudeten, the Carpathians, the Dinarides, the Balkan Range, the Rhodopides and, locally, of the Alps, dominated by [Deschampsia cespitosa], accompanied by a species cortŠge similar to that of the subalpine tall-herb communities.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 580, 583, 610; Matuszkiewicz, 1980, 1984; Sanda y al., 1980; Jenik y al., 1980: 12; Moravec y al., 1983: 17; Coldea, 1991: 446; Karner and Mucina, 1993: 496; Meshinev y al., 1995; Seliskar, 1998: 9).');
    'Communities of the subalpine or alpine level of the Sudeten, in particular, of the Giant Mountains (Krkonose, Karkonosze) and the Jesenik Mountains, dominated by [Molinia caerulea], accompanied by a species cortŠge comprising representatives of the [Betulo-Adenostyletea], the [Molinietalia], the [Phragmitetalia] and the [Caricetalia fuscae], in particular, [Deschampsia caespitosa] and [Phragmites australis].', '(Jenik y al., 1980: 22; Moravec y al., 1983: 16).');
    'Subalpine and alpine meso-hygrophile tall herb formations of the Pyrenees, the Cantabrian mountains, the Cordillera Central, the Iberian Range, with [Valeriana pyrenaica] and [Adenostyles alliariae] ssp. [hybrida] ([Adenostyles alliariae] ssp. [pyrenaica]). ', '(Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Gruber, 1978; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Ozenda, 1985; Martinez Parras y al., 1987; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987).');
