    '[Fagus orientalis]-[Abies nordmannia] forests of ubacs of the 1400-2200 m level of the northern flank of the Great Caucasus, with [Ulmus glabra], [Rhododendron luteum], [Euonymus latifolia], [Rubus caucasicus], [Galium odoratum], [Aruncus sylvestris], [Salvia glutinosa], [Polygonatum multiflorum], [Polygonatum polyanthemum], [Viola reichenbachiana], [Epilobium montanum], [Pulmonaria dacica], [Geranium robertianum], [Paris incompleta], [Mycelis muralis], [Ranunculus astrantifolius], [Festuca drymaea], [Festuca altissima], [Dryopteris filix-mas], [Dryopteris carthusiana].', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 536-538; Korotkov y al., 1991: 304; Röhrig, 1991h: 534).');
    '[Fagus orientalis]-[Abies nordmannia] forests of acid podzolized soils of the Great and central Caucasus, with [Daphne glomerata], [Vaccinium arctostaphylos], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Orthilia secunda], [Pyrola media], [Luzula sylvatica].', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 536-538; Korotkov y al., 1991: 305; Röhrig, 1991h: 534).');
    'Beech-dominated facies of the [Fagus orientalis]-[Quercus petraea]-[Carpinus caucasica] forests of the 1200-1300 m level of the southern flank of the Central Caucasus of central Georgia, with [Clinopodium vulgare], [Primula macrocalyx], [Salvia glutinosa], [Fragaria vesca], [Epilobium montanum], [Melica uniflora], [Poa nemoralis]. More mixed or hornbeam-dominated stands are listed in unit 41.H311.', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 536-538; Korotkov y al., 1991: 306; Röhrig, 1991h: 534).');
COMMIT;
    'Forests of [Fagus orientalis] on north slopes of the Elburz Mountains, at the 1400-1800 metre level, under the climatic influence of the Caspian Sea, with cool temperatures and moderate annual precipitation, typically with abundant snowfall; the beech is either accompanied by [Acer insigne], [Alnus subcordata], [Carpinus betulus], [Quercus castaneifolia], [Sorbus torminalis], [Taxus baccatus], [Ulmus glabra], or growing in pure formations, the presence of other tree species diminishing towards the upper altitudinal levels; a luxurient understorey includes [Ilex hyrcanica], [Daphne pontica], [Vaccinium arctostaphylos].', '(Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 241; Röhrig, 1991h: 535).');
    'Isolated beech forests of the Taurus system in western and southern Anatolia (Muraldag, Garur Daglari). ', '(Röhrig, 1991h: 534).');
    'Beech forests of the nemoral zone of the East Asian floral domaine, formed by [Fagus crenata] and [Fagus japonica] in Japan, by [Fagus multinervis] in Korea. ', '(Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 315-319; Ching, 1991: 550-552). ');
    'Beech forests of Japan, distributed on southern Hokkaido, on Honshu and, locally, on Kyushu, at elevations between about 500 and 1700 m, within the cool-temperate to subalpine transition zones, formed by [Fagus crenata] or [Fagus japonica], often associated with other broad-leaved trees including [Quercus crispula], [Acer spp.], [Betula ermanii], [Zelkova serrata], or with conifers, [Abies spp.], [Thujopsis dolobrata], [Picea spp.], [Cryptomeria japonica], with an understorey that may be formed of [Sasa kurilensis], [Sasamorpha purpurascens] or ferns.', '(Ching, 1991: 550-553; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 315-317; Shimizu, 1995: 204).');
    'Beech forests of Japan dominated by [Fagus crenata], sometimes associated with [Fagus japonica], widespread, in particular, in southwestern Hokkaido, on the Pacific side of northern Honshu, on mesic flat areas of the mountainous Pacific side of central Honshu, in southwestern Honshu and in the highlands of Kyushu.', '(Ching, 1991: 550-553; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 315-317; Shimizu, 1995: 204).');
    'Beech forests of Japan dominated by [Fagus japonica], recorded, in particular, from the central and southern parts of the Sea of Japan watershed of northern Honshu, where it associates with [Abies firma] and [Zelkova serrata].', '(Ching, 1991: 552; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 316).');
    'Forests analogous to those of the [Ilici-Fagion] but dominated by [Quercus petraea] or [Quercus robur], often accompanied by [Fagus sylvatica]. They differ from unit 41.51 by the representation of the group of [Maianthemum bifolium] in the herb layer. ', '(Roisin, 1962; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1963; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Durin y al., 1967; Tüxen, 1974; Sissingh, 1974; Frileux, 1974; Géhu, 1974; Clément y al., 1974; Tombal, 1974; Bugnon and Rameau, 1974; Timbal, 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Aaby, 1983; Noirfalise, 1984, 1987; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Rodwell, 1991a; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Acidophilous [Quercus petraea] forests with [Fagus sylvatica] of the Baltic and North Sea plains, north to southern Scandinavia and east to Poland, of Picardy, Normandy, Perche, the Paris region, western Morvan, Argonne, middle Belgium. ', '(Roisin, 1962; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1963; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Durin y al., 1967; Roisin, 1969: 221-222; Tüxen, 1974; Sissingh, 1974; Frileux, 1974; Clément y al., 1974; Tombal, 1974; Bugnon and Rameau, 1974; Timbal, 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Aaby, 1983; Noirfalise, 1984: units VI.3.3.1, VI.3.3.2, VI.3.3.3, VI.3.3.4, VI.3.3.5, VI.3.3.6; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.1 [p.]; Noirfalise, 1987; Delescaille y al., 1989: 46-47; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.1 [p.]).');
    '[Quercus petraea] or [Quercus robur] forests of Brittany, generally richer in epiphytes, mosses and evergreen shrubs than the forests of unit 41.521, transitional to unit 41.53. ', '(Durin y al., 1967; Clément y al., 1974; Géhu and Bournique, 1993: 104-105, 108).');
    '[Quercus robur] or [Quercus petraea]-dominated woods of dunes and dune slacks of the North Sea coasts, of very local and relict occurrence.   ', '(Westhoff y al., 1970; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Pott, 1992).');
    '[Quercus robur] woods on dunes of the Netherlands, with [Acer pseudoplatanus], [Euonymus europaeus], [Primula vulgaris], [Cynoglossum officinale], [Cirsium palustre], [Doronicum pardalianches], [Doronicum plantagineum], [Convallaria majalis], [Hyacinthoides non-scripta], [Polygonatum odoratum], [Ornithogalum umbellatum], [Asparagus officinalis], [Calamagrostis epigejos], [Carex arenaria], [Dryopteris carthusiana], [Dryopteris dilatata], [Mnium hornum]. ', '(Westhoff y al., 1970; Westhoff and den Held, 1975).');
    '[Quercus petraea-Populus tremula] woods of dune slacks of Borkum and Nordeney and the adjacent mainland coast of Lower Saxony, with [Sorbus aucuparia], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Lonicera periclymenum], [Polypodium vulgare].', '(Pott, 1992; Oberdorfer, 1994).');
    'Woods of [Quercus petraea], [Betula spp.] and [Sorbus aucuparia], with abundant ericoid shrubs, in particular [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Deschampsia flexuosa], ferns, notably [Pteridium aquilinum] and [Dryopteris dilatata], and a rather sparse muscinal layer, which is, however, more diverse than in the next unit. They are characteristic of very acid soils on the Pennine fringes, in northeastern England, the central Pennines, Lancashire, the Welsh border hills and the western Midlands. ', '(Rodwell, 1991a: unit W16b).');
    'Woods of [Quercus robur] and [Betula pendula], occasionally [Quercus petraea], with a species-poor field layer often almost limited to [Deschampsia flexuosa] and [Pteridium aquilinum], with, locally, [Calluna vulgaris] and [Vaccinium myrtillus], characteristic of very acid soils in central, southeastern, and locally southwestern, England. Differentiation from this unit of the uncommon English representatives of unit 41.51 is probably not well-marked and all highly acidophilous [Quercus robur] stands are perhaps best listed here.', '(Géhu, 1974; Rodwell, 1991a: W16a).');
    'Acidophilous [Quercus petraea] woods of the British Isles, with low, low-branched, trees, with many ferns, mosses, lichens and evergreen bushes; the herb layer is formed by the group of [Deschampsia flexuosa]. ', '(Massey, 1974; Kelly and Moore, 1974; Ozenda y al., 1979; Condry, 1981; Noirfalise, 1987; Rodwell, 1991a).');
    '[Quercus petraea] woods of Ireland, particulary rich in evergreen bushes, including [Arbutus unedo]. ', '(Kelly and Moore, 1974; Ozenda y al., 1979; Noirfalise, 1987; Rodwell, 1991a).');
    'Acidophilous [Quercus petraea] woods of western Britain, mostly found in Scotland, Cumbria, Wales and southwestern England, with a few outliers in northern England, in particular in Yorkshire.', '(McVean, 1964a: 150-158; Massey, 1974; Ozenda y al., 1979; Condry, 1981; Noirfalise, 1987; Rodwell, 1991a: units W17, W11).');
    '[Quercus faginea] forests of ubacs of the southern Valencian mountains (Aitana, Montcabrer, Benicadell), with [Acer granatense], [Fraxinus ornus] and [Taxus baccata]. ', '(Costa, 1987: 303).');
