    'Tall herb forests of [Picea abies] of northern Fennoscandia and of northern Russia west of the western Ural piedmont, installed on calcareous substrates, with a species-rich understorey dominated by [Aconitum septentrionale] ([Aconitum lycoctonum]), [Cicerbita alpina], [Alnus incana].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5a, 6a, 8, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8a, 9a, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 58, 63; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.2.4 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 370-374, 381-382, 407-451; Korotkov y al., 1991: 287; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.6 [p.]; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 58).');
    'Tall herb forests of [Picea abies] of southern boreal and subboreal Fennoscandia and Russia, west of the western Ural piedmont, of Belarus and the Baltic States, developed on calcareous brown forest soils, with a species-rich understorey dominated by [Actaea spicata], [Campanula latifolia], [Mercurialis perennis], [Sambucus nigra], and ferns.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 6a, 7a, 8, 11a, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 9a, 10a, 13a, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 58, 63, 107; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.2.4 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 370-374, 381-382, 383-387, 407-451; Korotkov y al., 1991: 287; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.6 [p.]; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 58; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Tall herb forests of [Picea abies] of calcareous brown soils of western Norway, developed under oceanic climate conditions with much [Betula pubescens] and an understorey harbouring western, oceanic species, sometimes dominated by [Matteuccia struthiopteris].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.2.4 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.6 [p.]).');
    'Tall herb [Picea obovata] forests of boreal and boreonemoral Russia, east of the Northern Dvina and Vetluga rivers, and west of the Ural piedmont, developed under continental climates.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5b, 6b, 7b, 11b, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8b, 9b, 10b, 13b, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 67-70; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 370-374; Korotkov y al., 1991: 287).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of western Eurasia, west of the middle Petchora, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], sometimes accompanied by [Picea abies], with an ericoid-dominated, moss-rich or lichen-rich undergrowth mostly formed by [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Empetrum nigrum].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 3, 9, 10; Saphronova, 1964c: units 11, 12 [p.]; Walter, 1974: 67-69, 76-78; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.1.2, 2.1.1.2a, 2.1.1.2b; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 375-378; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Korotkov y al., 1991: 280-283; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.1.1.2, 2.1.1.2a, 2.1.1.2b, 120-121; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 57; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Sparse, extensive forests of the taiga belt of western Eurasia, west of the middle Petchora, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris] and [Picea abies], with many birches and an understorey dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Empetrum nigrum], [Vaccinium myrtillus] and, in the north, [Vaccinium uliginosum], with [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], lichens, notably of genus [Cladonia], mosses ([Dicranum]). They are, in particular, characteristic of cold, low evaporation regions of Norwegian, Swedish and Finnish mountains, up to the subalpine belt, occupying heavy raw humus on podsols.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.2; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.2; Müller, 1998: Annex 1).');
    'Sparse woodlands of suboceanic subalpine Scandinavia dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], with much [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepandovii], accompanied by some low-growing [Picea abies], with an undergrowth dominated by [Calluna vulgaris] and [Empetrum hermaphroditum], with [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Betula nana], [Cornus suecica], [Deschampsia flexuosa] and thick cushions of lichens and mosses formed by [Cladonia islandica], [Cladonia rangiferina], [Cladonia sylvatica], [Dicranum scoparium], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Barbilophozia lycopodioides], [Dicranum fuscescens], [Hylocomium splendens], [Sphagnum nemoreum]. They are installed on podsols with heavy raw humus in cool, submaritime, moist mostly northern boreal regions.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.2a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.2a).');
    'Sparse woods of low-growing [Pinus sylvestris], and some elements of birch, of maritime climate regions of western Norway, at subalpine levels, with an undergrowth dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Empetrum nigrum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], and with a species cortŠge characterized by the presence of [Cornus suecica], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Blechnum spicant], [Pteridium aquilinum], [Bazzania trilobata], [Leucobryum glaucum], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus], [Sphagnum nemoreum], [Sphagnum quinquefarium]; [Picea abies] is absent.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.2b; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.2b).');
    '[Tilia]-dominated forests of eastern Central Europe and the southern nemoral zone of Russia, east of the range of [Fagus sylvatica] and, for the most part, of that of [Carpinus betulus], and west of the Volga, with [Quercus robur], [Acer platanoides] and [Ulmus montana]. ', '(Tolmachev, 1980: 103; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 31; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 44-67; Jahn, 1991: 453, 456, unit 6a-c; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Forests of the nemoral zone of Russia, east of the Volga, with an eastward trend of diminishing [Quercus robur] and augmenting [Tilia cordata], and an often luxuriant shrub layer comprizing, in particular, [Corylus avellana]. Many, or most, are dominated by lime and listed here rather than under unit 41.26C.', '(Tolmachev, 1980: 103; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 31; Jahn, 1991: 453, 456, unit 6d; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    '[Tilia cordata]-dominated forests of the montane and submontane zones of the Ural, mostly to the north and west of the forests of unit 41.26D, with [Quercus robur], [Acer platanoides], [Populus tremula].', '(Tolmachev, 1980: 103; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 31; Jahn, 1991: 453-454, units 7b, 6e). ');
    '[Tilia cordata]-dominated forests of the oak-hornbeam-lime forest complex occupying the central part of the Tauric chain of southern Crimea.', '(Tolmachev, 1980: 103; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    '[Tilia sibirica]-dominated forests of the Altai.', '(Tolmachev, 1980: 134).');
    '[Tilia mongolica]-dominated formations of sheltered valleys of Inner Mongolian steppes.', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 45).');
    'Mixed summer-green broad-leaved forests limited mainly to the mountains bordering the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea.', '(Zohary, 1973: 103-129, 566-578). ');
    'Mixed summer-green broad-leaved forests of the Pontic Range of northern Anatolia and the Stranja-Istranca of Thrace, with outlyers in the eastern Balkan Range.', '(Jordanoff, 1939; Zohary, 1973: 570-578; Velchev y al., 1983; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Noirfalise, 1987: units R2, R1 [p.]; Röhrig, 1991h: 532, 533; Jahn, 1991: 491; Bondev, 1991: units 79-86).');
    'Species-rich mixed forests of mountains of the western Pontic Range and the mountains of the western and southwestern Black Sea region, including the eastern Balkan Range, the Stranja-Istranca, typically with a varied, multispecific shrub layer and herb layer comprising many Euxinian elements.', '(Noirfalise, 1987: units R2, R1 [p.]; Röhrig, 1991h: 532, col 2, par 4, 533, col 1, par 1, 2; Jahn, 1991: 491, col 2, par 6; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 239-240; Bondev, 1991: units 79-86; Meshinev y al., 1995).');
    'Species-rich mixed forests of mountains of the western and southwestern Black Sea region, including the eastern Balkan Range, the Stranja-Istranca, composed of [Quercus polycarpa], [Quercus cerris], [Carpinus betulus], [Carpinus orientalis], [Sorbus torminalis], [Fagus orientalis], with a varied, multispecific shrub layer and herb layer comprising many Euxinian elements. ', '(Bondev, 1991: units 79-86).');
    'Mixed forests of [Fagus orientalis], [Carpinus betulus] and [Tilia tomentosa]
on well moistured soils of the Stranja mountains of southeastern Bulgaria, sometimes accompanied by the Balkan endemic [Quercus hartwissiana] and many species typical of the western Pontic [Fagus orientalis] forests (41.1E122), including the rare [Fritillaria pontica], [Cyclamen coum], [Primula vulgaris] ssp. [rosea], [Trachystemon orientalis], and [Scilla bithynica].', '(Bondev, 1991: unit 80; Meshinev y al., 1995).');
    'Mixed forests of [Quercus polycarpa], [Carpinus betulus], [Quercus cerris], [Sorbus torminalis], [Fagus orientalis] with [Quercus frainetto], [Carpinus orientalis], located on north-facing slopes, on moist, nutrient-rich soils of the Stranja mountains of southeastern Bulgaria, with an understorey comprising [Crataegus monogyna], [Mespilus germanica], [Rhododendron ponticum], [Daphne pontica], [Erica arborea], [Vaccinium arctostaphylos], [Calluna vulgaris], [Genista carinalis], [Brachypodium sylvaticum], [Festuca heterophylla], [Poa nemoralis], [Melica uniflora], [Primula vulgaris] ssp. [rosea], [Cyclamen coum], [Salvia forskaohlei], [Trachystemon orientalis], [Sesleria alba].', '(Jordanoff, 1939; Velchev y al., 1983; Bondev, 1991: unit 82; Meshinev y al., 1995).');
    'Mixed forests with a varied, multispecific shrub layer and herb layer comprising many Euxinian elements located within a narrow coastal fringe from sea level to about 1200 m in the western Pontic Range between the Bulgarian border and 32øE, east of Zonguldak. Species include [Quercus macranthera], [Quercus hartwissiana], [Quercus iberica], [Taxus baccata], [Ostrya carpinifolia], [Fraxinus ornus], [Prunus laurocerasus], [Staphylea pinnata], [Buxus sempervirens].', '(Noirfalise, 1987: units R2, R1 [p.]). ');
    'Mixed forests located within a narrow coastal fringe from sea level to about 800-900 m in the eastern Pontic Range, within the zone of tea cultivation. The tree layer includes [Quercus iberica], [Castanea sativa], [Fagus orientalis], [Carpinus betulus], occasional [Pinus sylvestris], the understorey comprises [Iris lazica], [Hypericum xylostelofolium], [Omphalodes cappadocica], [Oplismenus undulatifolius], [Rubus platyphylos].', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 535-538; Noirfalise, 1987: unit R3, R1 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 240-241; Röhrig, 1991h: 533, col 1, par 3, 4, col 2, par 1).');
    'Forests of [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [sylvestris] and [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [hamata] of the Nemoral and Mediterranean zones of western Eurasia and of their transitions to the Steppe zone. Included are, in particular, the forests of Scotland, of the Alpine system, of the Mediterranean peninsulas, of the lowlands of Central Europe, of the East European Nemoral zone and its adjacent wooded steppes, formed by [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [sylvestris], as well as those of Anatolia, of the Caucacus and of Crimea, formed by [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [hamata]. Excluded are the formations situated within the northern, non-Alpigenous, area of natural lowland occurrence of [Picea abies], dominated by northern forms of [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [sylvestris] ([Pinus sylvestris] var. [septentrionalis], [Pinus sylvestris] var. [rigensis], [Pinus sylvestris] var. [borealis], [Pinus sylvestris] var. [rossica]), and those dominated by [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [lapponica] or by [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [sibirica], all of which are treated as constituents of the taiga and its transitions to the nemoral and steppe zones, and are listed under units 42.C and 42.D. Also excluded are the forests formed by the Central Asian [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [kulundensis], listed under unit 42.E.', '(Gaussen y al., 1969; Ozenda, 1982:76; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Rushforth, 1987; Molotkov and Patlaj, 1991; Boratynski, 1991; Jahn, 1991; Bondev, 1991; Shugart y al., 1992).');
    'Relict, indigenous Scots pine forests of endemic [Pinus sylvestris] var. [scotica], limited to the central and northeastern Grampians of Scotland. They are mostly open and have a ground layer usually rich in ericaceous species and mosses, in particular, [Hylocomium splendens], and often harbouring, together with abundant [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Goodyera repens], [Listera cordata], [Corallorhiza trifida], [Linnaea borealis], [Trientalis europaea], [Pyrola minor], [Moneses uniflora], [Orthilia secunda]. Accompanying, dominated, tree species include [Juniperus communis], [Sorbus aucuparia], [Betula pubescens], [Betula pendula], [Ilex aquifolium], [Populus tremula].', '(McVean, 1964a: 146-150; Simms, 1971; Pearsall, 1971; Ratcliffe, 1977a; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W18).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] var. [scotica] forests with a heath-like ground cover of [Erica cinerea] and [Calluna vulgaris]. ', '(Simms, 1971; Pearsall, 1971; Ratcliffe, 1977a; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] var. [scotica] forests with a heath-like ground cover of [Vaccinium myrtillus] and [Vaccinium vitis-idaea]. ', '(Simms, 1971; Pearsall, 1971; Ratcliffe, 1977a; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] var. [scotica] forests with a closed canopy and an understorey formed mostly by mosses, in particular [Scapania gracilis], [Diplophyllum albicans], [Thuidium tamariscinum] and the hepatic [Anastrepta orcadensis].', '(Simms, 1971; Pearsall, 1971; Ratcliffe, 1977a; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] var. [scotica] forests with a ground cover rich in grass-like species, in particular [Luzula pilosa], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Agrostis capillaris], [Agrostis canina], [Festuca ovina], together with [Vaccinium spp.] and bryophytes.', '(Simms, 1971; Pearsall, 1971; Ratcliffe, 1977a; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] var. [scotica] forests of damp hollows, with carpets of [Sphagnum spp.], [Molinia caerulea] and [Erica tetralix]. ', '(Simms, 1971; Pearsall, 1971; Ratcliffe, 1977a; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987).');
    'Indigenous [Pinus sylvestris] forests of the lowlands of nemoral Europe, south of the main, boreal and boreonemoral, nonalpigenous, area of continuous natural lowland occurrence of [Picea abies], of adjacent wooded steppe regions, and of siliceous soils of the montane or collinar levels of the central European Hercynian ranges and the eastern Alpine system.', '(Oberdorfer, 1990; Schubert, 1991; Molotkov and Patlaj, 1991; Jahn, 1991; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Forests dominated by [Pinus sylvestris] of acid, often podsolized, sands of the plains and hills of middle Europe. Associated trees include [Quercus robur], [Quercus petraea], [Betula pendula], [Fagus sylvatica]; [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Calluna vulgaris], [Dicranum undulatum] are usually prominent in the ground layer, [Molinia caerulea] may be abundant in humid stands. ', '(Wendelberger, 1963; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Ozenda y al., 1979; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Ozenda, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988).');
    'Main-range acidophilous [Pinus sylvestris] forests of diluvial sands of the northeastern plains and hills of Central Europe, where they reach their greatest dominance, and of the nemoral belt of the middle and southern Sarmatic region, in areas of less xericity or continentality than those occupied by the steppe woods of unit 42.523. They are distributed from Franconia and the inner Bohemian basin, through eastern Germany, to western and central Poland, extending, more locally, in areas of greater prevalence of steppe woods, to eastern Poland, Belarus, the northern Ukraine and Russia to the eastern confines of the Nemoral zone of western Eurasia. They are very similar to some taiga formations of which they often represent an outpost beyond the boreal and boreonemoral range of [Picea abies]; their separation from boreo-nemoral taiga pine woods of unit 42.C is generally arbitrary and one of regional convenience.', '(Wendelberger, 1963; Saphronova, 1964a: units 31, 39; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 58; Sokolowski, 1965; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Holub y al., 1967; Walter, 1974: 113-116; Glazek, 1976; Matuszkiewicz, 1981a; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Moravec y al., 1983; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Ozenda, 1985; Noirfalise, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Solon, 1988; Korotkov y al., 1991; Molotkov and Patlaj, 1991; Jahn, 1991).');
    'Thasos [Pinus brutia] forests with dense ericaceous undergrowth. ', NULL);
    'Mostly sparse [Pinus brutia] formations of the lowlands of Samothrace. ', '(Rechinger, 1943, 1951; Davis, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    'Remnant [Pinus brutia] forests of Rhodes, still represented by some relatively natural formations with rich scrub undergrowth. ', '(Rechinger, 1943, 1951; Davis, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    'Fairly extensive [Pinus brutia] forests of Karpathos, distributed, in particular, in the northern coastal area, the southern interior and the middle elevation of Kali Limni. ', '(Rechinger, 1943, 1951; Turland y al., 1993: 6).');
    '[Pinus brutia] formations of the islands of Simi, Kos, Leros and Ikaria. ', '(Rechinger, 1943, 1951; Davis, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    '[Pinus brutia] forests of Greek Thrace, of the Chalkidi peninsula and of the Black Sea region of Turkey in Europe.', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    '[Pinus brutia] forests of Anatolia and of the Dardanelles, covering extensive areas in western and southwestern Anatolia, with isolated outposts in northern Anatolia.', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 342-343, 525-527; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    'Extensive [Pinus brutia] forests of the thermo-Mediterranean, meso-Mediterranean and, locally, supra-Mediterranean level of Caria, Pisidia, Pamphylia, Isauria, Cilicia in southwestern and south central Anatolia. ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 526-527; Noirfalise, 1987: units M13, T4, T3).');
    '[Pinus brutia] forests on serpentines of the region of Koycegiz and around the Gulf of Alexandrette.', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit M13 [p.]).');
    'Forests of [Pinus brutia] on marls of the central Taurus system.', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit M13 [p.]).');
    'Supramediterranean forests of [Pinus brutia], accompanied by [Centaurea babylonica] or [Centaurea ptosimoppapoides], located on limestones of the Atsaki region and on ultrabasic rocks the region of Marsin and Pos, of the southern Taurus system.', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit M13 [p.]).');
    'Forests of [Pinus brutia], accompanied by [Quercus microphylla], on ultrabasic rocks around the Gulf of Alexandrette.', 'Noirfalise, 1987: unit T4).');
    'Extensive [Pinus brutia] forests of the mostly meso-Mediterranean level of Mysia, Lydia, western Bithynia, western Phrygia of western Anatolia, with eastern garrigue undergrowth and dominated semideciduous or deciduous oaks. ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 342-343, 525-527; Noirfalise, 1987: unit M8a).');
    'Enclave [Pinus brutia] forests of the Euxine region of northern Anatolia, characteristic, in particular, of transverse inner valleys of the Pontic Ranges. ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973; Noirfalise, 1987: unit M8a [p.]).');
    '[Pinus brutia] forests of the thermo-Mediterranean, meso-Mediterranean and supra-Mediterranean levels of Cyprus, where it associates in particular with [Cupressus sempervirens] and with [Juniperus phoenicea]; it forms, in particular, great forests in the Pendadahtilos Range, in the regions of Karpassia and Akamas and in the Troodos Ranges where it replaces [Quercus alnifolia] on dry soils derived from eruptive basic rocks. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 303-308; Zohary, 1973: 153-155, 524-526; Meikle, 1977: 1, 2; Noirfalise, 1987: units T3, T4, M11, M13; Sfikas, 1992; Viney, 1994: xii).');
    '[Pinus brutia] forests of Lebanon, coastal Syria and the southeast coasts of the Gulf of Alexandrette in southern central Anatolia. [Pinus halepensis] may be associated with [Pinus brutia].', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    'Isolated [Pinus brutia] forests of western slopes of the mountains lying between the Tigris and the Zab rivers, on the northern rim of the Mesopotamian high plains, in northern Irak.', '(Zohary, 1973).');
    'Forests of [Pinus brutia] [s.l.] ([Pinus pityusa], [Pinus stankewiczii]) of the  mountains of southwestern Crimea.', '(Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Formations of [Pinus brutia] or its allies in the Caucasus system, in particular stands of [Pinus eldarica], apparently limited to a single mountain site in Georgia.', '(Davis, 1965; Rushforth, 1987).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of western Eurasia, limited to southern and central Finland, central and northern Sweden and southeastern Norway, the Baltic States, southern boreal and boreonemoral Russia, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], often accompanied by [Picea abies], which may dominate or codominate, with an ericoid-dominated, moss-rich and lichen-rich undergrowth mostly formed by [Vaccinium vitis-idaea] with [Empetrum nigrum], [Empetrum hermaphroditum]. The species cortŠge includes [Betula pubescens], [Calluna vulgaris], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Pyrola chlorantha], [Goodyera repens], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Lycopodium complanatum], [Cladonia spp.], [Dicranum scoparium], [Dicranum polysetum], [Dicranum fuscescens], [Hylocomium splendens], [Pleurozium schreberi]. They occur on sandy moraines or calcareous sand sediments in low rainfall areas.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 10; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 12; Walter, 1974: 67-69, 76-78; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.1.3, 2.1.3.2; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 375-378; Korotkov y al., 1991: 280-283; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.4; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 57; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of western Eurasia, west of the middle Petchora, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], sometimes accompanied by [Picea abies], with a grass-, small herb-, tall herb- or fern-dominated undergrowth.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 3, 9, 10; Saphronova, 1964c: units 11, 12 [p.]; Walter, 1974: 67-69, 76-78; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.1.2c, 2.1.1.4; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 375-378; Korotkov y al., 1991: 280-283; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.1.1.4a, 2.1.1.4b, 2.1.1.5, 2.1.1.6, 2.1.1.6a; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 57; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of southern and central Finland, central and northern Sweden and eastern Norway, the Baltic States, southern boreal and boreonemoral Russia, west of the middle Petchora, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], sometimes accompanied by [Picea abies], with a grass-, small herb-, tall herb- or fern-dominated undergrowth.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 10; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 12; Walter, 1974: 67-69, 76-78; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.4; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 375-378; Korotkov y al., 1991: 280-283; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.1.1.4b, 2.1.1.5, 2.1.1.6; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 57; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of southern and central Finland, central and northern Sweden and eastern Norway, the Baltic States, southern boreal and boreonemoral Russia, west of the middle Petchora, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], accompanied by [Betula pendula] and sometimes by [Picea abies], with a grass- and herb-rich undergrowth dominated by [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Melica nutans], [Convallaria majalis], [Melampyrum pratense], with [Cypripedium calceolus], [Epipactis helleborine], [Geranium sanguineum], [Hepatica nobilis].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 10; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.6; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of southern and central Finland, central and northern Sweden and eastern Norway, the Baltic States, southern boreal and boreonemoral Russia, west of the middle Petchora, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], often accompanied by [Betula pubescens], with a grass- and herb-rich undergrowth dominated by [Calamagrostis arundinacea] with [Anthyllis vulneraria], [Fragaria vesca], [Lathyrus pratensis], [Pulsatilla spp.], [Viola riviniana], [Viola rupestris].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.4b).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of southern and central Finland, central and northern Sweden and eastern Norway, the Baltic States, southern boreal and boreonemoral Russia, west of the middle Petchora, dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], often accompanied by [Betula pubescens] or [Populus tremula], with a grass- and herb-rich, in particular, legume-rich, undergrowth dominated by [Calamagrostis arundinacea] and [Convallaria majalis] with [Rubus saxatilis], [Rubus idaeus], [Ribes alpinum], [Rhamnus frangula], [Lonicera xylosteum], [Hepatica nobilis], [Lathyrus spp.], [Vicia sepium].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.5).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of Atlantic western Norway dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], accompanied by [Betula pendula] and sometimes [Picea abies], with a grass-, small herb-, tall herb- or fern-dominated undergrowth.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 3; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.1.1.6a, 2.1.1.6 [p.]).');
    'Conifer forests of the taiga belt of Atlantic western Norway dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], accompanied by [Betula pendula] and sometimes [Picea abies], with a grass-, small herb-, tall herb- or fern-rich undergrowth dominated by [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Melica nutans], [Convallaria majalis], [Melampyrum pratense], with [Sanicula europaea] and [Galium odoratum].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 3; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.4 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.6 [p.]).');
    '[Tilia]-dominated forests of the northern nemoral zone and of enclaves in the southern boreal zone of Fennoscandia, the Baltic States and Russia, east to the Volga, outside of the range of [Fagus sylvatica] and mostly of [Carpinus betulus]. [Tilia cordata] may be accompanied by [Quercus robur], [Acer platanoides], [Populus tremula], [Picea abies], [Corylus avellana], [Sorbus aucuparia], [Euonymus europaeus], [Daphne mezereum], [Galium odoratum], [Anemone nemorosa] and boreal herbs. ', '(Tolmachev, 1980: 103; Nordiska Ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.5; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 31-32; Jahn, 1991: 403, 453-455, unit 7a; Korotkov y al., 1991; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.5; Opermanis y al., 1997: 56; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Mixed forests of inner slopes of the Pontic Range generally in conditions of lower humidity and temperature than those of the Euxianian mixed forests of unit 41.H1, rich in species of [Quercus] and usually accompanied by [Carpinus betulus] or [Carpinus orientalis], sometimes with conifers. Characteristic species include [Quercus dshorochensis], [Quercus syspirensis], [Quercus anatolica], [Quercus iberica], [Quercus macranthera], [Acer cappadocium], [Fagus orientalis], [Abies bornmuelleriana].', '(Zohary, 1973: 570-578; Noirfalise, 1987: units Q1, Q4; Jahn, 1991: 491, col 2, par 4; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 239-240).');
    'Isolated oak-hornbeam forests of the Stranja and the Belgrat-Ormani, similar to woodlands of middle Europe in structure and field layer, but with [Quercus polycarpa], [Quercus frainetto], [Quercus cerris], [Quercus infectoria], dominated by, or rich in, [Carpinus betulus].', '(Zohary, 1973: 573; Horvat y al., 1974: 251-252; Jahn, 1991: 491-492).');
    'Oak-hornbeam forests of the western Pontic Range comprising, in particular, on calcareous marls, formations with [Quercus syspirensis], [Quercus anatolica], [Quercus iberica], with [Dictamnus albus] or, in the Kastamonu basin, with [Quercus iberica], [Abies bornmuelleriana], [Pinus sylvestris].', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit Q1, western sector). ');
    'Oak-hornbeam forests of the central Pontic Range, centered around Samsun, variable in composition depending on conditions of humidity, including, in particular, formations with [Quercus cerris], [Crataegus curvipetala] on schists, with [Quercus dshorochensis], [Quercus anatolica] on limestones or marls, with [Quercus syspirensis], [Fagus orientalis], [Daphne pontica] or, with [Carpinus betulus], [Carpinus orientalis], [Ruscus aculiatus] and an accompanying flora characteristic of rhododendron-beech forests that grade, at their upper limit, into the mixed [Fagus]-[Quercus iberica]-[Carpinus]-[Acer cappadocium] forests of higher altitudes.', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit Q1, central sector). ');
    'Oak-hornbeam forests of the eastern Pontic Range, including the Kelkit Cay and Harsit valleys, south of Trabzon, including, in particular, formations with [Quercus syspirensis], and an admixture of [Pinus pallasiana] and [Chamaecytisus pygmaeus] or, east of Erbaa, [Cedrus libani].', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit Q1, eastern sector). ');
