    'Woods of the Atlantic western extremity of the western Palaearctic taiga belt dominated by [Pinus sylvestris], [Betula pubescens] and [Picea abies], occupying calcareous substrates of the subalpine belt of central and northern Norway. They are characterized by a field layer containing both alpine and thermophile southern elements. The tall shrub layer contains much [Juniperus communis]; the undergrowth is dominated by [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Campanula rotundifolia], [Saxifraga oppositifolia], [Carex rupestris], with [Bartsia alpina], [Dryas octopetala], [Astragalus alpinus], [Gymnocarpium robertianum], [Hieracium vulgaris] [s.i.], [Saussurea alpina], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Viola biflora], [Pyrola norvegica], [Parnassia palustris], [Polygonatum verticillatum], [Epipactis atrorubens], [Carex digitata], [Elymus caninus] ([Roegneria canina]), [Festuca rubra], [Tortella tortuosa], [Rhytidium rugosum].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.6a).');
    'Sparse woods of low-growing [Pinus sylvestris], of northern Sweden, Finland and Norway, occurring under continental climate conditions with low humidity and wide fluctuations of temperature. The understorey is characterized by a dominance of [Calamagrostis lapponica], and a high density of lichens; the species cortŠge includes [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Pedicularis lapponica], [Cladonia alpestris], [Cladonia alpicola], [Cladonia mitis], [Cladonia rangiferina], [Dicranum polysetum], [Pleurozium schreberi].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 9; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.2c; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.4a).');
    'Woods of [Pinus sylvestris] of Fennoscandia, the Baltic States and northern Russia, with a very low, sparse, dwarf-shrub layer and a ground layer dominated by lichens mainly of genus [Cladonia], notably [Cladonia rangiferina], [Cladonia alpestris], [Cladonia mitis]. Participating species include [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Calluna vulgaris], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Cetraria islandica], [Dicranum polysetum], [Dicranum spurium], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Stereocaulon spp.], installed on podsols with a thin raw humus layer, often on sand sediment.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 3, 9, 10; Saphronova, 1964c: units 11, 12 [p.]; Walter, 1974: 67-69, 76-78; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.1; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 375-378; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Korotkov y al., 1991: 282; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.1; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 57; Christiansen y al., 1996: 44-49; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Lichen-carpeted [Pinus sylvestris] woods of the maritime climate region of western Norway, rich in [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 3; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.1 [p.]).');
    'Lichen-carpeted [Pinus sylvestris] woods of areas of continental climate regions of Fennoscandia, of the Baltic States and of the southern boreal and boreonemoral zones of northern Russia, particularly characteristic of eastern Sweden and Finland. Dominant lichens are [Cladonia rangiferina], [Cladonia alpestris], [Cladonia mitis] and, in coastal ¿stland, [Cladonia uncialis]. Eastern Swedish and southeastern Norwegian stands harbour [Anemone sylvestris].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 10; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 12; Walter, 1974: 67-69, 76-78; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.1 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 375-378; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Korotkov y al., 1991: 282; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.1 [p.]; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 57; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Lichen-carpeted [Pinus sylvestris] woods of northern boreal Russia, the Kola peninsula and extreme northeastern Fennoscandia.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 9; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 11; Walter, 1974: 67-69, 76-78; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 375-378).');
    'Woods of [Pinus sylvestris] colonizing often small, level, glacier-fashioned granite, gneiss or acidic-sediment rock outcrops of southern and middle Fennoscandia, with dense lichen carpets, mostly of [Cladonia rangiferina], or a varied lichen and moss cover, accompanied by small shrubs, grasses and petrophile forbs, sometimes by abundant [Juniperus communis].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: units 7.1.1.2, 7.1.1.3, [p.]).');
