    'Boreal and boreonemoral spruce, pine, larch or fir forests of Siberia and the Urals, extending west to the western piedmont of the Urals, the middle Pechora and middle Kama basins, and southeastwards to northern China. West of the Yenisei they are predominantly dark taiga forests, more species-rich than those of the western taiga, formed by [Picea obovata], [Abies sibirica], [Pinus sibirica], [Pinus sylvestris], in pure or mixed stands, with less common light taiga forests dominated by [Larix sibirica]. East of the Yenisei they are mostly light taiga forests, dominated by [Larix dahurica] ([Larix gmelinii]).', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 12-16; Saphronova, 1964b: units 3-13, 15-20; Saphronova, 1964c: units 14-29, 31-41; Tikhomirov, 1970: 37; Birot, 1970: 115-118, 127-128, 159-160, 170-171; Walter, 1974: 79-104; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 36; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 362-372, 387-405, 453-459; Rushforth, 1987; Rieley and Page, 1990; Molotkov and Patlaj, 1991; Boratynski, 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991: 276-278, 287-288, 288-292; Shugart y al., 1992; Huetz de Lemps, 1994: 85-87; Krassilov, 1995: 40).');
