    'Forests dominated by [Pinus nigra] ssp. [pallasiana] occupying slopes and ridges of the 500 metre to 1500 metre belt of the Thessalian Mount Olympus, Pieria and Vourninos, extending from the upper limit of the Mediterranean forest and shrub level to, and into, the beech forest zone, accompanied by species characteristic of both the Mediterranian and montane levels, most extensive on the northern side, constituting the most important forest element of the Olympic system.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 549-550; Gamisans and Hébrard, 1979; Strid, 1980: 46).');
    '[Juniperus thurifera] woods of the Atlas system of North Africa, mostly widespread in Morocco, where they reach their greatest development on the southern slopes of the High Atlas and are also present in the Middle Atlas and in the eastern Anti-Atlas, limited in Algeria to the Aures. They are confined to the 1800 to 3150 metre cold semiarid level, mixed in the lower part of the range with [Cedrus atlantica]. The undergrowth usually includes [Bupleurum  spinosum], [Prunus prostrata], [Daphne laureola], [Crataegus laciniata], [Buxus sempervirens], [Lonicera arborea].', '(Herbauts, 1973: 335-337; White, 1983: 156; Gauquelin y al., 1993: 403-404; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 79).');
