    'Forest formations dominated by [Juniperus excelsa] or the closely allied [Juniperus macropoda] ([Juniperus polycarpos], [Juniperus seravshanica]) of the Irano-Turanian plateaux and mountains of Anatolia, Iran, Afghanistan, extending to Lebanon, the Caucasus, Crimea, Cyprus and the Balkanic peninsula, in the periphery of the Pelagonides and Rhodopides. Arborescent matorrals, somewhat more widespread in Mediterranean and sub-Mediterranean regions, have been listed under unit 32.1331; montane prostrate scrubs, often difficult to segregate sharply from the mountain juniper woods in unit 31.438.', '(Schweinfurth, 1957; Riedl, 1968; Zohary, 1973: 570; Horvat y al., 1974; Noirfalise, 1987; Rushforth, 1987; Korotkov y al., 1991; Bondev, 1991).');
    '[Juniperus excelsa] forests of the [Ostryo-Carpinion] zone of the southern periphery of the Pelagonides, in particular of the mountains surrounding Lake Prespa in northern Greece where they occur up to 900-1000 m.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 170-171).');
    'Woods of [Juniperus excelsa], of the western and northern periphery of the Rhodopides, localized in the southwestern Bulgarian Struma trough, and in the northern foothills of the central Rhodope mountains near Krichim and Bachkovo, usually open, with deciduous forest elements including [Fraxinus ornus], [Pistacia terebinthus], [Carpinus orientalis], sometimes [Quercus pubescens], and many Mediterranean species, such as [Phillyrea latifolia], [Asparagus acutifolius], [Lonicera etrusca], [Achnatherum bromoides].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 170-171; Velchev y al., 1984; Bondev, 1991: unit 117; Meshinev, 1992).');
    '[Juniperus excelsa] forests of the [Ostryo-Carpinion] zone of the northern periphery of the Pelagonides, in particular of the Vardar and Crna Reka valleys of the northern F.Y.R. of Macedonia, at an altitude of 100-400 metres.', '(Em, 1962, 1985; Horvat y al., 1974: 170-171; Micevski, 1999).');
