    'Conifer forests of the Alps, the Carpathians, the Dinarides, the Balkan Range, the Rhodopes, the Apennines, the Jura, the Hercynian ranges, the Pontic Range and the Caucasus, dominated by [Picea abies], [Picea omorika] or [Picea orientalis]. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Somsak, 1983; Ozenda, 1985; Noirfalise, 1987: 44-45; Ferioli, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Jirasek, 1998). ');
    '[Picea abies] forests of the lower subalpine level, and of anomalous stations in the montane level, of the outer, intermediate and inner Alps; in the latter, they are often in continuity with the montane spruce forests of unit 42.22. The spruces, often stunted or columnar, are accompanied by an undergrowth of decidedly subalpine affinities. [Picea abies] forests of the lower subalpine level of the Carpathians.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Mayer, 1974; Horvat y al., 1974: 564-565; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Richard and Pautou, 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987: unit P4; Oberdorfer, 1990; Elias y al., 1991).');
