    'Tall-herb rich, hygrophile or mesohygrophile, [Picea abies] forests of high altitude stations of the Alps, subjected to prolonged snow cover and frequent fogs, with [Adenostyles spp.], [Chaerophyllum hirsutum], [Peucedanum ostruthium], [Ranunculus aconitifolius], [Aconitum vulparia], [Aconitum paniculatum], [Stellaria nemorum], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Cicerbita alpina]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 55-59; Ozenda, 1981: 209; Richard and Pautou, 1982: 171; Noirfalise, 1987: 45; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 73; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 311-315).');
    '[Picea abies] or [Picea abies]-[Larix decidua] forests of subalpine to high montane slopes of the Alps developed on base-rich and usually lime-rich substrates, in particular, on dolomites, limestones, calcschists, green schists, usually on steep rocky slopes, with an undergrowth dominated by [Adenostyles glabra] ([Adenostyles alpina]).', '(Mayer, 1974: 56-59; Horvat y al., 1974: 364-365; Noirfalise, 1987: 45; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 73; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 312-313; Seliskar, 1998: 7).');
    '[Picea abies] forests of the subalpine level of the Alps developed in high precipition regions on usually calcareous bedrock, sometimes on base-rich siliceous substrates such as flysch, with an undergrowth dominated by dense formations of tall herbs, in particular, [Adenostyles alliariae], [Cicerbita alpina], [Rumex alpestris].', '(Mayer, 1974: 55-56; Noirfalise, 1987: 45; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 313-315).');
    'Sphagnum-rich [Picea abies] forests of the Alps, developed on more or less peaty, humid but not waterlogged substrates, with [Listera cordata], [Sphagnum acutifolium], [Sphagnum quinquefarium], [Sphagnum girgensohnii]. Spruce forests developed in fens or swamps at the periphery of raised bogs or on waterlogged soils in forests are included in swamp forests of class 44, as unit 44.A411.  ', '(Mayer, 1974: 53; Noirfalise, 1987: 45; Ellenberg, 1988: 218; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 288, 290; Seliskar, 1998: 7-8).');
    '[Picea abies] forests on dry adrets of the northern and northwestern Alps, with [Vaccinium vitis-idaea] and a small admixture of [Vaccinium myrtillus] on siliceous soils over sandstones and carboniferous schists, with [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Polygala chamaebuxus], [Carex humilis] on lustrous schists, with [berberis vulgaris], [Valeriana montana], [Valeriana tripteris] on stabilized calcareous screes. ', '(Ozenda, 1981: 208-209, 210; Richard and Pautou, 1982: 171-172).');
    'Forests dominated by [Pinus nigra] ssp. [pallasiana] of the northern and central Pindus system.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 549-550; Gamisans and Hébrard, 1979).');
    '[Pinus nigra] ssp. [pallasiana]-dominated forests of the Pelagonides of north-central Greece, Albania and the F.Y.R. of Macedonia, north to the middle Treska Valley.', '(Em, 1962, 1978, 1981; Horvat y al., 1974: 170; Strid, 1989: 43; Hoda y al., 1998: 16; Micevski, 1999).');
    'Scattered [Pinus nigra] ssp. [pallasiana]-dominated forests of the Rila, Pirin, Slavianka, Rhodopes, Vrondous and Falakron, most widespread in the Rhodope, in part accompanied by [Quercus dalechampii], [Ostrya carpinifolia] (southern Rhodopes), [Abies alba] or [Pinus sylvestris].
', '(Strid, 1989: 43; Bondev, 1991: units 21, 41, 65-67, [p.]; Andreev y al., 1992: 84-85; Meshinev y al., 1993: 129).');
    'Uncommon [Pinus nigra] ssp. [pallasiana]-dominated forests of the beech and durmast oak levels of the western and central Balkan Range and its associated southern chains, sometimes accompanied by [Abies alba], by [Quercus dalechampii], or by [Ostrya carpinifolia].', '(Bondev, 1991: units 41, 66, 67, [p.]).');
    '[Pinus nigra] ssp. [pallasiana]-dominated forests of the Moeso-Macedonian mountains.', '(Bondev, 1991: 65, 66, [p.]).');
    '[Pinus nigra] ssp. [pallasiana]-dominated forests of the Aegean islands of Thasos and Samos.', '(Strid, 1989: 43).');
    'Relict thermophile forests of [Pinus banatica] ([Pinus nigra] var. [banatica]) developed on calcareous substrates of the montane level of the Southern Carpathians, in particular, of the Banat, with [Genista radiata], [Fraxinus ornus], [Cotinus coggygria], [Biscutella laevigata], [Ceterach officinarum], [Festuca xanthina], [Seseli rigidum], [Campanula kladniana], [Centaurea rhenana] and [Campanula divergens].', '(Wendelberger, 1963; Resmerita, 1972; Horvat y al., 1974: 515; Sanda y al., 1980: 132; Coldea, 1991: 506).');
    'Forests of [Pinus pallasiana] var. [caramanica] of the cold, snowy, high altitudes, above 1400 metres, of the Troodos Range, with [Euphorbia cassia] and numerous Cyprian endemics or near-endemics, among which [Platanthera holmboei], [Epipactis troodi], [Thlaspi cyprium] and [Jurinea cypria].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 308-309; Zohary, 1973: 28, 155, 343-344, 556; Meikle, 1977: 2; Noirfalise, 1987: unit H9; Sfikas, 1992; Flint and Stewart, 1992: 23).');
    'Lower altitudinal belt of [Pinus pallasiana] forests of Mount Troodos. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 308-309; Zohary, 1973: 28, 155, 343-344, 556; Noirfalise, 1987: unit H9 [p.]; Sfikas, 1992).');
    'Upper altitudinal belt of [Pinus pallasiana] forests of Mount Troodos, with [Juniperus foetidissima], [Sorbus umbellata] ssp. [oblongifolia], and the Cyprian endemics [Alyssum troodii], [Nepeta troodi], [Cynoglossum troodi], [Scorzonera trooda]. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 308-309; Noirfalise, 1987: unit H9 [p.]; Meikle, 1977: 2).');
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests of northwestern, southwestern and southern interior Anatolia, occurring between 1200 and 1800 metres altitude, in areas of only a few months of snow cover, moderate to low precipitation and up to six months of summer drought a year.', '(Wendelberger, 1963; Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests of northern and northwestern interior Anatolia, and of interior ranges of the western Pontic system, located at altitudes between 1200 and 1800 metres, in areas of two to four months of snow cover and four to five months of summer drought a year, with an understorey of [Cistus laurifolius], [Chamaecytisus pygmaeus], [Genista lydia], [Hypericum montbretii], [Iris chatii].', '(Davis, 1965; Noirfalise, 1987: unit H6).');
    'Western interior Anatolian forests of [Pinus pallasiana] accompanied by [Quercus cerris], [Populus tremula] and [Ferulago galbanifera].', NULL);
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests of western Anatolia, on marly calcareous and green rocks, with [Sesleria argentea].', NULL);
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests of the northwestern Anatolian pre-Pontic region, with [Lathyrus czeczottianus], situated on andesites, with marginal, more open, formations, extending locally to the southern side of the Pontic chain.', NULL);
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests of southwestern Anatolia, located on superficial soils, at altitudes between 1200 and 1800 metres, in the region lying between Fetihye-Mugla and Izmir, in areas with two to three months of snow cover and four to five months of summer drought a year; the understorey comprises [Adenocarpus complicatus], [Chamaecytisus eriocarpus], [Genista anatolica], [Genista lydia], [Chronanthus orientalis], [Hypericum adenocarpum], [Teucrium kotschyenum].', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit H7).');
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests established on eruptive rock, with [Symphytum brachycalyx].', NULL);
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests established on greenstone, with [Teucrium sandrasicum] and [Centaurea ensifolia].', NULL);
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests established on dolomitic rock, with [Agropyron panormitanum] and [Sesleria anatolica].', NULL);
    '[Juniperus excelsa]-dominated forests of the eastern part of the southern Crimean coast, with [Linosyris villosa], [Bothriochloa ischaemum], [Agropyron ponticum], [Carex caryophyllea], [Eryngium campestre], [Pimpinella lithophila].', '(Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    '[Juniperus excelsa]-dominated forests of the Crimean mountains, with [Phleum phleoides], [Potentilla taurica], [Campanula taurica], [Melica monticola], [Lappula barbata], [Alyssum rostratum], [Filipendula vulgaris], [Alopecurus vaginatus].', '(Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    '[Juniperus excelsa]-dominated forests of high altitudes, 1200-2000 metres, of the Lebanon Mountains and Ansariye Mountains, occupying generally more xeric sites than [Cedrus libani] and [Abies cilicica], including eastern, steppe-facing, slopes, though also mixed with them locally.', '(Zohary, 1973; Quézel, 1981a: 91).');
    'Open forest formations constituting a belt on high arid slopes of the Elburz, with more isolated occurrences in the mountains of Transcaucasia, of Tadzhikistan, of the Zagros, of the Irano-Afghan plateau, of the inner valleys of the western and eastern Himalayas and of the southeastern and southwestern Arabian peninsula, dominated by junipers of the [Juniperus excelsa] group, often united in an eastern species, the Persian juniper [Juniperus macropoda], or divided into several closely related species, [Juniperus macropoda], [Juniperus seravshanica], [Juniperus turcomanica], but by some taxonomists judged undistinguishable from [Juniperus excelsa]. [Juniperus semiglobosa] may also accompany the other forms or dominate the community in Tadzhikistan, Uzbekistan and Afghanistan.', '(Bobek, 1951; Schweinfurth, 1957; Riedl, 1968; Zohary, 1973; Walter, 1974: 262-265, 279, 327, 319; Rushforth, 1987; Walter and Breckle, 1991c).');
    'Forest formations dominated by [Juniperus foetidissima] of the Balkan peninsula, Cyprus, Anatolia, Transcaucasia. ', '(Rechinger, 1951: 51; Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 153). ');
    'Forest formations dominated by [Juniperus foetidissima] of the mountains of Greece, developed locally at high altitudes, on adrets of the upper supra-Mediterranean level, in particular, in the northern Pindus, in the region of the Vicos gorge. Arborescent matorrals, somewhat more widespread in Greece, including the Aegean archipelagoes (Samos), have been listed under unit 32.1332.', '(Rechinger, 1951; Polunin, 1980:106; Sfikas, 1984; Strid, 1989; Noirfalise, 1986). ');
    'Forest of [Juniperus foetidissima] of the upper level of Hionistra Peak in the Troodos Range. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 309; Meikle, 1977: 2; Sfikas, 1992).');
    'Presteppic, meso-Mediterranean or subalpine [Juniperus foetidissima]-dominated forests of Anatolia and neighbouring areas, of apparently very local occurrence, considerably less widespread than the [Juniperus excelsa]-dominated formations of the same regions.
', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973).');
    '[Juniperus drupacea] woods of Greece and Asia Minor. Part of the formations take the appearence of arborescent matorral, listed under unit 32.135.', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973; Polunin, 1980; Sfikas, 1984).');
    '[Juniperus drupacea] woods of the northern slopes of Mount Parnon and of the Karlik mountain in Thrace. ', '(Polunin, 1980; Sfikas, 1984; Kassioumis, 1988). ');
    '[Juniperus drupacea] woods of the Taurus and Amanus ranges. ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973).');
    '[Juniperus drupacea] woods of the Lebanon and Anti-Lebanon ranges. ', '(Zohary, 1973).');
    'Forests of [Tetraclinis articulata], a species restricted to North Africa, southeastern Spain and the Maltese Islands.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Le Houérou, 1969; Herbauts, 1973; Knapp, 1973: 481-483; Templado, 1974; Tomaselli, 1981b; White, 1983: 154).');
    'Xerothermophile forests of [Tetraclinis articulata], restricted to extreme southeastern Spain, are extinct in forest form. The relict formations dominated by this species, of exceptional biogeographical and historical importance, constitute arborescent matorrals and have been listed under unit 32.151. ', '(Templado, 1974; Tomaselli, 1981b). ');
    '[Tetraclinis articulata]-dominated woodland of the lower Mediterranean slopes of the Rif and of the Oran and Algiers Tell and littoral, of the lower northern slopes and rain shadow valleys of the Middle Atlas and High Atlas, of the northern slopes of the Anti-Atlas, with outposts in maritime ranges of Tunisia, in particular, Ichkeul and Cap Bon and on the Tunisian Dorsale. They are limited to oceanic and maritime semiarid levels. Many formations are degraded to arborescent matorrals, listed under unit 32.152.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Le Houérou, 1969; Herbauts, 1973: 332-333; Knapp, 1973: 481-483; White, 1983: 154).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of Iceland and western Norway with an ericoid-dominated undergrowth, formed mainly by [Empetrum hermaphroditum], dominant in Iceland, and [Vaccinium uliginosum], dominant in Norway, accompanied by [Calluna vulgaris], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Betula nana], [Deschampsia flexuosa], mosses and, in Iceland, [Juncus trifidus], [Kobresia myosuroides].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.1a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.1a).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of Iceland, with a mostly ericoid undergrowth, dominated by [Empetrum hermaphroditum], accompanied by [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Calluna vulgaris], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Betula nana], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Juncus trifidus], [Kobresia myosuroides], mosses and lichens.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.1a [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.1a [p.]).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of western Norway, with a mostly ericoid undergrowth dominated by [Vaccinium uliginosum], accompanied by [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Calluna vulgaris], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Betula nana], [Deschampsia flexuosa] and mosses.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.1a [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.1a [p.]).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of Iceland and of the oceanic southern boreal and oceanic middle boreal zones of Norway, developed on moist moraine podsols, with a field layer dominated by ferns.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.2b [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.2b [p.]).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of Iceland, developed on moist moraine podsols, dominated by [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii], with a fern field layer formed predominantly by [Gymnocarpium dryopteris], sometimes accompanied by [Dryopteris assimilis] or [Thelypteris phegopteris].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 64; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.2b [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.2b [p.]).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of the oceanic southern boreal and oceanic middle boreal zones of Norway, developed on moist moraine podsols, with a fern field layer formed predominantly by [Gymnocarpium dryopteris] accompanied by [Dryopteris assimilis], [Thelypteris phegopteris], [Blechnum spicant] or [Dryopteris expansa] and with [Oxalis acetosella], [Lophocolea bidentata], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus], [Rhytidiadelphus triquetrus].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.2b [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.2b [p.]).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of the lowlands of Iceland, occupying thick, relatively rich soils, with a heath-grassland undergrowth dominated by [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Agrostis capillaris], [Deschampsia flexuosa], accompanied by [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Salix callicarpaea] ([Salix arctica]), [Salix lanata], [Salix phylicifolia], [Campanula rotundifolia], [Galium verum], [Hierochloe odorata], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Festuca rubra] [s.l.], [Juncus trifida], [Kobresia myosuroides], [Lycopodium annotinum], [Equisetum pratense].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 64-65; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.2c; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.2c).');
    'Herb-rich woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] occupying relatively rich mull sandy moraine soils in climatically favourable regions of western Norway and Iceland, with affinities to the oro-Scandinavian calcicline mountain birch woods of unit 41.B725.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.2.4.3 [p.], 2.2.4.3a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of the lowlands of Iceland, characterized by a luxuriant shrub and herb layer rich in [Geranium sylvaticum] and [Rubus saxatile]. They mostly occupy hollows where snow lingers in spring, and are covered with snow in winter. Their species cortŠge may include [Salix spp.], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Populus tremula], [Juniperus communis], [Alchemilla vulgaris], [Campanula rotundifolia], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Fragraria vesca], [Galium verum], [Geum rivale], [Hieracium spp.], [Melampyrum sylvaticum], [Prunella vulgaris], [Trientalis europaea], [Elymus caninus] ([Roegneria canina]), [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Festuca rubra] [s.l.], [Hierochloe odorata], [Poa nemoralis], [Poa pratense], [Coeloglossum viride], [Dactylorhiza islandica], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex vaginata], [Luzula multiflora], [Equisetum arvense], [Equisetum pratense], [Athyrium filix-femina], [Gymnocarpium dryopteris] and mosses. These woods constitute, in their northern area of occurrence, the northernmost, dwarfed (0.5-1 m), stands of birch in Iceland.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 64; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.3a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] of rich mull soils in climatically favourable stations of oceanic boreal Norway with a forb-dominated herb layer that includes, among others, [Geranium sylvaticum], [Blechnum spicant], [Cornus suecica], [Thelypteris limbosperma], and a canopy and shrub layer that comprise [Alnus incana], [Populus tremula], [Corylus avellana], [Salix spp.], [Vaccinium spp.], [Juniperus communis].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.3 [p.]).');
    '[Picea abies] woods of anomalous stations at the montane or subalpine level of the Alps, in particular block forests of "ice cellars" (shaded rocky screes through which cold air flows), woods developed in valleys and depressions where cold air accumulates on clear nights, woods colonizing stabilised screes and narrow bands of rocks, woods on moist sites. ', '(Richard and Pautou, 1982: 169; Ellenberg, 1988: 209-210, 215-216, 451; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 322-324; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 74; Seliskar, 1998: 7).');
    '[Picea abies] forests, usually unmixed, forming, in most of the Carpathian arc, a lower subalpine belt between beech-fir or beech-fir-spruce forests of the montane level and the mugo pine upper subalpine zone.
', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Elias y al., 1991; Coldea, 1991; Coldea, 1993).');
    'Subalpine [Picea abies] forests of the northwestern and northern Carpathians of Poland and Slovakia. ', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Subalpine [Picea abies] forests of siliceous soils of the northwestern and northern Carpathians of Poland and Slovakia. ', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Subalpine [Picea abies] forests of calcareous ranges in the northwestern and northern Carpathians of Poland and Slovakia, in particular of the calcareous Tatras. ', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Subalpine [Picea abies] forests of the northern Eastern, the eastern and the southern Carpathians of the Ukraine and Romania.', '(Coldea, 1991; Coldea, 1993).');
    '[Picea abies] forests of the subalpine level, at 1550-1700 metres, of the Eastern Carpathians, with [Pinus mugo], [Pinus cembra], [Rhododendron myrtifolium], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Homogyne alpina], [Soldanella hungarica] ssp. [major] and [Calamagrostis villosa].', '(Coldea, 1991).');
    '[Picea abies] forests of the subalpine level (1600-1850m) of the Apuseni Mountains and the Southern Carpathians, with [Pinus mugo], [Pinus cembra], [Bruckenthalia spiculifolia], [Soldanella hungarica] ssp. [major], [Campanula abietina], [Campanula serrata], [Homogyne alpina] and [Calamagrostis villosa].
', '(Coldea, 1991).');
    '[Picea abies] forests of the upper montane level of the Eastern, Southern and Southwestern Carpathians, with a usually sparse herb layer mostly of acidophilous species including [Hieracium rotundatum], [Calamagrostis villosa], [Calamagrostis arundinacea], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Oxalis acetosella], [Campanula abietina], [Luzula luzuloides], [Luzula sylvatica].', '(Coldea, 1991: 508-512).');
    '[Picea abies] forest stands installed on wet, acid, peaty ground of the margins of bogs and marshes within the montane level of the Eastern and Southwestern Carpathians, with a mucinal layer of [Sphagnum palustre], [Sphagnum wulfianum], [Sphagnum squarrosum], [Bazzania trilobata]; regional species such as [Soldanella hungarica] ssp. [major], [Campanula abietina], [Valeriana simplicifolia], [Salix silesiaca], are characteristic and [Listera cordata] is sometimes present.', '(Borhidi, 1971; Stefureac, 1977; Coldea, 1991: 508-513).');
    '[Picea abies] forests frequently installed along streamsides and inner valleys of lower montane levels of the Eastern and western Southern Carpathians, with a cortŠge including [Adenostyletalia] elements, in particular [Leucanthemum waldsteinii], [Athyrium distentifolium], [Stellaria nemorosum]. ', '(Borhidi, 1971; Coldea, 1991: 512-513; Coldea, 1993: 45).');
    '[Picea abies] forests of the montane level of the inner Alps, characteristic of regions climatically unfavorable to both beech and fir. Analogous [Picea abies] forests of the montane and collinar levels of the inner basin of the Slovakian Carpathians subjected to a climate of high continentality. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Mayer, 1974; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Richard and Pautou, 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987: unit P3b; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Inner Alpine [Picea abies] forests of siliceous crystalline or schistous substrates, with [Calamagrostis villosa] and woodrushes. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 61-64; Richard and Pautou, 1982: 147-149; Noirfalise, 1987: 45; Ellenberg, 1988: 210-213; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 293-295, 317).');
    'Calcicolous inner Alpine [Picea abies] forests with [Calamagrostis varia], [Carex flacca], [Sesleria caerulea], [Hieracium trifidum], [Aster bellidiastrum]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 67-69; Richard and Pautou, 1982: 147; Noirfalise, 1987: 45; Ellenberg, 1988: 210-213; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 319-321).');
    'Xerophile, more or less mesotrophic inner Alpine [Picea abies] or [Picea abies]-[Abies alba] forests, often characterized by an admixture of deciduous trees, in particular [Acer pseudoplatanus], [Fraxinus excelsior], and with a species-rich herb layer comprising [Oxalis acetosella], [Galium rotundifolium], [Galium odoratum], [Anemone nemorosa], [Doronicum austriacum], [Petasites albus], [Primula elatior], [Fragaria vesca], [Cardamine trifolia], [Carex montana] and [Melica nutans].', '(Mayer, 1974: 64-67; Noirfalise, 1987: 45; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 315-317).');
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests of the Taurus and the Amanus mountains, sometimes accompanied by [Juniperus excelsa] or [Cedrus atlantica], located at altitudes between 1200-1400 metres and 1900-2100 metres, in areas with two to three months of snow cover, 500-1500 mm of rain and three to six months of summer drought a year, occupying more xeric sites than the cedar and fir forests.  
', '(Noirfalise, 1987: unit H8).');
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests occupying calcareous substrates of the Taurus Mountains, with [Thlaspi oxyceras].', NULL);
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests occupying marly sandstones of the Taurus Mountains, with [Symphytum palaestinum]. ', NULL);
    '[Pinus pallasiana] forests forming a narrow altitudinal belt on the southeastern slope of the southern part of the Crimean mountains, below the  forests of [Pinus sylvestris] ssp. [hamata] ([Pinus kochiana]).', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986).');
    'Plantations of pines of the [Pinus nigra] group, accompanied by seminatural undergrowth formations. These are usually calciphilous communities when accompanying [Pinus nigra], acidophilous ones when with [Pinus laricio]. In all cases they can be specified by codes borrowed from other units, used in conjunction with unit 42.67.', '(Wendelberger, 1963; Fenaroli, 1970, 1984; Bonin,1971; Horvat y al., 1974; Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Mavrommatis, 1978; Lopez-Gonzalez, 1982; Pignatti, 1982; Ozenda, 1985; Bassani, 1987; Ferioli, 1989; Strid, 1989; Pignatti, 1993).');
    'Woods of [Pinus heldreichii], [Pinus leucodermis] or [Pinus peuce]. ', NULL);
    'Local treeline formations of [Pinus heldreichii] or [Pinus leucodermis] restricted to the southern Balkans, northern Greece and southern Italy, usually open and with an undergrowth formed by stripped grasslands on dry, often stony or rocky soils.', '(Fenaroli, 1970, 1984; Bonin, 1971; Debazac and Mavrommatis, 1971; Horvat y al., 1974: 553, 560-562; Strid, 1980; Pignatti, 1982; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Bassani, 1987; Ferioli, 1989).');
    'Rare white-barked pine formations of high southern Italian mountains, limited to the Abruzzian Appenines (Montagna della Maiella), the Campanian Apennines (monti Picentini) and the Lucano-Calabrian Apennines (Pollino, monti Alpi di Latronico, monte la Spina, monti di Orsomarso, monte Montea, serra delle Ciavole). ', '(Fenaroli, 1970, 1984; Bonin, 1971; Pignatti, 1982; Braschi, 1986; Bassani, 1987; Ferioli, 1989). ');
