    '[Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [phoenicea] and [Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [lycia] forests of the Mediterranean and Saharo-Mediterranean regions. Mediterranean formations dominated by [Juniperus phoenicea] are scrubs, thickets or arborescent matorrals, listed under units 32.132, 32.45, 32.55, 32.B5 or, in dunal formations, unit 16.272. Exceptional, tall and dense formations, however, may be more appropriately characterized as woodland and listed in this unit. Saharo-Mediterranean formations may more often take the appearence of an open or steppe forest, listed here and under 9.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Zohary, 1973; Garcia and Purroy, 1973; Diez y al., 1975; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; White, 1983; Géhu, 1985; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 80).');
    'Uncommon forest-like [Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [phoenicea] and [Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [lycia] formations of rocky scarps, plateaux and slopes, coastal dunes of the western and central Mediterranean basin, the North African coastal areas, the eastern Aegean coast and Cyprus. Most Mediterranean formations dominated by [Juniperus phoenicea] are scrubs, thickets or arborescent matorrals, listed under units 32.132, 32.45, 32.55, 32.B5 or, in dunal formations, unit 16.272. Only exceptional, tall and dense formations, appropriately characterized as woodland, are listed in this unit.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Zohary, 1973; Garcia and Purroy, 1973; Diez y al., 1975; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; White, 1983; Géhu, 1985; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 80).');
    'Uncommon forest-like [Juniperus phoenicea] formations of rocky scarps, plateaux and slopes of the western and central Mediterranean basin, the western North African coastal areas, Crete, the eastern Aegean islands, the western Anatolian coasts, Cyprus, Jordan, the Sinai, Cyrenaica. Most Mediterranean formations dominated by [Juniperus phoenicea] are scrubs, thickets or arborescent matorrals, listed under units 32.132, 32.45, 32.55, 32.B5 or, in dunal formations, unit 16.272. Only exceptional, tall and dense formations, appropriately characterized as woodland, are listed in this unit.', '(Holmboe, 1914: 285-289; Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Zohary, 1973: 28, 153-154, 350-351, 522, 530; Meikle, 1977: 8; White, 1983: 153; Viney, 1994: xvi; Prpic, 1996: 67; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 80).');
    'Well-developed [Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [lycia] woods and forests of the inner belt of the juniper woods of fixed Mediterranean and Mediterraneo-Atlantic dunes. Thickets and low woods are placed in unit 16.272.', '(Garcia and Purroy, 1973; Knapp, 1973: 485; Diez y al., 1975; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Géhu, 1985; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 92).');
    '[Juniperus phoenicea] forests and steppe-forests of rocky high plateaux and mountains of the High Atlas, the Middle Atlas, the Anti-Atlas, the Moulouya Valley, central Algeria, the Saharan Atlas, the Tunisian Dorsale, Tripolitania, the Jebel Akhdar, the Sinai, Jordan and the western Arabian peninsula.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Kanter, 1967; Le Houérou, 1969; Zohary, 1973; Herbauts, 1973: 334-335; Knapp, 1973: 483; White, 1983: 153; Zahran and Willis, 1992: 299; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 80).');
    '[Platycladus orientalis] ([Thuja orientalis], [Biota orientalis]) forests scattered in restricted areas of the Hyrcanian zone of the Elburz range of northern Iran, constituting a very isolated occurrence of the species; they develop in the same 2000 to 2500 metre altitudinal level as the [Cupressus sempervirens] formations, or mixed with them; [Crataegus monogyna], [Paliurus spina-christi], [Pyrus cordata], [Quercus castaneifolia] accompany the thuja.', '(Riedel, 1968; Zohary, 1973: 532, 561; Rushforth, 1987; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 242-243).');
    'Eastern Mediterranean and western North African forests dominated by [Cedrus libani], [Cedrus brevifolia] or [Cedrus atlantica].', '(Noirfalise, 1987; Rushforth, 1987; Dallman, 1998; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 74-77).');
    'Forests of [Cedrus libani] of the Taurus system, of Paphlagonia and of the Levant.', '(Zohary, 1973; Quézel, 1981a: 91).');
    'Forests of [Cedrus libani] of the western Taurus, pure or mixed with [Acer sempervirens], [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus montana], [Populus tremula], developed at between 1500 and 2000 metres on limestones and rendzinas under a cold and snowy climate. The undergrowth includes [Alliaria officinalis], [Oryzopsis holciformis] and the endemics [Paeonia turcica], [Pentapera bocquetii], [Ebenus boissieri], [Campanula michauxioides].', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 560-561; Noirfalise, 1987: unit H10 [p.]).');
    'Tall [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] woods of the subalpine belt of Fennoscandian mountains, occasionally accompanied by [Alnus incana], [Prunus padus], [Salix spp.], with a fern-rich field layer dominated by [Athyrium filix-femina], [Matteuccia struthiopteris], [Dryopteris expansa], accompanied by [Athyrium distentifolium], [Phegopteris connectilis], [Thelypteris limbosperma] and tall herbs; the species cortŠge includes [Aconitum septentrionale] ([Aconitum lycoctonum]), [Solidago virgaurea], [Stellaria nemorum], [Viola biflora], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Geranium sylvestris], [Ribes rubrum], [Rubus idaeus], [Rubus saxatilis], [Calamagrostis purpurea], [Deschampsia cespitosa]; tall-fern hirch woods are developed on sandy moraines with good water supply.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.4a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.4a).');
    '[Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] ([Betula pubescens] ssp. [tortuosa], [Betula kusmisscheffii]) woods and thickets of the mountains and tundra timberline of the Kola peninsula.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 2; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 6; Walter, 1974: 40, 44; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 458-459). ');
    'Timberline birch woods and thickets of the Urals formed by krumholz [Betula pubescens] [s.l.] ([Betula tortuosa] [s.l.]).', '(Walter, 1974: 328, 329, 334, 335, 336, 338; Schroeder, 1998: 380).');
    '[Betula ermani] or [Betula middendorffii] woods and thickets forming at the timberline of the mountains of eastern Siberia, Kamchatka, Sakhaline and Hokkaido.', '(Saphronova, 1964c: unit 43; Walter, 1974; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 457-458; Schroeder, 1998: 377, 379).');
    '[Betula ermani] woods and thickets forming at the timberline of the mountains of Kamchatka, Sakhaline and Hokkaido.', '(Saphronova, 1964c: unit 43; Walter, 1974: 39, 40, 43, 48-50, 102; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 457-458; Schroeder, 1998: 377, 379).');
    '[Betula middendorffii] woods and thickets forming at the timberline of the mountains of eastern Siberia, in particular the Verkoiansk Range, the Anadyr Range, the mountains of the Ba¿kal area and of Transba¿kalia, the Greater Khingan Range.', '(Walter, 1974: 38, 43, 45, 46, 94, 95, 102, 219).');
    'Birch woods of the taiga belt, of the wooded tundra belt, and of the taiga-nemoral forest transition zone of Eurasia, formed by [Betula pendula], [Betula pubescens] [s.l.] or [Betula platyphylla].', '(Walter, 1974; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Jahn, 1991; Shugart y al., 1992; Påhlsson, 1994; Schroeder, 1998).');
    'Birch woods of the taiga and wooded tundra belts and of the transition zones between taiga and nemoral forests of Fennoscandia, the northern Sarmatic region and western Siberia, formed by [Betula pendula], or, sometimes, [Betula pubescens], with [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Agrostis capillaris], [Festuca ovina], [Trientalis europaea], [Melampyrum pratense], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Juniperus communis], [Rubus idaeus], [Equisetum sylvaticum] and, in some communities, [Cornus suecica].', '(Walter, 1974: 58, 80, 106, 108; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.2.4.5, 2.2.4.5a, 2.2.4.6; Jahn, 1991: 454; Shugart y al., 1992; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.2.1.5, 2.2.1.5a, 2.2.1.7; Schroeder, 1998: 311; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Birch woods of the taiga and wooded tundra belts of eastern Siberia and the eastern Siberian mountains, formed by [Betula platyphylla] or, sometimes, [Betula pendula].', '(Walter, 1974: 97, 102; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Schroeder, 1998: 300, 303, 314).');
    'Open, often parklike, woods of [Betula pendula], [Betula platyphylla] or [Betula pubescens] [s.l.] of the transition zone between steppe and taiga of Siberia, east of the range of the nemoral deciduous forests of the Sarmatic region.', '(Walter, 1974: 101-102, 156-157, 164, 166, 218, 224, 240; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 45; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 195; Korotkov y al., 1991: 301; Schroeder, 1998: 311).');
    'Open, often parklike, woods of [Betula pendula] and [Populus tremula] (listed under 41.D7 when dominated by the latter) of the transition zone between steppe and taiga of Siberia, east of the range of the nemoral deciduous forests of the Sarmatic region. The shrub layer includes [Lonicera altaica], [Lonicera tatarica], [Thelycrania alba] ([Cornus alba]), [Ribes nigrum], [Ribes rubrum], [Spiraea hypericifolia], [Cotoneaster multiflorus]; the meadow-like herb layer is formed by [Agrostis alba], [Calamagrostis arundinacea], [Poa pratensis], [Bromus inermis], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Astragalus danicus], [Campanula bononiensis]].', '(Walter, 1974: 156-157, 164, 218; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 45; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 195; Korotkov y al., 1991: 301; Schroeder, 1998: 311).');
    'Open, often parklike, woods of [Betula platyphylla] of the transition zone between Eastern Siberian steppes and the taiga of northern Siberia or of the Siberian mountains.', '(Walter, 1974: 101-102, 166, 224; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 45).');
    '[Betula kirghisorum] ([Betula pubescens] [s.l.]) woods, enclaved, south of the wooded steppe zone of Eurasia, within the northern steppe zone, on saline soils of northern Kazakhstan.', '(Walter, 1974: 240; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181). ');
    'Birch forests of the northern Black Sea basin, Anatolia, the Caucasus and neighbouring regions. ', '(Walter, 1974: 153-154, 185, 356, 375-376, 387-388; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Röhrig, 1991h: 532; Schroeder, 1998: 311).');
    'Restricted [Picea abies] forests of sub-alpine affinities of the Jura, comprising truly sub-alpine formations of the Haut-Jura, well developed but of small extent because of relatively low altitude and competition with [Pinus uncinata] formations, tall herb spruce forests as well as cold station or "ice cellar" formations similar to those of the northern outer Alps.', '(Richard and Pautou, 1982: 168, 171; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 74).');
    '[Picea abies] forests of the Black Forest, characteristic of the subalpine level and of edaphic enclaves and cold stations, rich in [Bazzania trilobata], with [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Listera cordata], [Lycopodium annotinum]. ', '(Noirfalise, 1987: 41; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 68-69).');
    'Edaphic [Picea abies] enclaves of the montane and submontane levels of the pre-Alps and the pre-Alpine plateaux rich in [Bazzania trilobata], in particular, block forests, boulder field forests, frost-pocket forests and woods on moist soils.', '(Oberdorfer, 1992b: 68-69; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 292-293; Seliskar, 1998: 7).');
    'Spruce forests of the montane or submontane levels of the outer Alps, of the mid-Pannonic hills, of the outer Western and Northern Carpathians, of the Eastern and Southern Carpathians, of the west Ukrainian pre-Carpathic hills and plateaux, of the Jura system and of the Hercynian arc dominated by [Picea abies] with a varying admixture of [Abies alba], [Fagus sylvatica] or both. They include spruce or fir-spruce forests and spruce-dominated facies of montane or submontane beech-fir forests.', '(Mayer, 1974; Horvat y al., 1974: 564-565; Ozenda, 1981; Richard and Pautou, 1982; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Sanda y al., 1992; Donita and Coldea, 1992; Coldea, 1992; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Wallnöfer, 1993b).');
    'Spruce and fir-spruce forests of the montane or submontane levels of the outer Alps, of the mid-Pannonic hills, of the outer Western and Northern Carpathians, of the Jura system and of the Hercynian arc, including spruce facies of fir-beech forests of the range of the [Fagion medio-europaeum]. Spruce-dominated facies of Alpine beech-fir forests of the range of the [Fagion illyricum] are listed separately in unit 42.2542.
', '(Mayer, 1974; Horvat y al., 1974: 564-565; Ozenda, 1981; Richard and Pautou, 1982; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Wallnöfer, 1993b).');
    'Neutrophile spruce forests of the montane or submontane levels of the outer Alps, of the mid-Pannonic hills, of the outer Western and Northern Carpathians, of the Jura system and of the Hercynian arc dominated by [Picea abies] with a varying admixture of [Abies alba], [Fagus sylvatica] or both. They include fir-spruce forests, with a species cortŠge composed by elements of the [Fagetalia] and of the [Piceetalia], as well as, within the range of [Fagion medio-europaeum] beech-fir forests, spruce-dominated facies of montane or submontane beech-fir forests.
', '(Mayer, 1974: 88-95, 112-115, 118; Horvat y al., 1974: 564-565; Ozenda, 1981: 166-173; Richard and Pautou, 1982: 126-131, 133-135; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 235-236; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 156-158, 159-163; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 315-317).');
    'Calciphile spruce forests of the montane or submontane levels of the outer Alps, of the outer Western and Northern Carpathians, of the Jura system and of the Hercynian arc dominated by [Picea abies] with a varying admixture of [Abies alba], [Fagus sylvatica] or both. They include fir-spruce forests, with a species cortŠge composed by elements of the [Fagetalia] and of the [Piceetalia], as well as, within the range of [Fagion medio-europaeum] beech-fir forests, spruce-dominated facies of montane or submontane beech-fir forests.', '(Mayer, 1974: 95-100; Horvat y al., 1974: 564-565; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 236-237; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 166; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 318-322).');
    'Acidiphile spruce forests of the montane or submontane levels of the outer Alps, of the outer Western and Northern Carpathians, of the Jura system and of the Hercynian arc dominated by [Picea abies] with a varying admixture of [Abies alba], [Fagus sylvatica] or both.', '(Mayer, 1974: 88-95; Horvat y al., 1974: 564-565; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 64-66; Ozenda, 1981: 168-170; Richard and Pautou, 1982: 131-133; Moravec y al., 1983: 78; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 64-68; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 293-295).');
    'Montane inner Alpine [Picea abies] or [Picea abies]-[Abies alba] forests of humid peaty-loamy soils characterized by a frequent admixture of deciduous trees, including [Alnus incana], a strongly developed moss layer and a rich herb layer with many hygrophiles, in particular, [Equisetum sylvaticum], [Equisetum arvense], [Equisetum pratense], [Equisetum telmateia], [Caltha palustris], [Valeriana dioica], [Veronica beccabunga], [Cardamine amara].', '(Wallnöfer, 1993b: 324-325).');
    '[Picea abies]-dominated facies of montane [Fagion illyricum] beech-fir forests of the southeastern outer Alps. Spruce-dominated forests of the same region replacing the beech-fir forests in stations edaphically or microclimatically unfavourable to beech and fir have been listed in unit 42.2541.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 422-428, 432-437; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 179-180; Seliskar, 1998: 3-4).');
    '[Picea abies]-dominated forests of the montane level of the Romanian, Ukrainian and eastern Serbian Carpathians, east of the Uz and the Stry, and of the west Ukrainian pre-Carpathic hills and plateaux, within the range of [Fagion dacicum] beech-fir forests, of which they may constitute a facies or a substitute in stations edaphically or microclimatically unfavourable to beech and fir.', '(Sanda y al., 1992: 117; Donita and Coldea, 1992: 147; Coldea, 1992: 174).');
    '[Pinus pinaster] forests of siliceous lower meso-Mediterranean areas of Provence, of marls and limestones of the upper meso-Mediterranean level of the Maritime Alps and the Ligurian Alps, and of mostly siliceous or clayey soils of the hills of Liguria and Tuscany. ', '(Archiloque y al., 1969; Fenaroli, 1970; Lavagne and Moutte, 1977; Brullo y al., 1977; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Pignatti, 1982; Guittonneau and Huon, 1983; Gamisans, 1985; Bournérias y al., 1991; Pignatti, 1993: 387-388).');
    '[Pinus pinaster]-dominated forests of the meso- and supra-Mediterranean levels of Corsica, mostly on granitic substrates; they are very developed, accompanied by a maquis-like understorey, in the meso-Mediterranean zone, mostly at its upper tier; they occur locally within the supra-Mediterranean zone, on adrets and at lower altitudes, as facies of laricio pine forests. ', '(Pignatti, 1982; Guittonneau and Huon, 1983; Gamisans, 1985).');
    '[Pinus pinaster] formations on granitic substrates of northern Sardinia, with [Arbutus unedo], [Quercus ilex], [Rosmarinus officinalis], [Erica arborea], [Genista corsica], [Lavandula stoechas], [Rubia peregrina], [Calicotome spinosa], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Teucrium marum]. ', '(Fenaroli, 1970; Pignatti, 1982).');
    '[Pinus pinaster] woods of Pantelleria. ', '(Fenaroli, 1970; Brullo y al., 1977; Pignatti, 1982).');
    'Dominant, probably subclimactic woodlands of Pantelleria, constituted by [Pinus pinaster], with [Genista aspalathoides], [Erica multiflora], [Cistus salvifolius], [Lavandula stoechas], [Rosmarinus officinalis], [Daphne gnidium], [Arbutus unedo], [Myrtus communis], [Erica arborea], [Carex illegitima]. ', '(Brullo y al., 1977).');
    'Mixed [Pinus pinaster] and [Quercus ilex] formations of Pantelleria Grande and Monte Gibele, with [Arbutus unedo] and [Erica arborea]. ', NULL);
    'Forests of [Pinus pinaster] ssp. [hamiltonii] of the humid and semihumid levels of mountains of Morocco, from 1019 metres in the Rif and between 1500 and 2200 metres in the middle and high Atlas. [Cedrus atlantica] and, in the Rif, the North African endemic [Abies marocana] and [Pinus salzmannii] ssp. [mauretanica] may enter in the composition of the forest.', '(Herbauts, 1973: 351; Knapp, 1973: 476; White, 1983: 155; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 78-79).');
    'Forests of [Pinus pinaster] ssp. [renoui] of Numidian sandstones of the humid littoral zone of eastern Algeria and extreme western Tunisia, with [Arbutus unedo], [Erica arborea], [Erica scoparia], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Halimium halimifolium], [Teucrium fruticans], [Ampelodesmos mauritanica].', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Knapp, 1973: 476; White, 1983: 155).');
