    'Forests of [Cedrus brevifolia], endemic to Cyprus where they are limited to the western summits of the Troodos range, in the 900-1400 metre range.', '(Holmboe, 1914: 310-315; Zohary, 1973: 28, 153, 345-346, 562; Meikle, 1977: 2; Rushforth, 1987; Sfikas, 1992).');
    'Forests of [Cedrus atlantica] of the cold, humid and sub-humid levels of the Rif, the Middle Atlas, the High Atlas, the Aures, the Kabylian mountains and the Constantine Tell.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Herbauts, 1973: 344-347; Knapp, 1973: 476-477; White, 1983: 155-156; Foucault, 1993b: 268; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 74-77).');
    'Boreal spruce, spruce-pine, pine, or occasionally larch, forests of Fennoscandia, northern and, mostly, extreme northeastern, Poland, the Baltic States, Belarus and European Russia, west of the middle Pechora, middle Kama basins and the western piedmont of the Urals, constituting the westernmost section of the continuous Eurasian northern taiga belt. They are predominantly dark taiga forests formed by [Picea abies], or, in the east, [Picea obovata], and [Pinus sylvestris], in pure or mixed stands, with only occasional, limited, edaphic pockets dominated by [Larix russica] ([Larix sukaczewii]).', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 3-11; Saphronova, 1964c: units 7-13; Tikhomirov, 1970: 37; Birot, 1970: 115-118, 121, 159-160, 170-171; Walter, 1974: 52-78, 105-117; Sokolowski, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 102-103, 210-212; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 362-392, 405-453; Rieley and Page, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Shugart y al., 1992; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994; Huetz de Lemps, 1994: 85-87; Krassilov, 1995: 40; Nilsson, 1996; Nilsson y al., 1996; Lundmark, 1996; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996).');
    'Forests of [Picea abies], [Picea obovata], or [Picea spp.] and [Pinus sylvestris], of Fennoscandia, Russia west of the Ural piedmont, Belarus, the Baltic States, northeastern Poland, with an understorey dominated by [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Deschampsia flexuosa] and mosses, developed on mesic moraine ground, on podsols with heavy raw humus. They constitute the most widespread and characteristic type of western spruce taiga in the boreal zone and extend to the boreonemoral zone. Accompanying small tree and shrub species include [Betula pubescens], [Sorbus aucuparia], [Empetrum spp.], [Juniperus communis], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Ledum palustre] (in the north), with a field layer comprising [Linnaea borealis], [Maianthemum bifolium], [Melampyrum pratense], [Solidago virgaurea], [Trientalis europaea], [Luzula pilosa], [Lycopodium annotinum], [Dicranum spp.], [Hylocomium splendens], [Pleurozium schreberi]. In the boreo-nemoral zone, deciduous trees may accompany the conifers, in particular, [Quercus robur], [Tilia cordata], [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus laevis], [Populus tremula].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5-8, 11, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8-10, 13 [p.]; Birot, 1970: 121, 159-160; Walter, 1974: 55-70, 107; Sokolowski, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.1, 2.1.3.3; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 370-371, 379-387, 407-451; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Rieley and Page, 1990: 31-34; Korotkov y al., 1991: 285-286; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.1; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 58; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Bilberry spruce and spruce-pine forests of boreal Fennoscandia and Russia, east of the Scandinavian mountains and west of the Northern Dvina and Vetluga rivers, extending in the subboreal zone, particularly in Scandinavia, developed under subcontinental to near-continental climates, dominated by [Picea abies], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris], and with a species cortŠge devoid of oceanic elements.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5a, 6a, 7a, 8, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8a, 9a, 10a, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 55-63; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.1 [p.], 2.1.3.3 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 370-371, 379-382, 407-451; Korotkov y al., 1991: 285-286; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.1 [p.]; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 58).');
    'Bilberry spruce and spruce-pine forests of western Norway, with a species cortŠge enriched in oceanic or suboceanic elements, in particular, [Betula pubescens], [Cornus suecica], [Plagiothecium undulatum], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 6a [p.]; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.1 [p.], 2.1.3.3 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.1 [p.]).');
    'Bilberry spruce and spruce-pine forests of boreal Russia, east of the Northern Dvina and Vetluga rivers, and west of the Ural piedmont, extending in the subboreal zone, developed under continental climates, dominated by [Picea obovata], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris] or [Abies sibirica].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5b, 6b, 7b, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8b, 9b, 10b, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 65-70; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 382-283; Korotkov y al., 1991: 285-286).');
    'Tall (up to 12 m) woods of the subalpine belt of Fennoscandian mountains dominated by [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii], with [Salix spp.], [Sorbus aucuparia], [Prunus padus] and an undergrowth dominated by tall herbs, comprising, together with abundant [Geranium sylvaticum], [Trollius europaeus], [Rubus saxatilis], [Aconitum septentrionale] ([Aconitum licoctonum]), [Cirsium helenioides], [Cicerbita alpina], [Epilobium angustifolium], [Ranunculus platanifolius]. The  well-developed taller shrub understorey is dominated by [Juniperus communis], accompanied by [Salix spp.]; dwarf shrubs are often absent and the moss and lichen layer is very poorly developed; ferns are common. The species cortŠge includes [Alchemilla spp.], [Astragalus alpinus], [Myosotis decumbens], [Paris quadrifolia], [Silene dioica], [Solidago virgaurea], [Stellaria nemorum], [Valeriana sambucifolia], [Vicia biflora], [Milium effusum], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Calamagrostis purpurea], [Anthoxanthum odoratum], [Carex vaginata]. These woods occupy well-drained, mull-rich soils.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.4).');
    '[Betula pendula] woods of the Ponto-Caspian basin, the Caucasus, Anatolia, western Iran and Mesopotamia, widespread south of the Ponto-Caspian depessions, represented by rare outposts north of the basin, in particular in Crimea. ', '(Walter, 1974: 356, 375-376, 385-388; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 538; Röhrig, 1991h: 532; Shugart y al., 1992: 22).');
    '[Betula litwinowii] and [Betula litwinowii-Betula pendula] woods of eastern Anatolia, the Caucasus and the Ponto-Caspian basin. ', '(Walter, 1974: 153-154, 185, 375-376, 387-388; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Röhrig, 1991h: 532).');
    'Woods of [Betula litwinowii], usually with [Betula pendula], of the regions of Tunceli, Erzurum and Kars, at between 1500 and 2500 metres. ', '(Röhrig, 1991h: 532).');
    '[Betula litwinowii]-dominated woods of the Bol''shoy and Malyy Kavkaz ranges.', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 538; Röhrig, 1991h: 532).');
    '[Betula pubescens] woods of the steppe regions of the northern Ponto-Caspian basin, characteristic in particular of the sand terrasses of the lower Dnjepr. ', '(Walter, 1974: 153-154, 185; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181).');
    'Birch woods of the Caucasus dominated by the scarce [Betula raddeana].', '(Walter, 1974: 375-376, 387-388; Röhrig, 1991h: 532).');
    'Woods and thickets of [Betula medwediewii], pure or mixed with [Quercus pontica], [Sorbus subfusca], [Rhododendron caucasicum], [Laurocerasus officinalis], [Ilex aquifolium], [Vaccinium arctostaphylos], characteristic of the 800 to 2300 m level of Transcaucasia, with isolated outposts in the eastern Black Sea region of Turkey. ', '(Walter, 1974: 387-388; Röhrig, 1991h: 532).');
    'Birch woods of the Caucasus system dominated by [Betula megrelica], local and limited to the subalpine level.', '(Walter, 1974: 387). ');
    '[Betula turkestanica], [Betula tadzhikistanica], [Betula chitralica] formations of the Tien Shan and Pamir Alai systems, and of the northeastern Afghan mountains.', '(Browicz, 1972; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Schroeder, 1998: 311).');
    '[Betula utilis] ([Betula jacquemontii]) woods and thickets constituting or participating in the timberline formations (2700-3350 m) of the Nuristan Himalayas.', '(Schweinfurth, 1957: 302-3O4; Kitamura, 1960: 14, 82; Walter, 1974: 283; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 190-195; Schroeder, 1998: 317, 363-365). ');
    '[Betula spp.]-dominated formations, most characteristic of the timberline, of the borea-nemoral, nemoral and warm temperate zones of Eastern Asia. Birch woods of the larch, larch-pine and larch-pine-spruce zones of the southern boreal mountains of eastern Asia.
', '(Walter, 1974: 103-104, 313, 318; Tolmachev, 1980: 180-181; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 36-38; Richardson, 1990: 52; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 283, 321-322; Schroeder, 1998: 274, 367, 376).');
    'Nonriparian, nonmarshy woods of the western Palaearctic region dominated by [Alnus spp.] ', '(Fenaroli, 1970; Simms, 1971; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Gamisans, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Ferioli, 1989; Bondev, 1991: unit 24; Rodwell, 1991a; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    '[Alnus cordata]-dominated formations of slopes with deep, loose, moist soils, endemic to the Campanian, Lucanian and Calabrian Apennines and the Castaniccia and San Petrone ranges of Corsica. ', '(Fenaroli, 1970; Gamisans, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Ferioli, 1989; Pignatti, 1998: unit 84). ');
    'Nonriparian, nonmarshy formations of the nemoral or boreonemoral zones dominated by [Alnus glutinosa] or [Alnus incana].', '(Simms, 1971; Ferchmin, 1980; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Bondev, 1991: unit 24; Korotkov y al., 1991; Rodwell, 1991a; Dyduch Falniowska, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Nonriparian, nonmarshy formations of Atlantic regions of the nemoral zone dominated by [Alnus glutinosa] or [Alnus incana].', '(Simms, 1971; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W6d; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.7).');
    'Forests of [Picea abies] with beech of the Southern Carpathians on calcareous substrates, generally located on south-facing slopes, with an herb layer dominated by [Asplenium viride], [Cystopteris fragilis] and [Saxifraga rotundifolia] ssp. [heuffelii]. ', '(Coldea, 1993: 44-45).');
    '[Picea abies]-dominated facies of neutrophile and acidophile forests of the high montane level of the Eastern and Southern Carpathians, in particular,  communities rich in [Orthilia secunda] and [Pyrola rotundifolia].', '(Coldea, 1991: 492, unit 6).');
    'Spruce forests of the subalpine, montane or submontane levels of the Dinarides dominated by [Picea abies] with a varying admixture of [Abies alba], [Fagus sylvatica] or both. They include subalpine spruce forests, edaphic or microclimatic montane spruce or fir-spruce forests and, occasionally, spruce-dominated facies of montane or submontane [Fagion illyricum] and [Fagion moesiacum] beech-fir forests. They extend throughout the range, from the northern edge of the Dinarides in Slovenia south to the Tara, Povlen, Zlatibor, Golija, Zeljin and Kopaonik ranges, immediately to the north of the Metohija depression. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 422-428, 432-437, 562-568).');
    '[Picea abies]-dominated forests of montane and subalpine block slopes and of karst-dolines of the Dinarides of Slovenia, Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina, within or immediately above the range of fir-beech forests of the [Fagion illyricum].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 432-436, 444-449, 444; Seliskar, 1998: 7-8).');
    '[Picea abies]-dominated forests of dolomite rendzina of the Dinarides of Croatia and western Bosnia-Herzegovina, within the range of fir-beech forests of the [Fagion illyricum], with a species cortŠge that combines raw humus species with calciphile and xerophile species.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 449-450).');
    '[Picea abies]-dominated forests of acid soils of the montane level of the Dinarides of Slovenia, Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina, within or immediately above the range of fir-beech forests of the [Fagion illyricum], with a species cortŠge characteristic of the [Vaccinio-Piceetalia], often including many ferns.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 437, 450-452).');
    'Spruce forests of the southern Dinarides of Serbia, developed on both calcareous and siliceous substrates, in particular in the Tara, Povlen, Zlatibor, Golija, Zeljin and Kopaonik ranges.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 565-568).');
    'Plantations of [Picea abies] in or near the present or recent natural range of the species, including all Hercynian and peri-Hercynian formations accompanied by seminatural undergrowth. Intensive, very dense and out-of-station plantations of [Picea abies] should be listed as unit 83.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Mayer, 1974; Horvat y al., 1974; Bary-Lenger y al., 1979; Ozenda, 1985).');
    '[Picea omorika]-dominated forests of the Drina basin of central Serbia.', '(Horvat y al., 1974; Rushforth, 1987).');
    '[Picea orientalis]-dominated forests of the Caucasus and of the eastern Pontic Range.', '(Walter, 1974: 386-387).');
    'Forests of the subalpine and sometimes montane levels of the Alps and the Carpathians, dominated by [Larix decidua] or [Pinus cembra]; the two species may form either pure or mixed stands, and may be associated with [Picea abies] or, in the western Alps, [Pinus uncinata].', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Mayer, 1974; Ozenda, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Oberdorfer, 1990). ');
    'Subalpine [Larix decidua], [Pinus cembra], or [Larix decidua]-[Pinus cembra] forests of the eastern and central Alps, mostly of the inner ranges, usually on siliceous substrates, with an often species-poor undergrowth comprising [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Rhododendron ferrugineum], [Calamagrostis villosa], [Luzula albida].', '(Ellenberg, 1963; Mayer, 1974; Ozenda, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 271-274).');
    'Forests limited to ubacs, formed by vigorous [Pinus cembra] in often pure, dense, shady stands, with rarer [Larix decidua] and sporadic [Picea abies]; the ground layer may include [Linnaea borealis], [Listera cordata]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 19-22)');
    'Forests characteristic of steep adrets in the lower subalpine level of the eastern intermediate Alps, usually dominated by [Pinus cembra], often in dense stands. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 25)');
    'More open forests than those of units 42.311 and 42.312, with [Pinus cembra] usually dominant, but [Larix decidua] more abundant and a more extensive heath element. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 22)');
    'Forests of adrets, usually open, with [Larix decidua] dominant, [Pinus cembra] and [Picea abies] in enclaves, and an undergrowth less rich in heaths but more in gramineous stands with [Calamagrostis villosa] and woodrushes. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 22-25)');
    'Xerophile [Larix decidua] and [Pinus cembra] forests of adrets with [Pinus mugo]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 25-26)');
    'Xerophile [Larix decidua] and [Pinus cembra] forests of adrets with [Juniperus nana] and [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 26)');
    '[Pinus pinea] forests of the foothills of the Southern Iberian Range and the plateaux of La Mancha, also mostly of artificial origin. ', NULL);
    '[Pinus pinea] formations of the Balearic Islands, native only on Ibiza and Formentera. ', '(Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Ciaran and Blanco, 1984; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115). ');
    '[Pinus pinea] formations of Provence, possibly spontaneous on coastal sands and in the Maures area. ', '(Loisel, 1971; Lavagne and Moutte, 1977; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Ozenda, 1981; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115; Bournérias y al., 1991).');
    '[Pinus pinea] woods of coastal sands, particularly of the Camargue, where it is associated with [Juniperus phoenicea] ssp. [lycia]. ', '(Molinier and Martin, 1980: 15).');
    '[Pinus pinea] woods of the Permian depression encircling the Maures, and a few neighbouring localities, associated mostly with maquis of [Cistus monspeliensis], [Cistus salvifolius], [Cistus ladanifer], [Erica scoparia]. ', '(Loisel, 1971; Lavagne and Moutte, 1977; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Ozenda, 1981; Bournérias y al., 1991).');
    '[Pinus pinea] formations of the littoral of Corsica, some of which may be of natural origin, in particular on old dunes of the east coast. ', '(Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115; Bournérias y al., 1990).');
    '[Pinus pinea] formations of Sardinia. ', '(Fenaroli, 1984; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115; Pratesi and Tassi, 1986; Ferioli, 1989). ');
    '[Pinus pinea] forest of coastal dunes of Iglesiente, west of Monte Linas, comprising plurisecular trees and of undoubted indigenous origin. ', NULL);
    'Other [Pinus pinea] woods of Sardinia, some particularly in the vicinity of Monte Linas, of possible native origin. ', NULL);
    '[Pinus pinea] formations of the Monti Peloritani, northwestern Sicily, of probable native origin. ', '(Fenaroli, 1984; Tassi, 1985; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115; Ferioli, 1989). ');
    'Large [Pinus pinea] forests and ancient plantations of the Tyrhenian and  Adriatic coasts of the Italian peninsula, in Liguria, Toscany, Latium, Campania, Emilia-Romagna (Ravenna) and Friuli-Venetia Giulia (Grado). At least the forests of the Adriatic coast, between Ravenna and the P¿, are of natural origine, with a continuous record since post-glacial times.', '(Fenaroli, 1984; Tassi, 1985; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115; Ferioli, 1989; Pignatti, 1993: 387-388). ');
    '[Pinus pinea] woods of the littoral and coastal hills of the Peloponnese, Chalcidice, Crete and Aegean islands, rather local but probably in part, at least, spontaneous; a splendid example exists, in particular, on Skiathos. ', '(Rechinger, 1943, 1951; Sfikas, 1978; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115; Kassioumis, 1988). ');
    '[Pinus pinea] forests of the southern Adriatic and Otranto Canal coastlands of Albania, where they form, in particular, considerable forests of varied composition on coastal sands between the Shkumbin and Seman rivers.', '(Demiri, 1962: 69-74; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115; Demiri, 1990: 320).');
    '[Pinus pinea] forests of the eastern Adriatic coastlands, distributed, in particular, in Istria and the Gulf of Rijeka and in southern Croatia.', '(Polunin and Walters, 1985: 114-115).');
    '[Pinus pinea] forests of Mediterranean enclaves on the southern Black Sea coast of Anatolia in extreme eastern Paphlegonia and in western and eastern Lazistan, some, at least, apparently indigenous. In Lazistan, they occur, in particular, on hill slopes, from sea level to the top of the coastal range, on eruptive rocks, with a rich undergrowth including [Cistus creticus], [Pistacia palaestina], [Juniperus oxycedrus].', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 342, 344, 527-529, 632).');
    '[Pinus pinea] forests of the Aegean and east Mediterranean coasts of Anatolia and of their Mediterranean hinterland.', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 342, 344, 527-528, 632).');
    '[Pinus pinea] forests of the Aegean hinterland of Anatolia in Mysia, Lydia and Caria, in places extensive, probably indigenous and possibly climax, in particular on sandstones away from the immediate coastal vicinity.', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 342, 344; Noirfalise, 1987: unit M12).');
    '[Pinus pinea] formations of sandy soils of the east Mediterranean coast of southwestern Anatolia, in the Gulf of Antalya, probably indigenous.  ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 342, 344).');
    '[Pinus pinea] formations of the mesomediterranean hills of the periphery of the Cilician plain in southern central Anatolia.  ', '(Davis, 1965; Zohary, 1973: 342, 344).');
    '[Pinus pinea] forests of Lebanon, isolated at the southeastern limit of the range of the species. They may have formerly extended to the coastal plain of Philistaea.', '(Zohary, 1973: 342, 345, 528-529, 632).');
    NULL, NULL);
    'Forests of [Picea abies], [Picea obovata], or of [Picea spp.] and [Pinus sylvestris], accompanied by deciduous trees ([Quercus robur], [Quercus petraea], [Tilia cordata], [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus laevis], [Populus tremula]), of boreonemoral Fennoscandia, boreonemoral Russia west of the Ural piedmont, Belarus, the Baltic States, northeastern Poland, with an understorey dominated by [Vaccinium myrtillus]. [Picea abies] is the main tree dominant west of the Oka and Vetluga rivers, [Picea obovata] east of them.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 11a, 11b, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 13a, 13b, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 107; Sokolowski, 1980; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 384; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Korotkov y al., 1991: 286; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.1 [p.]; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Forests of [Picea abies] or [Picea obovata], or of [Picea spp.] with [Pinus sylvestris], of Fennoscandia, Russia west of the western Ural piedmont, Belarus, the Baltic States, with an understorey dominated by ferns accompanied by ericaceous shrubs or phanerogamic herbs, by mosses and lichens.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5-8, 11, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8-10, 13 [p.]; Walter, 1974: 55-63, 107; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.2, 2.1.3.4; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 370-371, 379-382, 383-387, 407-451; Korotkov y al., 1991: 285-286; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.1.2.2, 2.1.2.5; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Forests of [Picea abies] or, in the east, [Picea obovata], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris], of boreal Fennoscandia, boreal Russia west of the western Ural piedmont, extending into the boreonemoral region, in particular, in Fennoscandia, with an understorey dominated by [Gymnocarpium dryopteris], [Oxalis acetosella], ericaceous shrubs and mosses. They occupy stations with a richer nutrient supply and a higher humidity level than those of the bilberry forests of unit 42.C1, with a lower humidity level than the tall fern forests of unit 42.C22 and with a lower nutrient supply than the small herb forests of unit 42.C3.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5, 6, 7, 8, 11, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8, 9, 10, 13, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 67; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 407; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Korotkov y al., 1991: 285-286; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.2).');
    'Small fern spruce and spruce-pine forests of boreal Fennoscandia and Russia, east of the Scandinavian mountains and west of the Northern Dvina and Vetluga rivers, extending in the subboreal zone, particularly in Scandinavia, developed under subcontinental to near-continental climates, dominated by [Picea abies], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris], and with a species cortŠge devoid of oceanic elements. The dominant [Gymnocarpium dryopteris] and [Oxalis acetosella] are accompanied by, in particular, [Thelypteris phaegopteris], [Dryopteris expansa], [Anemone nemorosa] and by the mosses [Brachythecium reflexum], [Hylocomium umbratum].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5a, 6a, 7a, 8, 11a, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8a, 9a, 10a, 13a, [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 407; Korotkov y al., 1991: 285-286; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Small fern spruce forests of western Norway, with a species cortŠge enriched in oceanic or suboceanic elements, in particular, [Thelypteris limbosperma], [Blechnum spicant], [Cornus suecica], [Luzula sylvatica], [Plagiothecium undulatum], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Small fern spruce and spruce-pine forests of boreal Russia, east of the Northern Dvina and Vetluga rivers, and west of the Ural piedmont, extending in the subboreal zone, developed under continental climates, dominated by [Picea obovata], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris] or [Abies sibirica].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5b, 6b, 7b, 11b, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8b, 9b, 10b, 13b, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 67).');
    'Forests of [Picea abies] or, in the east, [Picea obovata], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris] and/or [Populus tremula], of southern boreal and boreonemoral regions of Fennoscandia, Russia west of the western Ural piedmont, Belarus, the Baltic States, with an understorey dominated by ferns, in particular, [Athyrium filix-femina], [Dryopteris carthusiana], [Dryopteris expansa], [Dryopteris dilatata], [Phegopteris connectilis], [Gymnocarpium dryopteris], [Matteuccia struthiopteris], often with two tiers, one of taller ferns, one of medium-sized ferns, with a greater presence of herbs than of [Vaccinium myrtillus] and much [Oxalis acetosella], developing on mesic to moist moraines (podsol-acid brown forest earth). Accompanying species include [Betula pubescens], [Maianthemum bifolium], [Trientalis europaea], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Rubus saxatilis], [Stellaria nemorum], [Viola epipsila], [Paris quadrifolia], [Luzula pilosa], [Melica nutans], [Milium effusum], [Deschampsia flexuosa] [Equisetum sylvaticum], and mosses. They occupy stations with a richer nutrient supply than those of the bilberry forests of unit 42.C1 and of the small fern forests of unit 42.C21, with a lower nutrient supply than the small herb forests of unit 42.C3 and the tall herb forests of unit 42.C4, and with a higher humidity level than all except the latter. In the boreo-nemoral zone, deciduous trees, in particular, [Tilia cordata], [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus laevis], may form a second tree layer.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 6, 7, 11, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 9, 10, 13, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 63, 107; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.2, 2.1.3.4; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 382-384; Korotkov y al., 1991: 285-286; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.5; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Tall, closed [Alnus glutinosa] woods of Britain developed on relatively dry, generally alluvial, eutrophic soils, in particular, on old river terraces, with [Sambucus nigra], [Salix cinerea], [Crataegus monogyna], [Prunus spinosa], [Urtica dioica], [Poa trivialis], [Dryopteris dilatata], [Galium aparine], [Rubus fruticosus] [s.l.]', '(McVean, 1964a: 160-162; Simms, 1971; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W6d).');
    'Woods of coastal southern Norway dominated by [Alnus glutinosa] and [Alnus incana], accompanied by [Ulmus glabra] and [Fraxinus excelsior], with an herb-rich undergrowth dominated by [Melica nutans], [Poa nemoralis], [Ranunculus ficaria].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.7).');
    'Dry [Alnus incana] or [Alnus glutinosa] woods of nemoral Central Europe, in particular, great horsetail dry alder woods of Poland, dense alder stands of steep valley slopes of Great Poland, dominated by [Alnus incana] alone or by [Alnus glutinosa] and [Alnus incana] together, with a rich undergrowth composed predominantely of ruderal and riparian species; characteristic or abundant species include [Equisetum telmateia], [Lamium maculatum], [Myosotis sparsiflora], [Corylus avellana], [Chaerophyllum temulentum], [Urtica dioica], [Cardamine amara], [Veronica hederifolia].', '(Ferchmin, 1980; Dyduch Falniowska, 1992).');
    'Dry alder woods of the nemoral and boreonemoral regions of Lithuania, Russia, Belarus and Ukraine, in particular, nettle grey alder woods, tall herb-rich dry [Alnus incana] forests on comparatively fertile acid brown forest soils, recorded from the northern part of the Valday Upland and Lithuania, with [Urtica dioica], [Anthriscus sylvestris], [Mnium cuspidatum].', '(Korotkov y al., 1991: 297).');
    '[Alnus incana] woods of the subalpine level of the western Rhodopes, substitution facies of [Picea abies] forests, usually developed in wetter stations than those occupied by [Betula pendula] or [Populus tremula]. ', '(Bondev, 1991: unit 24). ');
    'Nonriparian, nonmarshy formations of the boreal zone of the Palaearctic region dominated by [Alnus glutinosa] or [Alnus incana].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Nonriparian, nonmarshy formations of the boreal zone of the Palaearctic region dominated by [Alnus glutinosa]. They are related to the shore woods of unit 44.24 and have a similar composition. ', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.3.2 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.4.2 [p.]; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Nonriparian, nonmarshy formations of the boreal zone of the Palaearctic region dominated by [Alnus incana], appearing, in particular, as first recolonisation stage on rich damp soils of central and northern Fennoscandia. They are related to the shore woods of unit 44.23 and have a similar composition.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.3.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.4.1 [p.]; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Woods of the western Palaearctic region dominated by [Populus tremula]. ', '(Zohary, 1973; Braun-Blanquet, 1975a; Ehrenreich y al., 1982; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Noirfalise, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Ferioli, 1989; Bondev, 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991; Jahn, 1991; Röhrig, 1991h; Rodwell, 1991a; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Woods of [Populus tremula] and [Corylus avellana], accompanied by a xerophile flora, of dry inner valleys of the Alps.', '(Braun-Blanquet, 1975a; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Noirfalise, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Ferioli, 1989).');
    'Pioneer and subclimax [Populus tremula] formations of plains and hills of nemoral Europe, in particular the North Sea-Baltic plain and lower Hercynian slopes, within the range of Atlantic and sub-Atlantic acidophilous oak woods, and of the adjacent large alluvial systems, such as that of the Po.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.7 [p]; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Noirfalise, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Ferioli, 1989; Korotkov y al., 1991: 295; Jahn, 1991; Röhrig, 1991h; Rodwell, 1991a: 115, 174; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.8 [p])');
    '[Populus tremula] formations of the montane level of nemoral and Mediterranean mountains of Europe, occurring, in particular, within the beech belt of high southern mountains. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 518; Noirfalise, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Bondev, 1991: units 22, 42).');
    '[Populus tremula] formations occurring within the sub- or supra-Mediterranean environment of the mixed deciduous broad-leaved forests of, in particular, the [Quercion frainetto]. ', '(Noirfalise, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Ferioli, 1989; Bondev, 1991; Jahn, 1991; Röhrig, 1991h).');
    '[Populus tremula] stands of the taiga zone and of the transition zone between taiga and nemoral woods of Fennoscandia and the northern Sarmatic region. ', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.4.7 [p]; Jahn, 1991: 454; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.1.8 [p]; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    '[Populus tremula]-dominated forests of the southwestern spurs of the Ural Mountains, part of the easternmost extension of the oak-lime nemoral forests.', '(Jahn, 1991: 454). ');
    'Hygrophile [Larix decidua]-[Pinus cembra] forests of stations with prolonged snow cover on lime-poor or lime-rich oligotrophic substrates, usually dominated by [Pinus cembra]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 26)');
    'Forests of stabilized block screes, dominated by [Larix decidua] or [Larix decidua] and [Pinus cembra], often with [Betula spp.] and [Pinus mugo]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 26)');
    'Forests of the edge of peatbogs, generally with [Pinus cembra] and no [Larix decidua], accompanied by [Pinus mugo], [Eriophorum spp.] and [Andromeda polifolia]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 26-27)');
    'Subalpine and montane [Larix decidua], [Larix decidua]-[Picea abies], [Pinus cembra] or [Larix decidua]-[Pinus cembra] forests of the eastern and central Alps, mostly of the outer ranges, on calcareous substrates, with a usually species-rich undergrowth including [Erica herbacea], [Polygala chamaebuxus], [Rhododendron hirsutum] or [Pinus mugo].', '(Mayer, 1974; Ozenda, 1985; Ellenberg, 1988; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 271-274).');
    'Forests of [Larix decidua] and [Pinus cembra] of the intermediate Alps and the northeastern outer Alps, developed in particular on hard limestone plateaux. ', '(Mayer, 1974; Ozenda, 1985; Ellenberg, 1988; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 271-272).');
    'Forests of limestone plateaux with [Pinus cembra] and [Larix decidua]. ', NULL);
    'Forests of [Pinus cembra] and [Larix decidua] with an undergrowth of [Pinus mugo] and [Rhododendron hirsutum]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 28)');
    'Forests of [Pinus cembra] and [Larix decidua] with an undergrowth of [Alnus viridis], tall herbs and [Rhododendron hirsutum]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 28)');
    'Subalpine and montane [Larix decidua]-[Pinus cembra] forests of the eastern and central Alps, mostly of the outer ranges, on calcareous substrates, with a  species-rich undergrowth formed by ericoid shrubs, with [Rhododendron hirsutum] usually dominant, accompanied by [Rhododendron ferrugineum], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Erica herbacea]; [Alnus viridis] and [Pinus mugo] are usually present but not dominant.', '(Mayer, 1974: 27-28).');
    'Forests of limestone plateaux with [Pinus cembra] and no or little [Larix decidua]. ', NULL);
    'Calcicolous [Larix decidua] or [Larix decidua]-[Picea abies] forests, mostly of the outer Alps, in which [Pinus cembra] is rare or absent. ', '(Mayer, 1974; Ozenda, 1985; Ellenberg, 1988; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 272-274; Seliskar, 1998: 8).');
    '[Larix decidua] forests of limestone plateaux, with [Rhododendron hirsutum] dominating the ground layer. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 28-29)');
    'Calcicolous forests of ubacs, often with very tall, vigorous trees and a rich grassy undergrowth in which, together with [Luzula sylvatica] and [Luzula luzulina], [Calamagrostis villosa], [Sesleria albicans], [Festuca rubra], [Carex ferruginea] or [Carex firma] can all locally dominate; acidophilous species, including [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Vaccinium myrtillus] and [Lycopodium annotinum], are confined to the foot of the larches. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 29-30)');
    '[Larix decidua] forest developed on shady limestone screes. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 29)');
    '[Larix decidua] and [Larix decidua]-[Picea abies] forests, usually of steep slopes in the montane and locally subalpine levels of the northern and southern eastern outer Alps, with [Erica herbacea], [Buphthalmum salicifolium], [Polygala chamaebuxus]. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 30)');
    'Subalpine [Larix decidua], [Larix decidua]-[Pinus cembra], [Larix decidua]-mountain pine, [Pinus cembra] and [Pinus cembra]-mountain pine forests of the western, and mostly southwestern Alps, in regions where [Pinus uncinata] usually associates with [Larix decidua] and/or [Pinus cembra].  Characteristically xeric, open formations, they are best characterized by their understorey.', '(Ozenda, 1985; Salomez, 1990). ');
    'Forests of the western inner and intermediate Alps dominated by [Larix decidua] or by mixed [Larix decidua] and [Pinus uncinata], with an occasional admixture of [Pinus cembra] or other conifers. ', '(Ozenda, 1985; Salomez, 1990). ');
    '[Larix decidua] and [Larix decidua]-[Pinus uncinata] forests with a heath understorey formed by [Rhododendron ferrugineum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Vaccinium uliginosum]. ', NULL);
    '[Larix decidua] and [Larix decidua]-[Pinus uncinata] forests with a grass-rich understorey. ', NULL);
    'forests [Larix decidua] and [Larix decidua]-[Pinus uncinata] forests with a tall-herb understorey. ', NULL);
    'Rare forests of the western Alps, dominated by [Pinus cembra] or mixed [Pinus cembra] and [Pinus uncinata]. ', '(Richard and Pautou, 1982; Ozenda, 1985; ApŠge, 1985; Gensac, 1987; Maurin y al., 1989; Salomez, 1990).');
    'Woods of [Pinus halepensis], a frequent colonist of thermo- and calcicolous meso-mediterranean scrubs. The distinction between spontaneous forests and long-established formations of artificial origin is often difficult. The latter are thus included here, while recent, obviously artificial groves are not.', '(Rechinger, 1943, 1951; Loisel, 1971; Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Lavagne and Moutte, 1977; Sfikas, 1978; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Pignatti, 1982; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Ciaran and Blanco, 1984; Fenaroli, 1984; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Tassi, 1985; Dupias, 1985; Gamisans, 1985; Pratesi and Tassi, 1986; Herranz Sanz and Gomez Campo, 1986; Kassioumis, 1988; Ferioli, 1989; Bournérias y al., 1990; Bournérias y al., 1991; Bournérias y al., 1992).');
    '[Pinus halepensis] forests of Spain, considered native for at least two-thirds of their considerable expanse; they are mostly restricted to eastern regions on the Mediterranean slope of the Catalonian mountains, the Maestrazgo, the pre-Baetic ranges of the upper Guadalquivir basin, the southern Andalusian mountains; they penetrate farther inland in the Ebro basin and around the headwaters of the Tagus and Guadalquivir systems. They appear to extend north along the coast of the French Golfe du Lion to the region of Agde.', '(Walter, 1973: 393-398; Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Ciaran and Blanco, 1984; Dupias, 1985; Herranz Sanz and Gomez Campo, 1986; Bournérias y al., 1992: 99-219).');
