    'Forests of [Picea abies] or, in the east, [Picea obovata], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris] and/or [Populus tremula], of southern boreal and boreonemoral regions of Fennoscandia, Russia west of the western Ural piedmont, Belarus, the Baltic States, extending locally in the middle and northern boreal zones, with an understorey dominated by  dwarf-shrubs and a low-growing herb layer, characteristic of calcareous substrates and warm stations, developed on acid brown forest soils with mull, or on weakly podsolized soils, with a preference for lowlying areas with fine sediments and a good water supply, sometimes with a tendency to waterlogging. They occupy stations with a richer nutrient supply than those of the bilberry forests of unit 42.C1 and of the fern forests of unit 42.C2, and with a lower humidity level than the fern forests and the tall herb forests of unit 42.C4. Accompanying tree and shrub species include a predominance of [Sorbus aucuparia], [Vaccinium myrtillus], with [Alnus spp.], [Betula spp.], [Juniperus communis], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], a field layer dominated by [Oxalis acetosella], [Melampyrum sylvaticum], [Maianthemum bifolium], [Trientalis europaea], [Gymnocarpium dryopteris], [Thelypteris phegopteris] accompanied by [Linnaea borealis], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Melampyrum pratense], [Solidago virgaurea], [Rubus saxatilis], [Viola riviniana], [Hieracium sylvatica] grp., [Pyrola spp.], [Paris quadrifolia], [Melica nutans], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Luzula pilosa], [Lycopodium annotinum], [Equisetum sylvaticum], and mosses. In the boreonemoral zone, deciduous trees, in particular, [Quercus robur], [Tilia cordata], [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus laevis], may form a second tree layer.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 6, 7, 8, 11, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 9, 10, 13, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 62-63, 107; Sokolowski, 1980; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 102-103, 210-212; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.3, 2.1.3.5; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 379-387, 407-451; Priednieks y al., 1989: 63-65; Korotkov y al., 1991: 286-287; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.4; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 58; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Small herb spruce and spruce-pine forests of southern boreal and boreonemoral  Fennoscandia and Eastern Europe, east of the Scandinavian mountains and west of the Northern Dvina and Vetluga rivers, extending locally in the middle and northern boreal zones, particularly in calcareous regions, developed under subcontinental to near-continental climates, dominated by [Picea abies], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris], with a species cortŠge devoid of oceanic elements.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 6a, 7a, 8, 11a, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 9a, 10a, 13a, [p.]; Walter, 1974: 62-63; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.3 [p.], 2.1.3.5 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 379-384, 407-451; Korotkov y al., 1991: 286-287; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.4 [p.]; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 58; Müller, 1998: Annex 1).');
    'Small herb spruce forests of western Norway, with a species cortŠge enriched in oceanic or suboceanic elements.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.2.3 [p.], 2.1.3.5 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.4 [p.]).');
    'Small herb spruce and spruce-pine forests of boreal Russia, east of the Northern Dvina and Vetluga rivers, and west of the Ural piedmont, extending in the subboreal zone, developed under continental climates, dominated by [Picea obovata], sometimes accompanied by [Pinus sylvestris] or [Abies sibirica].', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 6b, 7b, 11b, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 9b, 10b, 13b, [p.]; Korotkov y al., 1991: 286-287).');
    'Forests of [Picea abies], accompanied, in a second tree layer by deciduous trees, in particular, [Quercus robur], [Tilia cordata], [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus laevis], sometimes with [Pinus sylvestris] and/or [Populus tremula] in the canopy, with a low understorey dominated by  dwarf-shrubs and low-growing herbs, of which many are of nemoral affinities, often with a well-developed taller shrub layer that may include much [Sorbus aucuparia], characteristic of boreonemoral regions of Russia west of the western Ural piedmont, Belarus, the Baltic States and northeastern Poland.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: unit 11 [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 13 [p.]; Walter, 1974: 107; Sokolowski, 1980; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 102-103, 210-212; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 384-387, 407-451; Priednieks y al., 1989: 63-65; Korotkov y al., 1991: 286-287; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Forests of [Picea abies] or, in the east, [Picea obovata], of boreal and boreonemoral regions of Fennoscandia, Russia west of the western Ural piedmont, Belarus, the Baltic States, with a species-rich understorey dominated by tall herbs and ferns and with a significant component of deciduous trees, including [Betula pubescens], [Alnus incana], [Sorbus aucuparia]; the species cortŠge includes an abundance of [Oxalis acetosella] and [Sambucus nigra], [Actaea spicata], [Campanula latifolia], [Mercurialis perennis], [Aconitum septentrionale] ([Aconitum lycoctonum]), [Cicerbita alpina], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Angelica sylvestris], [Crepis paludosa], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Geum rivale], [Viola epipsila], [Melica nutans], [Milium effusum], [Paris quadrifolia], [Rubus idaeus], [Rubus saxatilis], [Trientalis europaea], [Trollius europaeus], [Equisetum pratense], [Equisetum sylvaticum], [Dryopteris expansa], [Athyrium filix-femina], [Matteuccia struthiopteris]. Tall-herb spruce forests occupy low-lying areas, slopes and ravines with fine sediment and good water supply, on calcareous brown forest soils. Their stations have a richer nutrient supply and a higher humidity level than those of the bilberry forests of unit 42.C1, of the fern forests of unit 42.C2 or of the small herb forests of unit 42.C3. In the boreonemoral zone, deciduous trees, in particular, [Tilia cordata], [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus laevis], may form a second tree layer.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 5-8, 11, [p.]; Saphronova, 1964c: units 8-10, 13 [p.]; Walter, 1974: 58, 63, 67-70, 107; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.2.4; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 370-374, 381-382, 383-387, 407-451; Korotkov y al., 1991: 287; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.2.6; Lundmark, 1996: 50-55; Kempe and von Segebaden, 1996: 58; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Open, often parklike, woods of [Populus tremula] and [Betula pendula] (listed under unit 41.B9 when dominated by the latter) of the transition zone between steppe and taiga of Siberia, east of the range of the nemoral deciduous forests of the Sarmatic region. The shrub layer includes [Lonicera altaica], [Lonicera tatarica], [Thelycrania alba] ([Cornus alba]), [Ribes nigrum], [Ribes rubrum], [Spiraea hypericifolia], [Cotoneaster multiflorus]; the meadow-like herb layer is formed by [Agrostis alba], [Calamagrostis arundinacea], [Poa pratensis], [Bromus inermis], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Astragalus danicus], [Campanula bononiensis].', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 45; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 195; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    '[Populus tremula] stands, sometimes vast, of the southern slopes of inner Pontic ranges. ', '(Zohary, 1973: 377; Noirfalise, 1987: unit Q6 [p.]; Röhrig, 1991h: 536).');
    '[Populus davidiana]-[Betula platyphylla] woods of the 2500-3000 metre spruce-pine zone of the Nanshan range of eastern central Asia and of the larch, larch-pine and larch-pine-spruce zones of the Ta-hsing-an Ling range of northeastern China.', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 36; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 318).');
    'Woods of the western Palaearctic region dominated by [Sorbus aucuparia], characteristic in particular of the Scottish Highlands. ', '(McVean, 1964a: 161; Noirfalise, 1987; Rodwell, 1991a: 198, 253, 265, 279). ');
    'Forests and woods dominated by [Ulmus spp.] or [Acer spp.] of dry, sometimes humid but nonriparian, stable soils of the nemoral western Palaearctic region. Ravine forests, on screes or colluvions, dominated by these species are listed in unit 41.3, riverine forests in unit 44.', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a; Bondev, 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Wirth, 1993; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    '[Ulmus minor] ([Ulmus carpinifolia], [Ulmus campestris]) or [Ulmus procera] woods of base- and nutrient-rich, often ruderal, terrain, dispersed along the western seaboard of Western Europe and in warm, dry, subcontinental areas of Central Europe, usually rich in species of southern affinities. 
', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 267-268; Bournérias, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1985; Rodwell, 1991a; Bondev, 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 97-98; Wirth, 1993: 69-70; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994).');
    'Nitrophile [Ulmus minor] or [Ulmus procera] woods of the western seaboard of the European continent, from northern France to Poland, distributed, in particular, in the Paris Basin, in the maritime dunes of the Netherlands and Belgium, on the dikes of the Dutch fluviatile district and on the cretaceous low Meuse hills, sporadically also in suburban forests, parks and green spaces throughout its range.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 153; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 267-268; Bournérias, 1984: 368-370; Noirfalise y al., 1985: units Ru, Rud; Julve, 1993: 118-119; Duvigneaud y al., 1996).');
    '[Ulmus minor] woods of the coasts of Normandy, Brittany and Vend¿e. ', '(Géhu and Géhu-Franck, 1985).');
    'Woods of the British Isles, mostly of the [Fraxinus]-[Acer]-[Mercurialis] type, invaded and dominated by suckering elms of the [Ulmus minor] group ([Ulmus carpinifolia], [Ulmus procera]); postcultural small-leaved elm groves are included.', '(Rodwell, 1991a: unit W8 [p.]). ');
    '[Ulmus minor] woods of dry, warm stations in regions of subcontinental climate of Central Europe, mostly secundary colonists of agricultural land on loess, marls, degraded chernozems or alluvial terrain, distributed in particular in southern German dry enclaves, in peri-Pannonic areas and in Bulgaria. ', '(Bondev, 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 97-98; Wirth, 1993: 69-70; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994). ');
    'Nonriparian, nonravine [Ulmus glabra] or [Ulmus laevis]-dominated formations of northern and central Europe.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.3; Oberdorfer, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.3; Opermanis y al., 1997: 56; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Forests and woods dominated by [Acer spp.] of dry, sometimes humid but nonriparian, stable soils of the nemoral western Palaearctic region, in particular, maple-dominated, pioneer, young and perturbed stands of the Atlantic and sub-Atlantic varied oak-hornbeam and ash forests of units 41.2 and 41.3.', '(Tanghe and Duvigneaud, 1978; Gallez-Richel, 1990: 78-79, 90, 99, 116).');
    '[Tilia spp.]-dominated forests and woods of dry, sometimes humid but nonriparian, stable soils of the nemoral and boreal zones of western and central Eurasia. Ravine forests, on screes or colluvions, dominated by these species are listed in unit 41.3, riverine forests in unit 44.', '(Tolmachev, 1980; Ehrenreich y al., 1982; Nordiska Ministerradet, 1984; Walter and Breckle,1986; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a; Jahn,1991; Korotkov y al., 1991; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Rare [Tilia]-dominated stands of nemoral western and central Europe, within the range of [Fagus sylvatica], often [Tilia]-dominated facies of lime-rich oak-hornbeam forests. They are distributed, in particular, in the Bohemian basin, in southern Scandinavia and in the British Isles.    ', '(Moravec y al., 1982: 148-152, unit 6 [p.]; Nordiska Ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.5 [p.]; Ellenberg, 1988: 145-146; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: units W8 [p.], W10 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.5 [p.]; Neuh¿uslova, 1998: 100, 101-102, 285, unit 12 [p.]).');
    'Silicicolous [Pinus cembra] forests of ubacs and mesic stations in the inner and intermediate western Alps (Belledonne, Chamrousse; Brian¿onnais). ', NULL);
    '[Pinus cembra] forests of adrets of the western inner Alps, in which [Pinus cembra] may be accompanied by [Pinus uncinata] and [Pinus sylvestris] over a heath of [Juniperus nana] and [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi]. ', NULL);
    'Limestone and gypsum [Pinus cembra] forests, developed on raw humus accumulated over calcic or hyper calcic substrates, with an exceptional juxtaposition of acidophilous and basiphilous companion species, occasional in the inner and intermediate Alps (Maurienne; Tarentaise, La Plagne, mont Charvet; Flaine) and very locally the outer Alps (Haut Giffre, Les Bornes) of France. ', NULL);
    'Formations of [Larix decidua] colonizing abandoned fields and pastures in lower levels of the Alps. Alpine [Larix decidua] plantations; plantations of [Larix decidua] out of range and of other [Larix spp.] or hybrids should be listed under unit 83. ', '(Mayer, 1974: 31-32; Ozenda, 1983, 1985; Seliskar, 1998: 8). ');
    'Uncommon [Larix decidua] or [Pinus cembra] formations of the Carpathians, each occurring as a single dominant, together as codominants, or mixed with spruce ([Picea abies]).', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Ozenda, 1985; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Timberline silicicolous [Larix decidua] and [Pinus cembra] formations of the Tatras.
', NULL);
    '[Larix decidua] and [Pinus cembra] formations of the dry, inner Carpathian Proprad basin.', NULL);
    'Local mixed forests of [Pinus cembra], [Picea abies] and [Pinus mugo], of the lower subalpine level (1650-1500 m), with regional species [Rhododendron myrtifolium], [Bruckenthalia spiculifolia], [Melampyrum saxosum], [Soldanella hungarica] ssp. [major], [Campanula abietina].', '(Chifu y al., 1984; Sanda y al., 1988: 474; Coldea, 1991: 514).');
    '[Larix decidua] woods on rocky calcareous substrates at the upper limit of the forest zone (1600-1750 metres) of the Southwestern Carpathians, sometimes with [Pinus cembra] and [Picea abies], and with an herb layer formed by [Saxifraga cuneifolia], [Soldanella hungarica] ssp. [major], [Campanula abietina], [Moneses uniflora], [Ranunculus carpaticus], [Aquilegia transsilvanica], [Hieracium rotundatum], [Tricetum fuscum].', '(Beldie, 1967; Coldea, 1991: 514-519).
');
    '[Pinus cembra] and [Picea abies]-dominated formations of the subalpine level of the Eastern and Southern Carpathians, formed at the upper forest limit, with a herb layer dominated by spruce forest species and a shrub layer with [Pinus mugo] and [Juniperus nana]. ', '(Borza, 1934; Coldea, 1991: 519-592).');
    '[Larix decidua] ssp. [polonica]-dominated facies of the white cinquefoil oak woods (units 41.7A11, 41.7A14) of Poland and the western Ukraine. ', '(Ozenda, 1985; Rushforth, 1987). ');
    'Mostly subalpine forests of the Alps, the Jura, the Pyrenees and the Iberian Range, dominated by [Pinus uncinata], usually open and with a very developed shrubby understory. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Gruber, 1978; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Dupias, 1985; Fernandez Gonzalez, 1986; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Ferioli, 1989; Maurin y al., 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990).');
    '[Pinus uncinata] forests of the western outer Alps, the Jura and Pyrenean ubacs, developed on siliceous or decalcified soils of the subalpine level with a predominately ericaceous undergrowh comprising [Rhododendron ferrugineum] (dominant), [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Calluna vulgaris], [Homogyne alpina], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Lycopodium annotinum].', '(Gruber, 1978; Ozenda, 1981, 1985; Richard and Pautou, 1982; Dupias, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Vigo and Ninot, 1987; Bolos y Capdevilla, 1987). ');
    '[Pinus uncinata] forests occupying hard limestone plateaux of the outer Alps, in the Chablais, the Aravis, the Bauges, the Chartreuse, the Vercors, the D¿voluy in which the almost pure calcareous bedrock is covered by a thick layer of raw humus supporting an acidophilous undergrowth dominated by [Rhododendron ferrugineum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Vaccinium uliginosum] accompanied by [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Lycopodium selago], [Selaginella spinosa], [Cladonia rangiferina], [Homogyne alpina], [Bartsia alpina], [Astrantia minor]. ', NULL);
    'Subalpine [Pinus uncinata] forests of the western Jura, similar to the Alpine formations of unit 42.411. ', NULL);
    '[Pinus uncinata] forests of ubacs of the Pyrenees developed on siliceous soils, or on decalcified soils in the calcareous ranges, in the more humid and snowy parts of the subalpine level, with a ground layer dominated by [Rhododendron ferrugineum] accompanied by [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Homogyne alpina], [Rosa alpina], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Oxalis acetosella], [Juniperus nana], [Calluna vulgaris], [Dryopteris linneana], [Polystichum spinulosum], [Solidago virgaurea]. ', NULL);
    'Sphagnum-rich [Betula pubescens] or [Betula carpatica] woods of the boreal and nemoral western Palaearctic in which [Molinia caerulea] is accompanied by a cortŠge of acid fen species, in particular, [Carex rostrata], [Carex nigra], [Carex echinata], [Juncus acutiflorus], [Agrostis canina], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Calamagrostis canescens] and by ericoid shrubs, in particular [Vaccinium uliginosum]. Depending on water level, regime of inundation, history of ligneous colonization and nature of the initial stage, the undergrowth may be dominated by [Molinia caerulea], by sedges [Carex spp.], by rushes [Juncus spp.], by [Scirpus cespitosus] or by ericoid shrubs, resulting in a number of rather distinctive habitats. Conifers, mostly [Picea abies], may participate in the canopy of boreal, northeastern nemoral, Hercynian subboreal and pre-Alpine communities; [Pinus sylvestris] has its westernmost relict stations in northwestern stands. Fennoscandian formations have a number of northern species, in particular [Calamagrostis purpurea], [Cornus suecica], [Empetrum spp.], [Rubus chamaemorus].', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 255-256; Mériaux y al., 1978; Noirfalise, 1984:  unit X.1.3.1; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.4.2.1 [p.], 3.4.2.2 [p.], 2.2.4.5b, 3.3.1.1; Rodwell, 1991a: units W4b, W4c; Pott, 1992: 359-362; Wallnöfer, 1993b: 306-307; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.2.1.3 [p.], 3.3.1.2 [p.], 2.2.1.64; Schubert y al., 1995: 102-103; Ilijanic, 1996: 108; Frankard y al., 1998: 29).');
    'Sphagnum-rich [Betula pubescens] or [Betula carpatica] woods of the boreal and nemoral western Palaearctic in which the presence of species characteristic of subhumid mineral soils indicate a transition towards acidophilous birch and oak woods; [Salix cinerea], [Alnus glutinosa], [Lysimachia vulgaris], [Luzula sylvatica], [Oxalis acetosella], [Deschampsia flexuosa] may be prominent, next to [Molinia caerulea]. Conifers, mostly [Picea abies], may participate in the canopy of boreal and subboreal communities.', '(De Zuttere, 1975: 11-12; Mériaux y al., 1978; Sokolowski, 1980; Noirfalise, 1984: unit X.1.3.2; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.4.3.1 [p.], 3.5.2.1 [p.], 2.2.4.6a, 3.3.3.2; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W4a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.1.3 [p.], 2.2.1.7a).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris]-dominated woods of bogs, fens and swamps of western Eurasia, mostly characteristic of the boreal and subboreal zones, with very localized outposts in nemoral mountains and in the steppe zone.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Muller, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Pott, 1992: 360-361; Påhlsson, 1994; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] formations of bogs and transition mires of the plains of subboreal and northern nemoral central and eastern Europe, with isolated stations in the Hercynian system.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Muller, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 283; Steiner, 1992).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] formations of bogs and transition mires of the plains of northern Germany, northern Poland and the northern nemoral Sarmatic region, with [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Calluna vulgaris], [Andromeda polifolia], [Myrica gale].', '(Valk, 1974: 156-158; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Valk, 1974; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 283).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] formations of bogs and transition mires of nemoral and boreonemoral eastern Europe and of inland sites in the Baltic lowlands of northern central Europe.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 105). ');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] formations of dunal depressions of the southern and southeastern Baltic coasts, with [Empetrum nigrum], [Erica tetralix], [Deschampsia flexuosa].', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 105). ');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] formations of bogs and transition mires of the Hercynian system, best represented in the Bohemian Quadrangle, with rare outposts farther west to the Vosges, with [Betula pubescens], [Betula carpatica], [Frangula alnus], [Sorbus aucuparia], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Andromeda polifolia].
', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Moravec y al., 1983;  Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Muller, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Steiner, 1992).');
    'Peri-Hercynian [Pinus sylvestris] formations of mires with species-poor undergrowth, comprising [Vaccinium myrtillus], usually dominant, [Calamagrostis villosa], [Sphagnum girgensohnii].
', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 101). ');
    'Isolated relict Scots pine mire woods of the Balkan peninsula, often with [Picea abies] and [Betula pubescens] and a sometimes species-rich cortŠge of fen, bog or transition mire species, including sphagna and cottonsedges.', '(Horvat y al., 1974).');
    'Scots pine mire wood of the Han-Kram range in southern Bosnia, in the Illyrian beech forest zone, with [Picea abies], [Betula pubescens] and [Salix pentandra], accompanied by [Frangula alnus], [Sorbus aucuparia], [Salix caprea], [Salix cinerea], [Sphagnum spp.], [Carex spp.], [Molinia caerulea], [Agrostis canina].   
', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 469-470).');
    '[Juniperus procera]-dominated formations of southwestern Arabia, northernmost outpost of a formation distributed from Arabia and the Red Sea hills of Sudan through the east African mountain archipelago south to the Nyika Plateau of Malawi. They are developed in the 1500 to 3000 metre level, and higher on Jebel Sabor, of the ranges that parallel the Red Sea coast in Yemen and near Taif. Accompanying the juniper are [Euryops arabica], [Dodonaea viscosa], [Themeda triandra].', '(Zohary, 1973: 246, 351, 352, 600; White, 1983; Donald and Theron, 1983; Walter and Breckle, 1991b: 386, 388).');
    'Broadleaved evergreen, sclerophyllous tropical montane forests and thickets  of southwestern Arabian mountains, with an outpost in the Gebel Elba of the Red Sea coastal mountains of Egypt. [Olea chrysophylla], [Tarchonanthus camphoratus], [Myrsine africana], [Buddleja polystachya], [Barbeya oleoides], [Maesa lanceolata], [Nuxia dentata], [Rhus abyssinica], [Rhus retinorrhoea], [Euclea kellau], [Teclea nobilis], [Celtis spp.], [Ficus spp.], [Dracaena ombet] participate in the composition of various communities.', '(Zohary, 1973: 246, 599, 600; Walter and Breckle, 1991b: 388; Zahran and Willis, 1992: 185, 186).');
    'Forests of the slopes of tropical mountains of the Far East, including lower montane rain forests, upper montane rain forests, tropical coniferous woodland, montane bamboo woodland, elfin forest, tropical krummholz formations, occurring in particular in Hainan and southern Yunnan.', '(Schnell, 1971a; Letouzey, 1978; Whitmore, 1978, 1989, 1992; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 174; Mei''e y al., 1985: 306, 307, 338 [i.a.]; Rieley and Page, 1990; Su, 1995: 198; Doumenge y al., 1995: 28; Hamilton y al., 1995: 9, 22; Long, 1995: 87-88; Ohsawa, 1995: 256).');
    'Edaphically determined forests of the evergreen and deciduous tropical forest zones, developed on hydromorphic, nonsaline soils and often characterized by a strong tendancy to monophytism. They include peat swamp tropical forests, fresh water swamp tropical forests, fresh water periodic swamp forests, tropical riverine forests. They are limited within the Palaearctic, as here defined, to the tropical Far East, where they have, however, been almost entirely cleared for cultivation.', '(Schnell, 1971a; Letouzey, 1978; Whitmore, 1978, 1989, 1992; Mei''e y al., 1985; Rieley and Page, 1990).');
    'Forests and woodlands of dry tropical regions, of simpler structure and considerably lower species richness than rain and monsoon forests, often characterized by a relatively low, open canopy. Included are varied formations known as closed dry forests, open dry forests, savanna woodland, wooded savanna, thorn forest, thorn woodland, tropical scrub, bushland. They are limited, within the Palaearctic, as here defined, to the Saharo-Mediterranean, Saharo-Sindian, Sahelian and Sino-Tropical zones.', '(Troupin, 1966; Huetz de Lemps, 1970; Schnell, 1971a, 1976; Zohary, 1973; Letouzey, 1978; White, 1983; Mei''e y al., 1985: 304, 306, 307, 338 ia; Rieley and Page, 1990; Su, 1995: 198).');
    '[Argania spinosa] thorn forests, thorn woodland, scrub forests and "bushlands" of the arid and semiarid levels of southwest Morocco, with [Acacia gummifera], [Ziziphus lotus], [Olea europaea], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Pistacia atlantica], and often abundant succulent [Euphorbia beaumierana] or [Euphorbia echinus].', '(Herbauts, 1973: 327-328; Knapp, 1973: 519-520; White, 1983: 150, 227; Foucault, 1993b: 269; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 86-88).');
    'Woods and stands, often riparian, formed by palm trees of the Mediterraneo-Saharan, Saharo-Sindian and Sahelian zones, including [Phoenix dactylifera], [Phoenix atlantica], [Nannorrhops ritchiana], [Hyphaene thebaica].', '(Zohary, 1973; Moore, 1980; White, 1983).');
    'Indigenous or spontaneous stands and long-established oasis plantations of [Phoenix dactylifera] of the Saharo-Sindian and Saharo-Mediterranean regions.', '(Herbauts, 1973: 326).');
    'Indigenous or spontaneous stands of [Phoenix dactylifera] installed on rocky slopes, in canyons, on coastal dunes and in saline or brackish wadis and flats, of the Saharo-Sindian and Saharo-Mediterranean regions. The area of indigenousness is unknown but has been suggested to be restricted to Arabia, or to encompass a much larger area, including, in particular, North Africa''s coastal dunes.', '(de Candolle, 1883; Zohary, 1973; Moore, 1980; Vanden Berghen, 1981; White, 1983). ');
    'Long-established plantations of [Phoenix dactylifera] of the Saharo-Sindian and Saharo-Mediterranean regions, entirely replacing the natural vegetation of desert and subdesert oases, and providing an important substitution habitat for animal communities.', '(Zohary, 1973; Moore, 1980; White, 1983: 218-219).');
    'Formations of the endemic [Phoenix atlantica] of the Cape Verde archipelago.', '(White, 1983: 251).');
    '[Hyphaene thebaica] woods and stands of wadis, mountain gorges, salt marshes, sand dunes and sometimes oases of the southern Sahara, the Sinai and the Arabian peninsula.', '(Zohary, 1973; White, 1983: 219; Orshan, 1986; Zahran and Willis, 1992).');
    '[Nannorrhops ritchiana] formations of southern Iran and eastern Afghanistan, characteristic of sheltered mountain valleys with a reasonably high water table.', '(Moore, 1980).');
