    'Diverse riparian forests of the middle courses of great rivers, inundated only by large floods. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Oberdorfer, 1990). ');
    'Fully developed, very tall, multi-layered, highly diverse riparian forests of oaks, ashes, elms, limes, maples, alders, poplars, cherries, apple, willows of the middle and lower courses of large medio-European river systems, in particular, the Rhine, the Danube, the Emst, the Elbe, the Saale, the Weser, the Oder, the Loire, the Rhone-Sa¿ne systems. Their highly complex structure is formed of eight strata to which participate up to 50 species of trees and shrubs. The upper arborescent stratum includes [Quercus robur], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Ulmus minor], [Ulmus laevis], [Ulmus glabra], [Populus alba], [Populus tremula], [Populus canescens], [Populus nigra], [Acer pseudoplatanus], [Acer platanoides], [Salix alba], [Alnus glutinosa], [Prunus avium], the lower arborescent stratum [Malus sylvestris], [Tilia cordata], the sub-arborescent shrub layer [Alnus incana], [Prunus padus] and [Crataegus monogyna]. There are very varied high and low shrub layers and numerous lianas, [Clematis vitalba], [Tamus communis], [Humulus lupulus], [Hedera helix] and [Vitis vinifera] ssp. [sylvestris]. Most diverse, structurally, floristically and faunistically, of all European ecosystems, and closest in that respect to tropical communities and to the warm temperate forests of the Pleistocene, the great fluvial forests of Europe are reduced to a few highly vulnerable examples, located mainly within the Rhine, Danube and Elbe systems.  ', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Medwecka-Kornas y al., 1966; Carbiener, 1970, 1983; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Matuszkiewicz, 1981b, 1984; Moravec y al., 1982; Korotkov y al., 1991: 297; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 102-103; Seliskar, 1998: 1).');
    'Fragments of oak-elm-ash forests of large medio-European river systems, very altered and with greatly reduced species richness. ', '(Yon and Tendron, 1981: 31, 32, 36, 42; Saintenoy-Simon and Duvigneaud, 1994).');
    'Mixed riverine forests of Ponto-Pannonic and sub-Mediterranean regions of southeastern Europe, usually dominated by [Quercus robur] and/or [Fraxinus angustifolia], with varying admixtures of [Ulmus minor], [Ulmus laevis], [Carpinus betulus], [Acer campestre], [Alnus glutinosa], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Salix alba], [Populus alba].', '(Simon, 1960; Karpati and Karpati, 1961, 1969; Emrovic y al., 1964; Glavac, 1969; Sanda, 1970; Horvat y al., 1974; Oprea, 1976; Soo, 1980; Pedrotti, 1980; Dierschke, 1980; Karpati, 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1982; Kassioumis, 1988; Bondev, 1991).');
    'Mixed hardwood riverine forests of the Sava and Drava basins and adjacent areas, within the [Carpinion betuli illyricum] region, dominated by [Quercus robur] or, with longer periods of inundation, [Fraxinus angustifolia] and [Alnus glutinosa].', '(Emrovic y al., 1964; Glavac, 1969; Horvat y al., 1974: 370-380; Pedrotti, 1980; Dierschke, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Prpic, 1996: 71; Seliskar, 1998: 1, 9).');
    'Riverine forests of the Illyrian region, in the Sava and Drava basins, with irradiations in the karst region of northeastern Italy and in the western Balkan peninsula, characteristic of areas with long inundation, dominated by [Fraxinus angustifolia], associated with [Alnus glutinosa] in high groundwater depressions away from the water course. [Quercus robur] and [Ulmus minor] participate in the major tree layer. The undergrowth is characterized by an abundance of [Leucojum aestivum], the presence of [Cardamine pratensis] ssp. [dentata], [Urtica radicans] and, in the alder-ash stands, [Frangula alnus], [Dryopteris carthusiana], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Valeriana dioica]. Particularly wet areas harbour [Hottonia palustris], [Hydrocharis morsus-ranae] and other standing water species.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 375-377; Pedrotti, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 48; Hoda y al., 1998: 16; Seliskar, 1998: 9).');
    'Riverine forests of the Sava and Drava basins characteristic of areas subjected to a shorter inundation period than those of occupied by the forests of unit 44.4311, dominated by [Quercus robur], with [Ulmus minor], [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Carpinus betulus], [Alnus glutinosa], [Genista tinctoria], [Leucojum aestivum], [Carex remota] and sometimes large expanses of [Carex brizoides] in pure colonies.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 377-379).');
    'Riverine forests of the Sava and Drava basins developed on the highest ground, dominated by [Quercus robur] and [Carpinus betulus], with [Ulmus minor], [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Alnus glutinosa], [Acer campestre], [Carex remota], [Carex strigosa], [Carex brizoides], often in large colonies that may dominate the herb layer.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 380).');
    'Scots pine mire woods of the western Rhodope of Bulgaria and of western and eastern Serbia, with occasional [Picea abies] and [Betula pubescens]; the accompanying cortŠge is related to that of acid fens and transition mires; [Eriophorum latifolium], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea] characterize constituting communities.   
', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 519).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris]-dominated woods of bogs of the boreal regions of western Eurasia.', '(Valk, 1974: 155-158; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.1.2.1, 3.1.2.2, 3.1.2.3; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 382; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.1.2, 3.1.1.3, 3.1.1.4).');
    'Scots pine bog woods of the western boreal region of the Palaearctic formed of 
[Pinus sylvestris] with a shrub layer dominated by [Ledum palustre], [Calluna vulgaris], [Chamaedaphne calyculata] in eastern Finland, or [Betula nana] in the north, with [Eriophorum vaginatum]; the mucinal layer is dominated by [Sphagnum angustifolium] with [Sphagunum fuscum], [Sphagnum magellanicum], [Sphagnum russowii], [Polytrichum strictum], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Aulaccomnium palustre], characteristic of dry mires with relatively low-lying ground-water surface.', '(Valk, 1974: 148; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.1.2.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.1.2).');
    'Scots pine bog woods of the western boreal region of the Palaearctic formed of 
[Pinus sylvestris] with a shrub layer dominated by the ericaceous shrubs [Calluna vulgaris], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae] and by [Betula nana], with [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Andromeda polifolia], [Empetrum nigrum], [Rubus chamaemorus], and a mucinal layer dominated by [Sphagnum fuscum] and [Pleurozium schreberi], accompanied by [Sphagnum magellanicum], [Cladonia rangiferina]. In Finland, this type of bog woods occupies entire mire areas. This type also occurs on hummocks in concentric raised bogs, on strings in the excentric bogs and aapa mires, and as marginal woodland around concentric raised bogs with treeless plateaux.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.1.2.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.1.3).');
    'Scots pine bog woods of the western boreal region of the Palaearctic formed of 
sparse, low growing [Pinus sylvestris] with a shrub layer dominated by [Calluna vulgaris].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.1.2.2 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Scots pine bog woods of the western boreal region of the Palaearctic formed of 
sparse, low growing [Pinus sylvestris] with a shrub layer dominated by [Empetrum nigrum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.1.2.2 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Scots pine bog woods of the western boreal region of the Palaearctic formed of 
sparse, low growing [Pinus sylvestris] with a shrub layer dominated by [Andromeda polifolia].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.1.2.2 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Scots pine bog woods of the western boreal region of the Palaearctic, with a 5-7 m high tree layer formed of [Pinus sylvestris], sometimes with an important admixture of birch, a field layer dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum], and a sphagnum carpet of, in particular, [Sphagnum angustifolium], [Sphagnum fuscum], of raised bogs and aapa mire fringes.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.1.2.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.1.4).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris]-dominated woods of fens of the boreal region of the western Palaearctic, with an understorey rich in or dominated by sedges, ericoid shrubs and acidophile or neutrocline sphagnum mosses.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.4.1.1, 2.1.1.5, 3.3.1.1, 3.3.1.1a, 3.4.1.3; Priednieks y al., 1989: 62-65; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.2.1.1, 2.1.1.3, 2.1.1.3a, 3.3.1.1).');
    'Scots pine fen woods of the western boreal region of the Palaearctic, with a tree layer of [Pinus sylvestris], field layer dominated by [Carex globularis], a dwarf-shrub layer sparser than in Scots pine fen woods of unit 44.A242, and a ground layer dominated by the acidophilous sphagna [Sphagnum angustifolium] or [Sphagnum fuscum]. The species cortŠge comprises [Betula nana], [Andromeda polifolia], [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum spp.], [Ledum palustre], [Myrica gale], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Carex pauciflora], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Polytrichum commune], [Sphagnum magellanicum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.4.1.1, 3.4.1.2 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.2.1.1).');
    'Oligotrophic, acidophile [Pinus sylvestris] woods of peat-forming fens, fen edges, bog edges, lake shores of the boreal region of the western Palaearctic with an understorey dominated by ericoid shrubs, in particular, [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Empetrum nigrum], [Ledum palustre], associated with [Betula nana], and accompanied by an abundance of [Eriophorum vaginatum], of acidophilous sphagnum mosses, in particular, [Sphagnum fuscum], [Sphagnum angustifolium], [Sphagnum nemoreum], [Sphagnum russowii], and of lichens of genus [Cladonia]. The species cortŠge habitually includes [Picea abies], [Betula pubescens], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Calluna vulgaris], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Molinia caerulea], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Polytrichum commune] and, regionally, [Chamaedaphnae calyculata], [Erica tetralix], [Myrica gale], [Carex globulosa].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.3.1.1, 2.1.1.5, 3.3.1.1a; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.1.1.3, 2.1.1.3a).');
    'Thorn forests, thorn woodlands and savanna woodlands of the Saharo-Sindian region, locally reaching the Mediterraneo-Saharan region, and of the Sahelian region of Mauritania, dominated by acacias ([Acacia], [Prosopis]), or species of genera [Ziziphus], [Balanites], [Maerua], [Maytenus], [Salvadora].', NULL);
    'Acacia-dominated formations of the northern confines of the Sahara, in the Saharo-Mediterranean transition zone.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Huetz de Lemps, 1970: 124; Herbauts, 1973: 325-326; Knapp, 1973: 521-522; Bousquet, 1992; Foucault, 1993b: 269; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 90-91).');
    '[Acacia raddiana]-dominated savanna woodland of the northern fringes of the Sahara, now limited to a very few relict formations in the Oued Dra basin of Morocco and adjacent Algerian regions and in the Djebel Bou-Hedma of central Tunisia, where it constitutes an essential potential habitat and restoration center for the endangered antelope [Oryx dammah], with [Ziziphus lotus], [Retama retam], [Periploca laevigata], [Aristida plumosa], [Aristida obtusa], [Digitaria nodosa], [Cenchrus ciliaris].', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Huetz de Lemps, 1970: 124; Herbauts, 1973: 325-326; Knapp, 1973: 521-522; Bousquet, 1992; Foucault, 1993b: 269; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 90-91).');
    'Endemic [Acacia gummifera] woodland and scrub land of the plateaux of western Morocco, now reduced to remnant stands, in particular, at Haouz-Tadla. The acacias are accompanied by [Ephedra altissima], [Asparagus stipularis], [Lavandula multiflora], [Ballota hispanica], [Bryonia dioica], [Peganum harmala] and many therophytes.', '(Herbauts, 1973: 328; Knapp, 1973: 520; White, 1983: 227-228; Foucault, 1993b: 269; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 90-91).');
    'Open woodland or savanna woodland, steppe woodland or desert woodland of the  Sahara, dominated by [Acacia raddiana], [Acacia ehrenbergiana], [Acacia seyal], [Ziziphus mauritiana], [Balanites aegyptiaca], [Maerua crassifolia], [Salvadora persica], [Calotropis procera], [Capparis decidua], with [Cassia italica], [Ziziphus lotus], [Caylusea hexagyna], [Lavandula stricta], [Seetzenia africana], [Panicum turgidum], characteristic of the rocky beds of wadis and the alluvial gravels of outwash fans.', '(Kanter, 1967; Huetz de Lemps, 1970; White, 1983: 219-220; Foucault, 1993b: 269; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 90-91).');
    '[Acacia]-dominated thorn woodlands of the Sahelian zone of Mauritania.', '(Huetz de Lemps, 1970; Schnell, 1976: 325; White, 1983).');
    'Open formations of [Acacia raddiana], [Acacia senegal], [Acacia ehrenbergiana], [Maerua crassifolia], [Balanites aegyptiaca], [Ziziphus mauritiana], [Combretum aculeatum], accompanied by steppic tropical grassland or rainy season temporary grasslands with therophytes, of the Sahelian region of Mauritania.', '(Adam, 1968a: 49; Huetz de Lemps, 1970; Schnell, 1976: 325; White, 1983: 206).');
    '[Acacia nilotica]-dominated communities, often closed, of the Senegal valley of Mauritania, developed in particular on dunes.', '(Adam, 1968a: 50; Schnell, 1976: 324, 325).');
    'Open woodland or savanna woodland, steppe woodland, savanoid desert or desert woodland of the Arabian Peninsula and the Sinai, dominated by [Acacia raddiana], [Acacia tortilis], [Acacia gerrardii], [Acacia hamulosa], [Balanites aegyptiaca] or [Ziziphus spina-christi], with [Maerua crassifolia], [Salvadora persica], [Calotropis procera], [Cordia gharaf], [Capparis decidua], [Capparis cartilaginea], [Hammada salicornica], [Anabasis articulata], [Gymnocarpos decander], [Cassia italica], [Panicum turgidum], mostly confined to wadis and depressions.', '(Zohary, 1973; Orshan, 1986; Abd El Rahman, 1986).');
    'Open woodland or savanna woodland of the tropical southwestern and southeastern plains and hills of the Arabian Peninsula and of extreme southeastern Egypt, dominated by [Acacia tortilis], [Acacia ehrenbergiana], [Acacia asak], [Acacia mellifera], [Acacia senegal], [Acacia oerfota], [Acacia seyal], [Acacia hamulosa], [Acacia laeta], [Acacia etbaica], [Balanites aegyptiaca], [Maerua crassifolia], [Aristida plumosa], [Lasiurus hirsutus], [Panicum turgidum].', '(Zohary, 1973; Abd El Rahman, 1986).');
    'Open woodland, savanna woodland or desert woodland of the subtropical desert zone of southern Iran, with [Acacia nilotica] ssp. [indica] ([Acacia flava]), [Acacia oerfota] ([Acacia aucheri]), [Prosopis farcta], [Prosopis spicigera], [Ziziphus spina-christi], [Ziziphus nummularia], [Calotropis procera], [Periploca aphylla], [Dodonaea viscosa], [Amygdalus arabica], [Capparis spinosa], [Hammada salicornica].', '(Zohary, 1963, 1973; Rechinger, 1986).');
    '[Ziziphus nummularia] thorn woodland of the Jalalabad basin of eastern Afghanistan, northwesternmost extension of pre-Sindian middle Indus communities.', '(Schweinfurth, 1957: 272; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 110-113). ');
    'Woods, thickets or wooded pastures of the Cape Verde Islands dominated by naturally or probably naturally occurring African trees characteristic of dry woodland communities, in particular, [Acacia albida], [Ficus capensis], [Ficus sycamorus], [Tamarindus indica], [Calotropis procera].', '(Grandvaux Barbosa, 1968a: 96; White, 1983: 251, 252).');
    '[Olea laperrinei] formations of wadis of the higher altitudes, above 1800 metres, of the Ahaggar, the Tafedest, the Mouydir, the Tassili N''Ajjer, with an admixture of Mediterranean, Saharan, Sahelian and Afro-montane species, including [Pistacia atlantica], [Rhus tripartita], [Artemisia campestris] ssp. [glutinosa], [Stipa parviflora], [Stipa capensis], [Oryzopsis coerulescens].', '(Quézel and Santa, 1963; Huetz de Lemps, 1970: 124-125; White, 1983; Bousquet, 1992).');
    'Communities of eutrophic Palaearctic waters, often with variable level, dominated by fairly tall, robust grasses of genus [Glyceria] (section [Hydropoa]).', '(Jordanoff, 1931; Lebrun y al., 1949; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Noirfalise y al., 1980; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 88-89; Mossberg y al., 1995: 560).');
    'Communities of eutrophic Palaearctic waters dominated by [Glyceria maxima], rather low, usually constituting strips in or along ditches or small streams, often in grasslands, requiring fairly constant inundation by eutrophic water and with a fairly rich associated flora.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 74; Horvat y al., 1974: 183, 273, 404; Tanghe, 1975: 85; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 78; Delescaille, 1987: 72; Korotkov y al., 1991: 25, 29-30; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 88-89; Seliskar, 1998: 14).');
    '[Glyceria triflora] formations of periodically dry sites of Siberia and extreme northeastern Europe.', '(Mirkin y al., 1985: 383; Korotkov y al., 1991: 25-26).');
    'Communities of the terrestrialization zone of Palaearctic lakes, ponds, rivers, brooks and canals, mostly with turbid water, dominated by [Leersia oryzoides].', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 77; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 90; Mossberg y al., 1995: 591; Seliskar, 1998: 14).');
    'Communities of the margins of muddy shores of lakes, slow-flowing rivers and alases of the Palaearctic domaine, from eastern Fennoscandia, eastern Germany, Lithuania and the Ukraine eastwards, including central Yakutia, dominated by [Scolochloa festucacea].', '(Mirkin y al., 1985: 383; Oberdorfer, 1990: 219; Korotkov y al., 1991: 27, 29; Mossberg y al., 1995: 588).');
    'Communities of the margins of Palaearctic mesotrophic acidicline lakes, rivers and swamps dominated by [Calamagrostis canescens].', '(Oberdorfer, 1990: 36; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 100-101; Mossberg y al., 1995: 583; Schubert y al., 1995: 233).');
    'Communities of the margins of Palaearctic lakes, rivers, brooks and swamps dominated by [Phalaris arundinacea], pure or mixed with [Phragmites australis], very tolerant of drying, pollution and perturbance, susceptible of forming the landward belt of reedbeds and often characteristic of degraded systems.  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 74; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974: 273, 404; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; De Sloover y al., 1980: 66-67; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 79; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Delescaille, 1987: 74; Korotkov y al., 1991: 34-35; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 107, 116-117; Mossberg y al., 1995: 588; Hoda y al., 1998: 6; Frankard y al., 1998: 36; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Formations of clubrushes ([Scirpus spp.]), often accompanied by rushes ([Juncus spp.]), fringing, to a depth of 1.5 metres, brackish, saline, or sometimes fresh, waters of coastal saltmarshes, coastal lagoons, athalassic saline waterbodies and tidal rivers of the Palaearctic region. [Scirpus tabernaemontani] ([Schoenoplectum tabernaemontani]), [Scirpus maritimus] ([Bolboschoenus maritimus]), [Scirpus triqueter], [Scirpus litoralis], [Scirpus pungens], with, in particular, [Juncus gerardi] and [Juncus maritimus], compose various communities in the western Palaearctic; [Scirpus iseensis] is one of the components of eastern Palaearctic formations. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 211-212; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 73; Ellenberg, 1963; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 154-155, 222, 273, 404; Mäemets, 1974: 57-58; Hanso, 1975: 100; Soo, 1980; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Babalonas, 1980: 623-625; Botch and Masing, 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 78; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 4.1.4.1 [p.], 4.2.1.1 [p.], 6.1.3.6 [p.]; Diaz Gonzales and Fernandez Prieto, 1987: 87; Costa, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988: 305-307; Kolbek y al., 1989; Lanfranco, 1989: 47; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 27-28, 53-54; Pott, 1992: 154; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 109-112; Påhlsson, 1994: units 4.2.4.1 [p.], 4.3.1.1 [p.], 6.1.3.5 [p.]; Pott, 1996: 98; Hoda y al., 1998: 6).');
    'Formations of eastern Asia, north to southern Russian Amurland, dominated by [Zizania latifolia]; they occur, naturalized, in the Volga delta.', '(Korotkov y al., 1991: 29).');
    'Reedbed-like rooted or floating mats, beds, rafts and islands formed by tropical or subtropical herbs.', NULL);
    'Formations of large Cyperaceae of genera [Carex] or [Cyperus] occupying the edge or the entirety of humid depressions, oligotrophic mires and rich fens of the Palaearctic region, on ground that can be dry for part of the year. They occur, in particular, on the landward side of reedbeds in waterside successions and as colonists of humid depressions on mineral soils, or of acid and alkaline fens.  ', '(Maire, 1957; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Soo, 1980; Wheeler, 1980a; Dethioux, 1982; Botch and Masing, 1983; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Steiner, 1992; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Northern Galician and western Cantabrian [Alnus glutinosa] galleries, with [Carex acuta] ssp. [broteriana].  ', NULL);
    'Mixed riverine forests of Pontic and submediterranean regions of the Balkan and Hellenic peninsulas, in particular, the Mauries forest of northern Greece, the riverine forests of the Maritsa and the Tundzha, the longos forests of coastal Bulgaria, and riverine forests of the submediterranean Dinaride system, usually dominated by [Quercus robur] and/or [Fraxinus angustifolia], with varying admixtures of [Ulmus minor], [Ulmus laevis], [Carpinus betulus], [Acer campestre], [Alnus glutinosa], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Salix alba], [Populus alba].', '(Karpati and Karpati, 1961; Horvat y al., 1974; Dierschke, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Kassioumis, 1988; Bondev, 1991).');
    'Rare mixed riparian forests of northern Greece, dominated by [Quercus robur] and [Fraxinus angustifolia], represented, in particular, by the remarkable Mouries forest in the Kilkis prefectorate. ', '(Kassioumis, 1988).');
    'Regularly inundated forests of Pontic coastal lowland rivers, in particular the Kamchija and the Batova, and of the shores of Lake Arkutino in the Ropotamo Reserve, with [Fraxinus oxycarpa], [Ulmus minor] ([Ulmus foliacea]), [Acer campestre], [Acer tataricum], [Quercus pedunculiflora], [Carpinus betulus] and lianas [Smilax excelsa], [Periploca graeca], [Clematis vitalba], [Vitis sylvestris], [Calystegia sepium], [Humulus lupulus], [Hedera helix].', '(Stojanoff, 1929; Meshinev y al., 1982; Bondev, 1991: units 140-142, 149-150 [p.]; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994).');
    'Inland longos forests of the Maritsa and Tundzha river systems, drier, of poorer species composition and fewer lianas than the coastal longos forests of unit 44.4322; they harbour the rare, local endemic [Colchicum diampolis] and the Pheasant, [Phasianus colchicus], native to this region.', '(Bondev, 1991: units 140, 142, 143, 149, [p.]; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994).');
    'Mixed riverine forests of the Adriatic fa¿ade of Albania, dominated by [Fraxinus angustifolia], with [Quercus robur] and, in some formations [Alnus glutinosa], [Populus alba], [Ulmus minor] or, in others, [Ulmus procera], [Acer campestre], [Carpinus orientalis], [Laurus nobilis], [Quercus coccifera], and with [Calystegia sepium], [Periploca graeca], [Pyracantha coccinea], [Hedera helix], [Crataegus monogyna], [Ruscus aculeatus], [Tamus communis], [Rosa sempervirens], [Smilax aspera], [Rubus ulmifolius], [Rubus nemoralis], constituting species-rich, multi-facies formations of very high biological value.', '(Karpati and Karpati, 1961; Horvat y al., 1974: 203-206; Hoda y al., 1998: 16).');
    'Mixed riverine [Fraxinus angustifolia] and [Quercus robur] forests of Albania, occupying the largest surfaces within the riverine forests complexes of Adriatic Albania.', '(Karpati and Karpati, 1961; Horvat y al., 1974: 203-206; Hoda y al., 1998: 17).');
    'Mixed riverine [Fraxinus angustifolia] forests of Albania subjected to long periods of inundation a species cortŠge that includes [Baldellia ranunculoides], [Alisma plantago-aquatica], [Iris pseudacorus], [Lythrum salicaria] and [Potamion] and [Phragmition] elements.', '(Karpati and Karpati, 1961; Horvat y al., 1974: 203-206; Hoda y al., 1998: 16).');
    'Mixed estuarine [Fraxinus angustifolia] forests of Albania with [Quercus robur], [Alnus glutinosa], [Populus alba], [Ulmus minor] and a species cortŠge that includes halophytes, in particular, [Juncus acutus] and [Samolus valerandi].  ', '(Karpati and Karpati, 1961; Horvat y al., 1974: 203-206; Hoda y al., 1998: 16).');
    'Mixed riverine [Fraxinus angustifolia] forests of Albania, forming the transition towards [Quercetea ilicis] mediterranean formations, with [Quercus robur], [Laurus nobilis], [Ulmus procera], [Acer campestre], [Carpinus orientalis], [Quercus coccifera], [Paliurus spina-christi], [Clematis viticela].', '(Karpati and Karpati, 1961; Horvat y al., 1974: 203-206; Hoda y al., 1998: 16).');
    'Riverine forest of Lake Scutari, with [Quercus robur] ssp. [scutariensis] and [Periploca graeca].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 207).');
    'Riverine forest of the Mirna Valley in Istria, dominated by [Fraxinus angustifolia] and [Quercus robur], with [Ulmus minor], [Alnus glutinosa], [Salix alba], [Carpinus betulus], [Frangula alnus], [Acer campestre], [Corylus avellana], [Euonymus europaeus], [Staphylea pinnata], [Lonicera caprifolium], [Pyrus pyraster], [Rubus caesius], [Vitis vinifera] ssp. [sylvestris], [Carex remota], [Rumex sanguineus], [Lycopus europaeus], [Cerastium sylvaticum], [Primula vulgaris], [Helleborus dumetorum] ssp. [atrorubens], [Lathyrus vernus].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 206-207).');
    'Riverine gallery forests of the Pannonic region, characteristic of the Danube basin, north to the lower Morava, of the Tisza basin and of the Danube-Tisza interfluve. They are dominated by [Quercus robur] and [Fraxinus angustifolia] ssp. [pannonica], sometimes with [Ulmus laevis], [Alnus glutinosa], [Carpinus betulus] and, in the wettest parts, [Populus alba]. The shrub layer includes [Acer campestre], [Acer tataricum], [Cornus sanguinea], [Crataegus monogyna], [Corylus avellana], [Ulmus minor]. The herb layer is dominated by [Carex acutiformis], [Carex elata], [Carex riparia], [Urtica dioica], [Urtica kioviensis] in the wetter belt ("[Fraxino pannonicae-Alnetum]"), by [Deschampsia cespitosa], [Veratrum album], [Polygonatum latifolium], [Symphytum officinale] otherwise.', '(Karpati and Karpati, 1969; Soo, 1980; Karpati, 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1981, 1986; Moravec y al., 1982; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 103-104; Prpic, 1996: 71).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] mire woods of Atlantic western Norway with a shrub-dominated undergrowth rich in [Erica tetralix] and [Myrica gale].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.5 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.3 [p]).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] mire woods of subcontinental regions of the boreal western Palaearctic, in particular, of Finland and northwestern Russia, with a shrub-dominated undergrowth rich in [Chamaedaphne calyculata] and [Ledum palustre].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.1.1.5 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.3 [p.]).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] mire woods of sub-Atlantic regions of the boreal western Palaearctic, in particular, of eastern Norway and Sweden, with a shrub-dominated undergrowth formed by ericoid shrubs of genera [Vaccinium] and [Empetrum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.1.1.5 [p.], 3.3.1.1 [p.], 3.3.1.1a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.3 [p.]).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] mire woods of Atlantic western Norway with an undergrowth dominated by [Molinia caerulea], with [Narthecium ossifragum], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Erica tetralix] and [Myrica gale].', '(Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.1.1.3a).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] fen woods of the boreal region of the western Palaearctic, with a sparse tree layer and an undergrowth comprising a combination of ericoid shrub hummocks and wetter lawns and depressions, constituting a highly varied ensemble that may include neutrophile or even basicline species. Sedges, in particular [Carex lasiocarpa] and [Carex rostrata], may be prominent or dominant; the species cortege includes [Andromeda polifolia], [Betula nana], [Empetrum spp.], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Pedicularis palustris], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Tofieldia pusilla], [Carex dioica], [Carex echinata], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Scirpus cespitosus] ssp. [cespitosus] ([Trichophorum cespitosum]), [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Molinia caerulea], [Equisetum fluviatile], [Drepanocladus badius], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Sphagnum fuscum], [Sphagnum platyphyllum], [Sphagnum magellanicum], [Sphagnum subsecundum], [Sphagnum teres], [Sphagnum warnstorfii].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.4.1.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.1.1).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris] mire woods of rich fens of the boreal region of the western Palaearctic west to Finland with a brown-moss rich undergrowth formed of herbs, graminids and small shrubs. The species cortŠge includes [Betula nana], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Salix nigricans] ([Salix myrsinifolia]), [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Juniperus communis], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Angelica sylvestris], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Potentilla erecta], [Pedicularis palustris], [Solidago virgaurea], [Carex lasiocarpa], [Carex vaginata], [Carex dioica], [Carex caespitosa], [Equisetum palustris], [Aulacomnium palustre], [Campylium stellatum], [Drepanocladus intermedius], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Hylocomium splendens], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Sphagnum fuscum], [Tomentypnum nitens].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.4.1.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.1.1).');
    '[Pinus sylvestris]-dominated mire woods of the wooded steppe and steppe zones of western Eurasia, in particular of the Ukraine, with [Betula pendula], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Salix spp.], [Chamaedaphne calyculata], [Carex pauciflora], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Sphagnum spp.]', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 144-145, 193).');
    NULL, NULL);
    'Woods or scrubs formed by erect or prostrate members of the [Pinus mugo] complex, namely the tall, single-stemmed [Pinus uncinata], the multi-stemmed, up to 8m tall, [Pinus rotundata], and the multi-stemmed, up to 2m tall, [Pinus mugo], developing on drier buttes and ridges of raised bogs, acid fens and transition moors of the Alps, the pre-Alpine plateaux and valleys, the Jura, the higher Hercynian ranges and associated hills and depressions, with [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Sphagnum spp.] and sometimes [Betula nana].', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 337, 340; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Ozenda, 1975; Delvosalle, 1977; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Moravec y al., 1983: 45, 46; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 93, 186-187; Pott, 1992: 354-355; Steiner, 1993: 175-176; Schubert y al., 1995: 103-104; Favarger and Robert, 1995b: 64; Rybnicek, 1998: 237-243, 302-304).');
    'Woods or scrubs of [Pinus uncinata], [Pinus rotundata] or [Pinus mugo] of drier buttes and ridges of raised bogs, acid fens and transition moors of the Alps, the pre-Alpine plateaux and valleys and the Jura.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 337, 340; Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Ozenda, 1975; Delvosalle, 1977; Pott, 1992: 354-355; Steiner, 1993: 175-176; Favarger and Robert, 1995b: 64). ');
    'Woods or scrubs of [Pinus rotundata] or [Pinus mugo] developing on drier buttes and ridges of raised bogs, acid fens and transition moors of the higher Hercynian ranges, from the Black Forest to the Bohemian Quadrangle, and of a few associated hills and depressions.', '(Oberdorfer, 1967, 1990; Ozenda, 1975; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Moravec y al., 1983: 45, 46; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 93, 186-187; Pott, 1992: 354-355; Steiner, 1993: 175-176; Schubert y al., 1995: 103-104; Rybnicek, 1998: 237-243, 302-304).');
    'Mesophilous ravine and valley gallery forest of the southeast of the Arabian peninsula, with [Ficus sycomorus], [Ficus glumosa], [Ficus lutea], [Ficus populifolia], [Ficus salicifolia], [Rhus glaucescens], [Diospyros mespilliformis], [Tamarindus indica], [Trichylia emetica], [Olea chrysophylla] and [Grewia spp.], [Combretum trichanthum], [Dracena spp.], [Phoenix reclinata] and many lianas.', '(Zohary, 1973; Walter and Breckle, 1991b).');
    'Evergreen bushland and thickets, semievergreen bushland and open woodland of Socotra, island outpost of East African evergreen and semievergreen bushlands and thickets, distributed on drier slopes of mountains and hills from central Tanzania to Eritrea and Ethiopia, with a maximum development in Ethiopian highlands.', '(Gwynne, 1968; Schnell, 1976; White, 1983).');
    'Open [Dracaena cinnabari]-dominated woodland of limestone slopes of the Hagghier Mountains and of the Hamadera Hills of Socotra, with [Boswellia ameero], [Boswellia elongata], [Boswellia socotrana], [Aloe perryi], [Adenium socotranum], [Mitolepis intricata].', '(Gwynne, 1968: 182-185; Schnell, 1976: 358-363; White, 1983: 115, 254).');
    'Formations of [Cephalocroton socotranus], [Carissa edulis], [Buxus hildebrandtii], [Dodonaea viscosa], [Ficus socotrana], [Indigofera sokotrana], [Ruellia insignis], [Boswellia ameero], [Euphorbia socotrana], of granite slopes of the Hagghier range of Socotra.', '(Gwynne, 1968: 183-184; Schnell, 1976: 358-363; White, 1983: 115, 254).');
    'Open, succulent, Socotran woodland dominated by [Dendrosicyos socotrana], the only arborescent Cucurbitaceae, belonging to a monospecific genus endemic to the island, accompanied by [Euphorbia arbuscula], [Euphorbia spiralis], [Adenium socotranum], [Dorstenia gigas], [Kleinia scottii], [Kalanchoe robusta], [Aloe perryi], [Cissus subaphylla], developed on sandstone plateaux and on limestone cliffs and valley slopes.', '(Gwynne, 1968: 182-183; Schnell, 1976: 358-363; White, 1983: 115, 254).');
    'Dry open evergreen sclerophyllous woodland developed on sub-Himalayan and sub-Hindukushian hills and plateaux of the Indus watershed of eastern Afghanistan, of Indo-Himalayan affinities, with [Olea ferruginea] ([Olea cuspidata]), [Monotheca buxifolia] ([Reptonia buxifolia]), [Quercus ballota], [Pistacia integerrima], [Ficus palmata], [Cotinus coggygria], [Punica granatum].', '(Schweinfurth, 1957: 272-273; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 110-113). ');
    'Closed dry forests, open dry forests, savanna woodland, thorn forests of the tropical regions of mainland China, of Hainan, Taiwan and of tropical Pacific islands.', '(Schnell, 1971a: 746-747; Mei''e y al., 1985: 304, 306 [i.a.]; Mueller-Dombois and Fosberg, 1998: 234-241).');
    'Tropical intertidal mud forests and thickets formed by mangroves and their associates. Worldwide, mangrove forests can be divided into two large ensembles, Atlantic-type mangals, species-poor formations characteristic of the west coast of Africa as well as of the tropical Pacific and Atlantic coasts of the Americas, and Oriental-type mangals, species-rich formations of the Indian Ocean, of the western and central Pacific and of their associated tropical seas. In the Palaearctic region, as here defined, Oriental mangals occur along the coasts of the Pacific, north to southern Japan, of the Arabian Sea, of the Red Sea, Atlantic mangals along the coasts of west Africa.', '(Schnell, 1971b: 798-841; Zohary, 1973; Chapman, 1977a; Chapman, 1977b; Zahran, 1977; Hosokawa y al., 1977; White, 1983: 260-262; Clark, 1990; Tomlinson, 1994; Archibold, 1995; Vanden Berghen, 1995).');
    'Species-poor [Rhizophora racemosa], [Rhizophora mangle], [Rhizophora harrisonii], [Avicennia nitida], [Avicennia schauerana] formations of the west coast of Africa and of the tropical Pacific and Atlantic coasts of the Americas, with [Laguncularia racemosa], [Conocarpus erectus], [Drepanocarpus lunulatus], [Acrostichum aureum], [Hibiscus tiliaceus]. The complex of formations is represented in the Palaearctic zone, as here defined, by extremely localized mangrove scrubs of the coast of Mauritania.', '(Schnell, 1971b; White, 1983: 260-262; Ward and Bunyard, 1992; Vanden Berghen, 1995).');
    'Species-rich [Rhizophora mucronata], [Rhizophora apiculata], [Rhizophora stylosa], [Rhizophora lamarckii], [Rhizophora mangle], [Avicennia marina], [Avicennia spp.], [Bruguiera spp.], [Ceriops spp.], [Kandelia spp.], [Sonneratia spp.], [Lumnitzera spp.], [Aegiceras spp.], [Xylocarpus spp.], [Acanthus spp.], [Nypa spp.] formations of the Indian Ocean, of the western and central Pacific and of their associated tropical seas, represented within the Palaearctic zone, as here defined, by mangrove communities of the Red Sea, of the Arabian Sea and of the western Pacific north to Hainan, Kwangtung, Kwangsi, Fukien, Taiwan and southern Japan.', '(Schnell, 1971b; Zahran, 1977: 217-218; Hosokawa y al., 1977: 281-287; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 44; Ward and Bunyard, 1992).');
    'Mire communities, for the most part turfogenic, of sedges, grasses, rushes, bryophytes and their associated species; tall helophyte fringes of water bodies. Complex systems of raised bogs, blanket bogs, rich fens, acidic fens, transition mires, boreal marsh-fens, aapa, palsa and polygon mires characterized by the presence of these communities, but also including formations otherwise typical of sections 22, 31, 37, 44. Spring systems.', NULL);
    'Palaearctic communities of social sedges of genus [Carex], usually dominated by one species that can be either tussock-forming or bed-forming. They are arranged according to dominant species. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; de Boer, 1974; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Schumacher, 1977; Bournérias, 1979, 1984: 229-230; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Soo, 1980; Wheeler, 1980a; Jermy y al., 1982; Pignatti, 1982; Dethioux, 1982; Moravec y al., 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Wolff, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1987; Costa, 1987; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Ladero Alvarez, 1987; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Elias y al., 1991; Steiner, 1992; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.4.1 [i.a.]).');
    'Formations of [Carex disticha] of Palaearctic humid alluvial meadows on clay and of temporarily drying peatbogs; often in contact with grasslands of the [Calthion] and sometimes placed in that alliance; they tolerate fairly long dessication and have a relatively rich accompanying flora.  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 75c; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Dethioux, 1982; Moravec y al., 1983: 34; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 79; Delescaille, 1987: 74; Korotkov y al., 1991: 31, 33; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 105; Julve, 1993: 90; Mossberg y al., 1995: 614).');
    'Palaearctic formations of the terrestrialisation zone of marshes, ponds and lakes on mostly mineral, neutral, basic or weakly acid substrates, dominated by large bed-forming, rhizomatous, sedges, in particular, [Carex acuta], [Carex acutiformis] or their relatives.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; van der Ploeg and Rudolphy, 1970, 1971; Horvat y al., 1974; Bournérias, 1979, 1984: 229-230; Dethioux, 1982; Botch and Masing, 1983; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 79; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Golub and Mirkin, 1986; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 31; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Mossberg y al., 1995).');
    'Palaearctic formations of [Carex acuta] of wet, alkaline or slightly acid depressions with mineral soil; [Carex acuta] does not tolerate prolonged dessication. The community is distributed, in particular, in northern France, the Low Countries, Central Europe south to the Sava and Drava valleys of Croatia, the northern Morava valley of Serbia and Romania, north to Poland, the Kaliningrad District, Lithuania and Latvia, in southern Scandinavia, in the Dnieper basin of northern Ukraine and southern Belarus, in the lower Volga Valley.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 75b [p.]; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Blazkova, 1971: 70; Horvat y al., 1974: 401, 492; Bournérias, 1979, 1984: 229-230; Dethioux, 1982; Botch and Masing, 1983; Moravec y al., 1983: 34; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 79; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.2.3.6, 6.1.2.4; Golub and Mirkin, 1986; Delescaille, 1987: 74; Korotkov y al., 1991: 32; Julve, 1993: 102; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 101-102; Påhlsson, 1994: units 5.2.3.6, 6.1.2.3; Mossberg y al., 1995: 641; Ilijanic, 1996: 108; Frankard y al., 1998: 35; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Palaearctic communities dominated by [Carex acutiformis], more tolerant of dessication than [Carex acuta], forming beds on mesotrophic, base-rich, neutral to slightly acid, peaty or mineral soils. Large beds may form in fens, often with [Carex paniculata]; otherwise, they are widespread along watercourses on the landward side of [Carex acuta] or [Carex vesicaria] beds, in alluvial plains, ditches and depressions of humid meadow systems; they may occupy stations that almost totally escape periodical inundation. ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 75b-b; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974: 184, 273; Tanghe, 1975: 86-87; Molinier and Martin, 1980: 55; Bournérias, 1979, 1984: 229-230; Dethioux, 1982; Moravec y al., 1983: 34; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 79; Delescaille, 1987: 74; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989; Korotkov y al., 1991: 31; Julve, 1993: 102; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 98-99; Mossberg y al., 1995: 621; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Formations of [Carex oenensis], restricted to oligotrophic, base-rich streamsides of the pre-Alpine Bavarian plateau.  ', '(Oberdorfer, 1990; Schönfelder y al., 1990: 689; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 102-103).');
    '[Carex buekii] formations of mesotrophic sandy or clayey soils in Franconia, eastern Bavaria, Saxony, northern Italy, eastern central Europe, eastern Europe and western Asia.  ', '(Pignatti, 1982; Moravec y al., 1983: 30; Oberdorfer, 1990: 689; Schönfelder y al., 1990: 689; Trpin and Vres, 1995: 29).');
    'Mesotrophic [Carex aquatilis] formations of northern Siberia and northern Europe, south to Lower Saxony, Friesland, Wales, Lakeland, Scotland, Ireland.', '(van der Ploeg and Rudolphy, 1970, 1971; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 4.1.2.6, 5.2.3.6b, 6.1.2.3; Korotkov y al., 1991: 31; Påhlsson, 1994: units 4.2.2.6, 5.2.3.6a, 6.1.2.2; Mossberg y al., 1995: 639).');
    '[Carex acuta] ssp. [broteriana] formations of Iberia, lining river courses on the inner side of alder galleries, or replacing them.  ', '(Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987: 153-154; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987: 442; Ladero Alvarez, 1987: 481).');
    'Palaearctic swamp communities dominated by [Carex melanostachya] ([Carex nutans]), characteristic of slightly saline soils of the Pannonic region, habitat of the uncommon [Carex curvata]. ', '(Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 106).');
    'Formations of the terrestrialisation zone of Mediterranean marshes, ponds, lakes, ditches dominated by [Carex hispida].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 41; Molinier and Martin, 1980: 55; Pignatti, 1982: III, 675; Lanfranco, 1989: 46; Gamisans, 1991: 322-326; Sfikas, 1992: 315).');
    'Riverine forests of [Quercus robur], [Quercus pedunculiflora], [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Fraxinus pallisiae], [Ulmus minor] and [Ulmus effusa] of the great floodplains of the lower Danube, with [Cornus sanguinea], [Viburnum opulus], [Frangula alnus], [Crataegus monogyna] in the shrub layer and [Rubus caesius], [Lysimachia nummularia], [Glechoma hederacea], [Convallaria majalis] in the herb layer.
', '(Simon, 1960; Sanda, 1970; Oprea, 1976; Bondev, 1991: units 140, 142, [p.]).');
    'Relict forests of the alluvial plain of the Po and its main tributaries, remnants of the greatest fluviatile system of Europe. They are formed by meso-hygrophile, mesotrophic, multi-layered, oak-ash-hornbeam-dominated communities ([Carpinion betuli]: [Polygonato multiflorae-Quercetum roboris]), with facies richer in ashes, willows and, mostly, alders, in the wettest areas ([Alno-Padion]). Constituent trees include [Quercus robur], [Quercus cerris], [Fraxinus excelsior], [Fraxinus ornus], [Carpinus betulus], [Ulmus minor], [Populus alba], [Populus nigra], [Acer campestre], [Acer pseudoplatanus], [Prunus padus], [Prunus avium], [Alnus glutinosa], [Salix alba], [Corylus avellana], [Sorbus torminalis], [Sorbus domestica], the shrub layers are formed, in particular, by [Ruscus aculeatus], [Cornus mas], [Cornus sanguinea], [Crataegus laevigata], [Crataegus monogyna], [Pyracantha coccinea], [Rubus fruticosus], [Rubus ulmifolius], [Rubus caesius], [Ribes uva-crispa], [Sambucus nigra], [Daphne mezereum], [Viburnum lantana], [Mespilus germanica], [Lonicera xylosteum], [Ligustrum vulgare], [Prunus spinosa], [Rosa canina], [Euonymus europaeus], [Rhamnus catharticus]; lianas are abundant, in particular, [Hedera helix], [Tamus communis], [Rubia peregrina], [Bryonia cretica]; in the herb layer occur, in particular, [Equisetum hyemale], [Symphytum officinale], [Polygonatum multiflorum], [Pulmonaria officinalis], [Lathyrus vernus], [Mercurialis perennis], [Primula acaulis], [Asarum europaeum], [Euphorbia dulcis], [Melittis melissophyllum], [Erythronium dens-canis], [Leucojum vernum], [Brachypodium sylvaticum], [Carex pilosa.] These forests are the habitat of the endangered endemic frog [Rana latastei].', '(Fenaroli, 1970; Tomaselli, 1970; Tosco, 1975; Ozenda y al., 1979; Ozenda, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987).');
    'Riverine forests of [Quercus robur], [Tilia cordata], [Ulmus laevis], [Ulmus effusa], [Alnus cordata] of the floodplains of great rivers of the Sarmatic nemoral and nemoro-steppic regions, distributed in the Baltic hinterland, in Polesia, along the rivers of the Podolian plateaux, and along those of the middle Russian plateaux and uplands, including the Belarus hills, the Valday Uplands, the Smolensk Uplands and the Central Russian Uplands, in the Volga-Kama system, in which [Tilia cordata] progressively replaces [Quercus robur] eastwards, extending south into the Pontic region, in particular along the lower Dniepr, and north into the southern boreal taiga zone.', '(Walter, 1974: 209; Yurkevich y al., 1979: 128-130; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 125, 132, 485; Korotkov y al., 1991: 296-297).');
