    'Forests of the boreonemoral transition zone between taiga and temperate lowland deciduous forests of the northwestern Palaearctic in which conifers, mostly [Pinus sylvestris], share the main canopy with deciduous trees, usually [Quercus robur] or [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii], accompanied by an undergrowth formed by lichens and dwarf, matted, ericoid shrubs. A number of subunits can be distinguished with species cortŠges similar to those of conifer taiga forests of unit 42.C8 or of deciduous woods of unit 41.5, in particular, 41.51 and 41.521, or of unit 41.B721. These can be indicated by addition of these codes to 43.2.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 11a, 11b; Saphronova, 1964c: units 13a, 13b; Birot, 1970: 115-118, 121, 159-160, 170-171; Walter, 1974: 105-117; Sokolowski, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.3.1.1; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 102-103, 210-212; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 135-145; Rieley and Page, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Shugart y al., 1992; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.3.1.1; Huetz de Lemps, 1994: 87).');
    'Forests of the boreonemoral transition zone between taiga and temperate lowland deciduous forests of the northwestern Palaearctic in which conifers, [Picea abies], [Picea obovata], [Pinus sylvestris], [Abies sibirica], share the main canopy with deciduous trees, mostly [Quercus robur], but also [Betula pendula], [Betula pubescens] or [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii], and sometimes, in the extreme southwest of the region, [Fagus sylvatica], accompanied by an undergrowth formed by ericoid shrubs and grasses, in particular, [Deschampsia cespitosa]. A number of subunits can be distinguished with species cortŠges similar to those of conifer taiga forests of units 42.C1, 42.C5 or 42.C6, or of deciduous woods of unit 41.5, in particular, 41.51 and 41.521, of units 41.121, 41.B8, or 41.B722. These can be indicated by addition of these codes to 43.3.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 11a, 11b; Saphronova, 1964c: units 13a, 13b; Birot, 1970: 115-118, 121, 159-160, 170-171; Walter, 1974: 105-117; Sokolowski, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.3.1.2; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 102-103, 210-212; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 135-145; Rieley and Page, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Shugart y al., 1992; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.3.1.2; Huetz de Lemps, 1994: 87).');
    'Mediterranean multi-layered riverine forests of base-rich soils submitted to seasonal prolonged inundation with slow drainage, with [Populus alba], [Populus nigra], [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Ulmus minor], [Salix alba], [Salix spp.], [Alnus spp.], lianas and often species of the [Quercetalia ilicis], distributed in the mediterranean regions of the Iberian peninsula, southern France, the Italic peninsula, the large Tyrrhenian islands, the Hellenic peninsula, the southern Balkan peninsula, North Africa, and their zones of transition to adjacent climatic zones. Formations physiognomically dominated by tall [Populus alba] and/or [Populus nigra] are listed here. The poplars may, however, be absent or sparse in some associations which are then dominated by [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Ulmus minor] and/or [Salix spp.] Such ensembles may, depending on their size, be treated as a local manifestation of a complex poplar ensemble, or listed under units 44.63 or 44.141. The poplar forests are usually the tall ligneous vegetation belt closest to the water in riverside catenas.', '(Oberdorfer, 1953; Braun-Blanquet and Bolos, 1957; Maire, 1961; Debazac and Mavrommatis, 1971; Horvat y al., 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1975c; Molinier y al., 1976; Lavagne and Moutte, 1977; Girerd, 1978; Dierschke, 1980; Molinier and Martin, 1980; Ozenda, 1981; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Harant and Jarry, 1983; Devaux y al., 1983; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Peinado Lorca y al., 1984; Darracq y al., 1984; Gamisans, 1985; Dupias, 1985; Chiappini, 1985b; Fernandez Gonzalez, 1986; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Alcaraz Ariza and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Vigo and Ninot, 1987; Martinez Parras y al., 1987; Aparicio Martinez and Silvestre Domingo, 1987; Baudière y al., 1988; Rallo and Pandolfi, 1988; Bondev, 1991).');
    'Riparian poplar galleries on inundatable eutrophic soils with permanent hydromorphy of the Iberian range, the Castilian plateau, the Ebro basin, the Mediterranean Iberian east, the great Baetic rivers, with [Populus alba], [Populus nigra], arborescent willows ([Salix neotricha], [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis], [Salix atrocinerea]), [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Ulmus minor] and [Celtis australis]. The naturalized madder, [Rubia tinctorum], grows in the shade of the eastern and central formations, the Atlantic [Salix atrocinerea] is an important component of the formations of the central Meseta, the Montes de Toledo and western Andalusia, and [Nerium oleander] penetrates the most thermophilous western Andalusian formations.  ', '(Oberdorfer, 1953; Braun-Blanquet and Bolos, 1957; Rivas-Martinez, 1975c; Dierschke, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Peinado Lorca y al., 1984; Fernandez Gonzalez, 1986; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Alcaraz Ariza and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Vigo and Ninot, 1987; Martinez Parras y al., 1987; Aparicio Martinez and Silvestre Domingo, 1987).');
