    '[Quercus suber] forests of Mediterranean regions of North Africa, extending from nearly sea level to over 2100 metres, mostly in the Tell, the Kroumirian mountains, the Rif, locally in coastal areas and in the Middle Atlas, the High Atlas, the Djebel Amour, the AurŠs and the Dorsale.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Knapp, 1973: 472-473; White, 1983: 151-152; Foucault, 1993b: 268; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 85-86).');
    'Open, xerophilous [Quercus suber] forests of Mediterranean regions of North Africa, widespread in northwestern Morroco, with a few relict outposts in the Oran-Mascara region of Algeria, mostly developed on Pliocene sands or on schist. A low shrub layer is composed of, in varying abundance depending on substrate and locality, [Teline linifolia], [Halimium halimifolium], [Halimium commutatum], [Cytisus arboreus], [Daphne gnidium], [Lavandula stoechas], [Stauracanthus boivinii], [Chamaerops humilis], and an herb layer rich in therophytes. The M¿mora forest of Morocco harbours the endemic [Pyrus mamorensis], scattered in the canopy.', '(Herbauts, 1973: 339-341; White, 1983: 151-152; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 86).');
    '[Quercus suber] forests of the subhumid level of the Rif, of the Tell and of the Saharan Atlas, east, very locally, to a few valley sites in the Tunisian Dorsale.  [Erica arborea], [Arbutus unedo], [Cistus salvifolius], [Lavandula stoechas] participate in the undergrowth.', '(Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Herbauts, 1973: 343; White, 1983: 152; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 86).');
    '[Quercus suber] forests of the humid level of the Algerian Tell, of the Kroumirian mountains and of their coastal fa¿ade, with a few outposts west to the Bab-Azhar forest of the Rif.  [Cytisus villosus] ([Cytisus triflorus]), [Erica arborea], [Erica scoparia], [Viburnum tinus], [Halimium halimioides], [Lavandula stoechas], [Pteridium aquilinum] dominate the undergrowth, with [Pistacia lentiscus] in warmer stations and [Quercus coccifera] in littoral regions.', '(Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Herbauts, 1973: 350; White, 1983: 152; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 86).');
    'Communities of bog lawns and of areas intermediate between hollows and hummocks in which often small loose cushions of [Sphagnum tenellum] dominate the ground layer, usally in association with [Sphagnum balticum], [Sphagnum rubellum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum subnitens], and with an emergent layer of [Eriophorum vaginatum], characteristic, in particular, of Finland, the southeastern Baltic coastlands, also recorded from Scandinavia, Britain and Ireland.', '(Sjörs, 1983: 82; Botch and Masing, 1983: 117; Bellamy, 1986: 42-43; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 27, 226; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.3.5 [p.]).');
    'Hollow-side and lawn communities of Palaearctic bogs dominated by the bright orange [Sphagnum pulchrum] associated with [Eriophorum vaginatum], recorded, in particular, from northwestern Central Europe, Ireland and western Britain.', '(Smith, 1978: 73; Bellamy, 1986: 42-43; Ellenberg, 1988: 337; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 27, 214; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M18 [p.], 184).');
    'Lawns and hummock-to-hollow transition communities of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Sphagnum papillosum] associated with [Eriophorum vaginatum], most characteristic of maritime and submaritime regions of the western and eastern Palaearctic, often constituting the dominant lawn community in Atlantic and sub-Atlantic bogs of nemoral Europe. [Erica tetralix] is a usual member of the community in western regions; when its cover exceeds that of [Eriophorum vaginatum] the stands should be listed under unit 51.115. In boreal Europe [Sphagnum papillosum] carpets are more characteristic of minerotrophic acidic fens than of bogs.', '(Duvigneaud, 1944: 13; Duvigneaud, 1949: 109-110; Botch and Masing, 1983: 126; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M18 [p.], 184; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 274-279, 285; Bellamy, 1986: 42-43; Ellenberg, 1988: 334, 339; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 52; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Lawns of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum] associated with [Sphagnum capillifolium] ([Sphagnum capillifolium] var. [capillifolium]).', '(Ellenberg, 1988: 338; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 93-94; Robbe, 1993: 52-53).');
    'Lawns of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum] associated with [Sphagnum recurvum], often highly prevalent in moderately wet bogs of nemoral Central Europe and Hercynian Western Europe. In boreal Europe, [Sphagnum recurvum] communities are mostly limited to fens.', '(Duvigneaud, 1944: 14-15; Duvigneaud, 1949: 74, 112-113; Lebrun y al., 1949: units 118d, 119b; Vanden Berghen, 1951a: 181, 185; Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 95-97; Ellenberg, 1988: 337; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 188; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 74; Coldea, 1991: 438; Pott, 1992: 192-193; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 274-279, 285-286, 292; Steiner, 1993: 177; Drachenfels, 1994: units 6.1 [p.], 6.3.1 [p.], 6.3.3 [p.]).');
    'Lawns of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum] associated with [Sphagnum fuscum] characteristic of subcontinental Fennoscandia, from eastern Sweden eastwards, of the eastern Baltic bog province of western Russia, of the Eastern Carpathians, of western Siberia.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 74, 113; Botch and Masing, 1983: 118; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.2.1; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 185; Coldea, 1991: 435-438; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.3.1).');
    'Lawns of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum] associated with [Sphagnum rubellum] ([Sphagnum capillifolium] var. [rubellum]) characteristic of relatively maritime climates, recorded, in particular, from southeastern Norway, western Sweden and the Danish archipelago, where [Sphagnum balticum] is a frequent accompanier, and from the Central Massif of France, where [Sphagnum magellanicum] is an associate.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1951b: 369, 371; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.2.2; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 94; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.3.3).');
    'Lawns of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum] associated with [Sphagnum balticum] characteristic of bogs of the nemoral region, in particular, of large areas of Sweden, of Finland, the Baltic States, Russia, western Siberia. Accompaniers include [Scirpus cespitosus], [Eriophorum russeolum], [Sphagnum rubellum], [Sphagnum tenellum], [Sphagnum lindbergii].', '(Ilomets, 1974: 195; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 64; Sjörs, 1983: 82; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116, 117, 120; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.2.4; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 198; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.3.5).');
    'Lawns of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum] associated with [Sphagnum angustifolium] characteristic of northeastern Europe and eastern Fennoscandia, mostly distributed in northern Karelia, the Lake and Bothnian gulf regions of Finland, rare in Sweden.', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 64; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.2.3; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 191; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.3.4).');
    'Lawns of Palaearctic bogs dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum] associated with [Sphagnum magellanicum] and [Sphagnum rubellum], sometimes accompanied by [Sphagnum tenellum], [Sphagnum angustifolium], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum fuscum] or [Sphagnum warnstorfii], characteristic, in particular, of the British Isles, southern Scandinavia, in Denmark, Norway and southern Sweden, of the northern and southern Alpine piedmont, of the Eastern Carpathians.', '(Ilomets, 1974: 195; Pedrotti, 1978: 242; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.2.5; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 61; Coldea, 1991: 435-438; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M18 [p.], 184; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 274-279, 286; Steiner, 1993: 172-173; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.3.2; Frankard y al., 1998: 39; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Tree and shrub vegetation of flood plains, marshes, fens and bogs of the nemoral, boreal, steppic, warm-temperate humid, mediterranean, cold desert and subtropical desert zones. Within the latter two zones and their transition areas, in which most or all tree growth is linked to permanent or temporary water courses or water tables, only the formations that depend on the highest water tables, such as the tamarix communities and those formed by northern riparian trees, have been included in this category, while wadi- or oasis-dependant thorn woodland and palm communities are included in unit 4B. ', '(Schweinfurth, 1957; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Zohary, 1973: 377-378, 385; Horvat y al., 1974; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Ozenda, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Pott, 1996).');
    '[Salix spp.] brush or arborescent formations, lining flowing water and submitted to periodic flooding, developed on recently deposited alluvion. Within the Palaearctic domaine, willow brushes are particularly characteristic of rivers originating in major mountain ranges. Shrubby willow formations also constitute an element of lowland and hill riverine successions in all major biomes, often making the belt closest to the water course. Taller arborescent willow formations often constitute the next belt landwards in riverine successions of lowland western nemoral, eastern nemoral and warm-temperate humid forest regions, and a large part of the less diverse riverine systems of the steppic, mediterranean and cold desert zones.', '(Schweinfurth, 1957; Maire, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Pedrotti, 1980; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Géhu, 1984a; Noirfalise, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Coldea, 1991; Bondev, 1991; Rodwell, 1991a; Grass, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Riverside brush of fast, pebbly, summer-high rivers originating in the Alps or other major Palaearctic mountain ranges with similar climate cycle, with [Salix spp.], [Myricaria germanica] and [Hippophae rhamnoides].  ', '(Schweinfurth, 1957; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Holub y al., 1967; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.5.1.2; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 360; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992: 331-332; Grass, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: units 7.2.1.2, 7.2.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Low, prostrate [Myricaria germanica] and [Salix spp.], in particular [Salix elaeagnos], [Salix purpurea] ssp. [gracilis], [Salix daphnoides], [Salix nigricans], formations of low, silty shoals in Alpine and peri-Alpine valleys, with outposts in the Carpathians and the northern Dinarides.  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Holub y al., 1967; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ozenda, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992: 331; Grass, 1993: 46-47; Sanda y al., 1998: 223; Seliskar, 1998: 9).');
    'Formations of [Salix elaeagnos], [Salix purpurea] ssp. [gracilis], [Salix daphnoides], [Salix nigricans] and [Hippophae rhamnoides] of higher gravel shoals in Alpine and peri-Alpine valleys, with outposts in and around the Carpathians and the Dinarides.  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 471; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Ozenda, 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992: 332; Grass, 1993: 47-48, 49-50; Sanda y al., 1998: 223; Seliskar, 1998: 9).');
    'Brush of fast, fluctuating, stony or gravelly rivers of the boreal mountains, with [Myricaria germanica], [Salix nigricans] ([Salix myrsinifolia]), [Salix phylicifolia], [Salix borealis], [Salix daphnoides], sometimes with [Hippophae rhamnoides], and [Rhacomitrium canescens].', '(Yon and Tendron, 1981; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.5.1.2; Påhlsson, 1994: units 7.2.1.2, 7.2.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Riverine brush of mountain streams of the Himalayan system, with [Salix spp.], [Betula utilis], [Myricaria germanica] and [Hippophae rhamnoides].', '(Schweinfurth, 1957; Walter, 1974: 283; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 360).');
    'Riverside brush of mountain streams and rivers originating in the Pontic Range and Caucasus system with [Salix spp.] and [Hippophae rhamnoides].', '(Zohary, 1973: 377; Walter, 1974: 403).');
