    'Willow-dominated scrub of banks and shoals of rivers of the steppe, wooded steppe, cold semidesert and desert zones of Eurasia and of their associated steppic or desert mountain ranges, in particular, of the Pannonic basin, of the Ponto-Sarmatic steppes, of the Central Eurasian and East Asian steppes, deserts and semideserts, of the Irano-Anatolian steppes and their mediterranean or desert transitions.', '(Zohary, 1973; Walter, 1974; Soo, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 125, 126, 292; Grass, 1993; Sanda y al., 1998).');
    'Willow-dominated scrub of banks and shoals of rivers of the Pannonic plain,  with [Salix purpurea] ssp. [lambertiana], [Salix triandra], [Salix viminalis].  ', '(Soo, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda y al., 1998: 222; Grass, 1993: 55-56).');
    'Willow-dominated scrub of banks and shoals of rivers of the Pontic and Sarmatic steppes and wooded steppes of southern Eastern Europe, in particular, of the lower Danube, the lower Prut, the lower Dniestr, the lower Dniepr basin, the lower and middle Don and Donetz system, the lower Volga basin, the Kouma and Terek basins, with [Salix triandra], [Salix cinerea], [Salix daphnoides] var. [acutifolia] ([Salix acutifolia]), shrubby [Salix alba], [Salix amygdalina], [Salix gmelini], [Salix purpurea], [Salix australior], and [Hippophae rhamnoides].', '(Walter, 1974: 205, 210, 211; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 125; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 79; Sanda y al., 1992: 136).');
    '[Platanus orientalis] forests of river courses of the submediterranean margin of the Anatolian plateau.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 96; Zohary, 1973: 278-283, 377, 606; Yon and Tendron, 1981).');
    '[Platanus orientalis] formations of streams and gorges of Cyprus, in particular, of the Troodos range.  ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 219-220, 246-247; Zohary, 1973: 154; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 49; Sfikas, 1992: 280).');
    '[Platanus orientalis] forests of river courses of the mediterranean plains and hills of the Levant.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 96; Zohary, 1973: 286-290, 604).');
    '[Platanus orientalis] forests of northern Irak, eastern Turkey, Iran and Afghanistan, in particular, of river gorges of the Kurdo-Zagrosian mountains.', '(Zohary, 1973: 163, 165, 192, 377, 606).');
    'Riverine forests dominated by the Tertiary relict [Liquidambar orientalis], with a very limited range in southern Asia Minor and Rhodes.', '(Davis, 1972; Zohary, 1973; Yon and Tendron, 1981).  ');
    '[Liquidambar orientalis] gallery forest of the Petaloudhes Valley of Rhodes, with poorly developed undergrowth and a ground layer dominated by [Adiantum capillus-veneris] in damp areas. This forest constitutes the only European formation of this species and harbours a unique, concentrated, aggregation of Jersey Tiger Moths, [Panaxia quadripunctaria].', '(Rechinger, 1951; Sfikas, 1984; Petanidou y al., 1991).');
    'Riverine forests of [Liquidambar orientalis] of Caria, Lycia, Pisidia and Pamphylia, including the extensive forest of the alluvial plain of Lake K¿ycegiz and of the river Dalaman in which [Liquidambar orientalis] is associated with [Alnus orientalis], [Platanus orientalis], [Ulmus spp.], [Smilax excelsa], [Periploca graeca], [Vitis vinifera]. ', '(Davis, 1972; Zohary, 1973; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 50; Noirfalise, 1987).');
    'Tamarisk, oleander, chaste tree galleries and thickets and similar low ligneous formations of permanent or temporary streams and wetlands of the thermo-Mediterranean zone and southwestern Iberia, and of the most hygromorphic locations within the Saharo-Mediterranean and Saharo-Sindian zones. ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Debazac and Mavrommatis, 1971; Lavagne and Moutte, 1971; Herbauts, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1974a; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Peinado y al., 1983; White, 1983; Géhu, 1984a; Izco y al., 1984; Veri and Pacioni, 1985; Chiappini, 1985a, 1985b; Ladero Alvarez, 1987).');
    'Thickets and galleries of [Nerium oleander], [Vitex agnus-castus] or [Tamarix spp.] of the southern parts of the Palaearctic domaine. ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Debazac and Mavrommatis, 1971; Lavagne and Moutte, 1971; Herbauts, 1973: 326; Horvat y al., 1974: 96; Yon and Tendron, 1981; White, 1983; Géhu, 1984a; Izco y al., 1984; Veri and Pacioni, 1985; Chiappini, 1985a, 1985b).');
    '[Nerium oleander] cordons and screens, often with [Tamarix spp.], [Vitex agnus-castus], [Dittrichia viscosa], [Saccharum ravennae], [Arundo donax], [Rubus ulmifolius], most typical of temporary water courses, but also lining small and sometimes large rivers, marking springs and areas of high water table in southern and eastern Iberia, very locally in eastern Provence, Liguria and Corsica (Saint-Florent), in southern Italy, Sardinia and Sicily, in southern and western Greece, the Aegean and Ionian archipelagoes, in Crete, in Albania, in the eastern Mediterranean, in North Africa, including northern Saharan regions, and in Mesopotamia. They are particularly abundant in the south and east of Iberia, in Sicily, in the Aegean and eastern Mediterranean region and in North Africa. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 217-219; Rechinger, 1951; Debazac and Mavrommatis, 1971; Lavagne and Moutte, 1971; Knapp, 1973: 487; Horvat y al., 1974: 94, 173, 203-204; Davis, 1978; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 46, 48, 49, 51; Pignatti, 1982; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; White, 1983: 219; Sfikas, 1984; Izco y al., 1984; Fenaroli, 1984; Gamisans, 1985; Pratesi and Tassi, 1985; Veri and Pacioni, 1985; Chiappini, 1985a, 1985b; Costa, 1987; Alcaraz Ariza and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Ferioli, 1989; Turland y al., 1993: 6; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 17; Hoda y al., 1998: 14).');
    '[Vitex agnus-castus] formations of temporary water courses and other humid sites within, mostly, the thermo-Mediterranean zone. They occur, though uncommonly, in Mediterranean southern and eastern Spain and in the Balearics; they are local and rare in eastern Provence, the Tyrrhenian coast of Italy, Puglia, the gulf of Taranto, Corsica, Sardinia, Sicily and the Maltese Islands. They are frequent in Greece, particularly along the Ionian coasts, where they can constitute dense thickets, uncommon again in the Aegean archipelagoes and Crete. They extend to the southern Balkans, Crimea, Mediterranean Asia Minor, Anatolia and North Africa, including the northern Saharan regions.', '(Holmboe, 1914: 219; Rechinger, 1951; Quézel and Santa, 1962; Debazac and Mavrommatis, 1971; Lavagne and Moutte, 1971; Zohary, 1973; Knapp, 1973: 487; Horvat y al., 1974: 94, 173; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 49, 51; Pignatti, 1982; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; White, 1983: 219; Izco y al., 1984; Sfikas, 1984; Gamisans, 1985; Chiappini, 1985a, 1985b; Lanfranco, 1989: 29; Turland y al., 1993: 6, 11; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 17; Hoda y al., 1998: 14).');
    'Lower and upper meso-Mediterranean [Quercus ilex] forests of Sardinia with [Viburnum tinus], [Phillyrea angustifolia], [Phillyrea latifolia], [Rhamnus alaternus], [Arbutus unedo], [Erica arborea], [Ruscus aculeatus], [Crataegus monogyna], [Rubia peregrina], [Smilax aspera], [Clematis flammula], [Clematis cirrhosa], [Clematis vitalba], [Rosa sempervirens], [Tamus communis], [Rubus ulmifolius], [Cyclamen repandum], [Carex hallerana], [Carex distachya], [Luzula forsteri], [Hedera helix], [Lonicera implexa] and [Pistacia lentiscus] in more thermo-Mediterranean areas. Extensive, fully developed, mature stands survive in particular in the hinterland of the Golfo di Orosei, around Mount Gennargentu, in the Barbagia, the Iglesiente, the Sarrabus, the Catena di Margine, on Monte Albo. They occupy a wide altitudinal range, grading at the upper limit into the more sub-Mediterranean formations of unit 45.32.', '(Pignatti, 1998: 417-421, 628).');
    '[Quercus ilex]-dominated formations of Tyrrhenian and Adriatic coastal areas of the northern half of the Italian peninsula with [Phillyrea media], [Phillyrea angustifolia], [Viburnum tinus], [Ruscus aculeatus], [Daphne gnidium], [Fraxinus ornus], [Rosa sempervirens], [Lonicera implexa], [Rubia peregrina], [Smilax aspera], [Myrtus communis], [Clematis flammula], [Tamus communis], [Carex olbiensis], [Luzula forsteri], [Cyclamen repandum] and often an admixture of [Quercus suber] or of the deciduous [Quercus pubescens] and [Quercus cerris]; at higher altitude they take on a more montane character with a greater prevalence of sub-Mediterranean elements. Although these formations are, like most other continental holm-oak communities, mostly degraded to arborescent matorral or coppice, fully developed forests subsist very locally, in particular in Toscany and Latium and, to a lesser extent, in Veneto and Emilia-Romagna.  ', '(Fenaroli, 1970; Tomaselli, 1970; Groppali y al., 1980; Poldini, 1989: 264; Pignatti, 1998: 411-416, 628).');
    '[Quercus ilex]-dominated forests and woods of the Adriatic coast of the Balkan peninsula, restricted to the Dalmatian archipelago and to a narrow coastal belt of the mainland extending from the gulf of Sarand¿ to Istria, with [Pistacia terebinthus], [Fraxinus ornus], [Coronilla emerus], [Ostrya carpinifolia], [Carpinus orientalis], [Laurus nobilis], [Viburnum tinus], [Rhamnus alaternus], [Rosa sempervirens], [Lonicera etrusca], [Clematis flammula], [Rubia peregrina], [Smilax aspera], [Vitis vinifera] ssp. [sylvestris], [Cyclamen purpurascens], [Prunus mahaleb], and, in the most thermic stands, [Myrtus communis] and [Juniperus phoenicea]. They are mostly degraded to arborescent matorral or coppice; fully developed forests are recorded very locally in the Dalmatian archipelago, in particular on Rab, Lokrum, Mljet and Brioni.', '(Oberdorfer, 1947; Horvat, 1962; Fenaroli, 1970; Tomaselli, 1970; Horvat y al., 1974: 132-133; Polunin, 1980; Groppali y al., 1980; Poldini, 1989: 264; Prpic, 1996: 66-67; Hoda y al., 1998: 13-14; Seliskar, 1998: 1).');
    'Mostly upper meso-Mediterranean [Quercus ilex]-dominated formations of Calabria and Sicily with [Viola alba] ssp. [dehnhardtii], [Teucrium siculum], [Carex distachya], [Cyclamen repandum], [Pyrus amygdaliformis], [Ruscus aculeatus], [Cytisus villosus], [Asparagus acutifolius], [Rubia peregrina], [Asplenium onopteris], [Luzula forsteri], [Lonicera etrusca], [Smilax aspera], [Rosa sempervirens] and, in some facies, [Chamaerops humilis], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Phillyrea media], [Arbutus unedo]; like the preceding formations, they are usually degraded to arborescent matorral or coppice, but fine stands survive locally, particularly in Sicily, Puglia (e.g. Bosco delle Pianelle) and Calabria (e.g. Boschi di Badolato).', '(Pignatti, 1998: 421-422, 629).');
    'Relictual pockets of [Quercus ilex] woodland of Pantelleria and the Maltese Islands.  
', '(Brullo y al., 1977; Lanfranco, 1999a; Schembri, 1999b).');
    'Relictual, mostly degraded pockets of acidophilous [Quercus ilex] woodland of Pantelleria.  ', '(Brullo y al., 1977; Pignatti, 1998: 417-421, 628).');
    '[Quercus ilex] woodland of the Maltese Islands, formerly widespread in all islands, now almost extinct in forest form, represented by small copses of old trees in four localities, all on the main island.', '(Lanfranco, 1989: 10; Lanfranco, 1999a; Schembri, 1999b).');
    '[Quercus ilex]-dominated formations of peninsular Greece and the Ionian and Aegean archipelagoes, with the exception of those of Crete; associated with [Quercus ilex] are [Quercus coccifera], [Arbutus andrachne], [Arbutus unedo], [Phillyrea latifolia], [Pistacia terebinthus], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Olea europaea], [Juniperus oxycedrus]; arborescent matorrals (unit 32.1) occur throughout the area, though much less commonly than in the western Mediterranean; reasonably extensive, fully developed, mature forest stands do not appear to remain.  ', NULL);
    'Uncommon [Quercus ilex] formations of Crete; small stands of arborescent matorral (unit 32.1), in which [Quercus ilex] may be associated with [Quercus coccifera] or [Quercus brachyphylla], occur sporadically, particularly on rocky slopes; orchard-like groves of old [Quercus ilex], [Quercus brachyphylla] and cultivated [Olea europaea] exist in the extreme west of the island; heavily grazed, they may be more akin to dehesa (unit 84.5) than to forest.  ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974; Sfikas, 1978; Polunin, 1980; Quézel, 1981b; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Turland y al., 1993: 5; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 16).');
    '[Quercus ilex] forests of the supra-mediterranean levels of northwestern Mediterranean and Adriatic hills and mountains, often mixed with deciduous oaks, [Acer spp.] or [Ostrya carpinifolia].  ', '(Archiloque y al., 1969; Fenaroli, 1970; Tomaselli, 1970; Ozenda, 1975, 1981; Lambinon y al., 1978; Groppali y al., 1980, 1981, 1983; Chiappini, 1985a, 1985b; Dupias, 1985; Veri and Pacioni, 1985; Gamisans, 1985; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Barneschi, 1988; Baudière y al., 1988).');
    'Dwarf shrub hummock communities of nemoral Europe and of the lowland and hill bogs of boreal Europe, west to Fennoscandia and the Baltic States, dominated by, or rich in, [Betula nana]. In nemoral Europe they are limited to isolated enclaves on hills of the Germano-Baltic plains and to rare stations within the greater Hercynian ranges and the Alps, where they represent relict outposts of the communities of unit 51.17, with which they share, in particular, besides [Betula nana], [Vaccinium microcarpus], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Chamaedaphne calyculata].', '(Sjörs, 1983: 80-81; Moravec y al., 1983: 45; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.1.1, 3.2.1.3, [p.]; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 93; Ellenberg, 1988: 337; Balevicius, 1992: 174-175; Steiner, 1993: 168-169; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.2.2, 3.1.2.3, [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Dwarf shrub hummock communities of subcontinental and continental, lowland or low montane boreal and boreonemoral Europe dominated by, or rich in, [Rubus chamaemorus], associated with [Calluna vulgaris] or with [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Ledum palustre], [Chamaedaphne calyculata], characteristic, in particular, of eastern Fennoscandia, the southeastern and eastern Baltic regions, Russia, with outposts in the eastern Hercynian ranges, in the Giant Mountains.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 114; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: Table 14, 99-100; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 53; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116, 117; Moravec y al., 1983: 45; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.1.1, 3.2.1.3, 3.2.1.2, [p.]; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 93; Ellenberg, 1988: 338; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 72-74; Pott, 1992: 191; Kruszelnicki and Fabiszewski, 1993: 93; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.2.2, 3.1.2.3, 3.1.2.4, [p.]; Slavik, 1998: 40).');
    'Shrub hummocks dominated by [Chamaedaphne calyculata], main shrub hummock type of the continental parts of the boreal and boreonemoral Palaearctic, in European Russia, Siberia, the Russian Far East, with outposts in Baltic regions and the eastern Hercynian ranges.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 114; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116, 118, 126, 127; Moravec y al., 1983: 45; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 93; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 72-74; Pott, 1992: 191).');
    '[Scirpus cespitosus]-dominated bogs or parts of bogs, mostly characteristic of the subalpine level of Hercynian, pre-Alpine and Alpine ranges.  ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 71; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 118c; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: Table 14, 99-100; Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 89; Moravec y al., 1983: 45; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 74; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 274-279, 287-288; Pott, 1992: 194; Steiner, 1993: 169, 173-175; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.2 [p.]; Schubert y al., 1995: 252).');
    'Bogs or parts of bogs dominated by [Erica tetralix] and [Sphagnum papillosum], characteristic of raised bog systems of Atlantic regions, particularly the British Isles, the low countries, northwestern Germany.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 70-71, 73; Vanden Berghen, 1951a: 172-184; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 74; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M18 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 192-193; Drachenfels, 1994: units 6.1.3, 6.4).');
    'Bogs or parts of bogs overwhelmingly dominated by [Eriophorum vaginatum], with a strongly impoverished species cortŠge, in particular, with very few sphagna, characteristic of degraded and, in particular, grazed, bog systems of Atlantic regions, notably of the Pennines.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 70, 112; Pearsall, 1971: 154; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M20 [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.3.3).');
    'Temporarily or permanently rainwater-filled depressions of bogs, occupied by communities similar to those of larger intermediate mires of units 54.5 or 54.6.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 76; Vanden Berghen, 1951a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 329, 334-337; Pearsall, 1971; Dierssen, 1978; Muller, 1978; Pedrotti, 1978; Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 87-88; Walter, 1979; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983: 82-83; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.3, 3.2.4.1 [p.], 5.1.2.2a [p.]; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Mollet y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Bellamy, 1986; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Rieley and Page, 1990: 111-112; Rodwell, 1991b: units M1 [p.], M2 [p.], M3 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 192; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 221-226; Julve, 1993: 108-109; Robbe, 1993: 55; Steiner, 1993: 131-136; Påhlsson, 1994: 210-214, units 3.1.4, 5.1.2.2a, [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: units 6.1, 6.2, [p.]).');
    'Constantly submerged hollows carpeted by floating or bottom-hugging mats of often bright green sphagna, in particular, [Sphagnum cuspidatum], [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum majus] ([Sphagnum dusenii]), [Sphagnum balticum], sometimes accompanied by bryopsid mosses, in particular, [Drepanocladus fluitans], [Lophozia inflata], and with a vascular cortŠge that may typically be dominated by [Rhynchospora alba], [Scheuchzeria palustris], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Menyanthes trifoliata] or [Carex limosa], and include [Carex paupercula], [Carex pauciflora], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Andromeda polifolia].', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 76; Vanden Berghen, 1951a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 334; Pearsall, 1971; Dierssen, 1978; Muller, 1978; Pedrotti, 1978; Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 87-88; Walter, 1979; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983: 82-83; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Mollet y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Bellamy, 1986; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Rodwell, 1991b: units M1 [p.], M2 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 192; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 221-226; Julve, 1993: 108-109; Robbe, 1993: 55; Steiner, 1993: 131-136; Påhlsson, 1994: 210-214, unit 3.1.4 [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: units 6.1, 6.2, [p.]).');
    'Willow scrub, often dense, lining water courses of western Eurasian nemoral lowlands and hills, including those of the British Isles, of nemoral Western Europe, north to Denmark and nemoral Scandinavia, south to Euro-Siberian Iberia, of Central Europe, within the range of medio-European, Illyrian, Dacian and Getic deciduous forests, north to the Baltic States, south to the lower and middle courses of rivers of the Alpine, northern Dinaric and Carpathian periphery, of Eastern Europe in the upper basin of the Dniepr system, in particular the basins of the Prypiat, the Berezina, the Dniepr, the Desna, the upper basin of the Don and the Khoper, the upper basin of the Volga system, in particular the basins of the Oka, the Tana, the Volga, the Kama, the Bielaia, with [Salix purpurea] ssp. [lambertiana], [Salix triandra], [Salix viminalis], [Salix daphnoides] var [acutifolia] ([Salix acutifolia]). ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 151; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Thill, 1964: 45; Mayer, 1974: 213; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Walter, 1974: 205; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984: unit VIII.2; Bournérias, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.5.1 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 125, 131, 132; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W6c; Korotkov y al., 1991: 272; Pott, 1992: 331; Grass, 1993: 50-52; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.5.1 [p.]; Sanda y al., 1998: 222; Seliskar, 1998: 9).');
    'Willow-dominated riverine scrubs of the Transvolgan, Kazakh, Kurgan, Ichim, Kulunda, Baraba, Barnaul steppe and wooded steppe regions and of the Kazakho-Dsungarian and Turanian semideserts and deserts. A number of species of willows, up to 12-15 in Turanian desert and semidesert areas, notably, [Salix blakii], [Salix wilhelmsiana], [Salix songarica], [Salix australior], [Salix euapiculata], [Salix flavida], [Salix microstacha], [Salix cheilophila], [Salix caspica], [Salix rosmarinifolia] associated with [Hippophae rhamnoides], [Myricaria germanica], [Elaeagnus oxycarpa], [Elaeagnus turkmanica], [Elaeagnus angustifolia], constitute various communities.', '(Walter, 1974: 241, 256).');
    'Willow-dominated riverine scrubs of the steppes and wooded steppes of Transbaikalia, Outer Mongolia, Inner Mongolia, the Songnen Plain of Northeast China, the western Loess Plateau of North China and of the Mongolian and Pamiro-Tibetan semideserts and deserts, with, in particular, [Salix flavida], [Salix microstacha], [Salix cheilophila].', '(Schweinfurth, 1957: 310; Walter, 1974: 224, 286, 308, 315, 319, 327).');
    'Willow-dominated scrub of banks and shoals of rivers of the steppes of the Anatolian Plateau, of the Koura basin of Transcaucasia, of the Hyrcanian lowlands, of the Iranian Plateau and of northern Mesopotamia, and of their mediterranean or desert transitions.', '(Zohary, 1973: 127, 297, 606, 607; Walter, 1974: 403).');
    'Willow thickets of the boreal and boreonemoral regions of Fennoscandia, the Baltic States, Belarus, Russia, northern China, Korea and Japan, dominated, in particular, by [Salix triandra], [Salix daphnoides], [Salix viminalis], [Salix pentandra], [Salix cinerea], [Salix phylicifolia], [Salix glauca], [Salix myrsinifolia], colonizing sands, gravels or silts of the banks of torrents, larger rivers, lakes and reservoirs at low or middle altitudes.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 2.2.5.1 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 126, 485; Påhlsson, 1994: 2.2.5.1 [p.]).');
    'Linear shrubby willow ([Salix spp.]) formations of river banks in plains, hills and low mountains of the Far Eastern nemoral and warm-temperate regions of the Palaearctic domaine, within the eastern Chinese, Korean and Japanese ranges of broad-leaved deciduous, mixed broad-leaved deciduous and evergreen, and temperate broad-leaved evergreen forests.', NULL);
