    'Bog hollows dominated by [Sphagnum cuspidatum], characteristic of Atlantic and sub-Atlantic Western and Central Europe, of Baltic regions, of southern Fennoscandia; associates include [Sphagnum balticum] in Fennoscandia and Baltic regions, [Sphagnum recurvum] in more Atlantic regions.', '(Ilomets, 1974: 195, 196; Dierssen, 1978: 417; Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 88; Botch and Masing, 1983: 117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.3.3; Ellenberg, 1988: 334; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 167; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M2 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 175-176, 192; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 226-227; Julve, 1993: 108-109; Steiner, 1993: 131-136; Påhlsson, 1994: 210-214, unit 3.1.4.3 [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: units 6.1, 6.2, [p.]; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Bog hollows dominated by [Sphagnum majus] ([Sphagnum dusenii]), particularly characteristic of Fennoscandia and boreal Eastern Europe, also locally prominent in Central Europe; associates include, in particular, [Sphagnum balticum].', '(Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 87-88; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116-117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.3.4; Ellenberg, 1988: 334; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 207-210; Pott, 1992: 175, 192; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 227; Steiner, 1993: 131-136; Påhlsson, 1994: 210-214, unit 3.1.4.4 [p.]).');
    'Bog hollows dominated by [Sphagnum auriculatum], characteristic of Atlantic regions, in particular, of the British Isles, western Scandinavia, Lower Saxony, also recorded from the Alps; associates include [Sphagnum subsecundum] ssp. [inundatum] and the bright orange-yellow [Sphagnum pulchrum].', '(Dierssen, 1978: 417; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 151; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M1 [p.]; Steiner, 1993: 131-136; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.1 [p.]).');
    'Bog hollows dominated by [Sphagnum balticum], characteristic of subcontinental and continental regions of the boreal western Palaearctic, from northeastern Sweden and Finland to western Siberia, and of Baltic regions; associates include [Sphagnum lindbergii], [Sphagnum majus], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum magellanicum].', '(Ilomets, 1974: 191, 195; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116, 120; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.3.1; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 198; Påhlsson, 1994: 210-214, unit 3.1.4.1; Drachenfels, 1994: units 6.1, 6.2, [p.]).');
    'Bog hollows dominated by [Sphagnum lindbergii] or, in eastern regions, by the very similar [Sphagnum lenense], characteristic of continental and eastern regions of the boreal and subarctic zones of the Palaearctic, from the White Sea area to the Far East, with outposts in the Alps and the Bohemian quadrangle; associates include [Sphagnum balticum] and  [Sphagnum papillosum].', '(Dierssen, 1978: 417; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116, 120-121; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 218, 219; Steiner, 1993: 131-136).');
    'Bog hollows dominated by [Sphagnum jensenii], characteristic, in particular, of bogs of boreal Russia, within the northeast European bog province; associates include, in particular, [Sphagnum majus].', '(Ilomets, 1974: 192; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 206).');
    'Bog hollows dominated by [Sphagnum angustifolium], characteristic of subcontinental bogs, in particular, of bogs of the great Hercynian ranges and of the Alps.', '(Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 88; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Julve, 1993: 108-109; Steiner, 1993: 131-136).');
    'Bog hollows dominated by usually small cushions of [Sphagnum tenellum], recorded from bogs of southern Fennoscandia, of the Baltic lands, of the Alpine periphery; associates include, in particular, [Sphagnum cuspidatum].', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.3.2 [p.]; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28, 226; Pott, 1992: 192; Julve, 1993: 108-109; Steiner, 1993: 131-136; Påhlsson, 1994: 210-214, unit 3.1.4.2 [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.2 [p.]; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Temporarily inundated shallow hollows, usually dominated by an often sparse cover of [Rhynchospora alba], with [Rhynchospora fusca], [Scheuchzeria palustris], [Drosera intermedia], [Lycopodiella inundata], sometimes dominated by [Eriophorum angustifolium] or [Eriophorum vaginatum], with a ground cover almost devoid of sphagna and often reduced to algae, in particular, the conjugate [Zygogonium ericetorum].   ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 76; Vanden Berghen, 1951a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 335-337; Pearsall, 1971; Dierssen, 1978; Muller, 1978; Pedrotti, 1978; Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 87-88; Walter, 1979; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983: 82-83; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.4.1, 5.1.2.2a [p.]; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Mollet y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Bellamy, 1986; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Rodwell, 1991b: units M1 [p.], M3 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 192; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 221-226; Julve, 1993: 108-109; Robbe, 1993: 55; Steiner, 1993: 131-136; Påhlsson, 1994: 210-214, units 3.1.4.5, 5.1.2.2a [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: units 6.1, 6.2, [p.]; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Larger, deep, permanently filled depressions, usually distrophic, occurring near the centre of raised bogs or along tension lines. Their planctonic communities are original. Floating plant communities may sometimes develop, in particular those comprising [Sparganium minimum] and [Utricularia spp.] (unit 22.45) and, sometimes, beds of [Nymphaea spp.] (unit 22.4311). ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Pearsall, 1971; Walter, 1979; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994: 201-214).');
    'Large pools or lakes occurring near the centre of central European raised bogs, often with relatively firm, steep banks colonized by trees or scrub forming a ring of woodland. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Pearsall, 1971; Mäemets, 1974: 40-42; Walter, 1979; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994: 201-214).');
    'Arborescent galleries of tall [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis], [Salix x rubens], [Populus nigra] and sometimes [Populus alba], lining lowland, hill or submontane rivers of nemoral and boreonemoral Eastern Europe and of eastern and southeastern Central Europe, including eastern Germany, the Baltic States, Poland, the Czech Repubic, Slovakia, the nemoral parts of Danubian and Balkan states, nemoral Belarus, the Ukraine and Russia, east to Bashkiria. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 373-374; Moravec y al., 1983: 71; Matuszkiewicz, 1981b; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 99, 202; Ellenberg, 1988: 259-260; Schubert and Vent, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991: 272; Sanda y al., 1998: 220-221; Seliskar, 1998: 9).');
    'Arborescent willow formations bordering watercourses of mediterranean regions of western Eurasia, willow-dominated belt or facies of the poplar-ash-elm forests. ', '(Maire, 1961; Knapp, 1973; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Rivas-Martinez, 1975c; Lopez, 1976; Francalancia and Orsomando, 1980; Pedrotti, 1980; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Ozenda, 1985; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Alcaraz Ariza and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Martinez Parras y al., 1987; Vigo and Ninot, 1987; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Ladero Alvarez, 1987; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1987; Rallo and Pandolfi, 1988).');
    'Riparian forests of the Mediterranean basin dominated by [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis] or their relatives.  ', '(Maire, 1961; Knapp, 1973; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Lopez, 1976; Francalancia and Orsomando, 1980; Pedrotti, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Pignatti, 1982; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987).');
    'Arborescent willow galleries dominated by [Salix neotricha] accompanied by [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis], [Populus nigra] and sometimes [Populus alba], [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Frangula alnus], [Sambucus nigra], [Ulmus spp.], forming as the ligneous vegetation closest to the water along the middle and lower course of large rivers of little seasonal amplitude in the meso- and supra-Mediterranean foothills of the Cantabrian Cordillera, the Iberian Range and neighbouring regions.  ', '(Lopez, 1976; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 46; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987). ');
    '[Salix alba]-, [Salix fragilis]- or [Salix x rubens]-dominated facies of Mediterranean riverine poplar-ash-elm forests developed along rivers of lowland Iberia, southern France, Italy, Dalmatia, Albania, the F.Y.R. of Macedonia, Greece, the Mediterranean islands, Cyprus and Mediterranean Asia Minor; the accompanying cortŠge does not differ from that of poplar- or ash-dominated facies. ', '(Holmboe, 1914: 58; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974: 174, 203, 204; Francalancia and Orsomando, 1980; Pedrotti, 1980; Pignatti, 1982; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Lanfranco, 1989: 9; Sfikas, 1992: 284; Hoda y al., 1998: 17; Lanfranco, 1999a).');
    '[Salix alba]-dominated facies of Mediterranean riverine poplar-ash-elm forests of the Maghreb, mostly limited to the northern Maghreb, locally occurring south to the Great Atlas.', '(Maire, 1961; Knapp, 1973: 481).');
    'Woods of arborescent willows, physiognomically dominated by [Salix atrocinerea] or [Salix cinerea], forming, in thermo-, meso- or supra-Mediterranean areas, on the banks of slow water courses; similar woods occupy soggy depressions (unit 44.92).  
', '(Rivas-Martinez, 1975c; Sfikas, 1978; Bolos, 1979; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Pignatti, 1982; Chiappini, 1985b; Navarro Andres and Valle Gutierrez, 1987; Asensi Marfil and Diez Garretas, 1987; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Ladero Alvarez, 1987; Rallo and Pandolfi, 1988).');
    'Riparian woods of [Salix atrocinerea] of central and eastern Iberia, with [Salix neotricha], [Salix salvifolia], [Frangula alnus], [Populus tremula], [Fraxinus angustifolia] and many lianas and brambles ([Rubus spp.]).  ', NULL);
    'Riparian woods formed almost exclusively by [Salix atrocinerea], with a few [Fraxinus angustifolia], numerous lianas and brambles ([Rubus spp.]) and an abundance of [Thelypteris palustris] in the undergrowth, characteristic of the southwestern Iberian peninsula.  ', NULL);
    'Riparian woods of [Salix atrocinerea] of Sardinia.  ', NULL);
    'Riparian woods of [Salix cinerea] of Italy and Greece.  ', NULL);
    'Riverine woods formed by [Salix cinerea] in the Middle Atlas, by [Salix atrocinerea] in Krumiria, northern Algeria, the northern Gharb and the Rif, by [Salix catalaunica] in the Rif, by [Salix jahandiezii] in the Middle and High Atlas.', '(Maire, 1961).');
    'Riparian communities forming mostly in ravines and gullies within the laurel forest belt of the Canary Islands and characterized by the presence of the tall endemic, [Salix canariensis]. The best preserved are found in the barranco de Los Cernicalos of Gran Canaria, in the caldera de Taburiente of La Palma and in the barranco del Infierne of Tenerife. ', '(Knapp, 1973: 576; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988).');
    'Willow-dominated riverine woods of the steppe, wooded steppe, cold semidesert and desert zones of Eurasia and of their associated steppic and desert mountain ranges.', '(Zohary, 1973; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix spp.], including [Tamarix smyrnensis] ([Tamarix pallasii], [Tamarix ramossissima] [auct.]), [Tamarix tetrandra], [Tamarix octandra] [i.a.], associated with river banks, wet areas and coastal localities of the Irano-Turanian floristic region and its irradiation areas within the steppe and cold desert zones of Eurasia, in particular, of the Pontic basin, of Central Eurasia, of East Asia, of Inner Anatolia, northern Iran and Afghanistan, of northern Mesopotamia.  ', '(Schiman-Czeika, 1964; Davis, 1967; Zohary, 1973; Walter, 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 51; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Walter and Breckle, 1991c; Andreev y al., 1992; Sanda y al., 1992).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix smyrnensis] ([Tamarix ramossissima] [auct.]), of stream sides and coastal localities of the Pontic steppe region of western Eurasia.', '(Walter, 1974; Sanda y al., 1980; Andreev y al., 1992; Sanda y al., 1992).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix smyrnensis] and/or [Tamarix tetrandra] on weakly saline sands of fresh water steppe streamsides of the western Pontic region, including river systems such as those of the lower Danube and the Maritza-Tunja basins.', '(Simon and Dihoru, 1963; Sanda y al., 1980; Andreev y al., 1992; Sanda y al., 1992: 136-137).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix smyrnensis] and/or [Tamarix tetrandra] on weakly saline sands of fresh water steppe streamsides of the western Pontic region, including the lower Danube basin, the Danube delta, the Maritza-Tunja basins and watercourses of the northeastern Tracian plain.', '(Simon and Dihoru, 1963; Sanda y al., 1980; Andreev y al., 1992).');
    '[Tamarix smyrnensis] stands occupying weakly saline sands of fresh water steppe streamsides of the lower Danube basin and the Danube delta, in Muntenia, Oltenia and Dobrogea, with much [Calamagrostis epigejos] and other herbs, including [Cynodon dactylon], [Agrostis stolonifera], [Cynanchum acutum].', '(Simon and Dihoru, 1963; Sanda y al., 1980; Sanda y al., 1992: 136-137, 369-370).');
    'Shrub communities of [Tamarix smyrnensis], [Tamarix ramosissima] and/or [Tamarix tetrandra] occupying weakly saline marine sand dunes of western Black Sea coastal areas.

', '(Sanda y al., 1980; Andreev y al., 1992).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix smyrnensis] ([Tamarix ramossissima] [auct.]), of stream sides and coastal localities of the northern and eastern Black Sea lowlands, within the range of central and eastern Pontic steppes.', '(Walter, 1974: 200, 365).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix spp.], including [Tamarix smyrnensis] ([Tamarix pallasii], [Tamarix ramossissima] [auct.]), [Tamarix tetrandra], [Tamarix octandra] [i.a.], of stream sides, wetlands and coastal localities of the Irano-Anatolian region.', '(Schiman-Czeika, 1964; Davis, 1967; Zohary, 1973: 385-386, 607; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 51; Walter and Breckle, 1991c).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix smyrnensis], [Tamarix tetrandra], [Tamarix octandra], [Tamarix hampeana] of fresh water stream sides and wetlands of Anatolia.', '(Schiman-Czeika, 1964; Davis, 1967; Zohary, 1973; Yon and Tendron, 1981: 51).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix spp.], including [Tamarix smyrnensis], [Tamarix octandra i.a.], of saline sites of Anatolia.', '(Schiman-Czeika, 1964; Davis, 1967; Zohary, 1973).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix spp.], in particular [Tamarix smyrnensis] ([Tamarix pallasii], [Tamarix ramossissima] [auct.]), of stream sides, wadis and wetlands of the Mesopotamian steppe region of southeastern Turkey, interior Syria, northwestern Irak and extreme eastern Iran.', '(Schiman-Czeika, 1964; Zohary, 1973: map 7-19, 606).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix spp.], including about 15 species, among them [Tamarix smyrnensis] ([Tamarix pallasii], [Tamarix ramossissima] [auct.]), [Tamarix laxa], [Tamarix hispida], of streamsides, wadis and wetlands of the Transvolgan, Kazakh, Kurgan, Ichim, Kulunda, Baraba, Barnaul steppe and wooded steppe regions and of the Kazakho-Dsungarian and Turanian semideserts and deserts, in particular, of the Kyzyl-Kum and Kara-Kum deserts.', '(Walter, 1974: 241, 244, 256; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 221; Walter and Breckle, 1991c).');
    'Formations of [Tamarix spp.], including [Tamarix smyrnensis] ([Tamarix pallasii], [Tamarix ramossissima] [auct.]), [Tamarix laxa], [Tamarix hispida], of streamsides, wadis and wetlands of the steppes of Transbaikalia, Outer Mongolia, Inner Mongolia, the Songnen Plain of Northeast China, the western Loess Plateau of North China, of the deserts and subdeserts of the Mongolian and Tibetan regions.

 

', '(Walter, 1974: 304-308, 310, 316; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 221, 309).');
    'Forests or thickets of [Tamarix spp.] forming in wadis of the subtropical deserts of the Palaearctic domaine. They include, in particular, formations of [Tamarix articulata] of the central Sahara, developed in large sandy wadis with a water table within 7 or 8 metres of the surface, sometimes constituting closed, fairly tall, up to 10 metres, riparian forests, otherwise, more open woodland stands or dense 2 to 3 metre tall thickets, with an undergrowth of [Stipagrostis pungens], [Leptadenia pyrotechnica], [Calligonum comosum] and chenopods. They also include [Tamarix gallica] galleries and thickets of wadis of the northern and northwestern Sahara that receive their water supply from the High Atlas or the Saharan Atlas.', '(White, 1983: 219; Ozenda, 1991: 77-78, 344-349; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 91-92).');
    'Forests and woodland of [Quercus rotundifolia] occupying mostly siliceous soils of the meso- and supra-Mediterranean areas of the western Meseta and neighbouring regions under more Atlantic, though generally dry, climates. Well-preserved examples are rare, most of the remaining wooded areas being under dehesa (84.5) regime. ', NULL);
    'Meso-Mediterranean [Quercus rotundifolia] formations widespread on the plains and plateaux of Extremadura, Alentejo and neighbouring regions, and in the Sierra Morena and the Montes de Toledo. It is almost entirely transformed into dehesa. ', NULL);
    'More northern, upper meso-Mediterranean and lower supra-Mediterranean [Quercus rotundifolia] formations, poorer in Mediterranean species, of the western plateaux of Old Castile and adjacent southern Leon and Galicia; [Genista hystrix] is a physiognomically striking element. Also essentially eliminated as forest formations, these woodlands constitute, together with the preceding unit, the basis for the western Iberian dehesa, one of the most characteristic landscapes of the peninsula and an importand habitat of larger fauna. ', NULL);
    '[Quercus rotundifolia] formations of the Cordillera Central, characteristic of cool meso-Mediterranean and sunny supra-Mediterranean slopes of the sierras de Guadarrama, de Gredos, de Bejar, de Ayllon and neighbouring areas; they extend east to siliceous enclaves of the Iberian Range. Adapted to a more continental climate than the two previous units, they are poorer in shrubs and lianas. They often constitute low, open woodland. ', NULL);
    'Summital [Quercus rotundifolia] elfin forests of the high elevations of the Montes de Toledo.  ', NULL);
    'Forests and woodland of [Quercus rotundifolia] developed in the meso- and supra-Mediterranean levels of Baetic mountains and foothills, and neighbouring interior plains. Well-preserved examples are extremely rare. ', NULL);
    'Woodland dominated by [Quercus rotundifolia] with [Juniperus oxycedrus], [Daphne gnidium], [Ruscus aculeatus], [Asparagus acutifolius], [Crataegus monogyna], [Lonicera implexa], [Rubia peregrina], [Paeonia coriacea], [Paeonia broteroi], [Endymion hispanicus] that represents the potential, mature vegetation of a great part of Andalusia, in the Guadalquivir basin, coastal areas and Baetic ranges, on base-rich and often silt-laden soils, under meso-Mediterranean conditions. They have been largely replaced by cultivation and, where they subsist, are often very degraded.  ', NULL);
    'Woodland dominated by [Quercus rotundifolia], with [Quercus faginea], [Acer monspessulanum], [Sorbus aria], [Sorbus aucuparia], [Taxus baccata], [Berberis hispanica], [Crataegus monogyna], [Lonicera arborea], [Daphne laureola], [Rosa spp.], [Polygala boissieri], [Helleborus foetidus] and many orchids, of the supra-Mediterranean level (1400-1900 m) of calcareous Baetic ranges. ', NULL);
    '[Quercus rotundifolia]-dominated woodland characteristic of the meso- and supra-Mediterranean levels of the Sierra Nevada and of a few siliceous mountain ranges of the arid Iberian South-east. Totally destroyed in the Sierra Nevada, this community is still represented by well-preserved examples in the sierras de Carrascoy and Alhamilla, and to a lesser extent, in the Sierra de Cabrera.  ', NULL);
    'Forests and woodland of [Quercus rotundifolia] developed in the thermo-Mediterranean zone of Andalusia and neighbouring areas. Well-preserved examples are extremely rare.  ', NULL);
    '[Quercus rotundifolia] formations of thermo-Mediterranean calcareous slopes of the Quadalquivir basin and the coastal foothills of Baetic and arid southeastern ranges, with [Olea europaea] var. [sylvestris], [Chamaerops humilis], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Smilax aspera], [Asparagus albus], [Rhamnus oleoides], [Quercus coccifera], [Clematis cirrhosa], [Aristolochia baetica], [Bupleurum gibraltarium] and, locally, [Maytenus senegalensis] or [Buxus balearica]. They have almost disappeared in forest form except in a few ranges of the arid Iberian Southeast.', NULL);
    'Formations of [Quercus rotundifolia] with [Myrtus communis], [Pulicaria odora], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Phillyrea angustifolia] and [Arbutus unedo] occupying the siliceous soil of the thermo-Mediterranean levels of eastern Andalusia between the Sea of Alboran and the coastal Tejeda, Almijara, Alpujarra and Gador ranges, a few granitic outcroppings of the Sierra Morena and limited enclaves of the Badajos region. They have almost entirely disappeared.  ', NULL);
    'Thermo-Mediterranean, basophilous forests and woodland of [Quercus rotundifolia] characteristic of the southeastern maritime fa¿ade of the Iberian peninsula in Valencia and Levante, rich in shrubs and lianas, with [Rubia peregrina] ssp. [longifolia], [Osyris quadripartita], [Chamaerops humilis], [Phillyrea angustifolia], [Clematis flammula]. Well-preserved examples survived until recently in, among others, the Sierra del Ave y Cortes de Pallas, in the Pobla Tornesa, in Millares, in Montduver. This community now appears extinct in its full forest form.', NULL);
