    'Relatively large, deep, permanently filled depressions occurring along tension lines of raised bogs.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Pearsall, 1971; Mäemets, 1974: 40-42; Walter, 1979; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994: 201-214).');
    'Paths of water runoff carving the marginal slope of the bog, carrying water from the centre to the lagg. They are in part colonized by intermediate mire or acid fen vegetation of units 54.5 or 54.4. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 108; Vanden Berghen, 1951a: 161, 175; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 213-215; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M21 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 191, 193; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.1.3 [p.]).');
    '[Narthecium ossifragum] colonies in seep rivulets, mostly characteristic of western bogs.  ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 108; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 117; Vanden Berghen, 1951a: 161; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 213-215; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M21 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 191, 193; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.1.3 [p.]; Frankard y al., 1998: 39).');
    '[Myrica gale] thickets of Atlantic raised bog soaks.  ', '(Vanden Berghen, 1951a: 175; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M21 [p.]; Pott, 1992: 191, 193).');
    'Ring of water surrounding raised bogs, often colonized by intermediate mire or acid fen communities of units 54.5 or 54.4, sometimes accompanied by more basicline species typical of neighbouring fens; [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Scirpus hudsonianus], [Carex rostrata], [Carex flava], [Parnassia palustris] are frequent components.  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Walter, 1979; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Parts of raised bogs colonized by shrubs or small trees of [Pinus rotundata], [Pinus sylvestris] var. [turfosa], [Picea abies], [Betula pubescens], [Betula carpatica], eventually leading to bog woods of unit 44.A.  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Brasseur y al., 1978: 45-46; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Succow and Jeschke, 1990).');
    'Communities of the boreoalpine, subalpine, arctoalpine and northern lowland regions of Iceland, Fennoscandia, the Kola peninsula and the Urals formed by hummocks, banks or plateaux of sphagna or of bryopsid mosses associated with small shrubs, particularly [Betula nana], also [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Rubus chamaemorus], accompanied by [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Carex nigra]. They may associate with depressions occupied by lawn, hollow or mud bottom communities; they are prone to a rapid dessication. They show affinities with blanket bogs of unit 52, in particular, with upland blanket bogs of unit 52.2 and northern boreal blanket bogs of unit 52.4. ', '(Walter, 1974: 44, 337-339; Sjörs, 1983: 80-81, 84-85; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.1.1 [p.], 3.2.1.1a, 3.2.1.1b, 3.2.1.1c, 3.2.1.1d; Ellenberg, 1988: 337; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.2.1, 3.1.2.1a, 3.1.2.1b, 3.1.2.1c, 3.1.2.1d).');
    'Communities of the boreoalpine, subalpine and arctoalpine regions of Fennoscandia, the Kola peninsula and the Urals formed by hummocks, banks or plateaux of sphagna dominated by [Sphagnum fuscum], sometimes with abundant lichens [Cladonia alpestris], [Cladonia rangiferina], [Cladonia sylvatica], with small shrubs, especially [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Betula nana], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], often with a presence or abundance of [Eriophorum vaginatum] and a species cortŠge that may include [Andromeda polifolia], [Arctostaphylos alpina], [Ledum palustre], [Loiseleuria procumbens], [Salix glauca], [Vaccinium microcarpus], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Pedicularis lapponica], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex dioica], [Carex rostrata], [Carex vaginata], [Eriophorum angustifolium].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.1.1 [p.], 3.2.1.1a, 3.2.1.1c; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.2.1, 3.1.2.1a, 3.1.2.1c).');
    'Communities of the boreoalpine, subalpine, arctoalpine and northern lowland regions of Iceland, Fennoscandia, the Kola peninsula and the Urals formed by hummocks, banks or plateaux of bryopsid mosses, including an abundance of [Dicranum bergeri], [Hylocomium splendens], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Polytrichum strictum], by small shrubs, especially [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Betula nana], [Vaccinium uliginosum] and, on the continent, [Ledum palustre], [Rubus chamaemorus], sometimes with an abundance of [Carex nigra] and [Eriophorum angustifolium]. The species cortŠge may include [Andromeda polifolia], [Empetrum nigrum], [Potentilla palustris], [Vaccinium microcarpum], [Agrostis canina], [Calamagrostis stricta], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex rariflora], [Carex rostrata], [Festuca rubra] [s.l.], and, in continental communities, [Cornus suecica], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Eriophorum vaginatum].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 77-79, 96; Walter, 1974: 44, 337-339; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.1.1b, 3.2.1.1d; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.1.2.1b, 3.1.2.1d).');
    'Drying, mowed or burned bogs invaded by [Molinia caerulea].  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 118f, 119d; Noirfalise y al., 1980; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.2.2 [p.]; Rodwell, 1991b; Steiner, 1993: 177; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.2.2 [p.]; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 6.5; Riecken y al., 1994: 131; Opermanis y al., 1997: 56; Frankard y al., 1998: 40).');
    'Riverine woods of the Pannonic basin formed by [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis] and often [Populus alba] or [Populus nigra], which may at times dominate, in particular, in Vojvodina.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 292-293; Soo, 1980).');
    'Riverine woods dominated by [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis] and [Populus nigra], of floodplains of rivers of the Pontic and Sarmatic steppes and wooded steppes of southern Eastern Europe, in particular, of the lower Danube, the lower Prut, the lower Dniestr, the lower Dniepr basin, the lower and middle Don and Donetz system, the lower Volga basin, the Kouma and Terek basins.', '(Stojanoff, 1948; Walter, 1974: 196, 205, 209-211; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 125; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 79; Sanda y al., 1992: 136).');
    'Riverine woods dominated by [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis] and [Populus nigra], of the floodplaines, valleys and basins of the lower Danube, its tributaries and delta of southern and eastern Romania, northeastern Bulgaria and Moldova, with [Fraxinus angustifolia], [Fraxinus pennsylvanica], accompanied by [Tamus communis], [Amorpha fruticosa], [Rubus caesius], [Lycopus europaeus], [Lycopus exaltatus], [Polygonum hydropiper].', '(Stojanoff, 1948; Donita and Dihoru, 1961; Donita y al., 1966; Sanda y al., 1980: 113; Bondev, 1991: 143 [p.]; Gastescu and Oltean, 1997; Sanda y al., 1998: 220-221).');
    'Riverine woods dominated by [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis] and [Populus nigra], of floodplaines of the northern Thracian plain of Bulgaria.', '(Bondev, 1991: unit 143 [p.]).');
    'Riverine woods dominated by [Salix alba], [Salix fragilis] and [Populus nigra], of floodplains of the lower Dniestr, the lower Dniepr basin, the lower and middle Don and Donetz system, the lower Volga basin, the Kouma and Terek basins, reaching a width of three kilometres on the lower Dniepr.', '(Stojanoff, 1948; Walter, 1974: 196, 205, 209-211; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 125; Chifu and Mititelu, 1992: 79; Sanda y al., 1992: 136).');
    'Willow-dominated riverine woods of the Transvolgan, Kazakh, Kurgan, Ichim, Kulunda, Baraba, Barnaul steppe and wooded steppe regions and of the Kazakho-Dsungarian and Turanian semideserts and deserts.', '(Walter, 1974: 163, 238, 241, 256; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 182-184, 232; Korotkov y al., 1991).');
    'Willow-dominated riverine woods of the steppes and wooded steppes of Transbaikalia, Outer Mongolia, Inner Mongolia, the Songnen Plain of Northeast China, the western Loess Plateau of North China and of the Mongolian and Pamiro-Tibetan semideserts and deserts.', '(Walter, 1974: 224, 315; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 184, 232; Mei''e y al., 1985: 152-153).');
    'Willow-dominated riverine woods of the steppes, wooded steppes, semideserts and deserts of the Anatolian Plateau, the Koura basin of Transcaucasia, the Hyrcanian lowlands, the Iranian Plateau and northern Mesopotamia, and their mediterranean or desert transitions.', '(Zohary, 1973: 127, 297, 606, 607; Walter, 1974: 403).');
    'Arborescent willow ([Salix spp.]) formations of river banks in plains, hills and low mountains of the Far Eastern nemoral and warm-temperate regions of the Palaearctic domaine, within the eastern Chinese, Korean and Japanese ranges of broad-leaved deciduous, mixed broad-leaved deciduous and evergreen, and temperate broad-leaved evergreen forests.', NULL);
    'Riverside, lakeside and seaside alder, birch or pine galleries and cordons of the boreal, boreonemoral and boreosteppic zones, of the high mountains of the nemoral zone and of their piedmont influence region, dominated by [Alnus incana] along the montane and submontane rivers of the Alps, the Carpathians, the northern Apennines, the Dinarides, the Balkan Range, the Rhodopides and neighbouring regions, by [Alnus incana] or [Alnus glutinosa] in boreal Fennoscandia and northeastern Europe, by [Betula pendula] or [Pinus sylvestris] in western Siberia. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Braun-Blanquet, 1975b; Ozenda, 1981; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Pignatti, 1982; Moravec y al., 1982; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Noirfalise, 1986; Ferioli, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    '[Alnus incana]-dominated formations lining watercourses in mountainous regions of the Alps, the Carpathians, the Dinarides, the Balkan Range, the Rhodopides, the Apennines and the Bohemian Quadrangle.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Braun-Blanquet, 1975b; Ozenda, 1981; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Pignatti, 1982; Moravec y al., 1982; Noirfalise, 1986; Ferioli, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Coldea, 1990, 1991; Andreev y al., 1992).');
    '[Alnus incana] formations of the upper reaches of Alpine, particularly inner Alpine, valleys, with outposts in the Dinarides, replacing, colonizing or fringing the pioneer willow scrubs of the [Salicion eleagni] (unit 44.11).  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974: 471; Braun-Blanquet, 1975b; Ozenda, 1981; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Pignatti, 1982; Noirfalise, 1986; Ferioli, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 91-96; Seliskar, 1998: 1).');
    'Relictual formations of [Alnus incana] of the northern Apennines.', '(Pignatti, 1982; Ozenda, 1985).');
    '[Alnus incana] galleries of the montane rivers of the western and northern Carpathians and of the Hercynian ranges of the Bohemian Quadrangle, best developed in the 400 to 600 metre altitudinal range, ascending to 900 metres.', '(Moravec y al., 1982; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Low, spiny, almost monospecific fringes formed by the Ibero-African shrubby spurge [Securinega tinctoria] on the outer edge of temporary or permanent water courses of great seasonal amplitude in the southwestern quadrant of the Iberian peninsula (Montes de Toledo, Sierra Morena, Extremadura, southwestern Andalusia, southern Portugal). Among the few associated plants, are the lianas [Bryonia cretica], [Tamus communis] and the endemic [Clematis campaniflora]. [Pyrus bourgaeana] may transgress from neighbouring communities.  ', '(Delvosalle and Duvigneaud, 1962; Rivas-Martinez, 1974a; Lopez Gonzalez, 1982; Géhu, 1984a; Ladero Alvarez, 1987: 483).');
    'Supra- and upper meso-Mediterranean riparian galleries of the Montes de Toledo (Cordillera Oretana), constituted by the lauriphyllous [Prunus lusitanica] and [Viburnum tinus]; they line water courses on the inner edge of alder galleries of 44.551 and 44.552, which they sometimes entirely replace.  ', '(Ladero Alvarez, 1987). ');
    'Tall scrub of Montes de Toledo streams, with [Frangula alnus], [Salix atrocinerea], [Salix salvifolia] and [Myrica gale].  ', '(Peinado y al., 1983; Ladero Alvarez, 1987).');
    'Woods and scrubs of marshy ground, waterlogged for most of the year, colonizing fens and marshy or permanently inundated alluvial terraces of rivers of the Palaearctic region. ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Sokolowski, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a; Korotkov y al., 1991; Coldea, 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Steiner, 1992; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Marshy [Alnus glutinosa]-dominated woods and scrubs of the Palaearctic region, usually with shrubby willows in the undergrowth.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Sokolowski, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.2.3.3, 3.3.4.1; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: units W5, W4c [p.]; Korotkov y al., 1991: 273-274; Coldea, 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.4.3; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Mesotrophic and meso-eutrophic [Alnus glutinosa] swamp woods of middle European and western Siberian, nemoral and subboreal, marshy depressions, with [Carex elongata], [Thelypteris palustris], [Dryopteris cristata], [Osmunda regalis], [Solanum dulcamara], [Calystegia sepium], [Ribes nigrum], [Calamagrostis canescens] and often, in acidocline variants, [Betula pubescens]. The constancy of [Carex elongata] is characteristic on the continent, less so in Britain. Tall sedges, [Carex paniculata], [Carex acutiformis], [Carex elata], often dominate the herb layer in the most humid types.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 277-278; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Sokolowski, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.3.3, 3.3.4.1; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W5; Coldea, 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991: 273-274; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Pott, 1992: 345; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.4.3).');
    'Eutrophic and mesotrophic alder woods of Atlantic Europe, distributed in the British Isles, western France, locally, northwestern Germany, poor in [Carex elongata], and harbouring, in particular, [Oenanthe crocata], [Osmunda regalis], [Carex laevigata], [Scutellaria minor]. They include all meso-eutrophic alder swamp woods of the British Isles and western France, as well as the less eutrophic woods of the zone of transition between the main range of this unit and the more continental range of unit 44.9112.', '(Ellenberg, 1988: 277-278; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W5; Pott, 1992: 345). ');
    'Mesotrophic and meso-eutrophic [Alnus glutinosa] swamp woods of sub-Atlantic and subcontinental regions of the European continent characterized in particular by the constant presence of [Carex elongata].  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 277-278; Horvat y al., 1974: 380-383, 471; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Zuttere, 1975: 10; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984: units IX.2.3.1, IX.2.3.2, IX.4; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Oberdorfer, 1990; Coldea, 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991: 273-274; Elias y al., 1991; Steiner, 1992; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 9).');
    'Mesotrophic and meso-eutrophic [Alnus glutinosa] swamp woods of subcontinental and continental regions of eastern Europe, from Mazuria and Masovia east to Bashkiria, often rich in [Carex elongata], [Ribes nigrum], [Sphagnum spp.], [Dryopteris cristata]; in the Sarmatic region, they may occupy extensive areas of nutrient-rich swamps, in particular in the Pripyat area.', '(Yurkevich y al., 1979: 154-155; Matuszkiewicz, 1981b, 1984; Botch and Masing, 1983; Ellenberg, 1988; Korotkov y al., 1991: 273-274; Jahn, 1991: 452, 453).');
    'Forests or woodland of [Quercus rotundifolia] occupying deep soils in the dry thermo-Mediterranean areas of the Balearic islands. Reasonably preserved examples are extremely rare.  ', NULL);
    '[Quercus rotundifolia] ([Quercus ilex] var. [ballota])-dominated forests of North Africa, surviving in forest form only in the sub-humid level of the Rif, of the Atlantic slopes of the Middle Atlas, the High Atlas and the Anti-Atlas, in the Algerian Tell.', '(Quézel and Santa, 1962; Knapp, 1973: 471-472; White, 1983: 150-151; Foucault, 1993b: 268; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 84-85).');
    'Tall, dense [Quercus ilex] forests of the humid level of the Rif and the Middle Atlas, very restricted in extent, rich in bryophytes and lichens and with a very diverse understorey of shrubs climbers and geophytes. Scattered [Acer monspessulanum], [Taxus baccata] and [Sorbus torminalis] may participate in the canopy which is otherwise almost pure.', '(Herbauts, 1973: 349-350; White, 1983: 151; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 82, 84-85). ');
    '[Quercus ilex]-dominated forests of the lower Mediterranean slopes of the Rif and of the Tell, of the Atlantic slopes of the Middle Atlas and of the High Atlas, southward very locally to the western Anti-Atlas. Developed on both siliceous and calcareous substrates in the Rif and the High Atlas, on calcareous soils only in the Middle Atlas, they are less tall and have a sparser, less species-rich understorey. Although subhumid [Quercus ilex]-dominated communities cover much greater areas than the humid formations of UNIT 45.351, and are relatively widespread, they are mostly degraded into arborescent matorrals and true forest stands are rare and limited.', '(Herbauts, 1973: 341-343; White, 1983: 150-151).');
    'Forest or woodland formations dominated by arborescent [Quercus coccifera] ([Quercus "calliprinos"], [Quercus "pseudococcifera"]) or [Quercus alnifolia].  ', '(Oberdorfer, 1947; Rechinger, 1951; Braun-Blanquet y al., 1956;  Horvat, 1962; Zohary, 1973; White, 1983: 152; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Pratesi and Tassi, 1985; Dallman, 1998).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera]-dominated formations of peninsular Greece, of the Ionian and Aegean archipelagoes and of Crete. Extensive, fully-developed stands exist in several areas of Crete. The most representative forests occupy valleys in the 700-800 m range of the southern slopes of the Psiloriti mountains; [Acer orientale], [Cephalanthera cucullata] and [Epipactis cretica] are associated. Other forests are found in the Lefka and Lassithi mountains; [Pyrus amygdaliformis], [Prunus webbii], [Pistacia terebinthus], [Phillyrea latifolia], [Styrax officinalis] are characteristic of various Cretan stands. Outside of Crete, forest stands are found sporadically, in particular on Ikaria, Samothrace and Mount Athos, where [Quercus coccifera] is associated with [Quercus ilex], and at high elevations of Rhodes, where [Quercus coccifera] forms woodland fragments with arborescent [Phillyrea media]. In many areas remnant tall [Quercus coccifera] may form arborescent matorral, as for instance on Ossa; coppice-like formations of young trees also occur.  ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Polunin, 1980: 124; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Turland y al., 1993: 5; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 16; Dallman, 1998: 196).');
    'Very local [Quercus coccifera] formations of Puglia and southern Sicily.  ', '(Pratesi and Tassi, 1985). ');
    'Extremely isolated [Quercus coccifera]-dominated forest of Nazare, Monte de S. Bartolomeu, with [Phillyrea media], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Phillyrea angustifolia], [Arbutus unedo], [Viburnum tinus], [Smilax aspera], [Asplenium onopteris].  ', '(Braun-Blanquet y al., 1956).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera]-dominated formations of the Rif, of the coasts of eastern Algeria and Tunisia and of Cyrenaica.', '(Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Knapp, 1973: 474; White, 1983: 152).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera]-dominated formations of coastal sands and coastal lowlands of eastern Algeria and Tunisia, mostly forming a low, dense, dunal forest, sometimes, however, up to 12 metres tall. Associated with the oak are [Juniperus phoenicea], [Juniperus oxycedrus] ssp. [macrocarpa], [Scrophularia sambucifolia], [Pistacia lentiscus], [Olea europaea], [Phillyrea angustifolia], [Ephedra altissima], [Calicotome villosa].', '(Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Knapp, 1973: 474; White, 1983: 152).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera]-dominated formations of the Rif, of very local occurrence, notably in the mountains above Ciuta, where the oak is accompanied by [Taxus baccata].', '(Gounot and Schoenenberger, 1967; Knapp, 1973: 474; White, 1983: 152).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera] ssp. [calliprinos] formations of the slopes of the Barqa Cyrenaica.', '(Knapp, 1973: 474).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera] ([Quercus calliprinos])-dominated formations of calcareous or ultra basic substrates of Cyprus.', '(Zohary, 1973; Noirfalise, 1987: unit M10; Sfikas, 1992).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera] ([Quercus calliprinos])-dominated forests or steppe-forests of Mediterranean and sub-Mediterranean Anatolia, with [Quercus brachyphylla], [Quercus infectoria], [Arbutus andrachne], [Acer syriacum], [Fontanesia philliraeoides], [Aristolochia altissima], [Cyclamen persicum], [Eryngium falcatum].', '(Zohary, 1973; Noirfalise, 1987: unit M10).');
    'Communities similar to raised bogs, on flat or gently sloping ground with poor surface drainage, in oceanic climates with heavy rainfall. In the strictest sense, blanket bogs are a habitat endemic to northwestern Europe, characteristic of the western and northern British Isles, the Faeroe Islands and the western seaboard of Scandinavia. Extensive bogs developed in similar conditions of mild oceanic climate and high precipitations in Pacific Eurasia share several characteristics with the northwestern European blanket bogs and may be included in this unit. In spite of some lateral water flow, blanket bogs are mostly ombrotrophic. They often cover extensive areas with local topographic features supporting distinct communities. Sphagna ([Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum tenellum], [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum magellanicum], [Sphagnum rubellum], [Sphagnum fuscum]) play an important role in all of them, accompanied by [Narthecium ossifragum], [Molinia caerulea], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Schoenus nigricans], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Calluna vulgaris]. Geographically segregated types, high and low altitude forms and numerous variants can be distinguished. Intact examples of blanket bogs are relatively uncommon.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 67-76; Pearsall, 1971; Pearsall and Pennington, 1977; Ratcliffe, 1977a, 1980; Doyle and Moore, 1978; Dierssen, 1978; Tüxen, 1978; Heal and Smith, 1978; Currie, 1979; Goodwillie, 1980; Condry, 1981; White and Doyle, 1982; Taylor, 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983: 126-127; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 14-15, 460-461; Bellamy, 1986; Ellenberg, 1988; Morrison, 1989: 96-113; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Rieley and Page, 1990: 110, 112-115; Rodwell, 1991b: 21-22; Pankhurst, 1991; Glooschenko y al., 1993: 433; Wilen and Tiner, 1993: 534; Påhlsson, 1994: 210, 211; Archibold, 1995: 320-321, 327, 328).');
    'Hyper-Atlantic blanket bogs of the western coastlands of Ireland, western Scotland and its islands, Cumberland, northern Wales and Devon, developed under very high rainfall climates. The main vascular plants are [Molinia caerulea], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Schoenus nigricans], [Rhynchospora alba], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Carex panicea], [Calluna vulgaris], [Erica tetralix], [Myrica gale], [Pedicularis sylvatica], [Potentilla erecta], [Polygala serpyllifolia], [Pinguicula lusitanica], [Drosera rotundifolia]. The colourful mucinal layer comprises the black and crimson liverwort [Pleurozia purpurea], the black and gold moss [Campylopus atrovirens], the wooly fringe moss [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum]; it is often dominated by sphagna ([Sphagnum auriculatum], [Sphagnum magellanicum], [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum nemoreum], [Sphagnum rubellum], [Sphagnum tenellum], [Sphagnum subnitens]), or, particularly in parts of western Ireland, mucilaginous algal deposits ([Zygogonium]).', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 70, 108; Pearsall, 1971; Ratcliffe, 1977a: 254-255; Doyle and Moore, 1978; Dierssen, 1978; Heal and Smith, 1978; Currie, 1979; Goodwillie, 1980; Condry, 1981; White and Doyle, 1982; Taylor, 1983; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Bellamy, 1986; Morrison, 1989; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Rieley and Page, 1990: 110, 112-115; Rodwell, 1991b: units M17, M1 [p.], M18 [p.], M15 [p.]).');
    'Deep-peat lawn and hummock communities of blanket bog expanses of western Ireland, western Scotland and its islands, the Lake District, northern Wales and Devon, composed of graminoids, ericoid shrubs and sphagna, forming extensive, relatively featureless, fairly flat or gently undulating, tracts with a fine-grained alternation of dominance among species or, on bogs with stronger surface undulations, better defined hummocks.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 70, 108; Pearsall, 1971: 147-151; Ratcliffe, 1977a: 254-255; Doyle and Moore, 1978; Dierssen, 1978; Currie, 1979; Goodwillie, 1980; White and Doyle, 1982; Rodwell, 1991b: units M17, M1 [p.], M18 [p.], M15 [p.]; Pankhurst, 1991: 42-43).');
    'Deep-peat lawn and hummock communities of blanket bog expanses of western Ireland, particularly the Mayo, Galway and Donegal peninsulas, composed of [Erica tetralix], [Calluna vulgaris], [Myrica gale], [Molinia caerulea], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Rhynchospora alba], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Schoenus nigricans], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum magellanicum], with [Drosera rotundifolia], [Drosera anglica], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Pinguicula lusitanica], [Pedicularis sylvatica], [Pleurozia purpurea] and [Zygogonium] algae.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1972: 171-185; Doyle and Moore, 1978: 216-219; Goodwillie, 1980: 38-42; Rodwell, 1991b: 179, unit M17).');
    'Deep-peat lawn and hummock communities of blanket bog expanses of western Britain composed of [Scirpus cespitosus], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Molinia caerulea], [Calluna vulgaris], [Erica tetralix], [Myrica gale], [Sphagnum rubellum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum tenellum], [Sphagnum subnitens], with [Drosera rotundifolia], [Juncus squarrosus], [Pleurozia purpurea], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], [Rhytidiadelphus loreus], [Cladonia spp.]', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 254-255; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M17).');
    'Waterlogged pool edges and bog surfaces of Hiberno-Britannic lowland blanket bogs marked by a scarcity of graminoids and shrubs, and a resulting physiognomic prominence of the sphagna, [Sphagnum magellanicum] or [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum rubellum], [Sphagnum cuspidatum], [Sphagnum auriculatum], [Sphagnum palustre], at times, particularly in Ireland, with [Zygogonium] algae deposits, often with [Drosera anglica], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Menyanthes trifoliata].', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 254-255; Doyle and Moore, 1978; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M17a [p.]).');
    '[Scirpus cespitosus]-[Erica tetralix] wet heaths of Hiberno-Britannic lowland blanket bog slopes or tops of slopes, developed on shallower peats, in better drained situations, in more mineralotrophic conditions than the communities of unit 52.11. Sphagna are less prominent in the ground layer with, in particular, a lesser prominence of [Sphagnum papillosum].', '(Doyle and Moore, 1978: 220-221; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M15 [p.]).');
    '[Alnus incana] galleries of the western and northern Carpathians and of the Bohemian Quadrangle, developed on damper substrates, with [Caltha palustris] ([Caltha laeta]), [Valeriana simplicifolia].', '(Pancer-Kotejowa, 1973; Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984).');
    '[Alnus incana] galleries along the upper reaches of Eastern Carpathian valleys, with regional species [Telekia speciosa], [Petasites kablikianus], [Symphytum cordatum], [Pulmonaria rubra], [Leucanthemum waldsteinii], which replace the pioneer willow scrubs of the [Salici purpureae-Myricarietum].
', '(Coldea, 1990, 1991).');
    '[Alnus incana] galleries of the montane Tara and Lim rivers of Montenegro, with [Aconitum toxicum], [Doronicum austriacum], [Oxalis acetosella] and many species shared with Alpine grey alder galleries.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 471-472).');
    '[Alnus incana] galleries lining watercourses of the upper levels of the central Balkan Range. ', '(Andreev y al., 1992: 229).');
    '[Alnus incana] galleries lining watercourses of the upper levels of Vitosha, Rila and the western Rhodope mountains.
', '(Andreev y al., 1992: 229).');
    'Alder formations of the middle course of rivers flowing from the Alps, in particular of rivers of the Danube, Rhine and Rhone systems. ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Braun-Blanquet, 1975b; Ozenda, 1981; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Noirfalise, 1986; Oberdorfer, 1990; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 95; Seliskar, 1998: 1).');
    '[Alnus incana]-dominated galleries and woods of the boreal zone of Fennoscandia and northeastern Europe, southwest to northeastern Poland, developed on nutrient-rich soils of river valleys, lakesides and the shores of the Gulf of Bothnia and the Gulf of Finland, periodically inundated by snow-melt waters or autumn rains, with [Betula pubescens], [Prunus padus], [Valeriana sambucifolia], [Anemone nemorosa], [Geranium sylvaticum], [Geum rivale], [Matteuccia struthiopteris], [Paris quadrifolia], [Silene dioica] ([Melandrium rubrum]), [Equisetum pratense].', '(Yon and Tendron, 1981; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 108; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.3.1 [p.]; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Endler, 1989; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.4.1 [p.]; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    '[Alnus glutinosa]-dominated galleries and woods of the boreal zone of Fennoscandia, developed in narrow cordons along rivers, on lakesides and on the coasts of the Baltic, with [Alnus incana], [Lycopus europaeus], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Lysimachia vulgaris], [Equisetum arvense].', '(Yon and Tendron, 1981; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.3.2 [p.]; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.4.2 [p.]; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Riverine woods and scrubs of western Siberian flood plains, dominated by [Betula pendula] or [Pinus sylvestris], with [Populus tremula], [Salix bebbiana], [Rosa majalis], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Equisetum sylvaticum].', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 483-484; Korotkov y al., 1991: 309-310).');
    'Formations of [Betula pendula], with [Calamagrostis langsdorfii], [Phalaroides arundinacea], [Lysimachia vulgaris], [Thalictrum simplex], [Lactuca sibirica], occupying river-bed ridges subject to brief flooding, of the Irtysh River valley.', NULL);
    'Formations of [Betula pendula], with [Rosa majalis], [Populus tremula], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Anemonidium dichotomum], [Galium boreale], [Hieracium umbellatum], [Ranunculus repens], [Agrostis gigantea], [Equisetum sylvaticum], of the Irtysh River valley.', NULL);
    'Formations of [Pinus sylvestris], with [Betula pendula], [Rosa majalis], [Prunella vulgaris], [Gnidium dubium], [Calamagrostis epigejos], [Pulmonaria dacica], [Maianthemum bifolium], occupying well-drained sites of the river flood-plain, Irtysh River valley.', NULL);
    'Formations of [Salix bebbiana], with [Betula pendula], [Vicia cracca], [Lythrum salicaria], [Gentiana pneumonanthe], of the river flood-plain, Irtysh River valley.', NULL);
    'Riverine woods and scrubs of eastern Siberian flood plains, with [Alnus fruticosa], [Populus suaveolens].', '(Walter, 1974: 46, 48).');
    'Riverside alder galleries and cordons of the Himalayas, formed by [Alnus nepalensis] or by [Alnus nepalensis] and [Alnus nitida], distributed both in the eastern Himalayas and in Nuristan, where they occur at the 2000-3500 m level.', '(Schweinfurth, 1957: 290, 300).');
    'Riverside and lakeside alder galleries and cordons of the Pontic Range and the Caucasus system, with [Alnus subcordata], [Alnus barbata] or [Alnus incana].', '(Browicz, 1972; Zohary, 1973: 378, 571, 574; Walter, 1974: 381, 387). ');
    'Riparian forests of [Fraxinus excelsior] and [Alnus glutinosa], sometimes [Alnus incana], of middle European and northern Iberian lowland or hill watercourses, on soils periodically inundated by the annual rise of the river level, but otherwise well-drained and aerated during low-water; they differ from riparian alder woods within unit 44.9 by the strong representation in the dominated layers of forest species not able to grow in permanently waterlogged soils.  ', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Bournérias, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.4 [p.]; Ellenberg, 1988; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W7; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.4 [p.]).');
    'Mesotrophic and meso-eutrophic [Alnus glutinosa] or [Alnus glutinosa]-[Alnus incana] swamp woods of northeastern Poland, the Baltic states, Fennoscandia, the northern Sarmatic region and Siberia, with [Calamagrostis canescens], [Athyrium filix-femina], [Cardamine amara], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Lysimachia thyrsiflora], [Carex elongata], [Carex remota], [Brachythecium rivulare], [Calliergon cordifolium], [Climacium dendroides], [Thuidium tamariscinum].', '(Sokolowski, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.2.3.3, 3.3.4.1; Ellenberg, 1988; Korotkov y al., 1991: 273-274; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.4.3).');
    'Meso-eutrophic [Alnus glutinosa] swamp woods of marshy intramontane depressions and floodplains, at the 500-800 m level of foothills of the eastern Carpathian system, in particular, the Harghita and Baraolt mountains, with [Carex elongata], [Calamagrostis canescens], [Thelypteris palustris], [Carex caespitosa], [Dryopteris carthusiana], [Calla palustris] and [Ligularia sibirica], most of which may dominate facies of the herb layer.', '(Coldea, 1991: 483-485; Coldea and Oltean, 1994).');
    '[Alnus glutinosa] swamp woods of the floodplains of southern Romania, developed along water bodies and in microdepressions on alluvial soils covered by stagnant or slowly moving water, with [Thelypteris palustris], [Festuca gigantea], [Lycopus europaeus], [Caltha palustris], [Veronica beccabunga], [Lythrum salicaria], [Oenanthe silaifolia], [Sium erectum], [Stellaria aquatica], [Carex acutiformis].', '(Paun and Popescu, 1971; Parvu, 1978; Popescu y al., 1981).');
    'Rare [Alnus glutinosa] swamp woods of peat bogs of central Romania, with [Spiraea salicifolia], [Euonymus nanus], [Frangula alnus], [Ribes nigrum], [Salix cinerea] in the shrub layer and [Carex elongata], [Calamagrostis canescens], [Ligularia sibirica], [Thelypteris palustris] in the herb layer.', '(Coldea, 1991: 483).');
    'Oligotrophic or meso-oligotrophic, acidocline [Alnus glutinosa] woods of fens and poorly drained banks of brooks or small rivers of western Europe, mostly characteristic of siliceous regions and Atlantic climates, south to Galicia. [Betula pubescens] and [Frangula alnus] often accompany the alders. The ground layer is usually rich in [Sphagnum spp.] and includes [Carex laevigata], [Equisetum sylvaticum] and many ferns, including [Oreopteris limbosperma], [Blechnum spicant], [Athyrium filix-femina], [Dryopteris cristata] and [Dryopteris carthusiana].', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Zuttere, 1975: 10; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; De Sloover y al., 1980: 77-79; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Noirfalise, 1984: unit IX.5; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Izco, 1987; Delescaille y al., 1989: 47; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W4c [p.]; Korotkov y al., 1991: 274; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Pott, 1992: 345-346; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993: 36).');
    'Rare swamp woods of the mediterranean and submediterranean zones of the southern Helleno-Balkanic peninsula.', '(Horvat y al., 1974).');
    'Rare swamp woods of the mediterranean evergreen oak zone of the Hellenic peninsula, such as the Athos peninsula swamp wood with [Arundo donax], [Equisetum telmateia], [Carex pendula], [Carex remota], [Humulus lupulus], [Osmunda regalis].  ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 119).');
    'Rare swamp woods of the submediterranean [Ostryo-Carpinion orientalis aegeicum] zone of the southern Balkan peninsula, recorded, in particular, from the southeastern F.Y.R. of Macedonia, with [Acer tataricum], [Frangula alnus], [Ligustrum vulgare], [Corylus avellana], [Rosa corymbifera], [Osmunda regalis], [Pteridium aquilinum], [Equisetum telmateia], [Thelypteris palustris] and a profusion of lianas, including [Periploca graeca], [Hedera helix], [Humulus lupulus], [Vitis vinifera] ssp. [sylvestris], [Calystegia sylvatica].', '(Rudski, 1938; Em, 1964; Horvat y al., 1974: 174; Micevski, 1999).');
    '[Alnus glutinosa] mire woods of the steppe zones of Eurasia, west to the Pannonic basin.', '(Soo, 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 195; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Mesotrophic and meso-eutrophic [Alnus glutinosa] swamp woods of the Pannonic basin.', '(Soo, 1980; Szujko-Lacza, 1986; Elias y al., 1991).');
    'Meso-eutrophic alder woods of mires of the east European steppe zone, south of the subboreal and nemoral regions.', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 195).');
    'Swamp woods of the Scandinavian lowlands dominated by [Alnus glutinosa] and [Alnus incana] with a shrub layer dominated by [Alnus spp.], [Betula pubescens] and various [Salix spp.] The field layer, sometimes very sparse, includes [Filipendula ulmaria], [Epilobium palustre], [Galium palustre], [Iris pseudacorus], [Lysimachia thyrsiflora], [Lysimachia vulgaris], [Viola palustris], [Calla palustris], [Thelypteris palustris], [Carex canescens], [Carex Elongata], [Carex rostrata], [Calamagrostis canescens], [Deschampsia caespitosa]. The ground layer, of mosses and sphagnums, is very poorly developed.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units  3.4.3.1, 3.5.2.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.1.3).');
    '[Alnus sibirica], [Alnus hirsuta], [Alnus trobeculosa] eutrophic mire woods of the eastern Palaearctic, sometimes with [Betula fruticosa], [Betula ovalifolia].', '(Lu, 1995: 50).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus coccifera] ([Quercus calliprinos])-dominated forests or steppe-forests of the Mediterranean Middle East, north to Syria and east to Jordan.', '(Zohary, 1973).');
    'Arborescent [Quercus alnifolia]-dominated formations of Cyprus, installed on basic eruptive substrates of the Troodos range, with [Acer sempervirens], [Teucrium kotschyanum], [Salvia cypria], [Crepis fraasii], [Sedum cyprium].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 294-300; Zohary, 1973: 153, 155, 357, 397, 562; Noirfalise, 1987: unit M11; Sfikas, 1992).');
    'Lauriphyllous and mixed lauriphyllous-xerophyllous evergreen forests of the Warm-Temperate Humid zones of the Eurasian continent and continental shelf islands and of humid enclaves within the Mediterranean zones. Lauriphyllous forests of the oceanic Macaronesian archipelagoes are listed separately under 45.6.', '(Walter, 1979).');
    '[Laurus nobilis]-dominated facies of evergreen oak forests characteristic of areas of warm-temperate humid conditions of the southern Atlantic coasts of the European continent and of humid microclimatic enclaves in the Mediterranean region, in particular, of coastal Asturias (cf.45.311), of Andalusia, of Istria and the Dalmatian coast.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 192; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987:93).');
    'Communities of the Ponto-Caspian warm-temperate humid zone of the southern shores of the Black and Caspian seas, dominated by lauriphyllous or xero-lauriphyllous evergreen tree species, in particular, [Laurus nobilis],  [Prunus laurocerasus] ([Laurocerasus officinalis]) and [Buxus hyrcanica], anomalous and often limited to exiguous enclaves within a predominantly deciduous forest environment.', '(Zohary, 1973: 371; Walter and Breckle, 1991c).');
    'Tree-size [Laurus nobilis] or [Prunus laurocerasus] ([Laurocerasus officinalis])-dominated communities of the southern Black Sea coast of Anatolia and of sea-facing slopes of Colchis.', '(Zohary, 1973:514; Walter and Breckle, 1991c).');
    '[Buxus hyrcanica]-dominated woods of the southern Caspian lowlands and lower slopes of the Elburz.', '(Walter and Breckle, 1991c).');
    'Species-rich, multistratum, lauriphyllous forests of the southern half of Honshu, of Shikoku, Kyushu and the Ryukyu islands, of southern Korea, of the southeastern quadrant of continental China and of the mountains of Taiwan and Hainan, dominated by evergreen Fagaceae, in particular of genera [Castanopsis], [Cyclobalanopsis], [Pasania], [Quercus], Lauraceae, of genera [Cinnamomum], [Machilus], Theaceae ([Camellia japonica], [Schima wallichii]), Myricaceae ([Myrica rubra]), with an admixture of conifers of genera [Podocarpus], [Torreya], [Pinus], [Abies], [Tsuga], many epiphytes and lianas, and a rich undergrowth of broadleaved evergreen small trees, shrubs, small shrubs, of vines, ferns and herbaceous plants. Mixed deciduous and evergreen broad-leaved forests, similar to the evergreen forests in their extreme species richness and mixed dominance, and bamboo forests of the warm temperate zone, mostly dominated by the monopodial [Phyllostachys bambusoides], in northern areas, or [Phyllostachys pubescens], in southern areas, are included.', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 41-43, 172-173; Satoo, 1983; Mei''e y al., 1985; Richardson, 1990: 40-42, 52-63).');
    'Mixed deciduous and evergreen broad-leaved forests of the northern part of the southeastern quadrant of continental China, forming a belt north of the Yangtze, in extreme southern Kansu, southern Shensi, southern Honan, northern Hupei, central Ahnwei, to the Pacific in central Kiangsu, similar to the evergreen forests of units 45.532 and 45.533 in their extreme species richness and mixed dominance, although with slightly fewer species. They are mostly limited to altitudes below 500 m. in the east, extend to 1800 m. in the west.  
The main broad-leaved evergreen constituents include [Quercus glauca], [Quercus gracilis], [Quercus myrsinaefolia], [Castanopsis sclerophylla], [Lithocarpus glabra], [Lithocarpus henryi], the Lauraceae [Cinnamomum camphora] and [Phoebe heareri], [Schima superba]), the broad-leaved deciduous components, [Quercus acutissima], [Quercus aliena], [Quercus variabilis], [Quercus fabri], [Quercus glandulifera], [Albizia kalkora], [Liquidanbar formosana], [Platycarya strobalicea], [Dalbergia huppeana], [Rhus chinensis], [Pistacia chinensis], [Diospyros kaki], [Sassafras tsuma]; associated conifers comprise [Pinus massoniana], [Cunninghamia lanceolata].', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 3, 31-35, 41; Mei''e y al., 1985; Richardson, 1990: 40-42, 52-56; Ching, 1991: 544, 547-548).');
    'Broad-leaved evergreen forests of Yunnan, southwestern Sichuan and western Guizhou, mostly dominated by Fagaceae of genera [Castanopsis], [Cyclobalanopsis], [Pasania], [Quercus], with Magnoliaceae, Lauraceae, in particular, of genus [Machilus], Theaceae, in particular [Schima wallichii]) and conifers of genera [Pinus], [Ketleeria], [Torreya], [Picea].', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 33, 43; Mei''e y al., 1985; Richardson, 1990: 40-41, 59-63).');
    'Communities of western Irish lowland blanket bogs occupying slope areas submitted to surface water movement and shallow hollows, rich in [Drosera intermedia], with [Riccardia pinguis], [Rhynchospora fusca] or [Carex limosa].', '(Doyle and Moore, 1978: 219).');
    'Communities of western Irish lowland blanket bogs occupying shallow drainage channels and shallow pools, rich in [Juncus bulbosus], [Eleocharis multicaulis] and [Carex panicea].', '(Doyle and Moore, 1978: 220).');
    'Wet depressions and seeps of Hiberno-Britannic lowland blanket bogs colonized by hollow communities similar to those of raised bog hollows of unit 51.121 or by other communities of the [Scheuchzerietalia palustris] (units 54.5, 54.6), communities of the [Caricetalia fuscae] (unit 54.4), of the [Utricularietalia intermedio-minoris] (unit 22.45), of the [Littorelletalia] (unit 22.31) or of the [Potamogetonetalia] (unit 22.43).', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 254-255; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M1 [p.], [i.a.]).');
    'Wet depressions and seeps of Hiberno-Britannic lowland blanket bogs colonized by hollow communities similar to those of raised bog hollows of unit 51.121, in particular, of unit 51.1213, dominated by [Sphagnum auriculatum], with [Sphagnum subsecundum] ssp. [inundatum] and the bright orange-yellow [Sphagnum pulchrum].
', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 254-255; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M1 [p.]).');
    'Wet depressions and seeps of Hiberno-Britannic lowland blanket bogs colonized by communities of the [Scheuchzerietalia palustris] (units 54.5, 54.6), communities of the [Caricetalia fuscae] (unit 54.4), of the [Utricularietalia intermedio-minoris] (unit 22.45), of the [Littorelletalia] (unit 22.31) or of the [Potamogetonetalia] (unit 22.43), which can be noted by use of appropriate codes. Among important elements are [Potamogeton polygonifolius], [Eriocaulon aquaticum], [Lobelia dortmanna], [Menyanthes trifoliata]. ', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 254-255).');
    'Blanket bogs of high ground, hills and mountains in Scotland, Ireland, western England and Wales. Characteristic species are [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Calluna vulgaris], [Erica tetralix], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] and abundant sphagnum mosses. Some of their communities show affinities with the boreoalpine hummocks of unit 51.17. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 70, 112; Pearsall, 1971; Pearsall and Pennington, 1977; Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255; Dierssen, 1978; Heal and Smith, 1978; Currie, 1979; Goodwillie, 1980; Ratcliffe, 1980; Condry, 1981; White and Doyle, 1982; Taylor, 1983; Polunin and Walters, 1985; Bellamy, 1986; Morrison, 1989; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Rieley and Page, 1990: 110, 112-115; Rodwell, 1991b: units M19, M2 [p.], M20 [p.]).');
    'Lawn and hummock communities of upland blanket bog expanses of Britain and Ireland, mostly distributed in the Scottish Highlands, the Southern Uplands, the Pennines, the Lake District, Wales, in Orkney, in northern, western, southwestern and upland eastern Ireland, dominated by an admixture of [Eriophorum vaginatum] and ericoid shrubs, with a varying amount of sphagna and hypnoid mosses.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit G4a; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M19 [p.]).');
    'Species-poor upland blanket bog lawn communities of the Pennines overwhelmingly dominated by an open or closed canopy of low [Eriophorum vaginatum] tussocks, with few ericoid shrubs and a sparse and patchy ground cover in which sphagna are scarce; the most common vascular associates are usually [Eriophorum angustifolium] and [Deschampsia flexuosa]. They are characteristic of heavily grazed and burned expanses of blanket bog.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit G4f; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M20 [p.]).');
    '[Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum magellanicum], [Sphagnum rubellum], [Sphagnum imbricatum], [Sphagnum fuscum] carpets and hummocks of the cottonsedge-ling blanket bogs, most characteristic of the moorlands of the Scottish Borders.  ', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit G4b; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M19 [p.]).');
    'Dwarf shrub-rich facies of Hiberno-Britannic upland cottongrass-ling blanket bogs, most characteristic of the eastern Scottish Highlands, with an abundance of [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Empetrum nigrum], [Betula nana], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Arctostaphylos alpinus] and [Sphagnum fuscum], with particularly close affinities to the boreoalpine hummocks of unit 51.17.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit G4d; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M19 [p.]).');
    'Lawn and hummock communities of Hiberno-Britannic upland blanket bogs dominated by [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], mostly characteristic of eroded or dried surfaces.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255; Ratcliffe, 1980: units G1b, G2b; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M19).');
    '[Erica tetralix] or, at lower altitudes, [Scirpus cespitosus]-[Erica tetralix] wet heaths of Hiberno-Britannic upland blanket bog slopes or tops of slopes, developed on shallower peats, in better drained situations, in more mineralotrophic conditions than the communities of unit 52.21. [Eriophorum vaginatum] is less prominent in the sward, and sphagna sparser in the ground cover, while shrubs, [Juncus squarrosus] and [Nardus stricta] are more vigorous or commoner.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: units G1, G2, G3, [p.]; Rodwell, 1991b: 204, units M16, M15, [p.]).');
    '[Alnus incana] riverine galleries of the western and northern Carpathians and of the Bohemian Quadrangle, developed on well drained substrates, in particular on gravel flats and the lower parts of valley slopes, with [Salvia glutinosa], [Thalictrum aquilegifolium], [Matteuccia struthiopteris].', '(Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 54-55; Medwecka-Kornas y al., 1966; Pancer-Kotejowa, 1973; Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984).');
    '[Fraxinus excelsior]-[Alnus glutinosa] formations of springs and small streams of Atlantic, sub-Atlantic and subcontinental middle Europe, usually dominated by ashes, with [Carex remota], [Carex pendula], [Carex strigosa], [Equisetum telmateia], [Rumex sanguineus], [Lysimachia nemorum], [Cardamine amara], [Chrysosplenium oppositifolium], [Chrysosplenium alternifolium], [Impatiens noli-tangere], [Ribes rubrum]. ', '(Noirfalise, 1952, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Duvigneaud and Mullenders, 1962; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W7; Korotkov y al., 1991; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Seliskar, 1998: 1).');
    'Formations of [Fraxinus excelsior] and [Alnus glutinosa] of sub-Atlantic and subcontinental middle Europe, distributed in western Europe, in northern, Central and Eastern Europe, extending south in Central Europe to the confines of the [Fagion sylvaticum], [Fagion illyricum] and [Carpinion illyricum] zones, with an abundance of [Carex remota], [Carex strigosa], [Carex pendula], [Carex sylvatica].', '(Noirfalise, 1952; Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Duvigneaud and Mullenders, 1962; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 140, 143, 144; Horvat y al., 1974: 471; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984: unit VIII.4a; Korotkov y al., 1991: 296; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 98-100; Seliskar, 1998: 1).');
    '[Fraxinus excelsior]-[Alnus glutinosa] woods of Atlantic, sub-Atlantic and subcontinental middle Europe, with a wetter soil occupied by [Cardamine amara] and [Chrysosplenium spp.], and often by [Impatiens noli-tangere]. ', '(Noirfalise, 1952; Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Duvigneaud and Mullenders, 1962; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984: unit VIII.4b; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W7a).');
    '[Fraxinus excelsior]-[Alnus glutinosa] woods of Atlantic, sub-Atlantic and subcontinental middle Europe, with an understorey rich in tall herbs, in particular, in sub-Atlantic areas, the tall [Cirsium oleraceum] and [Eupatorium cannabinum] and usually [Carex acutiformis]; these constitute a transition towards unit 44.332.', '(Noirfalise, 1952; Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Tüxen and Oberdorfer, 1958; Duvigneaud and Mullenders, 1962; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984: unit VIII.4c; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W7b).');
    '[Fraxinus excelsior]-[Alnus glutinosa] woods of sub-Atlantic and subcontinental middle Europe, of seeping hillside depressions and of moist peaty ground, with [Ribes rubrum]. ', NULL);
    '[Fraxinus excelsior]-[Alnus glutinosa] woods of calcareous inundated substrates adjacent to streams and springs of Great Britain and middle Europe, characterized by an abundant herb layer dominated by [Equisetum telmateia] and rich in mosses.', '(Page, 1988: 195-196; Oberdorfer, 1990: 63; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W7b [p.]; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 145-146; Oberdorfer, 1992c: 245-259, 270-277; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 98-99).');
    'Calciphile [Fraxinus excelsior]-[Alnus glutinosa] woods occupying inundated stream sides and hard water spring edges, in particular calcareous tuffs, of the collinar and montane Alpine periphery, characterized by an abundant herb layer dominated by [Equisetum telmateia] accompanied by [Carex remota], [Lysimachia nemorum], [Cratoneuron filicinum], often with many humid grassland and tall herb elements, such as [Mnium undulatum], [Lamium galeobdolon], [Brachypodium sylvaticum], [Deschampsia cespitosa], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Cirsium oleraceum], and [Caltha palustris].', '(Oberdorfer, 1990: 63; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 145-146; Oberdorfer, 1992c: 245-259, 270-277; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 98-99).');
    'Local and unusual [Fraxinus excelsior-Alnus glutinosa] woods of basic, spring-fed sites of Great Britain, in particular of calcareous tuffs, with [Quercus robur], abundant [Corylus avellana], accompanied by a swampy field layer dominated by [Equisetum telmateia], sometimes in association with scattered ferns, [Ranunculus ficaria], a loose carpet of mosses and occasional participation of tall herb community elements (37.1) or flood plain sward species (37.242).
', '(Page, 1988: 195-197; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W7b [p.]).');
    'Higrophile, neutrophile gallery woods of low mountain rivers of the [Fagion moesiacum] and [Fagion dacicum] zones, in particular of Serbia and the southern and eastern Carpathians of Rumania, notably the Apuseni mountains, dominated by [Fraxinus excelsior] and [Alnus glutinosa], with [Alnus incana], [Tilia cordata], [Ulmus glabra], [Acer pseudoplatanus], and [Carex remota] in the herb layer.', '(Wendelberger, 1965: 277; Boscaiu, 1971; Horvat y al., 1974: 521; Sanda y al., 1980: 118).');
