    'Low woods and scrubs colonizing fens, marshy floodplains and fringes of lakes and ponds of the western Palaearctic, dominated by large or medium sized shrubby willows, generally [Salix aurita], [Salix cinerea], [Salix atrocinerea], [Salix pentandra], alone or in association with [Frangula alnus], [Rhamnus cathartica], [Alnus glutinosa] or [Betula pubescens], any of which may, at times, dominate the upper canopy, or, in boreal regions and on cold subboreal plateaux, by very small arcto-alpine willows associated with [Betula humilis] or [Betula nana].', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.4.3.1, 3.5.2.1, 3.5.1.1, 2.2.5.1 [p.], 3.5.1.2, 3.5.1.3, 3.5.1.4, 3.5.1.5, 3.6.1.4f; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: units W1, W2, W3; Chifu y al., 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991; Coldea, 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Steiner, 1992; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.4.1.3, 3.3.1.3, 2.2.5.1 [p.], 3.2.1.2, 3.2.1.4, 3.3.1.4, 3.3.1.5, 3.4.1.4; Müller, 1998: 60).');
    'Mesotrophic or eutrophic low woods and scrubs colonizing fens, marshy floodplains and fringes of lakes and ponds of the western Palaearctic, dominated by [Salix cinerea], [Salix aurita] or, sometimes, [Salix atrocinerea], alone or in association with [Frangula alnus], [Rhamnus cathartica], [Alnus glutinosa] or [Betula pubescens], any of which may, at times, dominate the upper canopy.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.4.3.1, 3.5.2.1, 2.2.5.1, [p.]; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Delescaille, 1987: 81; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: units W1, W2a; Korotkov y al., 1991; Coldea, 1991; Pott, 1992: 348; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Steiner, 1992; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.4.1.3, 2.2.5.1, [p.]).');
    'Mesotrophic or eutrophic [Salix cinerea], [Salix aurita], or, sometimes, [Salix atrocinerea], and [Alnus glutinosa] scrubs of mires, fens, and water fringes of western Europe and northern Central Europe, within the Atlantic and sub-Atlantic domaines.  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Thoen and Bracke, 1971: 234-236; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.4.3.1, 3.5.2.1, 2.2.5.1, [p.]; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984: unit IX.7; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Delescaille, 1987: 81; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: units W1, W2a; Korotkov y al., 1991; Pott, 1992: 348; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.4.1.3, 2.2.5.1, [p.]).');
    '[Salix cinerea]-dominated scrubs of often relatively eutrophic mires of the warmer lowlands and submontane level of central, southeastern and eastern Europe. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 391, 471, 521; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993).');
    '[Salix cinerea] carrs occupying fen margins of the Eastern Carpathians and the Apuseni mountains, with [Frangula alnus], [Spirea salicifolia], [Ribes nigrum], [Euvonymous nana], [Calamagrostis canescens], [Lysimachia vulgaris], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Poa trivialis], [Galium palustre], [Myosotis palustris], [Deschampsia caespitosa].', '(Coldea, 1991: 478, 483, 484-485).');
    'Oligotrophic [Salix aurita] or [Salix cinerea] and [Betula pubescens] or [Betula carpatica] scrubs, rich in sphagnum, of bog edges and acid fens of nemoral Europe.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983; Noirfalise, 1984; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.5.1.1 [p.]; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W2b; Korotkov y al., 1991; Coldea, 1991; Oberdorfer, 1992b; Steiner, 1992; Pott, 1992: 348; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Medium-tall woods and brushes colonizing fens, marshy floodplains and fringes of lakes and ponds, dominated by the relatively large [Salix pentandra], particularly characteristic of boreal, subboreal and subcontinental Europe, from northern England through Scandinavia, northeastern Germany, Poland, Lithuania to Bashkiria in the northeast, to the Bohemian quadrangle, the Alpine piedmont of Bavaria and Hungary in the south, with outposts in the Netherlands, in subcontinental western Europe to the Black Forest and the Baar plateau, in continental southern Europe to Bulgaria.', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 234-235; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1983: 72; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 100; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 2.2.5.1, 3.5.1.1, 3.4.3.1, [p.]; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W3; Korotkov y al., 1991: 275-276; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 27-28; Pott, 1992: 347; Påhlsson, 1994: units 2.2.5.1, 3.3.1.3, 3.4.1.3, [p.]; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994).');
    'Dwarf [Salix repens], [Salix rosmarinifolia] and [Betula humilis] scrubs of bogs and fens, of eastern nemoral and boreonemoral Europe, with outposts constituting rare glacial relicts in the higher middle German Hercynian ranges and on northern pre-Alpine plateaux.', '(Pott, 1992: 346; Oberdorfer, 1992b: 25-27; Geisselbrecht-Taferner and Wallnöfer, 1993: 31-32).');
    'Broad-leaved evergreen forests of the great Red Basin of Sichuan, of the highlands of Guizhou, of the southeastern coastal provinces of Zhejiang (Chekiang), Fujian (Fukien), Guangdong (Kwangtung) and Guangxi (Kwangsi), below 1000 m, mostly on acidic sandstones, shales or granite, but in the Red Basin and in the highlands of Guizhou, also on limestones, mostly dominated by Fagaceae of genera [Quercus], [Castanopsis] and [Pasania], associated with Theaceae of genera [Shima] and [Hartia], Lauraceae of genera [Machilus], [Phoebe], [Beilschmiedia], [Cinnamomum], Magnoliaceae of genera [Magnolia], [Maglietia], [Illicium], [Michelia] and Hamamelidaceae of genera [Altingia], [Bucklandia] and [Liquidambar]. Forests of Zhejiang (Chekiang) are composed primarily of the Fagaceae [Quercus glauca] ([Cyclobalanopsis glauca]), [Quercus myrsinaefolia], [Castanopsis sclerophylla], [Lithocarpus glabra], of the Lauraceae [Phoebe cheareri], [Machilus thunbergii], of the Theacece [Shima superba]; those of Guangdong (Kwangtung), in the south, are of [Quercus nubium], [Castanopsis fissa], [Castanopsis fordii], [Castanopsis fabri], [Castanopsis fargestii], [Castanopsis carlesii], [Machilus panhoi], [Cinnamomum japonicum].', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 43; Mei''e y al., 1985; Richardson, 1990: 57-59).');
    'Warm temperate broad-leaved evergreen [Castanopsis]-[Shima] forests of the higher elevations of Taiwan.', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 41; Satoo, 1983: 169; Richardson, 1990: 57; Su, 1995: 198).');
    'Broad-leaved evergreen forests of southern Korea, distributed south of 35øN, in areas of mean annual temperatures greater than 14øC and on offshore islands, mostly formed by oaks [Quercus spp.] and camellias [Camellia spp.], with bamboos.', '(Satoo, 1983: 169; Ching, 1991: 554; Kim, 1995a: 160).');
    'Species-rich, multistratum, lauriphyllous forests of the southern half of Honshu, of Shikoku, Kyushu and the Ryukyu islands, dominated by evergreen Fagaceae, in particular of genera [Castanopsis], [Cyclobalanopsis], [Pasania], [Quercus], Lauraceae of genera [Cinnamomum], [Machilus], Theaceae ([Camellia japonica], [Schima wallichii]), Myricaceae ([Myrica rubra]), with an admixture of conifers of genera [Podocarpus], [Torreya], [Pinus], [Abies], [Tsuga], many epiphytes and lianas, and a rich undergrowth of broadleaved evergreen small trees, shrubs, small shrubs, of vines, ferns and herbaceous plants.', '(Satoo, 1983: 173-174).');
    'Bamboo forests of the warm temperate zone of China, Korea and Japan, mostly dominated by the monopodial [Phyllostachys bambusoides], in northern areas, or [Phyllostachys pubescens], in southern areas.', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 41-43, 172-173; Satoo, 1983; Mei''e y al., 1985; Richardson, 1990: 40-42, 52-63).');
    'Humid to hyper-humid, mist-bound, luxuriant, evergreen, lauriphyllous forests of the cloud belt of the Macaronesian islands, extremely rich in floral and faunal species, among which many are restricted to these communities. Genera such as [Picconia], [Semele], [Gesnouinia], [Lactucosonchus], [Ixanthus] are entirely endemic to these communnities, while others, such as [Isoplexis], [Visnea] and [Phyllis] reach in them their maximum development; in addition, each of the formations of the various archipelagoes harbours distinctive endemic species. Laurel forests are the most complex and remarkable relict of the humid sub-tropical vegetation of the Mioceno-Pliocene late Tertiary of southern Europe. Areas of intact forests have been drastically reduced to a level below which the preservation of their elements could not be sustained.  ', '(Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; Duvigneaud, 1977; White, 1983; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988; Santos, 1990).');
    'Lauriphyllous forests of the Azores, with [Laurus azorica], [Myrica faya], [Frangula azorica], [Ilex perado] ssp. [azorica], [Juniperus brevifolia], [Picconia azorica], [Prunus lusitanica] ssp. [azorica], [Euphorbia stygiana], [Viburnum tinus] ssp. [subcordatum], [Vaccinium cylindraceum], [Smilax divaricata]. The humid forests of the coastal areas ("[Myrico-Pittosporietum undulati] [p.]") have been totally or almost totally degraded, largely invaded by the introduced Australian [Pittosporum undulatum]. A better representation survives of the hyperhumid forests ([Culcito-Juniperion brevifoliae] [p.]) of higher elevations. ', '(White, 1983; Santos, 1990). ');
    'Lauriphyllous forests of Madeira with [Laurus azorica], [Persea indica], [Ocotea foetens], [Apollonias barbujana], [Pittosporum coriaceum], [Clethra arborea], [Visnea mocanera], [Picconia excelsa], [Prunus lusitanica] ssp. [hixa], [Heberdenia excelsa], [Vaccinium padifolium], [Ilex perado] ssp. [perado], [Ilex canariensis], [Myrica faya], [Erica arborea], [Hedera canariensis], [Isoplexis canariensis], [Euphorbia mellifera], [Sambucus lanceolata], [Teline maderensis] ([Cytisus maderensis]), [Sonchus fruticosus], [Senecio auritus] ([Senecio maderensis]), [Ruscus streptophyllus], [Rubus bollei], [Semele androgyna], [Smilax canariensis], [Tamus edulis], [Carex peregrina] and many ferns. These forests, which still occupy a relatively large surface, of the order of 10,000 ha (15% of their former surface), are the habitat of the threatened endemic Madeiran Pigeon, [Columba trocaz].', '(Duvigneaud, 1977; White, 1983; Santos, 1990). ');
    'Wet depressions and seeps of Hiberno-Britannic upland blanket bogs colonized by hollow communities similar to those of raised bog hollows of unit 51.121 or by other communities of the [Scheuchzerietalia palustris] (units 54.5, 54.6), communities of the [Caricetalia fuscae] (unit 54.4), of the [Utricularietalia intermedio-minoris] (unit 22.45), of the [Littorelletalia] (unit 22.31) or of the [Potamogetonetalia] (unit 22.43). Pools and hollows are less prominent in these blanket bogs than in the western blanket bogs of unit 52.1.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M2 [p.] [i.a.])');
    'Wet depressions and seeps of Hiberno-Britannic upland blanket bogs colonized by hollow communities similar to those of raised bog hollows of unit 51.121, in particular, of unit 51.1211, dominated by [Sphagnum cuspidatum] with [Sphagnum recurvum].', '(Rodwell, 1991b: unit M2 [p.] [i.a.])');
    'Wet depressions and seeps of Hiberno-Britannic upland blanket bogs colonized by communities of the [Scheuchzerietalia palustris] (units 54.5, 54.6), communities of the [Caricetalia fuscae] (unit 54.4), of the [Utricularietalia intermedio-minoris] (unit 22.45), of the [Littorelletalia] (unit 22.31) or of the [Potamogetonetalia] (unit 22.43), which can be noted by use of appropriate codes.', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 255])');
    'Blanket bogs of oceanic southern boreal affinities distributed in maritime western Norway from Rogaland, in the south, north to the Arctic Circle, and in the Faeroe Islands, characterized by the dominance of [Calluna]-[Rhacomitrium] and [Calluna]-[Sphagnum rubellum] communities.', '(Dierssen, 1978: 410; Goodwillie, 1980: 45-47; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 206-209, units 3.2.1.2, 3.2.1.4, 3.2.3.3, 3.2.3.2, 220, map 1.1; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 15; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Påhlsson, 1994: 210, units 3.1.2.4, 3.1.2.5, 3.1.4.3, 3.1.4.2).');
    'Main bog-surface and hummock communities of southern boreal blanket bogs dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], [Eriophorum vaginatum] and [Sphagnum rubellum], with [Erica tetralix], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Andromeda polifolia], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Sphagnum magellanicum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.1.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.2.4).');
    'Bog-surface and hummock communities characteristic of the southernmost southern boreal blanket bogs, in nemoral extreme southern Norway, oceanic southern boreal extreme western Norway, north to southern Tr¿ndelag, and in the Faeroe Islands, dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum nigrum], [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum], with [Cornus suecica], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Deschampsia flexuosa], [Dicranum elongatum], [Grimmia hypnoides], [Cladonia sylvatica].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.1.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.1.2.5).');
    'Hollow vegetation of southern boreal blanket bogs formed by [Sphagnum cuspidatum] and [Sphagnum tenellum], with [Rhynchospora alba], [Scheuchzeria palustris], [Drosera anglica], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Andromeda polifolia], [Carex limosa], [Eriophorum vaginatum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.3.3, 3.2.3.2, [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: 210, units 3.1.4.3, 3.1.4.2, [p.]).');
    'Blanket bogs of oceanic northern boreal affinities distributed in maritime western Norway, from southern Nordland to central Troms, characterized by the dominance of [Calluna]-[Empetrum]-[Sphagnum fuscum] communities.', '(Dierssen, 1978; Goodwillie, 1980: 45-47; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.2.1.1, 3.2.3.4, 220, map 1.2; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 15; Daniels and Eddy, 1990: 26-28; Påhlsson, 1994: 210, units 3.1.2.2, 3.1.4.4).');
    'Bog-surface and hummock communities of the northern boreal blanket bogs dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum spp.], [Vaccinium uliginosum] and [Sphagnum fuscum] with [Andromeda polifolia], [Vaccinium microcarpum], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Betula nana], [Cladonia rangiferina], [Cladonia sylvatica].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.1.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: 210, unit 3.1.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Hollow vegetation of northern boreal blanket bogs formed by [Sphagnum majus], with [Rhynchospora alba], [Scheuchzeria palustris], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Andromeda polifolia], [Carex limosa], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Drepanocladus fluitans].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.3.4; Påhlsson, 1994: 210, unit 3.1.4.4).');
    'Blanket bogs of Kamchatka and Sakhalin, with [Sphagnum fuscum], [Sphagnum lindbergii], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Empetrum nigrum], [Carex lyngbyei], [Carex middendorffii], [Cladonia spp.].   ', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 126, 127).');
    'Communities of the margins and of the floating rafts of lakes, rivers and brooks, or of eutrophic marshes and swamps, based on sociations of large graminoid, juncoid or broad-leaved plants, for the most part helophytes.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Knapp, 1973; Zohary, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Walter and Breckle, 1986, 1991c; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Rieley and Page, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Denny, 1993a; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994; Lu, 1995; Archibold, 1995).');
    'Alder or ash-alder galleries of the banks of fast-flowing rivers and large brooks replacing the peri-Alpine [Alnus incana] galleries in hills of middle  Europe away from the direct influence of alpine rivers and north to Denmark and southern Sweden. ', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Bournérias, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.4 [p.]; Ellenberg, 1988; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.4 [p.]).');
    'Alder or ash-alder galleries of the banks of fast-flowing nonalpine rivers and large brooks of hill and lowland regions of western, northern and central Europe. ', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Sloover y al., 1980: 75-76; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Bournérias, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.4 [p.]; Ellenberg, 1988; Wallnöfer y al., 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.4 [p.]; Seliskar, 1998: 1).');
    'Alder or ash-alder galleries of the banks of fast-flowing nonalpine rivers and large brooks of western, central and northwestern Europe. They are usually codominated by [Alnus glutinosa], [Fraxinus excelsior] and [Acer pseudoplatanus], accompanied by [Acer platanoides], [Ulmus glabra], [Ulmus laevis]. [Prunus padus] is frequent in the undergrowth, shrubs include [Ribes rubrum], [Ribes uva-crispa], [Corylus avellana]; the herb layer comprises [Stellaria nemorum], [Impatiens noli-tangere], [Aconitum vulparia], [Allium ursinum], [Geum rivale], [Athyrium filix-femina], [Dryopteris carthusiana], [Matteuccia struthiopteris], [Ranunculus platanifolius], [Urtica dioica], [Ranunculus ficaria], [Primula elatior], [Lamium galeobdolon] or [Filipendula ulmaria], [Luzula sylvatica]. The gallery may be enclosed within other forests or reduced to a thin line of alders along rivers traversing pastureland. ', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Thill, 1964: 46; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Sloover y al., 1980: 75-76; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1982; Bournérias, 1984; Noirfalise, 1984: units VIII.5.2.1, VIII.5.2.2; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 2.2.2.4 [p.]; Ellenberg, 1988; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W7; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 96-97, 97-98; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 2.2.3.4 [p.]; Seliskar, 1998: 1; Frankard y al., 1998: 30).');
    'Ash-alder-spruce galleries of the banks of fast-flowing rivers and large brooks of northeastern Central Europe. ', '(Sokolowski, 1980; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992; Korotkov y al., 1991: 296).');
    'Herb-rich [Alnus glutinosa]- or [Fraxinus excelsior] and [Alnus glutinosa]- dominated galleries of more montane affinities than those of the [Stellario-Alnetum], paralleling the [Alnetum incanae] in mountainous country away from the Alps and the main Carpathian ranges, in particular in and around the great Hercynian ranges of the Bohemian Quadrangle, north to the Silesian lowlands. [Alnus incana] is sometimes present; common in, or characteristic of the undergrowth are [Stellaria nemorum], [Chaerophyllum hirsutum], [Crepis paludosa], [Aegopodium podagraria], [Rubus idaeus], and, in some of the local variants, [Astrantia major], [Aruncus sylvestris].', '(Moravec y al., 1982; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 110; Ellenberg, 1988; Korotkov y al., 1991: 276).');
    'Woods of [Alnus glutinosa] and [Fraxinus excelsior] developed on alluvial soils along the middle and lower course of streams and rivers of pre-Carpathian hills, accompanied by [Frangula alnus] and [Ulmus laevis], with [Stellaria nemorum], [Aegopodium podagraria], [Matteuccia struthiopteris], [Carex remota], [Carex brizoides], [Equisetum maximum] and rich in [Fagetalia] and [Querco-Fagetea] species.', '(Lohmeyer, 1957; Karpati and Jurko, 1961; Soo, 1963a, 1980; Moravec y al., 1982).');
    'Eastern, central and, locally, western European [Fraxinus excelsior]-[Alnus glutinosa] woods of valleys of lowland slow and even-flowing rivers, with a rich undergrowth of tall herbs and shrubs.', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Carbiener, 1983; Rodwell, 1991a: unit W6a).');
    'Central European riverine and floodplain woods of valleys of lowland, often small, slow and even-flowing rivers, usually dominated by [Fraxinus excelsior] and/or [Alnus glutinosa], sometimes with [Picea abies], [Quercus robur], [Fagus sylvatica], with a rich undergrowth of tall herbs and shrubs. They may extend far into the floodplain, becoming progressively richer in [Quercus robur] and [Carpinion] species away from the stream or from lowlying areas.', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Carbiener, 1983).');
    '[Alnus glutinosa]-[Fraxinus excelsior] forests of large valleys of lowland slow and even-flowing Central European rivers, south to the Illyrian region, often extensive, and capable of occupying floodplains well beyond the riparian gallery, progressively richer in [Quercus robur] and [Carpinion] species towards the exterior. The undergrowth includes, besides [Prunus padus], [Humulus lupulus], [Rubus idaeus], [Rubus caesius], [Ribes nigrum], [Ribes rubrum], [Sambucus nigra], [Aegopodium podagraria], [Peucedanum palustre], [Glyceria maxima], [Iris pseudacorus], [Carex acutiformis], [Carex riparia], [Phalaris arundinacea], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Cirsium oleraceum], [Cirsium palustre].', '(Oberdorfer, 1953, 1990; Noirfalise and Sougnez, 1961; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974: 381, 383; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Soo, 1980; Yon and Tendron, 1981; Moravec y al., 1982; Carbiener, 1983; Noirfalise, 1984; Noirfalise y al., 1985; Wallnöfer y al., 1993: 100-101; Neuh¿uslova, 1998: 62-63, 280-281, unit 1).');
    'Low woods and scrubs colonizing fens, marshy floodplains and fringes of lakes and ponds of the boreal zone of the Palaearctic dominated by large or medium sized shrubby willows, generally [Salix cinerea] or [Salix aurita], accompanied by [Salix phylicifolia], [Salix nigricans] ([Salix myrsinifolia]) and the boreal [Salix glauca], [Salix lapponum], with sedges, in particular, [Carex aquatilis], [Carex caespitosa], brown mosses and sphagna.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 270: unit 3.5.1.1 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 485; Korotkov y al., 1991: 275; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.1.3 [p.]).');
    'Willow thickets or scrubs of mires of the mountains of the boreal zone of the Palaearctic region, characteristically forming along fen margins, on their hummocks or strings, sometimes in their lawns, with an understorey of dwarf shrubs, herbs, mosses and sphagna.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.5.1.2, 3.5.1.3, 3.5.1.4, 3.5.1.5, 3.6.1.4f; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.2.1.2, 3.2.1.4, 3.3.1.4, 3.3.1.5, 3.4.1.4).');
    'Willow thickets or scrubs of oligotrophic, acidic fens of the mountains of the boreal zone of the Palaearctic region, characteristically forming along fen margins, on their hummocks or strings, sometimes in their lawns, with an understorey of dwarf shrubs, herbs, mosses and sphagna.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.5.1.2, 3.5.1.3; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.2.1.2, 3.2.1.4).');
    'Willow scrub of mire margins and hummocks of poor, acid fens of boreal and arctic Scandinavia, dominated by [Salix glauca], [Salix lanata], [Salix lapponum], [Salix phylicifolia] accompanied by a relatively tall shrub layer dominated by [Calluna vulgaris], [Ledum palustre], [Diapensia lapponica], with [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-ideae], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Betula nana], an herb layer of [Carex bigelowii] and [Carex globularis] with [Molinia caerulea], [Calamagrostis lapponica], [Calamagrostis purpurea], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Pedicularis lapponica], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Rubus chamaemorus], sphagna ([Sphagnum fuscum], [Sphagnum russowii]) and mosses ([Pleurozium schreberi], [Dicranum elongatum]), characteristic of subalpine and lower alpine levels.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 271: unit 3.5.1.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.2.1.2).');
    'Willow scrub of boreal and arctic Scandinavia formed of scattered dense stands of [Salix glauca], [Salix lapponum], [Salix phylicifolia] on extensive sphagnum lawns, constituting mire margin communities, with a species cortŠge that includes [Carex canescens], [Carex magellanica], [Carex rostrata], [Potentilla palustris], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Sphagnum fallax], [Sphagnum lindbergii], [Sphagnum riparium], [Sphagnum squarrosum], installed on thin peat of poor, acid fens of subalpine and lower alpine levels.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.5.1.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.2.1.4).');
    'Willow thickets or scrubs of neutrocline oligotrophic fens of the mountains of the boreal zone of the Palaearctic region, characteristically forming along fen margins, on their hummocks or strings, sometimes in their lawns, with an understorey of dwarf shrubs, herbs, mosses and sphagna.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.5.1.4, 3.5.1.5; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.3.1.4, 3.3.1.5).');
    'Willow scrub of boreal and arctic Scandinavia formed of 1-1.5 m high [Salix lapponum] and [Salix phylicifolia] with a species-rich herb layer characterized by the dominance or presence of [Equisetum palustre], [Carex nigra], [Juncus filiformis], [Viola epipsila] and [Viola palustris], accompanied by [Parnassia palustris], [Pyrola minor], [Ranunculus acris], [Agrostis canina], [Agrostis mertensii],  [Festuca ovina], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Carex dioica], [Carex canescens], [Luzula frigida], [Luzula sudetica], with a ground layer of [Climacium dendroides], [Drepanocladus exannulatum], [Drepanocladus uncinatus], [Polytrichum commuune], developed on mire margins or strings, in medium-rich fen conditions of pH 5.5-6.5 with flowing water, at subalpine and lower alpine levels.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.5.1.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.1.4).');
    'Willow scrub, 1-1.5 m high, of boreal and arctic Scandinavia, dominated by [Salix lapponum], with [Salix glauca], [Salix hastata], [Salix phylcifolia], [Betula nana], [Betula pubescens], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Andromeda polifolia], [Potentilla palustris], [Parnassia palustris], [Pedicularis lapponicum], [Pedicularis sceptrum-carolinum], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Saussurea alpina], [Saxifraga stellaris], [Viola biflora], [Viola epipsila], [Viola palustris], [Dechampsia cespitosa], [Calamagrostis stricta], [Carex aquatilis, [Carex canescens, [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex juncella], [Carex magellanica], [Carex rostrata], [Carex rotundata], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Eriophorum vaginata], [Equisetum fluviatile], [Calliergon stramineus], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Cinclidium subrotundum], [Sphagnum squarrosum, [Sphagnum teres] and [Sphagnum warnstorfii], developed at subalpine levels on both drier and wetter, relatively nutrient-poor, substrates, as mire margin lawn communities.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.5.1.5; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.1.5).');
    'Lauriphyllous forests of the Canary Islands, with [Laurus azorica], [Picconia excelsa], [Persea indica], [Ocotea foetens], [Apollonias barbujana], [Visnea mocanera], [Pleiomeris canariensis] ([Myrsine canariensis]), [Ardisia bahamensis], [Prunus lusitanica], [Sambucus palmensis], [Euphorbia mellifera], [Ixanthus viscosus], [Rubus bollei], [Convolvulus canariensis], [Geranium canariensis], [Hedera canariensis], [Smilax aspera], [Smilax canariensis], [Canarina canariensis], [Semele androgyna], [Sideritis macrostachys], [Sideritis canariensis], [Cryptotaenia elegans], [Rubia peregrina], [Carex canariensis], [Asparagus fallax] and many ferns. They are the habitat of the threatened endemic laurel pigeons [Columba junionae] and [Columba bollei], now limited to La Gomera, Tenerife and La Palma. The laurel forests of each island harbour a distinctive set of endemic plants and animals, as exemplified by the species of the composite genus [Pericallis], the well-marked races of the chaffinch [Fringilla coelebs] or the carabid faunas. They are thus best listed separately. The total remnant surface of laurel forest for the four islands, La Gomera, Tenerife, La Palma and Hierro, does not exceed 5000 ha.', '(Delvosalle, 1964; Machado, 1976; Schmid, 1976; Bramwell, 1976; Follmann, 1976; Bacallado, 1976; Ortuno and Ceballos, 1977; White, 1983; Bramwell and Bramwell, 1983; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988).');
    'Laurel forests of La Gomera, best preserved and most extensive of the archipelago, with large areas of humid [Persea indica] -[Laurus azorica] forests ([Lauro-Perseetum indicae]), particularly in high areas, and good examples of [Ocotea foetens]-dominated forests, hyperhumid and very rich in ferns and epiphytes ([Athyrio-Ocoteetum foetentis]). ', NULL);
    'Laurel forests of Tenerife, mostly restricted to the Anaga range and Los Silos, with a few smaller patches in Guimar ravines and at a few north slope sites in the La Esperanza-Agua Garcia area and the Barranco de San Antonio - Icod area. There are good representations of til ([Ocotea foetens]) forests (Anaga), as well as of drier [Picconia excelsa-Apollonias barbujana] forests (Los Silos). ', NULL);
    'Laurel forests of La Palma essentially restricted to a few large, deep ravines of the northern slope, particularly in the Las Sauces area, including both [Lauro-Perseetum] vinyatigo-laurel and [Athyrio-Ocoteetum] til stands. ', NULL);
    'Laurel forests of Hierro, very small and limited to cliff sides in the Ensenada El Golfo area of the north coast. ', NULL);
    'Laurel forests of Gran Canaria, extinct. Very small, but fully expressed, fragments existed until very recently, notably at Los Tiles, but now appear to have been totally degraded. ', NULL);
    'Woods, often riparian, formed by palm trees of the Mediterranean and Macaronesian zones, [Phoenix theophrasti] of Crete and western Anatolia, and [Phoenix canariensis] of the Canary Islands.', '(Polunin, 1980; Bramwell and Bramwell, 1983; Sfikas, 1984, 1987; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Latridis, 1988; Kassioumis, 1988; Serrada y al., 1988; Turland y al., 1993: 6; Santos Guerra, 1993: 55; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 17).');
    'Relict [Phoenix theophrasti] woods of Crete, restricted to damp sandy coastal valleys; they include the extensive forest of Vai, where the luxuriant palm growth is accompanied by a thick shrubby undergrowth rich in [Nerium oleander], and about four other smaller coastal groves, notably on the south coast of the prefectorate of Rethimnon.  ', '(Polunin, 1980; Sfikas, 1984, 1987; Latridis, 1988; Kassioumis, 1988; Turland y al., 1993: 6; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 17).');
    'Relict [Phoenix canariensis] woods of the Canary Islands, mostly characteristic of the bottom of barrancos and of alluvial soils, below 600 metres. Palm groves are now very rare, but still exist in all the islands, with particularly representative examples at Haria on Lanzarote, Vega del Rio Palmas on Fuerteventura, Fataga, Maspalomas and the Barranco de Tirajana in Gran Canaria, Valle Gran Rey in La Gomera, Masca in Tenerife and Brena Alta in La Palma. ', '(Bramwell and Bramwell, 1983; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988; Santos Guerra, 1993: 55).');
    'Relict [Phoenix theophrasti] woods of western Anatolia, restricted to a few coastal valleys.', NULL);
    'Woods dominated by tall arborescent [Ilex aquifolium]. They occur in the supra-Mediterranean level of Sardinia and Corsica and in Atlantic mountains of northwestern Spain, mostly as a facies of the relict yew-holly forests (unit 42.A7). Other scattered occurrences exist, in particular, in England, as a facies of Atlantic acidophilous beech-oak forests of unit 41.52, of Germano-Baltic beech forests of unit 41.121 or of Atlantic neutrophile beech forests of unit 41.132, in Scotland and in Ireland.', '(McVean, 1964a: 162; Fenaroli, 1970; Groppali y al., 1983; Gamisans, 1985; Pratesi and Tassi, 1986; Noirfalise, 1986, 1987; Rodwell, 1991a: 242, 252, 264, 270).');
