    'Multistrata broadleaved evergreen forests, of great species diversity, situated in the lowlands within hyperhumid, warm tropical climates lacking a dry or a cold season. Limited within the Palaearctic, as here defined, to southern Hainan and to very limited relicts on southern Taiwan and in extreme southern mainland China, in southern Guangxi and southern Yunnan.', '(Richards, 1952; Birot, 1970; Schnell, 1971a; Daubenmire, 1978; Letouzey, 1978, 1979; Whitmore, 1978, 1989, 1992; Walter, 1979; Baumgartner, 1979; Livingstone, 1979; Fontaine y al., 1979; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 43-44; Mei''e y al., 1985: 293-296, 305, 337-339 [i.a.]; Rieley and Page, 1990; MacKinnon and Collins, 1991: 117, 120-121, 123, 125; Walter and Breckle, 1991b; Huetz de Lemps, 1994; Archibold, 1995; Su, 1995: 198).');
    'Multistrata, species-rich, broadleaved forests of warm, very humid, tropical climates marked by seasonal moisture stress, composed of both evergreen and deciduous species in the upper storey. Species-richness in the canopy is less, gregarious occurrence is more prevalent, emergent trees are usually scarcer than in evergreen rain forests. Limited within the Palaearctic, as here defined, to Hainan, Taiwan, southern Guangxi and southern Yunnan.', '(Schnell, 1971a; Letouzey, 1978; Whitmore, 1978, 1989, 1992; Ehrenreich y al., 1982:  43-44; Mei''e y al., 1985: 293-296, 300-302, 306, 336-338 [i.a.]; Rieley and Page, 1990; Su, 1995: 198).');
    'Seasonal forests of humid tropical and subtropical regions with a very protracted dry season, particularly characteristic of monsoonal climates, characterized by a mostly deciduous upper canopy, a predominantly evergreen lower canopy and well-developed shrub and herb layers. Species diversity of canopy trees is much less than in either evergreen or semievergreen rain forests and single dominance frequent, in particular, in Southeast Asia by [Tectona grandis] or [Shorea robusta]; bamboos often play a dominant role in the shrub layer. Limited within the Palaearctic, as here defined, to Hainan,  and to limited relicts on southern Taiwan, in southern Guangxi, southern Yunnan and, very locally, extreme southern Tibet.', '(Schnell, 1971a; Letouzey, 1978; Whitmore, 1978, 1989, 1992; Ehrenreich y al., 1982:  43-44; Mei''e y al., 1985: 293-296, 303, 335-337, 456 [i.a.]; Rieley and Page, 1990; MacKinnon and Collins, 1991: 117, 120-121, 123, 125).');
    'Forests of the slopes of tropical mountains, less species-rich, lower, more even-canopied than lowland rain forests, richer in microphyllous, cool-adapted species, often loaded with bryophytes and ferns. Included are lower montane rain forests, upper montane rain forests, tropical coniferous woodland, montane bamboo woodland, elfin forest, tropical krummholz formations. Limited within the Palaearctic, as here defined, to Eritreo-Arabian communities of the southern Arabian peninsula and Egypt, and to montane formations of the tropical Far East, occurring in particular in very limited areas on Hainan and in southern Yunnan.', '(Schnell, 1971a; Zohary, 1973; Letouzey, 1978; Whitmore, 1978, 1989, 1992; Ehrenreich y al., 1982; Mei''e y al., 1985; Rieley and Page, 1990; MacKinnon and Collins, 1991: 117, 120-121, 125; Su, 1995; Doumenge y al., 1995; Hamilton y al., 1995; Long, 1995; Flenley, 1995; Ohsawa, 1995).');
