    'Communities of cold slow-flowing waters of the Alps and pre-Alpine regions, and of the mountains of Fennoscandia formed by [Typha minima], [Typha shuttleworthii], [Juncus alpinus] ([Juncus alpinoarticulatus]), [Juncus arcticus], [Juncus castaneus], [Equisetum variegatum].', '(Dierssen, 1978: 419; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 263-272, 306; Pott, 1992: 187-188; Steiner, 1993: 156-158; Julve, 1993: 75).');
    'Communities of cold slow-flowing waters of the Alps and pre-Alpine regions dominated by [Typha minima] or [Typha shuttleworthii], with [Juncus alpinus] ([Juncus alpinoarticulatus]), [Equisetum variegatum].', '(Dierssen, 1978: 419; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 271-272; Pott, 1992: 187-188; Steiner, 1993: 157; Julve, 1993: 75; Seliskar, 1998: 14).
');
    'Arctoalpine communities of the Alps, the peri-Alpine region, the Jura, the Slovakian Western Carpathians and the Fennoscandian mountains dominated by [Equisetum variegatum] with [Juncus alpinus] ([Juncus alpinoarticulatus]), by [Juncus alpinus] and [Carex lepidocarpa], by [Juncus arcticus] or by [Juncus castaneus].', '(Kopecky, 1987: 171, 176; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 263-267, 268-271, 306; Pott, 1992: 187; Steiner, 1993: 156, 157-158; Julve, 1993: 75).');
    'Rare communities of micaceous stony flushes of the Highlands of Scotland and of upper Teesdale, with [Carex atrofusca], [Carex microglochin], [Carex demissa], [Carex dioica], [Carex panicea], [Juncus triglumis], [Juncus biglumis], [Juncus castaneus], [Kobresia simpliciuscula], [Tofieldia pusilla], [Saxifraga aizoides], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Equisetum variegatum], [Equisetum hyemale] and the moss [Blindia acuta].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit I1c; Jermy y al., 1982; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M11 [p.]).');
    'Raised features of the palsa mires of the Palaearctic domaine constructed of peat around a permafrost core of ice and peat, colonized by ombrotrophic communities of dwarf shrubs, mosses, sphagna and lichens. They may take the shape of relatively low and flat ridges, 0.50 to 1.5 or 2.0 metres high, or higher domes, up to 8 metres in height. The first may be more characteristic of the continuous permafrost zone, the second of discontinuous permafrost zone where permafrost disappears under the mostly minerotrophic intervening hollows.', '(Salmi, 1970: 143-152; Schenk, 1970a: 157; Svensson, 1970: 161-164; Ruuhijärvi, 1970: 322-323; Schenk, 1970b: 338-339; Goodwillie, 1980: 10; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 60-62; Sjörs, 1983: 87; Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 112-113; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 213, 248-249; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 27-28; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 461-465, 486-487; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 182-185; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 215; Pakarinen, 1995: 30, 32).');
    'Palsa domes, ridges and plateaux of Fennoscandia, restricted to the low alpine, subalpine and sometimes upper conifer forest levels of the northern, arctoalpine, Fennoscandian mountains of Troms, Finnmark, Swedish and Finnish Lapland, with outposts on the Dovre plateau in the boreoalpine mountains of Norway, occupied by dwarf shrub communities composed mainly of [Betula nana], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Ledum palustre], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Vaccinium myrtillus], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], with [Vaccinium microcarpum], the mosses [Dicranum elongatum], [Polytrichum alpestre], [Pleurozium schreberi] and lichens, in particular of genus [Cladonia].', '(Salmi, 1970: 143-152; Schenk, 1970a: 157; Svensson, 1970: 161-164; Ruuhijärvi, 1970: 322-323; Schenk, 1970b: 338-339; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 60-62; Sjörs, 1983: 87; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 213, unit 3.2.1.5; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 182-185; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 215; Pakarinen, 1995: 30, 32).');
    'Palsa mounds of the periglacial arctoalpine highlands of central Iceland, 0.5-2.5 metres high, 2-10 metres long, 1-7 metres broad, surrounded by a narrow lake-like lagg or a minerotrophic mud-bottom mire, generally of the Icelandic [Carex rostrata]-[Carex rariflora] type (unit 54.6242), occupied, on the tops, by shrub communities dominated by [Empetrum hermaphroditum], with [Dryas octopetala], [Salix herbacea], [Armeria maritima], [Silene acaulis], [Kobresia myosuroides], the mosses [Drepanocladus uncinatus], [Rhacomitrium canescens], the sphagnum [Sphagnum teres] and the lichen [Cetraria islandica], and on the lower slopes by communities dominated by [Salix glauca] ssp. [callicarpaea] ([Salix arctica]), [Salix herbacea] and [Calamagrostis neglecta].', '(Goodwillie, 1980: 10; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.2.1.6).');
    'Palsa mounds, mostly 2-3 metres high and with no mineral core, restricted to the tundra and forested tundra zones of the northern Kola Peninsula, occupied by dwarf shrub communities composed mainly of [Betula nana], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Rubus chamaemorus], mosses, including [Dicranum congestum], [Dicranum elongatum], [Polytrichum alpestre], and lichens.', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 112). ');
    'Palsa mounds of the lower Pechora lowlands, located north of the Arctic circle, mostly in the forested tundra zone, partly in the shrub tundra zone, in a 100 km-wide belt from the east coast of the White Sea and the Kanin Peninsula to the mouth of the Usa River, forming ridges or domes, occupied by [Betula nana], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum] and [Rubus chamaemorus], with mosses, including [Dicranum spp.], [Polytrichum spp.], [Sphagnum fuscum], and lichens.', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 112-113).');
    'Palsa mounds of the northern taiga, forested tundra and southern tundra zones of the Kara coastlands and hinterland in the middle and upper reaches of the Usa River, and of southern Nova¿a Zemlia, varying from 0.5 m to 6 m in height, with a mineral core, occupied by communities composed of [Betula nana], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Rubus chamaemorus], mosses including [Hylocomium splendens], [Pleurozium schreberi], [Polytrichum strictum], [Sphagnum fuscum], [Sphagnum nemoreum], and lichens.', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 113).');
    'Palsa mounds of the northern taiga and southern forested tundra zones of the West Siberian plain, between the Ob and the Yenissei, 2-4 m high in the north, 6-8 m in the south, occupied by by dwarf shrub communities composed mainly of [Betula nana], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Rubus chamaemorus] and hypnoid and sphagnoid mosses, or with sparse [Betula pubescens], [Larix sibirica], [Pinus sibirica].', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 113).');
    'High palsa mounds, characteristically 4-8 m in height, of the middle Siberian northern taiga and forested tundra zones of the Yenissei, lower Tunguska and stony Tunguska basins and uplands, south to the mouth of the Angara, occupied by dwarf shrub communities composed mainly of [Betula nana], [Chamaedaphne calyculata], [Ledum palustre], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Sphagnum fuscum], [Sphagnum capillifolium] and lichens, commonly with a participation of trees, such as [Betula pubescens], [Larix sibirica], [Pinus sylvestris].', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 113).');
    'High hummocks of [Sphagnum fuscum] of palsa mires of the western palsa mire region of the Palaearctic domaine, often congregating in broad fields, resulting, like the palsa mounds, from frost action, but with a core in which the frost is only seasonal though long-lasting.', '(Schenk, 1970a: 157; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 62; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 213; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 464-465; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 215, unit 3.1.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Calcareous cliff communities of the Rhodopes with [Campanula orphanidea] ([Petkovia orphanidea]), [Saxifraga stribrnyi], [Scabiosa rhodopensis], [Sideritis scardica], [Seseli rhodopeum], [Haberlea rhodopensis], [Morina persica], [Trachelium jacquinii] ssp. [rumelianum] ([Trachelium rumelianum]), [Campanula lanata], [Sesleria rigida], [Ceterach officinarum].', '(Meshinev y al., 1995).');
    'Calcareous cliff communities of the Balkan Range.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 595-599).');
    'Very rare and restricted [Ramonda serbica] communities of cliffs of the foothills of the western Balkan range.', '(Velchev y al., 1973; Meshinev and Apostolova, 1994).');
    'Calcareous cliff communities of the Vrachaanska mountains in the western Balkan Range, developed around 1400 metres of altitude, with [Festuca balcanica] ssp. [balcanica], [Festuca xanthina], [Achnatherum calamagrostis], [Juniperus sabina], [Daphne oleoides], [Syringa vulgaris], [Saxifraga rocheliana], [Polygala murbeckii].', '(Velchev, 1971).');
    'Calcareous cliff communities of the Dinarides and the southwestern foothills of the eastern Carpathian system.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 595-599; Coldea, 1991).');
    'Cliff communities of calcareous rocks of the Dinarides, from Croatia to Montenegro, with [Micromeria croatica], and a number of specialized species of limited distribution, some of them narrow endemics, characterizing diverse communities, including the small western Balkanic borage shrub [Moltkia petraea], the Piva gorge [Daphne malyana], the crassulid [Jovibarba heuffelii], the saxifrages [Saxifraga marginata] ssp. [rocheliana], [Saxifraga paniculata], the cinqfoils [Potentilla clusiana], [Potentilla colescens] ssp. [persicina], the bellflowers [Campanula fenestrellata] ([Campanula garganica]), [Campanula pyramidalis].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 595-597).');
    'Calcareous cliff communities of the southwestern foothills of the eastern Carpathian system, in the south of the Banat and, in particular, the Danube Iron Gates gorge, with [Micromeria pulegium], [Athamanta turbith] ssp. [hungarica], [Dianthus kitaibelii], [Silene saxifraga] ssp. [petraea], [Erysimum comatum], [Campanula crassipes].', '(Coldea, 1991: 355-358, 361).');
    'Communities of humid cliffs of the northern Dinarides, subjected to tufa formation, with [Carex brachystachys], [Valeriana elongata], [Aster bellidiastrum], [Campanula cochlearifolia] ssp. [croatica].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 595-598).');
    'Communities of shady, cool, often moist rockfaces of the Dinarides and neighbouring regions, Balkano-Illyrian vicariant of the [Cystopteridion] communities of unit 62.152, widespread at the montane beech level, with many ferns, including [Cystopteris montana], [Asplenium ruta-muraria], [Asplenium trichomanes], and with [Corydalis ochroleuca], [Moehringia muscosa], [Cardaminopsis croatica], [Saxifraga rotundifolia], [Campanula justiniana]. ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 463-464; Mucina, 1993f: 252).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the plains and hills of nemoral northern and middle Europe, very species-poor, usually occupying small surfaces within the environment of more extensive communities of units 34.1 or 34.35.', '(Pott, 1992: 105; Oberdorfer, 1993a: 26-33; Julve, 1993: 27; Mucina, 1993f: 255-260).');
    'Species-poor pioneer communities of calcareous cliffs and rocks of the lowlands of middle and northern Europe dominated by ferns, in particular, [Asplenium ruta-muraria]-[Asplenium trichomanes] communities of limestone fissures known from the Jura, the Werra and Saale regions, the Sauerland Massenkalk, the Harz, Belgium, France, and the boreonemoral alvars of ¿land, Gotland and V¿sterg¿tland, [Asplenium lepidum] formations of eastern Central Europe, [Cystopteris fragilis] formations of more shady rocks.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 36, 37; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 5.1.5.1b; Pott, 1992: 105; Oberdorfer, 1993a: 29-30; Julve, 1993: 28; Mucina, 1993f: 257-258; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 5.1.5.1b; Schubert y al., 1995: 182).');
    'Species-poor pioneer communities of calcareous cliffs and rocks of the lowlands of middle Europe dominated by small forbs.', '(Mucina, 1993f: 257-258).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the boreal and arctic zones of the Palaearctic domaine.', '(Walter, 1974; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Calcareous rock and cliff crevice communities of the mountains and uplands of the boreal and arctic zones of the western Palaearctic domaine, in particular of the Fennoscandian mountains.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Calcareous cliff crevice and rock communities of the alpine belt of boreal Fennoscandia formed by [Asplenium viride], [Woodsia glabella] and many xerophytes. [Saxifraga cotyledon], [Potentilla hyparctica], [Potentilla chamisonis], [Potentilla pulchella], [Kobresia myosuroides] are typical of various communities.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 1.1.2.1, 1.1.2.1a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.2.1 [p.]).');
    'Hard or porous rocky surfaces and chaotic rock jumbles formed by solidified lava flows originating from volcanoes and fissures of the Palaearctic domaine, unvegetated, occupied by lichens or mosses, or colonized by specialized, relatively sparse herb- or shrub-dominated communities. They are restricted to the Mid-Atlantic ridge and its associated fracture zones, in Iceland and the Macaronesian islands, responsible for a large proportion of the volume of recent lava in the world, to the collision zones and constructive margins of southern Eurasia, in the Mediterranean and Tethyan basins along the folds of the Alpine system, to the Red Sea rim, on the Arabian peninsula, and to the western Pacific rim and island arcs. A range of surface characteristics is presented by lava of differing composition, viscosity and gas content, including pahoehoe or ropy lava, aa, scoria, pumice and pillow lava. A gradient of increasing acidity and viscosity extends from basalts through andesites and dacites to rhyolites. ', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 66-74, 77-79, 93-94; Whittow, 1984: 305; Bernhardt, 1986; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988; Machado, 1989; Krafft and de Larouzière, 1991: 26-30; Summerfield, 1991: 111-112, 35; Einarsson, 1994: 45-51; Waugh, 1995: 8-28; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Pleistocene lava flows, fields, dykes, necks, domes, cones of Iceland, concentrated in the neovolcanic zones that stretch along the Mid-Atlantic Ridge from northeast Iceland to the Reykjanes peninsula, branch south of it to the Vestmann Islands, and occupy the Snaefell peninsula.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 66-67, 93-94; Bernhardt, 1986; Krafft and de Larouzière, 1991: 133-218; Summerfield, 1991: 111-112, 35; Påhlsson, 1994; Einarsson, 1994: 45-51; Waugh, 1995: 8-28; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 64-65, 73-116).');
    'Lava flows, fields, dykes, necks, domes, cones of Iceland devoid of vegetation or sparsely vegetated by algae, lichens and mosses, which constitute the first stage of colonisation, with covers of up to 20-40%. The main constituents of the vegetation are the lichens [Stereocaulon vesubianum], [Stereocaulon alpinum], [Stereocaulon arcticum], [Alectoria ochroleuca], [Cladonia pyxidata], [Lecidea spp.], [Lecanora spp.] and the mosses [Grimnia spp.], [Andreaea rupestris], [Andreaea obovata], [Rhacomitrium canescans], [Polytrichum spp.] accompanied by a very few vascular plants, including [Festuca richardsonii], [Thymus praecox] ssp [arcticus], [Poa subcaerulea].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 66-67, 93-94; Bernhardt, 1986: 245-246; Krafft and de Larouzière, 1991: 26-30; Summerfield, 1991: 111-112, 35; Einarsson, 1994: 45-51; Waugh, 1995: 8-28; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 64-65, 73-116; Jakobsson y al., 2000; Thordarson, 2000).');
    'Lava flows and lava fields of Iceland covered by continuous carpets of [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] (unit 36.3223 [p.]), forming thick mantles that cover very large surfaces over all parts of the relief, engulfing asperities, bridging gaps, draping protruding rocks with large cushions, or else, in less evolved complexes, forming preferentially in the depressions and concavities where some organic matter accumulates. Together with similar formations of the basaltic uplands (unit 62.331 x 36.3223), these moss heaths constitute a particularly original landscape of Iceland.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Hadac, 1972: 350-357; Bernhardt, 1986: 246-247; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Heaths, scrubs or low birch woods colonizing parts of lava flows and lava fields of Iceland, mostly in hollows where loess accumulates, within the [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] carpets of unit 66.312. [Empetrum spp.], [Arctostaphylos uva-ursi], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Betula nana] are the main heath components. At a later stage, [Betula pubescens] ssp. [czerepanovii] may invade and form scrubs and thickets. Subdivisions of division 3, in particular, of units 31.2113 and 31.4551, and of unit 41.B71, may be used in conjunction with unit 66.313 to describe the formations.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Bernhardt, 1986: 246; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Communities colonizing fissures, cracks, overhangs and cave entrances formed in lava flows and lava fields of Iceland, and on the faces of dykes, stacks and other surfaces protruding from them.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Blazkova, 1973: 225-230; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Bryophyte-dominated communities colonizing fissures or cavities  of lava flows and lava fields of Iceland, in particular, sciaphile communities of [Distichium capillaceum], [Pohlia cruda], [Mnium marginatum], [Timmia austriaca], [Bartramia ityphylla], [Mnium stellare], [Plagiothecium roeseanum] and [Cystopteris fragilis] characteristic of loess-collecting lava vesicular cavities and of shady ledges.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Blazkova, 1973: 225-230).');
    'Sparse vascular plant communities colonizing fissures and cracks of lava flows and lava fields of Iceland, and the faces of dykes, stacks and other surfaces protruding from them. Codes of division 62, in particular, of units 62.1C and 62.2A can be combined with unit 66.314 to further define the community.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Påhlsson, 1994).');
    'Lava flows, fields, dykes, necks, domes, cones of the Azores, the Canary Islands and the Cape Verde Islands.', '(Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 66-67, 94; Whittow, 1984: 305; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988; Machado, 1989; Krafft and de Larouzière, 1991: 425-447; Summerfield, 1991: 111-112, 35; Waugh, 1995: 8-28).');
    'Western Palaearctic fen communities dominated by [Sesleria caerulea], recorded, in particular, from peri-Pannonic regions, from the Bohemian Quadrangle, from the eastern Germano-Baltic plain and from the Eastern Carpathians where they constitute rare formations developed on the margins of  meso-eutrophic fens of the Brasov depressions, with an abundance of [Carex hostiana], [Carex panicea], [Phragmites australis], [Cirsium rivulare], [Equisetum palustre], [Sanguisorba officinalis], [Galium boreale], [Campylium stellatum].', '(Soo, 1980: 527; Moravec y al., 1983: 39; Korotkov y al., 1991: 260-261; Chifu y al., 1991).');
    'Rich [Carex atrofusca]-dominated fen communities of the lower alpine level    of boreoalpine and arctoalpine mountains of Fennoscandia, on calcareous substrates with near-surface ground water and relatively high pH; peat production is usually low and mineral earth can be bare. The species cortŠge typically includes [Carex vaginata], [Carex capillaris], [Carex parallela], [Carex dioica], [Carex bigelowii], [Juncus triglumis], [Juncus biglumis], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Saxifraga aizoides], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Tofieldia pusilla], [Salix reticulata], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Campylium stellatum].', '(Dierssen, 1978: 419; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4h; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.2.2).');
    'Pioneer communities colonizing neutral or basic gravelly, sandy, stony soil soaked by cold water on calcareous substrates of Greenland, with [Carex bicolor], [Carex microglochin], [Carex atrofusca], [Carex vaginata], [Carex saxatilis], [Carex capillaris], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex rupestris], [Carex parallela], [Kobresia simpliciuscula], [Juncus castaneus], [Juncus biglumis], [Tofieldia pusilla], [Saxifraga aizoides], [Saxifraga nathorstii], [Brachythecium turgidum], [Catoscopium nigritum], [Scorpidium turgescens], [Campylium stellatum], [Hypnum bambergeri].', '(Dierssen, 1978: 419; Fredskild, 1998, 2000). ');
