    'Topogenous or soligenous valley, basin or spring mire systems fed by waters poor in bases. As in the rich fens, the water level is at or near the surface of the substratum and peat formation is infra-aquatic. The mire communities themselves, dominated by small sedges and brown mosses or sphagna, belong to the [Caricetalia fuscae], but, in large fen systems, they are accompanied by acidocline wet grasslands ([Molinietalia caeruleae]), large sedge beds ([Magnocaricion]) and reed or related communities ([Phragmition]). Sphagnum hummocks (unit 51.11) form locally and transition mires (unit 54.5) or aquatic (unit 22.3), amphibian (unit 22.2) and spring (unit 54.1) communities colonize small depressions. Thus, codes from all the above categories are used in conjunction with the ones below to completely describe the fen. The subdivisions listed here are, in any case, understood to include, besides strict mire communities, their transitions to humid grasslands, and groupings phytosociologically affiliated with [Molinion] associations, but rich in species of the [Caricion fuscae], provided they are integrated in a fen system (somewhat paralleling the [Junco acutiflori-Caricetalia nigrae] of Rameau [et al.], 1989). Acidic fen communities also occur on small surfaces or within mosaics in other ecosystems, in particular in typical humid grasslands (37), humid woodlands and thickets (44), decalcified dune slacks (unit 16.3) and spring systems (unit 54.1). Their presence can be indicated by codes from this unit used in conjunction with the relevant main codes. Characteristic species of acidic mire communities are [Carex canescens], [Carex echinata], [Carex nigra], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Eriophorum scheuchzeri], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Juncus filiformis], [Agrostis canina], [Viola palustris], [Cardamine pratensis], [Ranunculus flammula] and the mosses [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Calliergon stramineum], [Calliergon cuspidatum], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Drepanocladus fluitans], [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum auritum], [Sphagnum cuspidatum], [Sphagnum subsecundum], [Sphagnum apiculatum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum russowii].', '(Duvigneaud, 1949; Braun-Blanquet, 1954, 1971a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Berset, 1969; Schumacker and Froment, 1971; Parent, 1973; Horvat y al., 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Schumacker, 1976; Wattez, 1976; Schumacher, 1977; Brasseur y al., 1977; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Brasseur y al., 1978; Dierssen, 1978; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Goodwillie, 1980; Ratcliffe, 1980; Sanda y al., 1980; Fernandez Prieto, 1983; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983; Moravec y al., 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Bournérias, 1984; Ochsenbein, 1984a, 1984b; Gamisans, 1985, 1991; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Martinez Parras and Peinado Lorca, 1987; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1987; Martinez Parras y al., 1987; Rameau y al., 1989; Salomez, 1990; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Oberdorfer, 1990; Elias y al., 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991; Coldea, 1991; Rodwell, 1991b: 22-24; Steiner, 1992; Oberdorfer, 1992a; Pott, 1992; Julve, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 216; Pakarinen, 1995; Schubert y al., 1995; Ilijanic, 1996: 108; Hoda y al., 1998: 7).');
    'Swards of [Eriophorum scheuchzeri] of Palaearctic boreal fens and of acidic lake shores in the Alps and the eastern Carpathians.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 95; Braun-Blanquet, 1954: 28-29; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 428; Braun-Blanquet, 1971a; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Dierssen, 1978: 418;  Sanda y al., 1980: 50; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Coldea, 1991: 424-428; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 234-239; Pott, 1992: 179; Steiner, 1992: 144-145; Julve, 1993: 75; Påhlsson, 1994; Mossberg y al., 1995: 605).');
    'Almost pure swards of [Eriophorum scheuchzeri] fringing small, cold, acidic lakes above the tree limit in the Alps and the Eastern Carpathians. They are related to both the boreal communities of unit 54.412 and to the arctoboreal marsh-fens of unit 54.71.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 95; Braun-Blanquet, 1954: 28-29; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 428; Braun-Blanquet, 1971a; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Dierssen, 1978: 418;  Sanda y al., 1980: 50; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Coldea, 1991: 424-428; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 234-239; Pott, 1992: 179; Steiner, 1992: 144-145; Julve, 1993: 75).');
    'Pools, hollows and laggs of palsa mires of the subarctic and northern boreal zone of the Palaearctic domaine, mostly inundated, minerotrophic or partly minerotrophic, acidocline to basicline. They are predominantly colonized by transition mire communities of unit 54.5 or mud-bottom communities of unit 54.62.', '(Salmi, 1970: 143-152; Svensson, 1970: 161-164; Goodwillie, 1980: 10; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 60-62; Sjörs, 1983: 87; Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 112-113; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 213; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 27-28; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 461-465, 486-487; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 182-185; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 215; Pakarinen, 1995: 30, 32).');
    'Pools, hollows and laggs of palsa mires of the subarctic and northern boreal zone of the Palaearctic domaine colonized by mud-bottom communities of unit 54.62.', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 60-62; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 213, unit 3.6.3 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 461-465, 486-487; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 215).');
    'Pools, hollows and laggs of palsa mires of the subarctic and northern boreal zone of the Palaearctic domaine colonized by transition mire communities of unit 54.5. Characteristic species include [Eriophorum russeolum], [Eriophorum angustifolum], [Carex limosa], [Carex rotundata], [Carex rostrata], [Carex aquatilis], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Potentilla palustris], [Sphagnum lindbergii], [Sphagnum majus], [Sphagnum fimbriatum], [Sphagnum girgensohnii], [Sphagnum riparium], [Sphagnum obtusum], [Sphagnum squarrosum], [Sphagnum flexuosum], [Drepanocladus vernicosus].', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 60-62; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 213, unit 3.6.2.2 [p.]; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 461-465, 486-487; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 215, unit 3.3.3.1 [p.]).');
    'Complex mires of the Arctic and subarctic zones of the Palaearctic domaine  patterned by a surface microrelief of large, 10 to 30 metres in diameter, low-centre or high-centre polygons formed by the juxtaposition of dry, 0.3 to 0.5 metres high, ridges covered by shrubs, hypnoid mosses and sphagna, and of wet hollows occupied by grasses, sedges, mosses and sphagna. They are distributed, mostly in the tundra and forested tundra zones, from Va¿gatch Island and the Yugorskiy peninsula to the Chukotka peninsula.', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1970: 322-323; Walter, 1974: 31-40; Botch and Masing, 1983: 107-112, 125; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 70, 182).');
    'Ridges and flat tops of polygons of polygon mires of the Arctic and subarctic zones of the Palaearctic domaine, covered by shrubs, hypnoid mosses and sphagna.', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 107-112, 125; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 70, 182).');
    'Ridges and flat tops of polygons of polygon mires of the Arctic zone of the Palaearctic domaine occupied by mostly graminoid communities, formed of sedges, woodrushes and grasses, with willows, in particular, [Salix pulchra], [Salix reptans], mosses, notably [Aulacomnium palustre], [Aulacomnium turgidum], [Homalothecium nitens], and the sphagna [Sphagnum fimbriatum], [Sphagnum girgensohnii].', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 109).');
    'Ridges and flat tops of polygons of polygon mires of the northern subarctic zone of the Palaearctic domaine formed by the dwarf willows [Salix pulchra] and [Salix reptans], by [Dryas punctata], by the sedge [Carex stans], by grasses, in particular, [Arctagrostis latifolia], by mosses, notably [Aulacomnium palustre], [Aulacomnium turgidum], [Homalothecium nitens], [Hylocomium splendens] and by [Sphagnum fimbriatum].', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 111).');
    'Ridges and flat tops of polygons of polygon mires of the southern subarctic zone of the Palaearctic domaine formed by the dwarf shrubs [Betula nana], [Ledum decumbens], [Vaccinium vitis-idaea], [Rubus chamaemorus], the mosses [Dicranum spp.], [Polytrichum strictum], and the sphagna [Sphagnum lenense], [Sphagnum nemoreum].', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 111-112).');
    'Hollows and cracks of polygon mires of the Arctic and subarctic zones of the Palaearctic domaine, occupied by the grasses [Arctophila fulva], [Dupontia fischeri], the sedges [Carex stans], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex rariflora], [Carex rotundata], the hypnoid mosses [Drepanocladus spp.], [Mnium spp.] and the sphagna [Sphagnum balticum], [Sphagnum majus]. ', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 107-112, 125; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 70, 182).');
    'Mires of the arid Central Asian mountains, in particular, of the Tyan Shan and the Pamir, of the Tibetan plateau and of the Himalyan system.', '(Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 47; Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 132, 141; Lu, 1995).');
    'Mires of the continental regions of Siberia and the Far East, in particular, of the Central Siberian plateau, of northeast Siberia, of south Yakutia, of the Angara, of northern Dahuria, of Mongolia, of the Amur lowlands and of continental China, together with those of the Altai and Sayn mountains.', '(Botch and Masing, 1983: 110, 124-126, 130-131; Lu, 1995).  ');
