    'Lava flows, fields, dykes, necks, domes, cones of the Azores, the Canary Islands and the Cape Verde Islands, unvegetated, occupied by usually discontinuous communities dominated by algae, lichens or mosses, sometimes colonized by very sparse vascular plants. Barren lava fields of Fuerteventura, Lobos and Lanzarote are the main habitat of the endemic and vulnerable Canary Shrew, [Crocidura canariensis].', '(Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 66-67, 94; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988; Machado, 1989; Hutterer, 1999: 62-63).');
    'Lava flows, fields, dykes, necks, domes, cones of the Azores, the Canary Islands and the Cape Verde Islands, occupied by open or closed communities dominated by herbs, shrubs or trees, in particular, of units 31.7F, 31.31, 31.846, 32.8, 42.9, 42.A8, 45. Codes of these units can be combined with 66.322 to define habitats.', '(Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 66-67, 94; Whittow, 1984: 305; Wildpret de la Torre and del Arco Aguilar, 1987; Serrada y al., 1988; Machado, 1989; Krafft and de Larouzière, 1991: 26-30; Summerfield, 1991: 111-112, 35; Waugh, 1995: 8-28).');
