    'Acidic fen communities of lowland, collinar and montane areas of western and northern Central Europe, excluding the British Isles and the Iberian peninsula, extending eastward in the Baltic plain to Lithuania. [Carex nigra], [Carex canescens] and [Carex echinata] are always represented, often accompanied by dispersed [Carex rostrata]. Rushes, [Juncus filiformis], [Juncus articulatus], [Juncus acutiflorus], [Juncus effusus], may be numerous, often marking the transition towards humid grasslands of the [Molinietalia], the moss layer is formed by [Sphagnum apiculatum], [Sphagnum cuspidatum], [Sphagnum recurvum] and [Polytrichum commune] in the more oligotrophic, acidic sites, by brown mosses [Drepanocladus fluitans], [Calliergon stramineum], [Calliergon cuspidatum], in more mesotrophic situations. Other characteristic species include [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Eriophorum vaginatum], [Agrostis canina], [Molinia caerulea], [Pedicularis palustris], [Viola palustris], [Parnassia palustris], [Comarum palustre], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Ranunculus flammula] and [Willemetia stipitata]. Included in this unit are the extensive peatlands of Hercynian valley fens, often invaded by rushes, and with characters both of the transition mires and of the humid grasslands.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 94; Lebrun y al., 1949: units 115, 116 [p.]; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 320; Schumacker and Froment, 1971; Parent, 1973; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Schumacker, 1976; Wattez, 1976; Schumacher, 1977; Brasseur y al., 1977: 51-52; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Brasseur y al., 1978: 41-42; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Goodwillie, 1980; Lembrechts and Van Straaten, 1982: 346-347; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Bournérias, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Korotkov y al., 1991: 258; Pott, 1992: 181-182; Julve, 1993: 71; Schubert y al., 1995: 246).');
    'Sedge-dominated acidic fen formations in which [Carex canescens], accompanied by [Agrostis canina], is often the most abundant, with a brown moss layer that can sometimes be very partial; [Carex nigra], [Carex echinata] and [Carex magellanica] facies also occur.  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 150; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 199; De Sloover y al., 1980: 70-71; Thoen and Schmidt, 1984: 137-139; Frankard y al., 1998: 36).');
    'Acidic fen formations in which [Carex nigra], [Carex canescens], [Carex echinata] and sometimes [Carex rostrata] are accompanied by, and sometimes dominated by, abundant rushes, in particular [Juncus filiformis] and [Juncus acutiflorus], and with a pleurocarpic moss layer.  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 115, 116, [p.]; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 199; Frankard y al., 1998: 38).');
    'Sphagnum peatlands in which the herbaceous sward is formed by [Carex nigra], [Carex canescens], [Carex echinata] and [Carex rostrata], generally with [Eriophorum angustifolium] and [Eriophorum vaginatum]. These very wet formations are closely related to transition mires.  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 115 [p.]).');
    'Sphagnum peatlands in which the herbaceous sward is formed by [Carex nigra], [Carex canescens], [Carex echinata], [Carex rostrata] and abundant rushes, in particular [Juncus filiformis] and [Juncus acutiflorus], generally with [Eriophorum angustifolium] and [Eriophorum vaginatum]. These formations are often related to wet grasslands.  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 115, 116, [p.]).');
    'Sphagnum peatlands in which the herbaceous sward is formed by [Agrostis canina] ssp. [stolonifera], often with [Carex rostrata] or [Eriophorum angustifolium]; the muscinal layer being usually formed by [Sphagnum recurvum] with [Polytrichum commune].  ', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 115 [p.]; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 62-63; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Zarnowiec y al., 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991: 258; Dyduch-Falniowska, 1992).');
    'Acidic sphagnum fens of the British Isles in which the herbaceous sward is formed by [Carex echinata], [Carex canescens], [Carex nigra] or [Carex rostrata] and sometimes [Juncus effusus], [Juncus acutiflorus] or [Nardus stricta].  ', '(Ratcliffe, 1980; Rodwell, 1991b: 22-24, units M6, M7). ');
    'Acidic sphagnum fens of the British Isles dominated by [Carex canescens], [Carex echinata], [Carex nigra], [Carex panicea], [Carex demissa], [Carex rostrata], with [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum russowii].  ', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3b; Rodwell, 1991b: units M6a, M6b). ');
    'Acidic sphagnum fens of the British Isles physiognomically dominated by [Juncus effusus] and [Juncus acutiflorus], with [Carex echinata], [Carex nigra], [Agrostis stolonifera], [Sphagnum recurvum], [Polytrichum commune].  ', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: units H2a, H2b; Rodwell, 1991b: units M6c, M6d). ');
    'Very local fens of the high Scottish Highlands, with [Carex echinata], [Carex nigra], [Carex bigelowii], [Carex aquatilis], [Carex rariflora], [Saxifraga stellaris], [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum lindbergii], [Sphagnum riparium], [Sphagnum russowii].  ', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3h; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M7). ');
    '[Carex] acidic fens of the Pyrenees, mostly dominated by [Carex nigra], with [Carex echinata] or [Carex panicea], very similar to those of the Alps, in particular to the floristically rather impoverished southwestern Alpine communities, sometimes dominated by [Carex rostrata], with [Carex canescens] ([Carex curta]) or [Carex echinata] and [Agrostis canina].  ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 94; Gruber, 1978; Vanden Berghen and Peeters, 1982: 186-187; Dupias, 1985: 161; Vigo and Ninot, 1987: 382).');
