    'Terrestrialization formations of [Carex appropinquata] ([Carex paradoxa]), alone or mixed with [Carex paniculata], essentially of mesotrophic, basicline peaty or mineral soils of the Palaearctic domaine.  ', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Horvat y al., 1974; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Dethioux, 1982; Moravec y al., 1983: 33; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 79; Korotkov y al., 1991: 31; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 98; Mossberg y al., 1995: 612; Trpin and Vres, 1995: 29).');
    'Terrestrialization formations of Palaearctic lakes, ponds and swamps dominated by [Carex diandra].', '(Moravec y al., 1983: 33; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989: 267-268; Balatova-Tulackova y al., 1993: 100; Trpin and Vres, 1995: 29; Overal, 1996a: 101).');
    'Spring communities of montane, sometimes collinar, lowland or subalpine, well-lit, lime-poor waters of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by mosses, in particular, [Philonotis fontana], with [Epilobium nutans], [Epilobium obscurum], [Epilobium palustre], [Epilobium parviflorum], [Montia fontana], [Stellaria alsine], [Galium uliginosum], [Ranunculus repens], [Veronica beccabunga], [Equisetum fluviatile].', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 191; Schumacher, 1977; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; Moravec y al., 1983: 37; Hadac, 1983: 342-345; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 75; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991b: 29, unit M35; Coldea, 1991: 412-416; Pott, 1992: 168-169; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 205; Zechmeister, 1993: 220-222; Schubert y al., 1995: 218).');
    'Spring communities of montane, sometimes collinar, lowland or subalpine well-lit, lime-poor waters of the Alpine system, the western and central European Hercynian ranges and neighbouring regions dominated by mosses, in particular, by [Philonotis fontana], with [Bryum pseudotriquetum], [Calliergonella cuspitata], [Dicranella palustris], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Galium palustre], [Montia fontana], [Stellaria alsine].', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 71; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 191; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 105; Schumacher, 1977; Bournérias, 1979, 1984; De Sloover y al., 1980: 69; Moravec y al., 1983: 37; Hadac, 1983: 343-345; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 75; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992: 168-169; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 205; Zechmeister, 1993: 220-222; Schubert y al., 1995: 218; Frankard y al., 1998: 39).');
    'Spring mires of soft-water springs of warm, oceanic, western lowlands of Britain, with an often crowded cover of vascular plants and bryophytes, formed by [Ranunculus omiophyllus], [Montia fontana], [Ranunculus flammula], [Potamogeton polygonifolius], [Sphagnum auriculatum], [Philonotis fontana].', '(Rodwell, 1991b: 29, unit M35).');
    'Bryophyte dominated spring communities of alpine, subalpine, boreoalpine, arctoalpine, and sometimes upland, well-lit, lime-poor cold waters of the northern Palaearctic mountains and hills, of the Alpine system and of the great Hercynian ranges, mostly dominated by [Philonotis seriata], [Bryum schleicheri] or, in the north and west, [Philonotis fontana], with a vascular species cortŠge marked by arcto-alpine species, among which [Saxifraga stellaris] is usually prominent. Somewhat intermediate between the communities of unit 54.1111 and those of units 54.1113 and 54.1114, they extend to relatively low upland regions in northern Europe, in the British isles, and, as glacial relicts, in the Hercynian ranges and their periphery.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 430-431; Hadac, 1971a: 30-32; Horvat y al., 1974: 631; Moravec y al., 1983: 37; Hadac, 1983: 345-350; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 75; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Hadac, 1985a; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991b: 29, units M32, M34; Coldea, 1991: 412-416; Pott, 1992: 168; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 203-204; Zechmeister, 1993: 223-224; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.5.1.1, 3.5.1.2, 3.5.1.3, 3.5.1.3a).');
    'Bryophyte dominated communities of cold, oxygen-rich, soft-water springs of the lower, middle and upper alpine zones of the boreoalpine and arctoalpine mountains of Fennoscandia, formed by [Philonotis fontana], with [Pohlia drummondii] and [Scapania uliginosa], accompanied by a sparse formation of vascular plants, most prominent of which are [Ranunculus nivalis] and [Saxifraga stellaris]; the species cortŠge may also include [Carex lachenalii], [Cerastium cerastoides], [Juncus biglumis], [Oxyria digyna], [Poa alpina] ssp. [vivipara], [Ranunculus pygmaeus], [Saxifraga aizoides], [Saxifraga cernua], [Veronica alpina] and, in Finnmark, [Ranunculus sulphureus]. The [Philonotis] spring communities of this unit border onto the [Saxifraga oppositifolia]-[Oxyria digyna] snow-patch communities of unit 36.12364. Some bryophyte spring communities of boreal Fennoscandia are dominated by [Drepanocladus exannulatus] and/or [Sphagnum lindbergii], with [Sphagnum riparium], [Sphagnum teres], a sparse representation of [Philonotis seriata], and an absence of [Cratoneuron spp.]. The sparse vascular plant component may include individuals of [Andromeda polifolia], [Equisetum hornemannii], [Equisetum sylvaticum], [Salix glauca]; there is an absence of wet-fen species typical of other spring communities. These communities may be transitional towards the communities of unit 54.1111.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.6.2.a, 3.6.6.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.5.1.3, 3.5.1.1 [p.]).');
