    'Moss carpets, often thick and extensive, developed over more or less level surfaces of rock or erosional rock debris accumulations of lowlands, hills and mountains of boreal, boreo-nemoral or arctic regions of the Palaearctic, particularly characteristic of basaltic, siliceous, or sometimes calcareous, summits and plateaux of the North-Atlantic, in Iceland, the Faeroes, Scotland and, locally, the Scandinavian mountains, northern England and northern Wales, Greenland, Spitzbergen. These moss-heaths, dominated by [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] or [Rhacomitrium canescens] (unit 62.331 x 36.322), constitute, together with the lava-field formations of unit 66.312 (unit 66.312 x 36.3223), one of the most original landscapes of Iceland and the North Atantic.', '(McVean, 1964e; Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 82-85; Pearsall, 1971: 80-85; Påhlsson, 1994; Gudjonsson and Gislason, 1998).');
