    'Spring mires of calcareous, often petrifying, springs of the Palaearctic domaine. Their specialized communities, usually dominated by bryophytes, belong to the [Cratoneurion commutati]. Characteristic species are the mosses [Cratoneuron filicinum], [Cratoneuron commutatum], [Cratoneuron commutatum] var. [falcatum], [Catoscopium nigritum], [Eucladium verticillatum], [Gymnostomum recurvirostrae], with [Equisetum telmateia], [Equisetum variegatum] and flowering plants including [Cochlearia pyrenaica], [Arabis soyeri], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Saxifraga aizoides]. The associated swamp communities belong to the [Caricetalia davallianae] and their presence can be recorded by the use, simultaneously with one of the codes of 54.12, of a code of 54.2. Large petrifying springs form tufa cones that constitute singular habitats with several interacting plant and animal communities; they have thus been individualized below.', '(Symoens y al., 1951; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 430-431; Braun-Blanquet y al., 1964b: 36; Parent, 1973: 96-109; Horvat y al., 1974: 492-495, 631, 654; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 193-194; Braun-Blanquet, 1978a: 115-117; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Bournérias, 1979, 1984: 224; Soo, 1980: 527; Moravec y al., 1983: 37-38; Hadac, 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 75; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Korotkov y al., 1991: 252-253; Elias y al., 1991; Rodwell, 1991b: 29, units M37, M38; Coldea, 1991: 413-415, 416-417; Pott, 1992: 171-173; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 209-212; Ruzickova y al., 1992: 103; Zechmeister, 1993: 229-236; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.5.2.1 [p.], 3.5.2.2, 3.5.2.2a, 3.5.2.3; Drachenfels, 1994: 90-92; Schubert y al., 1995: 218-220; Müller, 1998: Annex 5).');
    'Communities of calcareous, petrifying springs of the Alps, the pre-Alpine regions and of the middle European Hercynian ranges and their periphery, forming and colonizing large tufa deposits. When active, tufa springs comprise a hydrosere in which the [Cratoneurion] plants, and in particular, [Cratoneuron spp.], are accompanied by fen species such as [Carex lepidocarpa] and [Sesleria caerulea]; the latter may physiognomically dominate both the hydrosere and the adjacent xerosere, developed on fossil tufa deposits, in which it is accompanied by [Brometalia] plants.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 44, 45; Symoens y al., 1951: 339-350; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 430-431; Parent, 1973: 96-109; Moravec y al., 1983: 37-38; Pott, 1992: 171-173; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 209-213; Stewart and Church, 1992: 36; Zechmeister, 1993: 229-236; Schubert y al., 1995: 218-220; Seliskar, 1998: 14).');
    'Tufa springs of Alpine and Hercynian regions in which the main building components are mosses of genus [Cratoneuron], generally [Cratoneuron commutatum], sometimes [Cratoneuron filicinum] or an association of both.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: units 44, 45; Symoens y al., 1951: 339-350; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 430-431; Parent, 1973: 96-109; Moravec y al., 1983: 38; De Sloover and Goosens, 1984: 40-43; Duvigneaud and Saintenoy-Simon, 1991; Duvigneaud and Saintenoy-Simon, 1992; Pott, 1992: 171-173; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 209-212; Zechmeister, 1993: 229-236; Schubert y al., 1995: 219; Seliskar, 1998: 14).');
    'Tufa springs in which the main tufa forming species is the moss [Catoscopium nigritum], apparently limited to the northern Alpine piedmont, where they are rare, to the calcareous Alps, where they may be somewhat commoner, and to the  mid-German ranges, where they are extremely rare and endangered, recorded from  the Rh¿n.', '(Oberdorfer, 1992a: 213; Zechmeister, 1993: 229-236; Schubert y al., 1995: 220).');
    'Tufa springs and tufa seeps in which the main building component is the moss [Eucladium verticillatum], a former of travertine, uncommon, recorded from localities scattered between northern Germany, southern Belgium and the Alpine regions, mostly on steep, rocky slopes.', '(Symoens y al., 1951: 345-346, 348; De Sloover and Goosens, 1984: 39-42; Pott, 1992: 172; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 213; Duvigneaud and Saintenoy-Simon, 1992; Zechmeister, 1993: 229-236; Schubert y al., 1995: 219).');
    'Tufa springs in which the main building components are algae, in particular, [Scytonema myochrous], [Scytonema mirabile], [Nostoc verrucosum], associated with the moss [Eucladium verticillatum], known from Alpine and peri-Alpine regions and from the periphery of the Hercynian ranges.', '(De Sloover and Goosens, 1984: 39, 42-45; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 213; Zechmeister, 1993: 235-236).');
    'Communities of calcareous springs, seeps and flushes of the nemoral and lowland boreal western Palaearctic domaine in which tufa formation is absent or limited to encrustation of the constituting mosses without building of large deposits. They are characteristic of high altitudes, maritime climates and semishaded stations, all situations unfavourable to tufa formation.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 430-431; Braun-Blanquet y al., 1964b: 36; Horvat y al., 1974:  631, 654; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 193-194; Braun-Blanquet, 1978a: 115-117; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Bournérias, 1979, 1984: 224; Soo, 1980: 527; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit I4e; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 75; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Page, 1988: 321-322, 384-386; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Rodwell, 1991b: 29, units M37, M38; Coldea, 1991: 413-415, 416-417; Pott, 1992: 171-173; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 209-212; Ruzickova y al., 1992: 103; Zechmeister, 1993: 229-236; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.5.2.1 [p.], 3.5.2.2, 3.5.2.3; Drachenfels, 1994: 90-92; Schubert y al., 1995: 218-220).');
    'Mire communities of boreal regions of the Palaearctic domaine, in particular of the subalpine and lower alpine levels of Fennoscandian mountains, with a sphagnum ground layer dominated by [Sphagnum lindbergii] and a field layer dominated by [Scirpus cespitosus], occupying sites within a wide nutrient range, the deergrass being especially abundant in rich fen situations. Accompanying species that may occur with varying frequency include sedges, [Carex limosa], [Carex pauciflora], [Carex rariflora], [Carex rotundata], [Eriophorum vaginatum], which may dominate or codominate, and dicots, [Andromeda polifolia], [Betula nana], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Empetrum hermaphroditum], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Vaccinium microcarpa]; the bryophyte cortŠge includes [Caliergon stramineum], [Drepanocladus badius], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum tenellum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.2.1e; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.2.3.4).');
    '[Carex dacica] ([Carex nigra] ssp. [dacica]) acidic fens of the northwestern Caucasus, with [Primula auriculata].', '(Korotkov y al., 1991: 258-259).');
    'Wetlands mostly or largely occupied by peat-forming plant communities developed at the surface of oligotrophic or meso-oligotrophic water reaching a level above, sometimes well above, the substratum, providing little or no mineral or nutrient supply. Their characteristics are thus intermediate between those of soligenous and topogenous mires and those of strictly ombrogenous bogs. In large systems, the most prominent communities are swaying swards, floating carpets or quaking mires formed by medium sized or small sedges, associated with sphagna or brown mosses. They are accompanied by aquatic and amphibious communities (units 22.3, 22.4) and by formations transitional to these on the one hand, to fens (units 54.2, 54.4), bogs (unit 51.1) or humid grasslands (37) on the other; sphagnum buttes (units 51.11), in particular, are often an important feature. Tall sedge and reed communities (53), willow and alder carrs (44) invade part of the peatland. Transition mires form mostly as colonists of oligotrophic ponds and lakes, large bog pools or laggs. Their distribution is mostly northern peri-Alpine, peri-Hercynian and northern European. Outside of transition mire systems, their communities can be found in bog hollows (unit 51.12), in blanket bogs (52), in depressions of rich or acidic fens (units 54.2, 54.4), in spring systems (unit 54.1), in humid heaths (unit 31.1) and a few other habitats. Characteristic species include [Eriophorum gracile], [Carex lasiocarpa], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex limosa], [Scheuchzeria palustris], [Hammarbya paludosa], [Liparis loeselii], [Calla palustris]. Transition mires are an extremely important refuge of specialized, threatened species of both plants and animals; their richness and diversity in remarkable invertebrates, dragonflies among others, is even greater than that of most other mire ecosystems.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Duvigneaud, 1949; Robyns, 1958; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Rybnicek, 1970; Braun-Blanquet, 1971a; Géhu and Wattez, 1971; Parent, 1973; Lambinon, 1974; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Willems y al., 1975; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Muller, 1978; Schumacker, 1978; Brasseur y al., 1978; Dierssen, 1978; Petermann and Seibert, 1979; Ratcliffe, 1980; Soo, 1980; Goodwillie, 1980; Lembrechts and Van Straaten, 1982; Jermy y al., 1982; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983; Moravec y al., 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Bournérias, 1984; Ochsenbein, 1984a, 1984b; Fabri y al., 1985; Mollet y al., 1985; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Rameau y al., 1989; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Elias y al., 1991; Rodwell, 1991b; Coldea, 1991; Steiner, 1992, 1993; Pott, 1992; Oberdorfer, 1992a; Julve, 1993; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 216; Pakarinen, 1995; Schubert y al., 1995).');
