    'Limestone rocks and cliffs of lowlands, hills and low mountains of the nemoral zone of the Palaearctic, harbouring impoverished, paucispecific, fissure communities.', '(Ellenberg, 1988: 452-453).');
    'Limestone rocks and cliffs of lowlands, hills and low mountains of the Mediterranean region, harbouring specialized Mediterranean chasmophyte communities.', '(Meikle, 1977; Viney, 1994; Zanzucchi, 1994; Bozicevic, 1996; Demetropoulos, 1996; Bousquet, 1997; Christofides, 1998).');
    'Siliceous rocks and cliffs of lowlands, hills and mountains of nondesert regions of the Palaearctic. Their lichen communities are composed of external crustose lichens ([Rhizocarpon]), navel lichens ([Umbilicaria]) and fruticose lichens ([Ramalina], [Cornicularia], [Rhizoplaca]).', '(Whitten and Brooks, 1972; Ellenberg, 1988: 453, 452-455, 484-485; Summerfield, 1991: 151-152, 165, 182-183). ');
    'Siliceous rocks, cliffs and nunataks of nondesert arctic regions and of the nival, or aeolian, level of mountains of the Palaearctic.', '(Einarsson, 1970; Barry and Ives, 1974; Hattersley-Smith, 1974; Ives, 1974; Bird, 1974; Caine, 1974; Ellenberg, 1988: 448-460; Hansen, 1995: 9). ');
    'Siliceous rocks and cliffs of the alpine to montane levels of high mountains of the mediterranean, nemoral, boreonemoral and boreal zones of the Palaearctic, harbouring specialized alpine chasmophyte communities.', '(Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 105; Ellenberg, 1988: 452-455; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996; Puytorac y al., 1997).');
    'Mires of spring or seep systems of nemoral Europe fed by lime-rich waters over clay soils physiognomically dominated by the presence, alongside [Cratoneurion commutati] communities, of colonies of the large horsetail [Equisetum telmateia], pure or accompanied by other species characteristic of lowland tall herb communities (unit 37.1); these colonies may be dense, extensive and up to three metres tall.', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 193; Page, 1988: 384-386; Schubert y al., 1995: 219).');
    'Mires of spring or seep systems of boreal and nemoral Europe fed by lime-rich waters over sand or gravel soils physiognomically dominated by the presence, alongside [Cratoneurion commutati] formations, of communities belonging to or related to arcto-alpine riverine swards (unit 54.3) or subalpine willowherb stream communities (unit 24.22) comprising in particular stands of the perennial horsetail [Equisetum variegatum]. ', '(Page, 1988: 321-322; Steiner, 1993: 156).');
    'Communities of calcareous springs, flushes, seeps or parts of spring systems of nemoral and boreal Europe in which, alongside an abundant representation of bryophytes, assemblages of small dicots or sedges contribute significantly to the formation''s appearance. Mosses of genus [Cratoneuron] usually remain the main bryophyte component, and there may be a modest amount of tufa encrustation and deposition. Characteristic vascular species include, in particular, [Cochlearia pyrenaica], [Arabis soyeri], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Saxifraga aizoides], and fen species belonging to the cortŠge of the [Caricetalia davallianae].', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 193-194; Soo, 1980: 527; Hadac, 1983: 352; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 75; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.6.2; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M38; Coldea, 1991: 417; Pott, 1992: 171-172; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 209-212; Ruzickova y al., 1992: 103; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.5.2.1; Schubert y al., 1995: 219).');
    'Rare, local glacial relict communities of calcareous springs, flushes or seeps of the northern Alpine piedmont, the Swabian Alb, Franconia, the Rh¿n, Sauerland and the Eastern Carpathians of Romania comprising [Cochlearia pyrenaica] with [Cratoneuron commutatum] and a [Cratoneurion] vascular cortŠge.', '(Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Coldea, 1991: 417; Pott, 1992: 172; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 209-212).');
    'Communities of calcareous springs, flushes, seeps or parts of spring systems of northern nemoral Europe formed by [Cratoneuron commutatum], [Cratoneuron filicinum], [Philonotis calcarea], with a relatively prominent accompanying assembly of vascular plants that may include [Cardamine amara], [Chrysosplenium alternifolium], [Filipendula ulmaria], [Caltha palustris].', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 193-194; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Pott, 1992: 171-172; Schubert y al., 1995: 219).');
    'Communities of calcareous springs, flushes, seeps of the British Isles dominated by [Cratoneuron commutatum] and/or [Cratoneuron filicinum], accompanied by a more varied bryophyte cortŠge and by a richer and usually more abundant vascular cortŠge than is characteristic of the communities of unit 54.1221. [Bryum pseudotriquetum] and [Philonotis fontana] may be prominent among the mosses, small sedges, in particular, [Carex demissa], [Carex nigra], [Carex panicea], [Carex pulicaris], [Carex flacca], [Carex dioica], are important among the vascular elements and sometimes abundant.', '(Rodwell, 1991b: unit M38).');
    'Communities of calcareous springs, flushes, seeps or parts of spring systems of Fennoscandia, including subalpine and lower alpine areas, dominated by mosses, especially [Philonotis fontana], [Pohlia albicans] and [Bryum weigelii], with [Brachythecium rivulare], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Philonotis seriata], and a relatively sparse field layer formed of wet-meadow species, including [Angelica archangelica], [Equisetum arvense], [Poa pratensis], [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]), [Saxifraga stellaris], [Viola biflora].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.6.2 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.5.2.1 [p.]).');
    'Rare, local formations of the Alpine periphery comprising the rare and threatened [Armeria purpurea], colonizing springs of the Bavarian plateau, near Memmingen in the Benninger Ried, at the contact of [Cratoneurion] communities, to which they belong, with [Primulo-Schoenetum] fen communities, and resurgences of the Friulian low plain, in fen communities also including the endemic [Erucastrum palustre] ([Brassica palustris]), the rare [Senecio doria] and [Anagalis tenella].', '(Farneti y al., 1977: 161; Pignatti, 1982: I-476, II-296, III-125; Oberdorfer, 1990: 748; Schubert and Vent, 1990: 188).');
    'Endemic [Cochlearia polonica] formations of cold springs and very clear fast-running brooks of fluvioglacial sand deposits over limestones of the Polish Jurassic region.', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 75). ');
    'Calcareous spring communities, usually dominated by [Saxifraga aizoides], [Silene pusilla], [Caltha laeta], [Cratoneuron commutatum], with regional species, such as [Doronicum carpaticum], [Chrysosplenium alpinum], [Achillea schurii].', '(Coldea, 1991: 417).');
    'Calcareous tufa-forming spring communities of the subalpine and lower alpine levels of the boreonemoral and boreoalpine mountains of Fennoscandia, dominated by brown mosses, in particular by [Cratoneuron] species, with a relatively thin assembly of vascular species formed by elements of both fens and wet meadows, usually with a prominence of [Cystopteris montana] or [Saxifraga aizoides].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.6.3a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.5.2.2a).');
    'Acidocline quaking mires and floating mats of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex lasiocarpa] associated with sphagna ([Sphagnum angustifolium], [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum lindbergii], [Sphagnum pulchrum], [Sphagnum balticum], [Sphagnum dusenii], [Sphagnum magellanicum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum subsecundum], [Sphagnum riparium], [Sphagnum subnitens], [Sphagnum cuspidatum], [Sphagnum flexuosum], [Sphagnum fimbriatum], [Sphagnum palustre], [Sphagnum auriculatum]) and [Polytrichum commune]. Characteristic accompanying species include [Carex rostrata], [Carex nigra], [Carex panicea], [Equisetum fluviatile], [Narthecium ossifragum], [Dactylorhiza sphagnicola], [Comarum palustre], [Vaccinium oxycoccos].', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 95; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 110a; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 200-201, 210; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.2.1, 3.6.2.1a, 3.6.2.1b, [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.2.4.1, 3.2.4.1a, 3.2.4.1b, [p.]).');
    'Mesotrophic quaking mires and floating mats of the Palaearctic domaine, mostly characteristic of the boreal region, dominated by [Carex lasiocarpa] associated with sphagna and brown mosses, in particular with the mesotrophic species [Sphagnum subsecundum], [Sphagnum contortum], [Drepanocladus revolvens].', '(Lembrechts and Van Straaten, 1982: 347-352; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.2.2, 3.6.2.2a, 3.6.2.2b, [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.3.3.1, 3.3.3.1a, 3.3.3.1b, [p.]).');
    'Transition mire communities of boreal and western nemoral regions of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex diandra] in association with [Carex lasiocarpa], [Carex appropinquata], [Carex limosa], [Carex lepidocarpa], [Eriophorum gracile], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Comarum palustre], [Hydrocotyle vulgaris], [Pedicularis palustris] and an abundance of bryophytes, including the pleurocarps [Campylium stellatum], [Drepanocladus intermedius] and the liverwort [Riccardia pinguis], usually forming open swards. These mires are an important habitat for the threatened [Liparis loeselii].', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 98-99; Lambinon, 1974; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 203-204; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Wheeler, 1980a: 374; Wheeler, 1980b: 413-416; Wheeler, 1980c: 775; Moravec y al., 1983: 40, 42; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M9b; Coldea, 1991: 419-422; Korotkov y al., 1991: 262; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M9b; Pott, 1992: 178; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 232-233; Steiner, 1993: 140; Julve, 1993: 71; Schubert y al., 1995: 245).');
    'Transition mire communities of boreal and western nemoral regions of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex rostrata] or, in western Siberia, [Carex rotundata], on sphagnum or, sometimes, pleurocarp carpets, usually constituting sparse low formations. They extend south, in the mountains of the southern Palaearctic, to the Caucasus. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 92-93, 101-102; Parent, 1973: 34; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 209-210; Dierssen, 1978: 416; Schumacker, 1978: 472-474; Petermann and Seibert, 1979: 84; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3c; Moravec y al., 1983: 44; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Rodwell, 1991b: units M4, M5, [p.], M8; Korotkov y al., 1991: 258-259, 263; Pott, 1992: 178; Steiner, 1993: 138-141; Julve, 1993: 71-72; Påhlsson, 1994; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Transition mire communities of boreal and western nemoral regions of the Palaearctic domaine constituted by mats of acidophilous sphagna with a usually low, open growth of [Carex rostrata], accompanied by [Carex nigra], [Carex canescens], [Carex limosa], [Vaccinium oxycoccos]; the main sphagna are [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum angustifolium], [Sphagnum auriculatum], [Sphagnum flexuosum], [Sphagnum riparium], [Sphagnum obtusum], [Sphagnum dusenii]. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 92-93; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 209-210; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3c; Moravec y al., 1983: 44; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.2.1, 3.6.2.1a, 3.6.2.1b, 3.6.2.2, 3.6.2.2a, 3.6.2.2b; Rodwell, 1991b: units M4, M5, [p.]; Coldea, 1991: 424-428; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.2.4.1, 3.2.4.1a, 3.2.4.1b, 3.3.3.1, 3.3.3.1a, 3.3.3.1b).');
    'Transition mire communities of boreal and western nemoral regions of the Palaearctic domaine formed by [Carex rostrata] with basiphilous sphagna or pleurocarps.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 92, 101-102; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3e; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.3.4, 3.6.3.4a, 3.6.3.4b; Rodwell, 1991b: units M8, M9a; Påhlsson, 1994; Seliskar, 1998: 15).');
    'Transition mire communities of boreal and western nemoral regions of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex rostrata] accompanied by basiphilous sphagna, [Sphagnum contortum], [Sphagnum teres], [Sphagnum warnstorfii], [Sphagnum squarrosum]. They are most characteristic of boreal regions, restricted at lower latitudes to the montane to subalpine belts.', '(Dierssen, 1978: 418; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3e; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M8; Korotkov y al., 1991: 259; Steiner, 1993: 145-146).');
    'Transition mire communities of boreal and western nemoral regions of the Palaearctic domaine formed by [Carex rostrata] with brown mosses, in particular, [Calliergon cuspidatum], [Calliergon giganteum], [Campylium stellatum], [Scorpidium scorpioides], [Drepanocladus revolvens]. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 92, 101-102; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3g; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.2.4, 3.6.2.4a, 3.6.2.4b; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M9a; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.4.3.1, 3.4.3.1a, 3.4.3.1b, [p.]).');
    'Limestone and ophiolite screes of Cyprus, in particular, limestone and ophiolite screes of the Troodos range, limestone screes of the Kyrenia range, flysch, sandstone and conglomerate screes of the Kythrean formation. Endemic plants include [Alyssum troodi], of Troodos serpentine substrates, [Hedysarum cyprium] and [Salvia veneris] of the Kythrean formation.', '(Holmboe, 1914: 89; Meikle, 1977: 2; Sfikas, 1992: 110-111; Viney, 1994: xiii-xiv; Christofides, 1998). ');
    'Calcareous and serpentine screes of the alpine, subalpine and, locally, montane, levels of the Dinarides, the Pelagonides and the Moeso-Macedonian mountains, and of the upper mesomediterranean and supramediterranean [Orno-Quercetum ilicis] and [Ostryo-Carpinion adriaticum] zones of Istria, the Dalmatian coast and Montenegro.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 146, 220-221, 464-465, 601-603; Géhu, 1984a; Lovric, 1993a).');
