    'Wetlands of the Palaearctic region mostly or largely occupied by peat- or tufa-producing small sedge and brown moss communities developed on soils permanently waterlogged, with a soligenous or topogenous base-rich, nutrient-poor, often calcareous water supply, and with the water table at, or slightly above or below, the substratum. Peat formation, when it occurs, is infra-aquatic. Calciphile small sedges and other Cyperaceae usually dominate the mire communities, which belong to the [Caricion davallianae], characterized by a usually prominent "brown moss" carpet formed by [Campylium stellatum], [Drepanocladus intermedius], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Cratoneuron commutatum], [Acrocladium cuspidatum], [Ctenidium molluscum], [Fissidens adianthoides], [Bryum pseudotriquetrum] and others, a grasslike growth of [Schoenus nigricans], [Schoenus ferrugineus], [Eriophorum latifolium], [Carex davalliana], [Carex flava], [Carex lepidocarpa], [Carex hostiana], [Carex panicea], [Juncus subnodulosus], [Scirpus cespitosus], [Eleocharis quinqueflora], and a very rich flora including [Tofieldia calyculata], [Dactylorhiza incarnata], [Dactylorhiza traunsteineri], [Dactylorhiza traunsteinerioides], [Dactylorhiza russowii], [Dactylorhiza majalis] ssp. [brevifolia], [Dactylorhiza cruenta], [Liparis loeselii], [Herminium monorchis], [Epipactis palustris], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Pedicularis sceptrum-carolinum], [Primula farinosa], [Swertia perennis]. Wet grasslands ([Molinietalia caerulaea], 37), tall sedge beds ([Magnocaricion], 53.2), reed formations ([Phragmition], 53.1), fen sedge beds ([Cladietum mariscae], 53.3), may form part of the fen system, with communities related to transition mires (54.5, 54.6) and amphibious or aquatic vegetation (22.3, 22.4) or spring communities (54.1) developing in depressions. The subunits below, which can, alone or in combination, and together with codes selected from the categories just mentioned, specify the composition of the fen, are understood to include the mire communities [sensu stricto] ([Caricion davallianae]), their transition to the [Molinion], and assemblages that, although they may be phytosociologically referrable to alkaline [Molinion] associations, contain a large representation of the [Caricion davallianae] species listed, in addition to being integrated in the fen system; this somewhat parallels the definition of an integrated class [Molinio-Caricetalia davallianae] in Rameau [et al.], 1989. Outside of rich fen systems, fen communities can occur on small surfaces in dune slack systems (16.3), in transition mires (54.5), in wet grasslands (37), on tufa cones (54.121) and in a few other situations. The codes below can be used, in conjunction with the principal code relevant, to signal their presence. Rich fens are exceptionally endowed with spectacular, specialized, strictly restricted species. They are among the habitats that have undergone the most serious decline. They are essentially extinct in several regions and gravely endangered in most. A very few large systems remain, in particular in pre-Alpine Bavaria, in the Italian pre-Alps,in collinar and montane eastern France, in northeastern Germany, in the coastal marshes of northern France, in southeastern and northern England, in Wales and in Ireland. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1947, 1949; Braun-Blanquet, 1954, 1971a; Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Vanden Berghen, 1963; Braun-Blanquet y al., 1964b; Berset, 1969; Géhu and Wattez, 1971; Herbauts, 1971; Parent, 1973; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; Schumacher, 1977; Guinochet and Vilmorin, 1978; Dierssen, 1978; Soo, 1980; Ratcliffe, 1980; Wheeler, 1980a, 1980b, 1980c; Goodwillie, 1980; Jermy y al., 1982; Lembrechts and Van Straaten, 1982; Wheeler y al., 1983; Ruuhijärvi, 1983; Sjörs, 1983; Moravec y al., 1983; Botch and Masing, 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Schmid, 1984; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Bournérias, 1984; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Gruber, 1984; Dupias, 1985; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987; Rameau y al., 1989; Succow and Jeschke, 1990; Oberdorfer, 1990; Elias y al., 1991; Korotkov y al., 1991; Rodwell, 1991b: 24-26; Coldea, 1991; Steiner, 1992; Stewart and Church, 1992: 36; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 216; Pakarinen, 1995; Ilijanic, 1996: 108; Hoda y al., 1998: 7).');
    'Transition mire communities of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex limosa], with brown mosses and sphagna, forming low floating or quaking swards.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 99; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 108b; Rybnicek, 1970: 240-242, 247-248; Parent, 1973: 35-39; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 209; Dierssen, 1978: 416: Muller, 1978; Schumacker, 1978: 462-465; Moravec y al., 1983: 40, 42; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.2.4, 3.6.2.4a 3.6.2.4b; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Korotkov y al., 1991: 261; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M4 [p.]; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 226; Pott, 1992: 175-176; Steiner, 1993: 133-135; Julve, 1993: 71-72; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.4.3.1, 3.4.3.1a, 3.4.3.1b; Schubert y al., 1995: 244).');
    'Basicline [Carex limosa] swards and floating rafts of the Palaearctic domaine, with [Carex lasiocarpa], [Carex lepidocarpa], [Eriophorum gracile] and a rich bryophyte cortŠge formed by the mosses [Scorpidium scorpioides], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Calliergon giganteum], [Calliergon trifarium], [Calliergon stramineum], [Campylium stellatum], [Bryum pseudotriquetum], the liverwort [Riccardia pinguis], and occasionally sphagna. [Scheuchzeria palustris] or [Liparis loeselii] may be present. Outside of transition mires, elements of these communities occur in the depressions of rich fens. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 99; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 108b; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.2.4, 3.6.2.4a 3.6.2.4b; Moravec y al., 1983: 40, 42; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.4.3.1, 3.4.3.1a, 3.4.3.1b).');
    'Acidocline [Carex limosa] swards and floating rafts of the Palaearctic domaine, with [Scheuchzeria palustris], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Drosera anglica], [Menyanthes trifoliata] and the sphagna [Sphagnum recurvum], [Sphagnum subsecundum], [Sphagnum imbricatum], [Sphagnum papillosum] and [Menyanthes trifoliata]. Outside of transition mires, elements of these communities, and notably [Scheuchzeria palustris], occur in deep hollows of bogs (unit 51.121), with [Rhynchospora alba] and [Carex pauciflora] and often without [Carex limosa].', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 108a; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 209; Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 106; Moravec y al., 1983: 44; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.2.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.2.4.1 [p.]).');
    'Transition mire communities of the northern boreal regions of the Palaearctic domaine, characteristic, in particular, of northern Finland, forming in flarks and rimpis of aapa mires, composed of a sparse field layer dominated by [Carex limosa] and [Scheuchzeria palustris] and a continuous ground layer of [Sphagnum annulatum], [Sphagnum balticum], [Sphagnum lindbergii], [Sphagnum majus].', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 99; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.2.1c; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.2.4.1c).');
    'Transition mire communities of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex chordorrhiza], forming short to medium-tall, usually inundated, swards, predominantly boreal, distributed in Fennoscandia, Lithuania, Russia, Belarus, Siberia and, very locally, in Scotland, with a disjunct area of occurrence in Central Europe, in pre-Alpine, eastern Hercynian and eastern Carpathian regions.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 96; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.2.4b; Moravec y al., 1983: 42, 44; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Coldea, 1991: 422-423; Korotkov y al., 1991: 262; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M4 [p.]; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 233; Pott, 1992: 178; Steiner, 1993: 141; Julve, 1993: 71; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.3.1; Schubert y al., 1995: 245).');
    '[Carex chordorrhiza]-dominated transition mire communities of the boreal Palaearctic, of Scotland, of eastern Hercynian and pre-Alpine regions, with [Carex limosa] and varied pleurocarps, [Scorpidium scorpioides], [Calliergon trifarium], [Calliergon stramineum], [Campylium stellatum], [Paludella squarrosa], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Drepanocladus procerus] or, occasionally, sphagna.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 96; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.2.4b; Moravec y al., 1983: 42, 44; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Korotkov y al., 1991: 262; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M4 [p.]; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 233; Pott, 1992: 178; Steiner, 1993: 141; Julve, 1993: 71; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.3.1; Schubert y al., 1995: 245).');
    'Rare formations of neutral and meso-eutrophic fens of the East Carpathian Rodna mountains, dominated by [Carex chordorrhiza], [Swertia perennis] and [Allium sibiricum], with the local characteristic [Valeriana simplicifolia].', '(Coldea, 1991: 419-421, 422-423).');
    'Transition mire communities of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex heleonastes], often associated with [Meesea triquetra], forming short to medium-tall swards, of local distribution in transition mires and in bog hollows of peri-Alpine and northern European areas.', '(Dierssen, 1978: 418; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Oberdorfer, 1990: 37; Korotkov y al., 1991: 263; Pott, 1992: 178; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 233; Lekavicius, 1992: 267-268; Julve, 1993: 72).');
    '[Rhynchospora alba]-rich formations of transition mires of the Palaearctic domaine, with [Drosera anglica], [Drosera intermedia], [Drosera rotundifolia], [Vaccinium oxycoccos], [Carex limosa], [Carex rostrata], [Sphagnum recurvum] and sometimes with [Eleocharis quinqueflora], [Eriophorum latifolium], [Andromeda polifolia] or [Scheuchzeria palustris].', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988: 322; Rybnicek, 1970: 242-247; Westhoff and den Held, 1975: 208-209; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Schumacker, 1978: 465-469; Muller, 1978; Moravec y al., 1983: 43, 44; Coldea, 1991: 418-422; Korotkov y al., 1991: 262; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M2 [p.]; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 226; Pott, 1992: 176; Steiner, 1992, 1993: 135-136; Schubert y al., 1995: 243).');
    'Shrub-rich scree communities of screes of the subalpine and low alpine levels of the boreoalpine and arctoalpine mountains of Fennoscandia, resulting from stabilization and shrub invasion of the screes of unit 61.611. Characteristic shrubs include the usually dominant [Juniperus communis] and [Cotoneaster integerrimus].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.2).');
    'Open pioneer communities of gravel and stone screes of Iceland and the Faeroes dominated by [Cerastium alpinum] or, on the Faeroes, [Cerastium arcticum], with [Festuca vivipara] and a number of mosses, especially [Rhacomitrium spp.], and lichens, in particular of genus [Stereocaulon].
', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.3a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.3a).');
    'Open communities of dry, more or less stabilised, screes of moderatly steep lower slopes of Icelandic mountains, characterized by the prominence of [Alchemilla alpina] and [Thymus arcticus].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.3b; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.3b).');
    'Very open, scattered, communities of acidic, dry to humid, humus-poor, gravel, stone and block screes of the upper montane, subalpine, low alpine and middle alpine levels of Fennoscandian mountains, formed by heliophile species, with a prominence of [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Juncus trifidus] and lichens.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.4).');
    'Very sparse communities colonizing gravelly soils on wind-swept, snow-free, dry, porous lava fields and upland plateaux of Iceland, from near sealevel to 800 m, with [Armeria maritima], [Silene acaulis], [Thymus praecox] ssp. [arcticus], [Cardaminopsis petraea], [Cerastium alpinum], [Festuca vivipara], and, in particular on lowland lava fields of the Reykjanes peninsula, [Arenaria norvegica], [Silene uniflora]. Bryophytes are almost absent, [Rhacomitrium lanuginosum] achieving a less than 1% cover on southwestern Icelandic lava fields.', '(Steindorsson, 1945; Steindorsson, 1967: 70-77, 90, table XXXVII; Hadac, 1972: 350-352; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.5; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.5).');
    'Sparse scree communities of tussock-forming [Rhodiola rosea] and [Silene acaulis] of south-southeastern slopes of mountains of Iceland, of very local distribution.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.6; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.6).');
    'Sparse communities of snow-bound upland and mountain screes of Iceland and the Faeroes, extending, as pioneer formations, to the lowlands, dominated by [Salix herbacea], mosses, especially [Rhacomitrium spp.], and lichens, in particular, of genus [Stereocaulon].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.7; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.7).');
    'Screes of the mountains and uplands of Greenland.', '(Fredskild, 1998, 2000).');
    'Pioneer open communities of unstable, gravelly, humus-poor, highly calcareous screes of the subalpine, low alpine and middle alpine levels of the boreoalpine and arctoalpine mountains of Fennoscandia formed by [Arenaria norvegica] and a number of endemic species or species of restricted range, including [Arenaria humifusa], [Arenaria pseudofrigida], [Artemisia norvegica], [Papaver] species of the [Papaver radicatum] group, [Papaver relictum], [Papaver laestadianum], [Braya linearis].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 1.1.4.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.1.4.3).');
    'Communities of screes of the mountains and uplands of the boreal and arctic zones of the central Palaearctic domaine. Included are the screes of the Chibiny range, of the Urals, of the chains of northern central Siberia, from the Putorany to the Tscherski range, of the mountains of southern Siberia, from the Altai to the Stanowoi range, situated in areas of high to very high continentality.', '(Walter, 1974: 23, 44, 338, 347).');
    'Scree communities of the mountains and uplands of the boreal and arctic zones of the eastern Palaearctic domaine. Included are the screes of the Anadyr, Tschuktschi, Korjak, Kamchatka, Amurland and Sakalin mountains, situated in regions of Pacific climate influence.', '(Walter, 1974: 23, 46).');
    'Scree communities of the mountains and steppe hills of Anatolia, the Levant, the Kurdo-Zagrosian and Irano-Turanian regions, Crimea, of the Pontic range, the Caucasus, the Elburz, the Central Asian mountains, the Himalayan system.', '(Zohary, 1973: 499, map 7; Walter, 1974: 23; Géhu, 1984a: unit 14.1.4).');
    'Screes of the mountains and steppe hills of the mediterranean and submediterranean regions of Anatolia.', '(Géhu, 1984a: unit 14.1.4).');
    'Screes of the supramediterranean level of the mountains and hills of Anatolia.', '(Géhu, 1984a: unit 14.1.4.1).');
    'Screes of the oromediterranean level of the mountains and hills of Anatolia.', '(Géhu, 1984a: unit 14.1.4.2).');
    'Screes of the high mountains of the Levant.', '(Zohary, 1973: 499).');
    'Screes of the mountains and steppe hills of the Kurdo-Zagrosian and Irano-Turanian regions of southwestern Asia.', '(Zohary, 1973: 499).');
    'Glacier-like tongues of angular talus extending out from a cirque and slowly moving downslope under the effect of gravity and of underlying, fully covered, interstitial ice.', '(Østrem, 1974: 229, 247; John, 1983: 61; Whittow, 1984: 459).');
    'Fairly large ridges or mounds of morainic material containing buried ice, originating from till deposited on former glacier ice or from morainic material deposited on a snow bank, adjacent to the ice front.', '(Østrem, 1974: 246; Whittow, 1984: 263).');
    'Small ice masses, permanent, or with an existence of a few years, derived in particular from snow-drifting, avalanches, or ice deposition in cold-bottom karst dolines.', '(Østrem, 1974: 229; Whittow, 1984: 224).');
    'Masses of snow and ice formed by the consolidation under pressure of snow falling on high ground, moving outward and downward from the zone of accumulation to lower ground.', '(Hattersley-Smith, 1974: 195-203, 212-213; Østrem, 1974: 227-229; Whittow, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988; Clark, 1990; Einarsson, 1994: 155-162; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 35-46; Summerfield, 1991: 261-290).');
    'Dome-like ice masses unconstrained by topography, together with their outlet glaciers. They are characteristic of arctic regions. The largest ice sheet in the northern hemisphere is that of Greenland. Smaller ice sheets and ice caps occur in Iceland, Jan Mayen, Spitsbergen, southern Norway, Franz Josef Land, Severnaya Zemlya and the islands of the De-Longa group.', '(Hattersley-Smith, 1974: 195-200, 203-205, 207-209, 210-213; Østrem, 1974: 229; Whittow, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988; Clark, 1990; Einarsson, 1994: 155-162; Lefauconnier and Slupetzky, 1995; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 35-45; Summerfield, 1991: 261-263).');
    'Glaciers constrained by topography, including cirque glaciers, valley glaciers, mountain glaciers, piedmont glaciers. They are characteristic, in particular, of the large mountain ranges of the Alpine system, occurring also in arctic regions, notably on Novaya Zemlya, in the subpolar and polar Urals, in the east Siberian mountains and, locally, in Iceland.', '(Hattersley-Smith, 1974: 208-209; Østrem, 1974: 227-229, ; Whittow, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988; Clark, 1990; Einarsson, 1994: 162; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 45-46; Summerfield, 1991: 261-290).');
    'Habitats, habitat complexes and landscapes dominated by accumulations of sand, rarely of silt or clay, deposited by aeolian processes and often possessing marked constructional relief, developed within the boreal, nemoral, steppic, warm-temperate humid, mediterranean or subdesert steppe zones, separated from the coast and its dune cordons by nondunal habitats. Unvegetated areas, algae-, lichen- or bryophyte-dominated pioneer communities and very sparse communities of higher plants are listed in this section. Other communities are noted by combination of units of this section with units from sections 3 or 4. Desert sands are excluded and listed under section 7.', '(Ellenberg, 1963, 1988; Flint, 1971; Bird, 1974: 713; Summerfield, 1991: 235-238, 242-257; Einarsson, 1994: 187; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996: 54).');
    'Dunes of the North Sea and Baltic plains, formed of quartzic sands originating in redeposited and reworked glacial drift and outwash. They are highly siliceous in the Netherlands, northern Belgium and northwestern Germany, progressively slightly less oligotrophic and with a more continental cortŠge in northeastern Germany, Poland and the eastern Baltic plain. The dune systems, particularly the large ones, harbour a unique ensemble of interacting communities and harbour many specialized and restricted organisms. They have considerably regressed and the remaining examples are fragile and often threatened. The presence of the various elements of the ecosystem can be indicated by simultaneous use of the codes below and of those relevant to the types of plant communities they represent.', '(Traets, 1956; Flint, 1971; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Smidt, 1981; Fuller, 1982; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Van Dijk y al., 1984; Webb, 1986; Dijkhuizen and Tuttel, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994; Pott, 1996; Opermanis y al., 1997: 57).');
    'Formations of unstable Germano-Baltic fluvioglacial inland sands with [Corynephorus canescens], [Carex arenaria], [Spergula morisonii], [Teesdalia nudicaulis] and carpets of fruticose lichens ([Cladonia], [Cetraria]) (cf. unit 35.23). Communities of Jutland are rich in [Ammophila arenaria]. ', '(Traets, 1956; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Smidt, 1981; Fuller, 1982; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Van Dijk y al., 1984; Webb, 1986; Dijkhuizen and Tuttel, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 4.1.3.1c; Opermanis y al., 1997: 57).');
    'Grasslands of more stabilized Germano-Baltic fluvioglacial inland dune systems with [Agrostis spp.] and [Corynephorus canescens] or other acidophilous grasses; their composition can be specified by use of codes of of 35 other than of unit 35.23.  ', '(Traets, 1956; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Smidt, 1981; Fuller, 1982; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 5.1.4.1 [p.], 5.1.4.2a [p.]; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Van Dijk y al., 1984; Webb, 1986; Dijkhuizen and Tuttel, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Påhlsson, 1994: units 4.1.4.1 [p.], 4.1.4.1a [p.]).');
    'Heaths colonizing Germano-Baltic fluvioglacial inland dunes. ', '(Traets, 1956; Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Smidt, 1981; Drachenfels y al., 1984; Webb, 1986; Dijkhuizen and Tuttel, 1987; Ellenberg, 1988; Pott, 1996).');
    'Crowberry heaths (unit 31.2272) of the relict wandering dunes of Drente and southern Friesland, with [Empetrum nigrum], [Salix arenaria], [Lophochloa cuspidata], [Pseudoscleropodium purum], [Hylocomium splendens].  ', '(Westhoff and den Held, 1975; De Smidt, 1981; Dijkhuizen and Tuttel, 1987).');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated or -rich communities of rich fens of nemoral, Pannonic and Pontic Europe, of wide distribution, though less common in Alpine and peri-Alpine regions than the next unit, and confined to lower altitudes. Rushes, [Juncus subnodulosus] in British and western continental inland fens, [Juncus balticus] in dune-slack fens, are often abundant. Other accompanying species include [Carex lepidocarpa], [Carex hostiana], [Carex panicea], [Carex pulicaris], [Eriophorum latifolium], [Molinia caerulea], [Dactylorhiza incarnata], [Dactylorhiza praetermissa], [Dactylorhiza purpurella], [Dactylorhiza traunsteineri], [Dactylorhiza traunsteinerioides], [Epipactis palustris], [Parnassia palustris], [Pinguicula vulgaris], brown mosses and, locally, [Pinguicula lusitanica] and [Drosera anglica]. These communities have enormously regressed, particularly in northern and northwestern continental Europe, and are extinct in many regions.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949; Duvigneaud, 1949; Wendelberger, 1965; Horvat y al., 1974: 495; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975; Provost, 1975; Dierssen, 1978; Soo, 1980; Ratcliffe, 1980; Wheeler, 1980b; Goodwillie, 1980; Moravec y al., 1983; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989; Oberdorfer, 1990; Korotkov y al., 1991; Chifu y al., 1991; Westhoff and van Oosten, 1991; Rodwell, 1991b; Coldea, 1991; Pott, 1992; Oberdorfer, 1992a; Steiner, 1992, 1993; Meshinev y al., 1994: units 29, 30, 27; Drachenfels, 1994; Schubert y al., 1995).');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated or -rich communities of rich fens of the British Isles.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 98; Braun-Blanquet and Tüxen, 1952; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H5; Wheeler, 1980b; Ellenberg, 1988: 320; Rodwell, 1991b: units M10d, M13, M14).');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated or -rich communities of rich fens of Great Britain.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H5; Wheeler, 1980b; Ellenberg, 1988: 320; Rodwell, 1991b: units M10d, M13, M14). ');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated or -rich communities of rich fens of Ireland.', '(Braun-Blanquet and Tüxen, 1952; Rodwell, 1991b: 135).');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated or -rich communities of rich fens of Atlantic continental Europe, from western France to Schleswig-Holstein.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 97; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 113; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 205; Bournérias, 1984: 249-256; Ellenberg, 1988: 320; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Westhoff and van Oosten, 1991; Pott, 1992: 182-183; Julve, 1993: 72-73; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 3.11.2).');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated or -rich communities of inland rich fens of Atlantic and sub-Atlantic nemoral continental Europe, recorded from France, in particular from the Perche, the Vexin, the Paris basin, the Valois, the Champagne, the Tonnerrois, the Brenne, the Aisne, from central and southeastern Belgium, from Schleswig-Holstein. They are everywhere very rare and threatened, extinct in Belgium, near to extinction in Schleswig-Holstein.', '(Duvigneaud, 1944: 13; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 113; Duvigneaud, 1949: 97; Bournérias, 1984: 249-256; Ellenberg, 1988: 320; Westhoff and van Oosten, 1991; Pott, 1992: 182; Julve, 1993: 72-73).');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated or -rich communities of rich fens of humid dune slacks of the Dutch and German North Sea coasts and islands and of the North Sea and English Channel coasts of France, south to the Cotentin peninsula. These communities, which have undergone an extremely severe decline, are an important refuge of the threatened orchid [Liparis loeselii], and of many other species of restricted distribution and ecology. ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 98; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 205; Provost, 1975; Ellenberg, 1988: 320; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Westhoff and van Oosten, 1991: 129-139, 235, 252, 291, 354; Pott, 1992: 183; Julve, 1993: 73; Drachenfels, 1994: unit 3.11.2).');
    '[Schoenus nigricans]-dominated communities of calcareous fens with strong water-level fluctuations of summer-warm Alpine and peri-Alpine regions of Germany, Switzerland, Austria, Italy, France, of the Bohemian Quadrangle, and of subcontinental Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Poland and Lithuania.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 97-98; Moravec y al., 1983: 39; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Ellenberg, 1988: 320; Balatova-Tulackova and Venanzoni, 1989: 277-280; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Korotkov y al., 1991: 260; Steiner, 1992, 1993: 150-151; Pott, 1992: 182; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 244-250; Lekavicius, 1992: 274; Julve, 1993: 72-73; Schubert y al., 1995: 248-249).');
