    'Natural caves, cave systems, underground waters and subterranean interstitial spaces. Caves and their associated waters (units 65.1-65.7) harbour varied, but paucispecific, communities of animals, fungi and algae that are restricted to them (troglobiont organisms), or are physiologically and ecologically capable of conducting their entire life cycle within them (troglophile organisms), or are dependent on them for part of the life cycle (subtroglophile organisms). Underground waters not associated with caves (stygon, unit 65.8) and interstitial spaces (units 65.9, 65.A) harbour distinctive faunas.', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972; Ginet and Decou, 1977; Vornatscher, 1979; Neuherz, 1979; Passauer, 1979; Cei y al., 1982; Culver, 1986; Leser, 1994; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996; Bozicevic, 1996; Celhar, 1997).');
    'Caves harbouring communities that include troglobic amphibians or fish, limited worldwide to a very small number of highly distinctive organisms, mostly relict forms of extremely limited distribution, including 15 species of amphibians, limited to North America and Europe, and about 38 species of fishes belonging to 13 families, notably, Cyprinidae, Gobiidae, Bythitidae, Pimelodidae, Characidae, Cobitidae, Amblyopsidae, Clariidae, Ictaluridae, Trichomycteridae, Ophidiidae, Synbranchidae. Palaearctic representatives include a unique amphibian, as well as cyprinids and gobiid fishes. ', '(Pavan, 1958; Thinès and Tercafs, 1972: 55-64; Ginet and Decou, 1977; Vornatscher, 1979; Neuherz, 1979; Banister, 1985; Culver, 1986; Camacho, 1992; Chapman, 1993: 37; Aljancic, 1993; Leser, 1994; Celhar, 1997; Mrsic, 1997).');
    'Basiphilous fen communities of the Western Carpathians, in particular, of the Pieniny and the Tatras, and of intramountain depressions at the 400-500 m level of the Eastern Carpathians, dominated by the small sedges [Carex davalliana], [Carex flava], [Carex distans], [Carex hostiana], [Carex panicea] and other fen species such as [Eriophorum latifolium], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Primula farinosa], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Pedicularis palustris], [Valeriana simplicifolia].
', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Ellenberg, 1988: 320-321; Coldea, 1991: 430-434).');
    'Fen communities of middle latitudes of continental Western Europe and of Central Europe, recorded from the Netherlands, Belgium, western Germany, France, northern Italy including the Apuan Alps, Austria, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland, Romania, with [Carex dioica], [Carex lepidocarpa], [Carex flava], [Carex demissa], [Carex serotina], [Carex panicea], [Eriophorum latifolium], [Juncus articulatus] and [Campylium stellatum].', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 101; Vanden Berghen, 1963; Rybnicek, 1970: 233-236; Parent, 1973: 39-40; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Jenik y al., 1980: 16; Lembrechts and Van Straaten, 1982: 332, 340-346; Moravec y al., 1983: 40; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Gerdol and Tomaselli, 1987; Coldea, 1991: 430-435; Steiner, 1992; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 261; Pott, 1992: 187; Steiner, 1993: 147-148).');
    'Rare exiguous alkaline spring and gulley communities of the montane level of the Cordillera Cantabrica, with [Carex lepidocarpa], [Carex demissa], [Carex davalliana], [Carex echinata], [Carex nigra], [Carex panicea], [Eriophorum latifolium], [Eleocharis quinqueflora], [Juncus articulatus], [Juncus alpestris], [Equisetum variegatum], [Pinguicula grandiflora], [Parnassia palustris] and, in more eastern communities, [Tofieldia calyculata], [Primula farinosa], [Bartsia alpina].  ', '(Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Gruber, 1984; Dupias, 1985; Diaz Gonzalez and Fernandez Prieto, 1987).');
    'Calcareous fens of the southern Iberian Range (Sierra de Gudar, Sierra de Javalambre). ', '(Rivas-Goday and Borja, 1961; Gruber, 1984: 28).');
    'Fen formations of nemoral Europe intermediate between the [Caricion davallianae] and the [Caricion fuscae], often developed in ecotonal situations, with [Carex pulicaris] and [Carex dioica], dispersed over a fairly wide range in continental middle Europe.  ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 101; Schumacker y al., 1974: 12-13; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 204; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Korotkov y al., 1991: 260; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 261; Pott, 1992: 187; Steiner, 1993: 148; Frankard y al., 1998: 36).');
    'Rich fen communities of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex nigra], accompanied by basiphile species and brown mosses.  ', '(Ratcliffe, 1977a: 297; Dierssen, 1978: 419; Ratcliffe, 1980: units H3f, H3d, H3i; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4d; Rodwell, 1991b: 97; Pott, 1992: 180; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 235-239, 241-243; Steiner, 1993: 147-148; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.2.3).');
    'Weakly alkaline, neutral or slightly acid fen communities of the montane to subalpine belt of the Alps and the greater Hercynian ranges, in particular, the Black Forest, the Vosges and the Bohemian Quadrangle, and of neighbouring hills, dominated by [Carex nigra], accompanied by calciphile species, brown mosses and basiphile sphagna. They are transitional between the rich fen communities of unit 54.2 and the acidic fen communities of unit 54.4, in particular, of unit 54.421, closely related to the dioecious-yellow-flea sedge communities of units 54.253 and 54.256, of which some of them constitute facies. Similar [Carex nigra]-dominated or -rich stands occur in more Atlantic regions, in particular, of the British Isles; they are probably best treated as part of the regionally more prevalent unit 54.25.', '(Matuszkiewicz and Matuszkiewicz, 1975: 86-87; Ratcliffe, 1977a: 297; Dierssen, 1978: 419; Ratcliffe, 1980: units H3f, H3d, H3i; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4d; Matuszkiewicz, 1984: 92; Oberdorfer, 1990; Rodwell, 1991b: 97; Pott, 1992: 180; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 235-239, 241-243; Steiner, 1993: 147-148; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.2.3).');
    '[Carex nigra]-dominated fen communities of the subalpine to lower alpine zones of the boreoalpine and arctoalpine mountains of Fennoscandia occupying lowlying areas affected by running water (pH 5.5-6.0), among low (0.20 m) willow brush of, notably, [Salix hastata], [Salix lanata], [Salix lapponum], [Salix phylicifolia], comprising poor fen margin vegetation with, in some parts, an admixture of medium rich fen elements, and with a ground layer mainly of brown mosses. The sedge-rich species cortŠge includes [Carex bigelowii], [Carex canescens], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex dioica], [Carex flava], [Carex limosa], [Carex magellanica], [Carex panicea], [Carex rostrata], [Carex rotundata], [Eriophorum angustifolia], [Scirpus cespitosus] ssp. [cespitosus] ([Trichophorum cespitosum]), [Phleum alpinum], [Poa pratensis] [s.l.], [Caltha palustris], [Cardamine pratensis], [Pedicularis palustris], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Polygonum viviparum], [Potentilla erecta], [Potentilla palustris], [Viola palustris], [Salaginella salaginoides], [Thalictrum alpinum], and bryophytes [Aulacomnium palustre], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Calliergon stramineum], [Cinclidium stygium], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Paludella squarrosa], [Philonotis fontana], [Sphagnum warnstorfii].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4d [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.2.3 [p.]).');
    'Very sparse mesotrophic mud-bottom communities associated with standing or flowing, relatively low pH, waters of subalpine and lower alpine zones of boreal mountains of Fennoscandia. Both the sedge assembly and the bryophyte contingent may be very poorly developed or even absent, dominance being achieved by representatives of either, in particular, by the sedges [Carex limosa] or [Eriophorum angustifolium], by the hepatics [Cephalozia spp.] or [Gymnocolea inflata], by brown mosses of genus [Drepanocladus], notably [Drepanocladus fluitans]. The species cortŠge may also include [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex livida], [Eriophorum gracile], [Rhynchospora alba], [Rhynchospora fusca], [Juncus stygius], [Hammarbya paludosa], [Phragmites australis], [Drosera anglica], [Utricularia intermedia], [Lycopodiella inundata], and the bryophytes [Calliergon spp.], [Cladopiella fluitans], [Sphagnum annulatum], [Sphagnum compactum], [Sphagnum papillosum], [Sphagnum platyphyllum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.3.2a; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.3.4d).');
    'Communities of wet depressions of Iceland dominated by cyperacids, in particular, [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex nigra], [Carex rariflora], [Carex rostrata], [Carex lyngbyei], accompanied by brown mosses, notably, [Calliergon giganteum], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Drepanocladus tundrae], [Scorpidium scorpidioides], leaving variable amounts of bare muds exposed.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b, 1970; Hadac, 1969, 1985a; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.3.2b, 3.6.3.2c, 3.6.3.2d; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.3.3.4a, 3.3.3.4b, 3.3.3.4c).');
    'Relatively open, mainly cyperacid, communities of humid depressions, muddy flats and standing waters of Iceland dominated or codominated by [Carex chordorrhiza], with [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Carex nigra] and the brown mosses [Calliergon giganteum], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Drepanocladus tundrae], [Scorpidium scorpidioides].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 77-79; Vanden Berghen, 1970; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.3.2b; Hadac, 1985a: 168-170; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.3.4a  [p.]).');
    'Communities of Iceland colonizing bare muds on gently sloping terrain with slightly moving ground water in lowland to lower alpine elevations of Iceland dominated or codominated by [Carex rariflora], with a presence of mosses often more prominent than in the communities of unit 54.6241. The species cortŠge includes [Carex rostrata], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex nigra], [Carex saxatilis], [Calamagrostis stricta], [Equisetum palustre], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Cinclidium stygium], [Sphagnum girgensohnii], [Aneura pinguis], [Calliergon giganteum], [Oncophorus wahlenbergii], [Paludella squarrosa].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 77; Vanden Berghen, 1970; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.3.2c; Hadac, 1985a: 164-166; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.3.4b [p.]).');
    'Communities of wet depressions and muds, river and lake edges of Iceland and the Faeroe Islands dominated by [Carex lyngbyei], with a cyperacid-rich cortŠge and brown mosses, in particular, [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Calliergon giganteum], [Calliergon stramineum], [Calliergon sarmentosum].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 80; Vanden Berghen, 1970; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.3.2d; Hadac, 1985a: 170; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.3.4c).');
    'Communities of wet depressions of Iceland dominated by [Carex nigra], accompanied by [Carex rariflora], [Carex lyngbyei], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Potentilla palustris], the brown mosses [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Calliergon giganteum], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Calliergon stramineum], the Mniaceae [Pseudobryum cinclidioides], [Cinclidium stygium].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 77; Hadac, 1969: 8-9; Vanden Berghen, 1970; Hadac, 1985a: 163; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.3.3.4a [p.]).');
    'Communities of wet depressions of Iceland dominated by [Carex rostrata] variably accompanied by [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex nigra], [Carex rariflora] and brown mosses, notably [Calliergon giganteum], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Scorpidium scorpidioides].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 77; Vanden Berghen, 1970; Hadac, 1985a: 168-170; Påhlsson, 1994: units 3.3.3.4a [p.], 3.3.3.4b [p.]).');
    'Communities of wet depressions, muds and peaty soils of Iceland dominated by [Eriophorum angustifolium], with [Carex nigra], [Carex rostrata], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Calamagrostis neglecta], [Polygonum viviparum], [Viola palustris], [Salix herbacea], [Equisetum palustre] and hypnid mosses, notably [Calliergon giganteum], [Rhytidiadelphus squarrosus], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Scorpidium scorpidioides], [Calliergonella cuspidata], [Hylocomium splendens].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 77-79; Hadac, 1969: 11-13; Vanden Berghen,1970; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: units 3.6.3.2b; Hadac, 1985a: 166-168; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.3.4a [p.]).');
    'Calcareous cliffs of the southern Biokovo coastlands of central Dalmatia, with [Inula spp.], [Centaurea cuspidata], [Seseli tomentosum].', '(Lovric, 1993a: 408; Ilijanic, 1996: 110). ');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the Adriadic meso-mediterranean coast lands of the southern Dalmatian coast, in part constituting the upper levels of sea-cliffs of unit 18.221B, in particular, communities dominated by [Putoria calabrica].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 144; Lovric, 1993a: 411; Ilijanic, 1996: 111).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the Dalmatian mesomediterranean zone, widespread on rocks and man-made structures, with [Umbilicus horizontalis] and asplenioid ferns.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 144; Ilijanic, 1996: 111).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the central and eastern Pyrenees, with [Saxifraga media], [Saxifraga longifolia], [Saxifraga aretioides], [Potentilla alchimilloides], [Potentilla nivalis], [Ramonda myconi], [Asperula hirta].  ', '(Gruber, 1978; Géhu, 1984a: unit 13.1.2.2 [p.]; Dupias, 1985; Julve, 1993: 29).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the Maritime Alps and northern Apennines, with [Saxifraga lingulata], [Primula marginata], [Primula allionii], [Phyteuma charmelii], [Phyteuma villarsii], [Silene campanula], [Potentilla saxifraga], [Ballota frutescens].  ', '(Niklfeld, 1962; Gruber, 1978; Géhu, 1984a: unit 13.1.2.2 [p.]; Julve, 1993: 28).');
    'Cliff and rock communities of the supra- and oro-Mediterranean levels of calcareous Iberian mountains, of the central Apennines and of the calcareous mountains of the large Tyrrhenian islands.', '(Bellot Rodriguez, 1979; Fernandez Prieto, 1983; Géhu, 1984a; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Aparicio Martinez and Silvestre Domingo, 1987; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Martinez Parras y al., 1987; Gamisans, 1991; Mucina, 1993f).');
    'Cliff and rock communities of the supra- and oro-Mediterranean levels of calcareous Iberian mountains. ', '(Bellot Rodriguez, 1979; Fernandez Prieto, 1983; Géhu, 1984a; Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b; Aparicio Martinez and Silvestre Domingo, 1987; Peinado Lorca and Rivas-Martinez, 1987; Martinez Parras y al., 1987).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the Cantabrian Cordillera and a few other northwestern Iberian ranges, with [Asperula hirta], [Asplenium viride], [Erinus alpinus], [Globularia repens], [Hypericum nummularium], [Rhamnus pumilus], [Saxifraga aretioides].  ', '(Rivas-Martinez y al., 1984b: 152-155).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of high altitudes of Baetic and sub-Baetic ranges of eastern Andalusia, with [Linaria verticillata], [Potentilla caulescens], [Saxifraga camposii], [Saxifraga erioblasta], [Teucrium rotundifolium], [Silene boryi].  ', '(Martinez-Parras y al., 1987: 56).');
