    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the montane or subalpine levels of the central Apennines and of the calcareous mountains of the large Tyrrhenian islands.', '(Gamisans, 1991; Mucina, 1993f).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the cryo-oromediterranean and supramediterranean levels of Corsica, limited to rare limestone outcrops, in particular, of the Chapelle Sant''Angelu de Lanu summit and of the Punta di u Fornellu, with [Arenaria bertolonii], [Potentilla crassinervia], [Festuca sardoa], [Dianthus sylvestris] ssp. [godronianus], [Ptychotis saxifraga], [Elymus corsicus].', '(Gamisans, 1991: 219-220, 265, 357).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the montane or subalpine levels of the central Apennines.', '(Mucina, 1993f: 244).');
    'Cool, shaded calcareous cliff and rock communities of the west Mediterranean regions, formed mostly of bryophytes and ferns, including [Polypodium cambricum] ssp. [australe] ([Polypodium australe]), and with [Selaginella denticulata]. ', '(Julve, 1993: 29).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the Alps and the Carpathians, of lesser satellite ranges and of submediterranean areas of the northern Tyrrhenian periphery. ', '(Géhu, 1984a; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Coldea, 1991; Julve, 1993; Mucina, 1993f).');
    'Well-lit calcareous cliff and rock communities of the Alps and neighbouring regions, including upper Provence, upper Languedoc, the pre-Pyrenees and CorbiŠres, the Catalonian mountains, with [Potentilla caulescens], [Potentilla clusiana], [Potentilla nitida], [Primula auricula], [Hieracium humile], [Cardaminopsis petraea], [Androsace helvetica], [Minuartia rupestris].  ', '(Géhu, 1984a; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Julve, 1993: 28; Mucina, 1993f: 243-251; Seliskar, 1998: 13).');
    'Caves of the Adriatic karst system of Italy, Slovenia, Croatia and Montenegro, harbouring the relict amphibian [Proteus anguinus], the most remarkable of all troglobiont vertebrates.', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972; Ginet and Decou, 1977: 154-155; Culver, 1986; Habe, 1988; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992; Aljancic, 1993; Chapman, 1993; Tvrtkovic, 1996; Mrsic, 1997).');
    'Caves harbouring communities that include troglobic fish, limited in the Palaearctic region to representatives of the Cyprinidae and Gobiidae. ', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972: 56, 63; Banister, 1985: 82; Culver, 1986; Camacho, 1992; Chapman, 1993: 37).');
    'Caves harbouring communities that include troglobic Cyprinidae, known, in particular, from Iran, Iraq, Oman and from China. ', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972: 56; Banister, 1985: 82; Culver, 1986).');
    'Caves of the Near and Middle East harbouring communities that include troglobic Cyprinidae, mostly loaches or garrine fishes, known, in particular, from Iran, Iraq and Oman.', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972: 56; Cei y al., 1982: 29; Banister, 1985: 82; Culver, 1986).');
    'Caves of the Near and Middle East harbouring communities that include troglobic garrine fishes, known, in particular, from Iran, Iraq and Oman.', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972: 56; Cei y al., 1982: 29; Banister, 1985: 82; Culver, 1986).');
    'Caves of the Iranian plateau harbouring the Cyprinid [Iranocypris typhlops].', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972; Cei y al., 1982: 29).');
    'Caves of the Euphrates basin of Irak harbouring the Cyprinid [Typhlogarra widdowsoni].', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972).');
    'Caves of Oman harbouring communities that include troglobic garrine fishes of genus [Garra].', '(Banister, 1985: 82).');
    'Caves of Iraq harbouring communities that include the troglobic cyprinid of unknown affinities [Caecocypris].', '(Banister, 1985: 82).');
    'Caves of the Near and Middle East harbouring communities that include troglobic loaches, known, in particular, from Iran.', '(Banister, 1985: 82).');
    'Caves of the eastern Palaearctic harbouring communities that include troglobic Cyprinidae, known, in particular, from China, with two species of loaches and one with garrine fishes. ', '(Banister, 1985: 80, 82).');
    'Caves harbouring communities that include troglobic Gobiidae, known from Japan, with two species, [Luciogobius albus] and [Luciogobius pallidus].', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972: 63).');
    'Caves of the main Eurasian and African landmasses essential to parts of the life-cycle of vertebrate subtroglophiles (elective periodic trogloxenes). ', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972; Ginet and Decou, 1977; Vornatscher, 1979; Neuherz, 1979; Culver, 1986; Stebbings, 1988; Corbett, 1989; Ransome, 1990; Schober and Grimmberger, 1991; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992; Macdonald and Barrett, 1993; Aljancic, 1993; Leser, 1994; Celhar, 1997).');
    'Caves of the main Eurasian and African landmasses providing an essential habitat of reptilian and amphibian subtroglophiles (elective periodic trogloxenes).', '(Corbett, 1989: 222; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992: 235-236, 239-240).');
    'Caves harbouring the salamanders [Speleomantes] ([Hydromantes]), [Speleomantes ambrosii] and [Speleomantes italicus] of southeastern France and northern and central Italy.', '(Corbett, 1989: 222; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992: 235-236, 239-240).');
    'Caves harbouring the salamander [Speleomantes ambrosii] ([Hydromantes ambrosii]) of southeastern France and northern Italy, with several races of extremely local distribution, in particular, in the Ligurian Alps, the Maritime alps, the Provence Alpes.', '(Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992: 235-236).');
    'Caves harbouring the salamander [Speleomantes italicus] ([Speleomantes]  = [Hydromantes]) of northern and central Italy, with two races of local distribution in the Apuan Alps, the Modenan, Emilian, Toscan, Umbrian, Marchesian Apennines.', '(Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992: 239-240).');
    'Caves of the main Eurasian and African landmasses providing an essential habitat of reptilian subtroglophiles (elective periodic trogloxenes), in particular, geckos or snakes.', NULL);
    'Caves of the Eurasian and North African landmasses, under normally oxygenated, buffered microclimates, generally large and crossed by watercourses or excavated near epigean watercourses, with permanent or temporary colonies of bats, in majority belonging to the Vespertilionidae. ', '(Stebbings, 1988; Ransome, 1990; Schober and Grimmberger, 1991; Macdonald and Barrett, 1993; Tvrtkovic, 1996).');
    'Caves of the islands of Eurasia and North Africa essential to parts of the life-cycle of vertebrate subtroglophiles (elective periodic trogloxenes).', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972; Ginet and Decou, 1977; Culver, 1986; Stebbings, 1988; Erminio, 1988; Corbett, 1989; Ransome, 1990; Schober and Grimmberger, 1991; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992; Macdonald and Barrett, 1993; Leser, 1994).');
    '[Carex nigra]-dominated fen communities of the lowlands of Iceland with a variable species cortŠge that may include [Carex rariflora], [Carex lyngbyei],  [Carex canescens], [Eriophorum angustifolia], [Scirpus cespitosus] ssp. [cespitosus] ([Trichophorum cespitosum]), [Juncus filiformis], [Calamagrostis stricta], [Potentilla palustris], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Polygonum viviparum], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Salix callicarpaea] ([Salix arctica]), [Equisetum palustre], [Selaginella selaginoides] and bryophytes [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Calliergonella cuspidata], [Polytrichum commune], [Aulacomnium palustre], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Calliergon stramineum], [Calliergon giganteum], [Cinclidium stygium], [Cinclidium subrotundum], [Climacium dendroides], [Hypnum spp.], [Oncophorus wahlenbergii], [Sphagnum girgensohnii]. Hummocks with heath mosses and sphagna are common; these communities are modified by grazing, resulting, notably, in a reduced willow component.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969a: 77; Hadac, 1969: 10-11, 13-20; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4d [p.]; Hadac, 1985a: 161-163; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.2.3 [p.]).');
    '[Carex saxatilis]-dominated communities of calcareous mires of mountains of the northern regions of the Palaearctic domaine. They are intermediate between rich fen communities of unit 54.2 and arctoalpine communities of unit 54.3.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 102; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3j; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4i; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M12; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.2.3).');
    '[Carex saxatilis]-dominated mires of high calcareous mountains of the Central Highlands of Scotland, with [Carex saxatilis], [Juncus triglumis], [Juncus castaneus], [Saxifraga aizoides] and brown mosses. ', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit H3j; Jermy y al., 1982; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M12).');
    'Extremely rich [Carex saxatilis]-dominated fen communities of the lower alpine level of the boreoalpine and arctoalpine mountains of Fennoscandia, occupying sites with relatively long snow cover, bordering on snow patch communities, on extremely moist, relatively rich substrates (pH 5-6.5), often difficult to distinguish from the boreal scorched sedge fen communities of unit 54.35. [Carex buxbaumii] may be abundant, [Juncus triglumis] and [Polygonum viviparum] ([Bistorta vivipara]) are characteristic; the moss layer is dominated by [Drepanocladum revolvens] var. [intermedius], with [Bryum pseudotriquetrum], [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Calliergon trifarium], [Paludella squarrosa], [Scorpidium scorpioides]. The vascular species cortŠge may also include [Cerastium cerastoides], [Pinguicula alpina], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Salix herbacea], [Saxifraga stellaris], [Veronica alpina], [Juncus castaneus], [Selaginella selaginoides].', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 102; Dierssen, 1978: 418; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4i; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.2.3).');
    'Mostly subalpine formations dominated by [Carex frigida], colonizing seepages and flushes on stony slopes of the Alps, the Pyrenees and the Black Forest, with [Carex davalliana], [Carex demissa], [Carex panicea], [Carex nigra], [Juncus triglumis], [Juncus castaneus], [Blysmus compressus], [Tofieldia calyculata], [Parnassia palustris], [Pinguicula vulgaris], [Pinguicula grandiflora], [Primula farinosa], [Saxifraga aizoides], [Campylium stellatum].  ', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 96; Dierssen, 1978: 419; Oberdorfer, 1990; Pott, 1992: 186; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 268, 306; Steiner, 1992, 1993: 155-156; Julve, 1993: 75).');
    '[Carex demissa]-[Saxifraga aizoides] communities of submontane base-rich seeps in northern Wales, northern England, southern Scotland and, mostly, the Scottish Highlands, with [Juncus articulatus], [Carex panicea], [Eleocharis quinqueflora], [Selaginella selaginoides] and brown mosses. Montane saxifrage-sedge flushes with glacial relicts have been listed under unit 54.34.', '(Ratcliffe, 1980: unit I1b; Rodwell, 1991b: unit M11).');
    'Rich fen communities of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Eleocharis quinqueflora] ([Eleocharis pauciflora]), for the most part species-poor pioneering formations, relatively widespread, though decreasing and threatened, in the boreal region, in the Baltic plain, in western Hercynian hills and in Alpine and peri-Alpine regions.', '(Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 112; Duvigneaud, 1949: 97; Parent, 1973: 34; Dierssen, 1978: 419; Moravec y al., 1983: 39; Bournérias, 1984: 250-251; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Korotkov y al., 1991: 260; Rodwell, 1991b: M10b [p.], M11 [p.]; Steiner, 1992, 1993: 154-155; Pott, 1992: 186; Schubert y al., 1995: 250).');
    'Usually rare and isolated small sedge rich fens of the high mountains of the eastern Mediterranean, the Euxinian periphery, Anatolia, central Eurasia, developed around springs, rivulets and seeps on limestones and ultrabasic rocks, in particular, ophiolites. Characteristic plants often include butterworts, sometimes of very restricted distribution, in particular, [Pinguicula hirtiflora], [Pinguicula balcanica], [Pinguicula crystallina].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 216-217; Horvat y al., 1974: 654, 655, 656).');
    'Rare and isolated small sedge rich fens of the high mountains of Greece, in particular [Blysmus compressus]-dominated communities with [Parnassia palustris], [Veronica balcanica], [Veronica anagallis-aquatica], [Eleocharis uniglumis], [Eleocharis quinqueflora], [Carex hirta], and with [Juncus thomasii], [Bellis perennis] or [Leontodon hispidus] on limestone, [Pinguicula hirtiflora], [Pinguicula balcanica], [Soldanella pindicola], [Eriophorum latifolium], [Carex nigra] on ophiolites.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 654, 655, 656).');
    'Rare fens forming around springs in the mountains of Cyprus, with small herbs, sedges and rushes, harbouring, in particular, [Pinguicula crystallina] and [Epipactis veratrifolia].', '(Holmboe, 1914: 216-217).');
    'Mud-bottom communities of calcareous waters of the boreal region of the Palaearctic, in particular of the northern boreal region and of the subalpine and low alpine levels of boreoalpine and arctoalpine mountains, most characteristic of rich flarks and rimpis in mountainous aapa regions, often with iron ochre, formed by a sparse cover of sedges and rushes, variously dominated by [Carex limosa], [Carex rostrata], [Carex chordorrhiza], [Carex lasiocarpa], [Carex livida] or [Juncus stygius], and a generally poorly developed bryophyte assembly formed by brown mosses, notably [Scorpidium scorpioides], also [Calliergon sarmentosum], [Calliergon stramineum], [Calliergon trifarium], [Drepanocladus exannulatus], with the sphagnum [Sphagnum subfuscum] and microalgae. The vascular species cortŠge comprises [Carex dioica], [Carex magellanica], [Carex rariflora], [Eleocharis quinqueflora], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Eriophorum gracile], [Rhynchospora alba], [Rhynchospora fusca], [Hammarbya paludosa], [Phragmites australis], [Triglochin palustre], [Utricularia intermedia].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.3.3; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.4.3.3).');
    'Sedge or grass formations of arctic, subarctic, arctoalpine and boreoalpine regions of the Palaearctic, often almost monospecific, often with an insignificant bryophyte component, sometimes with substantial [Calliergon], [Bryum] or [Philonotis] moss cover, occupying fine-grained, often sandy, long-submerged but well aerated, alluvial deposits in the inundation zone of rivers, brooks, lakes or deltas, relatively nutrient-rich, in part through the contribution of regular flooding, and with a variable lime content. ', '(Hadac, 1969: 3-4; Sjörs, 1983: 88; Botch and Masing, 1983: 116; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 217, unit 3.6.5; Polunin and Walters, 1985: 33, 36; Hadac, 1985a: 159-161; Hadac, 1989: 134, 138-142; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2).');
    '[Eriophorum scheuchzeri]- or [Eriophorum angustifolium]-dominated marsh-fen communities of fine-grained long-submerged alluvial deposits of the inundation zone of rivers, brooks, lakes or deltas of the arctic, subarctic, arctoalpine and boreoalpine regions of the Palaearctic.', '(Hadac, 1969: 3-4; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 217, unit 3.6.5 [p.]; Hadac, 1985a: 159-161; Hadac, 1989: 134, 138-142; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Stands of [Eriophorum scheuchzeri], often continuous, often monospecific, of subalpine and lower alpine levels of boreal Fennoscandia and of the lowland to lower alpine zones of Iceland, Spitzbergen, Greenland, occupying sandy and/or clayey alluvial deposits, in particular, along the shores of lakes and watercourses and in deltas, with no ground layer or a sometimes fairly continuous moss component. Fennoscandian communities may include [Carex canescens], [Carex nigra], [Epilobium palustre], [Eriophorum angustifolium], and abundant [Deschampsia cespitosa] or [Deschampsia alpina], with no bryophytes or a few mosses, such as [Calliergon cordifolium], [Pohlia spp.]; Icelandic communities may also have [Agrostis stolonifera], [Catabrosa aquatica], [Juncus alpinoarticulatus] ssp. [nodulosum], [Ranunculus hyperboreus], [Triglochin palustre] and the moss [Philonotis fontana]. Spitzbergen communities include [Deschampsia alpina], [Juncus biglumus], [Dupontia pelligera], [Saxifraga foliolosa], [Equisetum boreale] and a substantial moss component, in particular of [Calliergon sarmentosum] or [Bryum spp.].', '(Hadac, 1969: 6-8; Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 96; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.5.1 [p.]; Hadac, 1985a: 159-161; Hadac, 1989: 134, 138-142; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2.2 [p.]; Mossberg y al., 1995: 605; Gensbol, 1996: 86-87, 426).');
    'Stands of [Eriophorum angustifolium], often monospecific, of subalpine and lower alpine levels of boreal Fennoscandia, occupying periodically waterlogged, relatively nutrient-deficient, high-pH substrates with a finer grain texture than that of the alluvions colonized by the [Calamagrostis stricta] communities of unit 54.72. The species cortŠge may include [Carex aquatilis], [Equisetum fluviatile], [Caltha palustris], [Juncus filiformis], [Petasites frigidus], [Ranunculus repens], [Subularia aquatica].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.5.3 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2.4 [p.]).');
    'Grass- or forb-dominated marsh-fen communities of fine-grained long-submerged alluvial deposits of the inundation zone of rivers, brooks, lakes or deltas of the arctic, subarctic, arctoalpine and boreoalpine regions of the Palaearctic.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 217, unit 3.6.5 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Stands of [Calamagrostis stricta], often monospecific and with no moss layer, of spring-flooded sands of subalpine and lower alpine levels of boreal Fennoscandia and of the hills and highlands of Iceland, developed in drier localities than the [Eriophorum scheuchzeri]-dominated communities of unit 54.71. Accompanying species include [Equisetum arvense], [Juncus articus], [Salix lanata]. In Fennoscandian communities, meadow species, such as [Alchemilla spp.], [Angelica archangelica], [Ranunculus acris], [Rumex acetosa], may be present on small elevations. In Iceland, [Agrostis stolonifera] and [Eriophorum scheuchzeri] are typical, with [Catabrosa aquatica], [Eleocharis uniglumis], [Ranunculus hyperboreus], [Salix callicarpaea] ([Salix arctica]).', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.5.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2.3).');
    'Stands of [Petasites frigidus], often monospecific, of subalpine and lower alpine levels of boreal Fennoscandia, occupying periodically waterlogged, relatively nutrient-deficient, high-pH substrates with a finer grain texture than that of the alluvions colonized by the [Calamagrostis stricta] communities of unit 54.72. The species cortŠge may include [Carex aquatilis], [Equisetum fluviatile], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Caltha palustris], [Juncus filiformis], [Ranunculus repens], [Subularia aquatica].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.5.3 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2.4 [p.]).');
    'Communities of shady, cool, often moist rockfaces of the Alps and neighbouring regions, of the Carpathians, of the Jura, the Hercynian ranges, the British Isles, with many ferns, including [Cystopteris fragilis], [Cystopteris regia], [Asplenium viride], [Asplenium scolopendrium], [Asplenium trichomanes], and with [Carex brachystachys]. ', '(Géhu, 1984a; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Ellenberg, 1988; Oberdorfer, 1990; Coldea, 1991; Seliskar, 1998: 14).');
    'Rock-crack communities of sunny rock faces of the alpine and subalpine levels of the Carpathians.', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Coldea, 1991: 349-354).');
    'Rock-crack communities of sunny rock faces of the alpine and subalpine levels of the high northwestern Carpathians, of Alpine affinities.', '(Matuszkiewicz, 1984).');
    'Rock-crack communities of sunny rock faces of the alpine and subalpine levels of the eastern Carpathian system, characterized by the prevalence of Dacian endemics.', '(Coldea, 1991: 349-354).');
    'Rock-crack communities of sunny rock faces of the Eastern Carpathians, formed by [Silene zawadzkii].', '(Coldea, 1991: 351-353).');
    'Rock-crack communities of sunny rock faces of the southeastern Carpathians, formed by [Artemisia eriantha] and [Gypsophila petraea].', '(Coldea, 1991: 351-353).');
    'Rock-crack communities of abrupt slopes and humid ubacs of the Bucegi and Ceahlau mountains of the Southern Carpathians, formed by [Saxifraga moschata] and [Saxifraga oppositifolia] with [Draba kotschyi].', '(Coldea, 1991: 351-353).');
    'Rock-crack communities of sunny rock faces of the Retezat mountains in the western Southern Carpathians, formed by [Saxifraga marginata] ssp. [rocheliana] with species of Dacio-Balkanic affinities.', '(Coldea, 1991: 351-353).');
    'Rock-crack communities of semishady rock faces of the southeastern Carpathians, formed by the endemic [Saxifraga mutata] ssp. [demissa] and [Gypsophila petraea].', '(Coldea, 1991: 352-354).');
    'Calcareous cliff and rock communities of the thermo- and meso-Mediterranean zones of mainland Greece and Albania, up to the [Abies cephalonica] belt, with [Campanula versicolor], [Campanula rupestris], [Sideritis roeseri], [Stachys candida], [Hypericum vesiculosum], [Asperula arcadiensis], [Galium boryanum], [Centaurea pelia], [Alkanna graeca], [Alyssum orientale], [Linaria microcalyx], [Onosma frutescens], [Inula candida], [Centranthus ruber], [Silene congesta], [Teucrium flavum].  ', '(Quézel, 1964; Géhu, 1984a: unit 13.1.3.1.1; Dimopoulos y al., 1997: 316, 320-321, 324-334; Hoda y al., 1998: 19).');
    'Calcareous and ultrabasic cliff and rock communities of Crete, the Aegean archipelagoes, Cyprus, the Mediterranean coastlands of Anatolia and the Levant. They constitute one of the most diverse and endemic-rich groups of cliff communities.', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974: 103-106; Meikle, 1977: 2; Sfikas, 1987; Latridis, 1988; Viney, 1994: xiii-xiv; Dimopoulos y al., 1997).');
    'Cliff and chasm communities of Crete, with [Petromarula pinnata], [Galium fruticosum], [Centaurea argentea], [Ebenus cretica], [Verbascum arcturus] ([Celsia arcturus]), [Inula candida], [Eryngium ternatum], [Asperula incana], [Dianthus juniperinus], [Aster canus], [Campanula pelviformis], [Campanula saxatilis]. ', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974: 104-105; Sfikas, 1987; Latridis, 1988; Turland y al., 1993: 9-10; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 23-24; Dimopoulos y al., 1997: 316-318, 320-321, 324-334).');
    'Relatively widespread cliff and chasm communities of the lowlands and hills of western and central Crete.', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974; Sfikas, 1987; Latridis, 1988; Turland y al., 1993: 9-10; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 23-24; Dimopoulos y al., 1997: 316-318, 320-321, 324-334).');
    'Cliff and chasm communities of the arid lowlands and hills of eastern Crete.', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974; Sfikas, 1987; Latridis, 1988; Turland y al., 1993: 9-10; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 23-24; Dimopoulos y al., 1997: 316-318, 320-321, 324-334).');
    'Cliff and chasm communities of the high altitudes of Crete.', '(Rechinger, 1951; Horvat y al., 1974; Sfikas, 1987; Latridis, 1988; Turland y al., 1993: 9-10; Jahn and Schönfelder, 1995: 23-24; Dimopoulos y al., 1997: 316-318, 320-321, 324-334).');
    'Cliff and rock communities of Karpathos, with [Teucrium heliotropifolium], [Silene fruticosa], [Galium incurvum], [Inula heterolepis].  ', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 104-105).');
    'Cliff and rock communities of Rhodes, Samos, Ikaria, Lesbos with [Campanula hagielia], [Lactuca leburnea], [Dianthus rhodensis], [Inula heterolepis], [Rosularia serrata], [Sedum creticum].', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 104-106).');
    'Caves on islands off the main Eurasian and African landmasses providing an essential habitat of reptilian and amphibian subtroglophiles (elective periodic trogloxenes).', '(Erminio, 1988; Corbett, 1989; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992).');
    'Caves of the calcareous massifs of Sardinia harbouring salamanders of the genus [Speleomantes] ([Hydromantes]) and constituting an essential habitat for their existence.
', '(Erminio, 1988; Corbett, 1989: 222; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992: 235-241).');
    'Caves of the Sulcis and the Iglesiente of southwestern Sardinia, notably in the Domusnovas area of the Fiuminese massif, harbouring [Speleomantes genei]. ', '(Erminio, 1988; Corbett, 1989; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992).');
    'Caves of the Gerrei and of the Salto di Quirra in the southeastern quadrant of Sardinia, harbouring [Speleomantes imperialis].
', '(Erminio, 1988; Corbett, 1989; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992).');
    'Caves of the Monte Albo massif of eastern Sardinia, harbouring [Speleomantes flavus].', '(Erminio, 1988; Corbett, 1989; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992).');
    'Caves of the massifs facing the Gulf of Orosei, notably of the Orosei, Dorgali, Oliena, Orgosolo, Baunei areas of eastern Sardinia, harbouring [Speleomantes supramontis].', '(Erminio, 1988; Corbett, 1989; Nöllert and Nöllert, 1992).');
    'Caves of the Ryukyu archipelago harbouring [Gymnodactylus yamashinae] or [Eublapheris splendens].', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972: 54-55).');
    'Caves of the islands of Eurasia and North Africa with permanent or temporary colonies of bats. ', '(Stebbings, 1988; Lanfranco and Schembri, 1989: 134-135; Ransome, 1990; Schober and Grimmberger, 1991; Macdonald and Barrett, 1993; Tvrtkovic, 1996; Demetropoulos, 1996).');
    'Caves harbouring communities that include no troglobiont amphibians or fish, but include troglobiont invertebrates, limited worldwide to a relatively small number of species belonging to a limited number of groups, and including remarkable relict species. In the Palaearctic region, the majority are situated in the northern Mediterranean basin and the peri-Pontic region. Gastropoda, Opiliones, Chilopoda (Lithobiidae), Collembol, Coleoptera (Bathysciinae and Trechinae subfamilies) among the terrestrial faunas, Turbellaria, Gastropoda and Urodela, among the aquatic faunas, are characteristic of their communities, and essentially restricted to caves of temperate regions. 


', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972; Ginet and Decou, 1977; Vornatscher, 1979; Neuherz, 1979; Cei y al., 1982: 26-31; Culver, 1986; Aljancic, 1993; Leser, 1994; Celhar, 1997; Mrsic, 1997).');
    'Caves under normally oxygenated, buffered microclimates, dry, humidified by seeps or crossed by permanent or temporary watercourses, but not retaining glaciers, and harbouring communities of troglobiont invertebrates, often including remarkable relict species.

', '(Cei y al., 1982: 26-31; Schembri, 1989: 72, 74, 75; Tvrtkovic, 1996; Mrsic, 1997).');
    'Caves under normally oxygenated, buffered microclimates, harbouring communities of troglobiont invertebrates, and in which past and present conditions permit the retention of glaciers; they are rare, known in particular from the Carpathians of Romania and Slovakia, the Alps and the Jura. 


', '(Bleahu y al., 1976; Racovita, 1980).');
    'Caves under normally oxygenated, buffered microclimates, warmed and humidified by geothermal waters, and harbouring communities of troglobiont invertebrates. ', NULL);
    'Deoxygenated, relatively warm caves, with atmospheres rich in carbon dioxide and sulphur vapour or methane and hydrogen sulfide, harbouring relict thermophile faunas of highly distinctive troglobiont and stygobiont invertebrates.', NULL);
    'Caves harbouring ecosystems linked to sulphurous geothermal waters in a  relatively warm, deoxygenated methane- and hydrogen sulfide-rich atmosphere.
 

', NULL);
    'Movile cave of the southern Romanian Dobrogea, harbouring a singular chemoautotrophically based ecosystem linked to sulphurous geothermal waters in a quasi-closed, relatively warm (20øC), deoxygenated methane- and hydrogen sulfide-rich atmosphere, comprising a unique, totally isolated, thermophile and thiophile relict fauna of highly distinctive troglobiont and stygobiont invertebrates. ', '(Lascu, 1989; Sarbu and Popa, 1992; Lascu y al., 1993; Decu and Juberthie, 1994).');
    'Hydrothermal sulphur caves of Hungary, Croatia and Slovenia.
 

', NULL);
    'Adam cave from Baile Herculane, Romania, relatively warm, deoxygenated, with very much carbon dioxide, partly influenced by sulphur vapours, harbouring a  relict thermophile fauna; a very rich trophic substratum (guano) is present. ', '(Decu y al., 1974, 1976).');
    'Caves harbouring communities that include no troglobiont organisms, but include troglophile invertebrates. Generally, they are caves crossed by watercourses or with rich trophic substratum, excavated in limestone afforested zones.', '(Thinès and Tercafs, 1972; Ginet and Decou, 1977; Vornatscher, 1979; Neuherz, 1979; Culver, 1986; Aljancic, 1993; Leser, 1994; Tvrtkovic, 1996; Celhar, 1997).');
    'Alkaline fen communities of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by [Carex rostrata], accompanied by a carpet of brown mosses, sometimes with basicline sphagna, and few vascular plants other than sedges, occupying very wet sites in rich fen complexes; these communities, which grade into transition mire communities of unit 54.5, or into tall sedge communities of units 53.2141 or 53.2125, are best characterized in the Fennoscandian mountains, although they can be individualized in other fen systems, in particular, in upland Britain.   Accompanying species include [Carex aquatilis], [Carex juncella], [Carex rotundata], [Eriophorum angustifolia], [Viola epipsila], and small willows, notably [Salix lapponum], [Salix glauca].', '(Ratcliffe, 1980; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4l; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.2.5).');
    'Meso-eutrophic fen communities dominated by [Scirpus hudsonianus] ([Trichophorum alpinum]), with [Drepanocladus revolvens], [Scorpidium spp.], [Chrysohypnum stellatum], recorded from Scandinavia, from Germano-Baltic moraine land, from the subalpine and alpine levels of the Alps and the greater Hercynian ranges. They may constitute a [Scirpus hudsonianus] facies of the yellow-dioecious sedge fens of unit 54.253.', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 100; Rybnicek, 1970: 231-233; Jenik y al., 1980: 16; Ellenberg, 1988: 319; Oberdorfer, 1990: 38; Pott, 1992: 185-186; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 261; Steiner, 1993: 148).');
    '[Scirpus cespitosus]-dominated communities of alkaline fens, mainly characteristic of oceanic to subcontinental parts of the boreal region and of the alpine and subalpine levels of the Alps and the Pyrenees, at altitudes superior to those of the [Caricetum davallianae] communities of unit 54.23, including their deergrass-rich facies (unit 54.232).', '(Duvigneaud, 1949: 100; Dierssen, 1978: 419; Vanden Berghen and Peeters, 1982: 183-186; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4g; Oberdorfer, 1992a: 235-239, 242; Steiner, 1993: 153-154; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.2.3b).');
    '[Blysmus compressus]-dominated stands of rich fens of northern and central Europe, south, in the Alpine system, to the montane Illyrian beech level of the central Dinarides, to the subalpine level of the Paeonian mountains, and to the montane and subalpine levels of the Apuseni Mountains and of the Southern and Eastern Carpathians.', '(Horvat y al., 1974: 630, 495; Matuszkiewicz, 1984; Coldea, 1991: 430-434).');
    'Simplified and pioneer fen communities of the western Palaearctic formed mostly by a few nongramineous species, in particular, [Anagallis tenella]-[Parnassia palustris] communities and [Saxifraga mutata] communities.', '(Oberdorfer, 1992a: 261, 262; Steiner, 1993: 156-157). ');
    'Fen communities of calcareous wet dune slacks of northern France, Belgium, the Netherlands and the North Sea coast of Germany dominated by sedges, in particular, [Carex trinervis], [Carex scandinavica], or by [Juncus anceps], with no or little [Schoenus nigricans] and with, among a number of characteristic accompaniers, [Juncus subnodulosus], [Parnassia palustris], [Gentianella amarella], [Herminium monorchis], [Epipactis palustris].', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Duvigneaud, 1949: 98; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 114; Lambinon, 1955: 118-121; Herbauts, 1971: 52-57; Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 204-205; Westhoff and Van Oosten, 1991: 124, 291, 322; Pott, 1992: 184; Opermanis y al., 1997: 57).');
    'Fen communities of calcareous wet dune slacks of northern France and Belgium formed by [Carex trinervis], [Carex scandinavica], [Juncus anceps], [Juncus subnodulosus], [Parnassia palustris], [Gentianella amarella], [Herminium monorchis], [Drepanocladus aduncus], [Campylium stellatum], without, or with little, [Schoenus nigricans]. These communities, limited to dunal systems and for which this code will thus be used in conjunction with those of unit 16.33, are gravely threatened.', '(Duvigneaud, 1947; Duvigneaud, 1949: 98; Lebrun y al., 1949: unit 114; Lambinon, 1955: 118-121; Herbauts, 1971: 52-57).');
    'Fen communities of calcareous wet dune slacks of the Netherlands and Germany, almost entirely limited to the North Sea Islands, dominated by [Juncus anceps] ([Juncus alpinoarcticus] ssp. [atricapillus]) with a rich cortŠge of flowering plants, including [Parnassia palustris], [Gentiana amarella] ssp. [uliginosa], [Centaurium littorale], [Centaurium erythraea], [Pedicularis palustris], [Epipactis palustris], [Dactylorhiza incarnata].', '(Westhoff and Den Held, 1975: 204-205; Westhoff and Van Oosten, 1991: 124, 291, 322; Pott, 1992: 184).');
    'Fens invaded by [Peucedanum palustre], [Eupatorium cannabinum], [Cicuta virosa], [Symphytum officinale], [Lysimachia vulgaris], [Cladium mariscus], [Phragmites australis], [Glyceria maxima], [Calamagrostis canescens].  ', '(Wheeler, 1980a, 1980c).');
    'Rich fen [Carex bigelowii]-dominated communities of the lower alpine level of Iceland, descending, in the north, into the lowlands, occupying level substrates subjected to water movement and fluctuating moisture, with a consequently variable vegetation; mosses play a major role. The species cortŠge may include [Carex capillaris], [Carex dioica], [Carex nigra], [Carex rariflora], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Calamagrostis stricta], [Festuca rubra] [s.l.], [Phleum alpinum], [Polygonum vivipara], [Saxifraga hirculum], [Salix callicarpaea] ([Salix arctica]), [Salix herbacea], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Thalictrum alpinum], [Equisetum palustre], [Equisetum arvense], [Equisetum variegatum].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.1.4j; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 3.3.2.3a).');
    '[Carex spp.]-dominated marsh-fen communities of fine-grained long-submerged alluvial deposits of the inundation zone of rivers, brooks, lakes or deltas of the arctic, subarctic, arctoalpine and boreoalpine regions of the Palaearctic.', '(Sjörs, 1983: 88; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 217, unit 3.6.5 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Stands of [Carex aquatilis], often monospecific, of subalpine and lower alpine levels of boreal Fennoscandia, occupying periodically waterlogged, relatively nutrient-deficient, high-pH substrates with a finer grain texture than that of the alluvions colonized by the [Calamagrostis stricta] communities of unit 54.72. The species cortŠge may include [Equisetum fluviatile], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Caltha palustris], [Juncus filiformis], [Petasites frigidus], [Ranunculus repens], [Subularia aquatica].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.5.3 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2.4 [p.]).');
    'Open, pioneering  [Carex lyngbyei]-dominated communities of Iceland and the Faeroe Islands colonizing loose clays and sands of virtually level, lowlying shores of rivers and lakes, subjected to regular flooding from snowmelt and heavy rains. The species cortŠge includes [Agrostis stolonifera], [Alopecurus geniculatus], [Caltha palustris], [Cardamine pratensis], [Carex nigra], [Epilobium palustre], [Equisetum fluviatile], [Eriophorum angustifolium], [Menyanthes trifoliata], [Potentilla palustris] and, in Iceland, [Calamagrostis stricta], [Carex canescens], [Carex chordorrhiza]. Formerly used for haycutting, these communities are nowadays important for cattle grazing.', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 3.6.5.4; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.2.2.5).');
    'Mire complexes of the central and northern boreal zones of the western Palaearctic domaine, often extensive, with a concave or flat, gently to very slightly sloping surface patterned by an alternance of slightly to substantially raised ridges and hummocks (strings), with minerotrophic or ombrotrophic characteristics, and of minerotrophic pools and hollows (flarks), arranged perpendicularly to the slope direction. They are distributed in particular in subatlantic and subcontinental Fennoscandia, the southern Kola peninsula and nothern Karelia, in the Pechora lowlands, the Timan mountains and the Urals, in the middle basin of the Obi, east to th middle Ienissei.', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1970: 319-322; Schenk, 1970b: 335-340; Goodwillie, 1980: 10; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 56-60; Sjörs, 1983: 86-87; Botch and Masing, 1983: 113-117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 212; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 182-185; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 214-215; Pakarinen, 1995: 32).');
    'Ridges and hummocks of aapa mires of the western boreal zone of the Palaearctic domaine, minerotrophic or partly ombrotrophic, generally long and narrow, lying perpendicular to the slope direction, alternating with elongated water-filled depressions. Low strings carry [Molinia]- or sedge-dominated communities, higher strings communities very similar to those of bog hummocks, unsually with small shrubs or pines.  ', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1970: 319-322; Schenk, 1970b: 335-340; Goodwillie, 1980: 10; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 56-60; Sjörs, 1983: 86-87; Botch and Masing, 1983: 113-117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 212; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 182; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 214-215).');
    'Strings of aapa mires of the Palaearctic domaine, characteristic of the northern and central aapa mire regions, often tall or very tall, dominated by [Sphagnum fuscum], usually in conjunction with shrubs of unit 54.815.', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 58-59; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 212, unit 3.2.1.1 [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 214-215, unit 3.1.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Strings of aapa mires of the Palaearctic domaine, characteristic of the southern aapa mire regions, often relatively low, dominated by sedges of genus [Carex], in particular, [Carex lasiocarpa], associated with sphagna, often [Sphagnum papillosum].', '(Ilomets, 1974: 192; Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 58; Botch and Masing, 1983: 114-115).');
    'Strings of aapa mires of the Palaearctic domaine, mostly of the southern aapa mire regions, dominated by cottonsedges of genus [Eriophorum].', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 59; Botch and Masing, 1983: 114).');
    'Strings of aapa mires of the Palaearctic domaine, mostly of the southern aapa mire regions, usually low or very low, dominated by [Molinia caerulea].', '(Goodwillie, 1980: 10; Sjörs, 1983: 86; Botch and Masing, 1983: 114).');
    'Strings of aapa mires of the Palaearctic domaine dominated by dwarf shrubs, similar to those that occupy raised bog hummocks, in particular [Calluna vulgaris], [Empetrum spp.], [Vaccinium uliginosum], [Betula nana], [Rubus chamaemorus], [Ledum palustre], [Chamaedaphne calyculata], and in the Usa River basin of northeastern Europe, [Alnus fruticosa], associated mostly with [Sphagnum fuscum].', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 56-60; Sjörs, 1983: 86-87; Botch and Masing, 1983: 113-117; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 212, unit 3.2.1.1 [p.]; Succow and Jeschke, 1990: 182; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 214-215, unit 3.1.2.2 [p.]).');
    'Strings of aapa mires of the Palaearctic domaine, occupied by often sparse and small [Pinus sylvestris] or [Betula spp.]. Codes from unit 44.A can be used to further define communities.', '(Ruuhijärvi, 1983: 58-59; Sjörs, 1983: 86; Botch and Masing, 1983: 115; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: 212, unit 3.4.1.1, 3.1.2.2, 3.1.2.3, [p.]; Påhlsson, 1994: 211, 214-215, unit 3.2.1.1, 3.1.1.3, 3.1.1.4, [p.]).');
    'Fumaroles and solfataras of the areas of active volcanism of the eastern Mediterranean basins, in particular, of the Aegean and the Levantine Sea.  ', '(Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 73; Krafft and de Larouzière, 1991).');
    'Gas vents, fumaroles, solfataras, mofettes, related to late Tertiary volcanism of the western Alpine system, its periphery, its satellite mountain complexes and its interior basins, including the Pyrenees, the Alps, the Carpathians, and, notably, the Eastern Carpathians, the Jura, the Dinarides, the Hellenides, the Hercynian ranges, the Iberian mountains, the Atlas, the Taurus.  Included in particular are the extensive mofette systems of Bohemia and of the mountains constituting the Bohemian Quadrangle, in particular, those of the bogs of Soos, in the Cheb district of western Bohemia.', NULL);
    'Gas vents, fumaroles, solfataras, mofettes of the Caucasus and of western Asian mountains and plateaux, in particular, of the slopes of the Nemrut Dag in Turkey and of the Damavand and Taftan in Iran.', '(Cei y al., 1982: 133; Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 73).');
    'Gas vents, fumaroles, solfataras, mofettes of the the Central Asian mountains and their periphery.', NULL);
    'Gas vents, fumaroles, solfataras, mofettes related to active volcanism of the Rift, along the Arabian peninsula shores of the Red Sea and in neighbouring regions.', NULL);
    'Hot or cold gas vents of the zones of volcanic activity lining the Pacific margins of Eurasia, in particular, of the Jigokudani volcanic site on Hokkaido.', '(Grin y al., 1976: 98-99; Cei y al., 1982: 135; Rittmann and Rittmann, 1983: 77; Walter and Breckle, 1991c: 317).');
    'Gas vents, fumaroles, solfataras, mofettes of the North African desert ranges and their periphery.', NULL);
    'Acid or alkaline springs heated by geothermal energy, located in regions of present or past volcanic activity, producing a continuous flow of water at temperatures significantly above the air temperature. Springs and tepid pools at temperatures below 50ø C may host a few species of specialized animals, those at temperatures between 50ø C and 75ø C harbour bluegreen algae that may form conspicuous mats, those at temperatures above 75ø C are inhabited only by heterotrophic bacteria; the  margins of the springs and the water-saturated substrates may host distinctive biotic communities, including superior plants.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b; Whitten and Brooks, 1972; Cei y al., 1982; Maldonado, 1985; Clark, 1990; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Hot springs related to active volcanism of the islands, coasts and hinterland of the Mediterranean basins.', NULL);
    'Hot springs of the islands, coasts and hinterland of the areas of active volcanism of the western Mediterranean basins, in particular, of the Tyrrhenian Sea and of the Strait of Sicily.  ', NULL);
    'Hot springs of the islands, coasts and hinterland of the areas of active volcanism of the eastern Mediterranean basins, in particular, of the Aegean and the Levantine Sea.  ', NULL);
    'Hot springs related to active volcanism of the southern north Atlantic, on the mid-Atlantic ridge islands of the Azores and on the Canary Islands, Madeira and the Cape Verde Islands.', NULL);
    'Hot springs related to active volcanism of the northern North Atlantic, on the mid-Atlantic ridge islands, Iceland and Jan Mayen.', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 90; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984; Påhlsson, 1994; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Warm outflow water of Icelandic hot springs, often extremely basic, with a pH approaching 8-9, mostly devoid of macrophytic vegetation at temperatures above 35ø C, otherwise with species assemblies that vary with water temperature and conditions at each site, including altitude. Characteristic species include [Crassula aquatica], [Hydrocotyle vulgaris] and [Callitriche stagnatilis].', '(Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 7.2.2; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.3.2.2; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Moss and vascular plants communities occurring on warm and moist soils around Icelandic hot springs. Soaked, very hot substrates nearest to the spring are colonized by Cyanophycea, small hepatics, in particular, [Fossombronia dumortieri] and a moss of genus [Archidium]; a more external belt is often characterized by the exuberant development of sphagna, while hypnoids develop beyond. Generally, bryophytes tolerate soil temperatures up to 50ø C, while vascular plants occur at lower temperatures. Vascular species assemblies are highly varied, depending on altitude and ground temperature, and comprise species limited in Iceland to these hot soil situations, in particular, [Filaginella uliginosa] ([Gnaphalium uliginosum]), [Hydrocotyle vulgaris], [Mentha aquatica], [Polygonum persicaria] ([Persicaria maculosa]), [Plantago major] var. [pygmaea], [Blechnum spicant] var. [fallax], [Ophioglossum azoricum].', '(Vanden Berghen, 1969b: 90; Nordiska ministerradet, 1984: unit 7.2.1; Påhlsson, 1994: unit 7.3.2.1; Kristinsson, 1998).');
    'Hot springs related to late Tertiary volcanism of the western Alpine system, its periphery, its satellite mountain complexes and its interior basins, including the Baetic mountains, the Rif, the Tell, the Atlas, the Pyreneo-Cantabrian range, the Alps, the Carpathians, the mountains of the Balkan peninsula, the Jura, the Hercynian ranges of Iberia, the Central Massif, the northern Hercynian arc. They include, in particular, Romanian geothermal waters harbouring formations of [Nymphaea lotus] (unit 22.43113).', NULL);
    'Hot springs related to late Tertiary volcanism of the central Alpine system,  its periphery, its satellite mountain complexes and its interior basins, including the Caucasus, the Pontic range, the Anatolian plateau, the Taurus, the Zagros, the Elburz. ', '(Cei y al., 1982: 133).');
    'Hot springs related to late Tertiary volcanism of the eastern Alpine system,  its periphery, its satellite mountain complexes and its interior basins, including the Himalayas and the connected ranges of the Pamir-Alai, the Tien Shan and the Hindu Kush.', '(Cei y al., 1982: 131).');
    'Hot springs related to active volcanism of the Rift, along the shores of the Red Sea, the Jordan Valley and in neighbouring regions, in particular, springs of the shores of the Sea of Galilee.', NULL);
    'Hot springs of the zone of active volcanism of the Pacific ring of fire in Kamchatka, the Japanese archipelago and neighbouring areas of far-eastern Asia.', '(Cei y al., 1982: 135).');
    'Hot springs related to past or present volcanism of Saharan Africa.', NULL);
    'Springs from which heated water and steam is ejected, sometimes violently, at periodic intervals, in active or recently active volcanic regions. Major geysers are rare, known from only four areas in the world, and within the Palaearctic region, as here defined, only from Iceland and the northwestern Pacific rim. The proximal zone of geysers may host distinctive communities of lower plants and invertebrates.', '(Whitten and Brooks, 1972; Clark, 1990; Cei y al., 1982; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Geysers of Iceland, of which about 10 are presently active, in particular, in southern Iceland.', '(Cei y al., 1982: 130-144; Einarsson, 1994; Gudmundsson and Kjartansson, 1996).');
    'Geysers of the zone of volcanic activity riming the Pacific margins of Eurasia, including, for example, those of the Valley of the Geysers, Kamtchatka and of the Jigokudani volcanic site on Hokkaido.', '(Grin y al., 1976: 98-99; Cei y al., 1982: 131).');
    'Unvegetated or sparsely vegetated formations of geographically significant extent, developed under arctic, temperate or tropical climates in extreme conditions of low precipitation and high evaporation. Included are all shrub-dominated, grass-dominated or succulent-dominated communities exposed to arid or very arid conditions, typically with annual precipitation inferior to 200 mm, and, as semideserts, shrub-dominated or succulent-dominated, including arborescent succulent-dominated, communities, usually strongly lacunar, formed under semiarid conditions, with annual precipitation that may reach 500 mm or 600 mm. Grass-dominated communities constituted under the latter conditions and representing encroachments of steppes characteristic of neighbouring regions are listed under 3, while all communities that comprise a reasonably continuous, closed or open, stratum of trees, other than arborescent succulents, are listed under 4, most often under 4B. Communities dependent on permanent or temporary surface water are excluded and listed in units 15, 2, 3 or 5; nonarborescent communities dependent on phreatic water are included in unit 7.', '(Rieley and Page, 1990).');
    'Formations of the most extreme parts of the Arctic zone, characterized by mostly bare ground worked by solifluction and colonized by algae and very species-poor, extremely open communities constituded by lichens, mosses, liverworts and a very restricted number of vascular plants. They are restricted within the Palaearctic as here defined, to the northern tip of the Ta¿myr peninsula, to Greenland and to the islands of the Arctic Ocean.  ', '(Walter and Breckle, 1986: 508, 515-519; Aleksandrova, 1988; Callaghan y al., 2001).');
    'Polar deserts of the Nordaustlandet of the Spitzbergen archipelago, Victoria Island, Franz Josef Land and the north end of Novaya Zemlya.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 3, 49-125).');
    'Polar deserts of the Nordaustlandet of the Spitzbergen archipelago. ', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 3, 50; Torkildsen, 1991: 154).');
    'Polar deserts of the small ice-free part of Victoria Island, with an impoverished vegetation comprising a few species of mosses, lichens and ground-covering algae.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 3, 50, 121).');
    'Polar deserts of the northern part of the Franz Josef archipelago.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 3, 50, 53-120; Safronova and Glazovskij, 1995).');
    'Stone fields, rock heaps and sandy-loamy deluviums of the Franz Josef archipelago devoid of all vegetation, mostly characteristic of areas with prolonged snow cover.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 61).');
    'Polar deserts of the Franz Josef archipelago occupied by uniform, species-poor assemblages of widely scattered higher and lower plants, constituting a negligible ground cover.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 61).');
    'Polar deserts of the Franz Josef archipelago occupied by a continuous cover of higher and lower plants, broken by bare stones and patches of bare ground.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 61).');
    'Polar deserts of the southern part of the Franz Josef archipelago.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 53-120; Safronova and Glazovskij, 1995).');
    'Polar deserts of the north end of Novaya Zemlya.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 121-125).');
    'Polar deserts of the North Land Archipelago (Severnaya Zemlya), the extreme northern tip of the Taimyr peninsula and the de Longa Islands, north of the New Siberian Islands.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 3, 126-154).');
    'Polar deserts of ice-free areas of the very glaciated northern islands of the Severnaya Zemlya archipelago, including Ostrov Komsomolets, Ostrov Pioner and the Ostrova Sedova.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 130-133).');
    'Polar deserts of the southern islands of the Severnaya Zemlya archipelago, including Ostrov Oktyabr''skoy, Ostrov Revolyutsii, Ostrov Bol''shevik, Ostrov Malyy Ta¿myr, Ostrov Starokadomskogo, less glaciated than the northern islands.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 133-142).');
    'Polar deserts of the extreme northern tip of the Taimyr peninsula (Mys Chelyuskin).', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 3, 142-151).');
    'Polar deserts of the three islands of the Ostrova de Longa group (De Long Islands), north of the New Siberian Islands.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 3, 151-154).');
    'Polar deserts of the Lincoln Sea coasts of extreme northern Greenland.', '(Aleksandrova, 1988: 2, 3).');
    'Interior continental deserts or semideserts of temperate areas beyond the reach of moisture-laden winds ("d¿serts d''¿loignement") and rain-shadow deserts or semideserts lying on the leeward side of high mountain ranges which intercept the rain-bearing winds ("d¿serts d''abri"). In the Palaearctic region they are represented by the deserts and semideserts of the Central Eurasian desert region.', '(Birot, 1970; Zohary, 1973; Walter, 1974: 229-327; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 46-47, 48; Walter and Box, 1983a, 1983b, 1983c, 1983d, 1983e, 1983f, 1983g; Breckle, 1983; West, 1983g; Kaul, 1983; Shmida, 1985; Walter and Breckle, 1986; Schultz, 1988: 224-225; Rieley and Page, 1990; Allan and Warren, 1993; Demangeot, 1994: 125-126; Archibold, 1995).');
    'Interior continental deserts or semideserts of the Caspian lowlands, the northern Aralo-Caspian depression and Dzungaria, the Atrek basin, the Ustyurt Plateau, the Kyzyl-Kum and Kara-Kum, the Kopet Dag, the Central Asian mountains of the Tien-Shan system.', '(Saphronova, 1964a: units 56-64; Saphronova, 1964b: units 61, 75-80; Saphronova, 1964c: units 81-83, 93-98; Birot, 1970; Walter, 1974: 229-327; Walter and Box, 1983a, 1983b, 1983c, 1983d, 1983e; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 232, units I [p], II, 216-293).');
    'Interior continental deserts or semideserts of the Iranian and Afghan plateaux, south of the Kopet Dag and the Pamir. ', '(Saphronova, 1964b: units 81-82, 95; Birot, 1970; Zohary, 1973: units 17, 20, 33; Walter and Box, 1983a; Breckle, 1983).');
    'Interior continental deserts or semideserts of Mongolia, inner Mongolia and the Cis-Hsing-An region, including the Gobi, of the Pei Shan, of Kashgaria and the Tarim Basin with the Takla Makan, of the Ala Shan and the Ordos, of the Kansu corridor and the Tsaidam region.', '(Saphronova, 1964b: units 88-91; Birot, 1970; Walter, 1974: 229-327; Ehrenreich y al., 1982: 46-47, 48; Walter and Box, 1983a, 1983g; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 232, unit III).');
    'High-altitude interior continental deserts or semideserts of the Pamir and the Tibetan plateau.', '(Saphronova, 1964b: units 92-93; Saphronova, 1964c: unit 99; Birot, 1970; Walter, 1974: 229-327; Walter and Box, 1983a, 1983f, 1983g, 1983h; Kaul, 1983; Walter and Breckle, 1986: 232, unit IV).');
    'Sunny deserts and arid shrublands developed under tropical or subtropical climates. Most characteristically and extensively, they are situated within the horse latitudes, the 30ø-35ø belts of high atmospheric pressure zones or Hadley cells producing low precipitation and high insolation. Under anomalous local conditions of rain shadow or trade wind regimes, arid shrublands or succulent and arborescent succulent communities may form in other parts of the tropics. They are physiognomically similar to the horse latitude semideserts and are included in this unit. In the Palaearctic region, this unit encompasses the extremely extensive horse-latitude Saharo-Sindian deserts and their semidesert transition to mediterranean habitats or other formations.', '(Zohary, 1973; White, 1983: 216-224; Danin, 1983; Evenari, 1985a, 1985b; Shmida, 1985; Orshan, 1986; Abd el Rahman, 1986; Le Houérou, 1986; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986; Monod, 1986; Shmida y al., 1986; Rieley and Page, 1990; Ozenda, 1991; Huetz de Lemps, 1994; Archibold, 1995).');
    'Hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, within the Saharo-Arabian floristic domaine; they include most of the Sahara Desert, the Sinai Desert, the Neguev, the Arabian Desert and the Southern Mesopotamian Desert.', '(Zohary, 1973: Map 7, units 21-23; White, 1983: 216-224; Danin, 1983; Evenari, 1985a, 1985b; Shmida, 1985; Orshan, 1986; Abd el Rahman, 1986; Le Houérou, 1986; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986; Shmida y al., 1986; Rieley and Page, 1990; Ozenda, 1991; Huetz de Lemps, 1994; Shuaib, 1995; Archibold, 1995).');
    'Species-poor communities of ergs and barkans of the Saharo-Sindian region, including less mobile dunes harbouring communities of graminids and shrubs with roots able to penetrate deeper, moisture retaing layers of sand, or rare communities of annuals, as well as highly mobile, constantly shifting, sands devoid of any vegetation.', '(Herbauts, 1973: 325; White, 1983: 220; Zahran and Willis, 1992). ');
    'Species-poor communities of ergs and barkhans of the Saharo-Sindian region dominated by gramino¿d species, especially drinn, [Aristida pungens] ([Stipagrostis pungens]), sometimes with [Cyperus conglomeratus].', '(Herbauts, 1973: 325; White, 1983: 220; Ozenda, 1991: 70-71, 138-139, 166).');
    'Shrub-dominated communities of dunes of the Saharo-Sindian region variously composed of, in particular, [Ephedra alata], [Retama retam], [Genista saharae], [Calligonum azel], the chenopod shrub [Cornulaca monacantha], sometimes with herbaceous plants, including [Cyperus conglomeratus], [Aristida pungens], or small shrubs, such as the borage [Moltkia ciliata].', '(Herbauts, 1973: 325; White, 1983: 220; Ozenda, 1991: 70-71, 138-139, 239, 392; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 92).');
    'Large unvegetated ergs or barkhans of the Saharo-Arabian desert zone, prominent in areas where rainfall is very low, less than 20 mm per year, and episodic, with many consecutive rainless years, occupying extensive surfaces, in particular, in the eastern Sahara.', '(White, 1983: 223-224).');
    'Ephemeral communities of dunes of the Saharo-Sindian region formed of annuals, such as [Malcolmia aegyptiaca], appearing after bouts of precipitation.', '(White, 1983: 220).');
    'Communities of sandy regs, sandy areas protected from erosion by a cover of superficial slightly larger rock fragments, of the Saharo-Sindian region, particularly frequent in areas of hyperaridity, subject to episodic rains, with as little as 10-20 mm being sufficient to provoke the development of a flush of ephemeral vegetation; communities are homogeneous, comprised almost exclusively of therophyte species, including [Athenatherum forscalii] ([Danthonia]), [Plantago ciliata], [Polycarpaea repens] ([Polycarpaea fragilis]), [Monsonia nivea], [Ifloga spicata], [Fagonia glutimosa].', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; White, 1983: 220).');
    'Gravel-covered hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, constituted of heterogeneous deposits of, in particular, coarse alluvions or conglomarates, from which fine material has been removed by wind action; beneath the often compacted suface a powdery mass of gypsum accumulates and may form a strong hardpan at somewhat greater depths.', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; Herbauts, 1973: 323-325; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 71-72).');
    'Diffuse communities of gravel-covered hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula formed by shrubs, in particular, [Hammada scoparia] ([Haloxylon articulatum]) [Cornulaca monacantha], [Randonia africana], [Hammada elegans] ([Haloxylon salicornicum]), grasses, notably [Stipagrostis plumosa], [Stipagrostis obtusa], [Stipagrostis ciliata], [Lasiurus hirsutus], [Panicum turgidum], geophytes, [Androcymbium spp.], [Asphodelus], or annuals, [Daucus spp.], [Ammodaucus spp.].', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; Herbauts, 1973: 323-325; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 71-72).');
    'Diffuse communities of gravel-covered hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula formed by shrubs, in particular, in the northern Sahara, the chenopod [Haloxylon scoparium], often degraded as a result of fuel-gathering. [Stipagrostis obrtusa] may form after rains on regs, notably of the Central Sahara.', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; Herbauts, 1973: 323-325; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 71-72).');
    'Regs covered by sands of variable depths, of hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, capabable of supporting communities, often with a denser cover than the bare regs of unit 73.1211, that may include grasses, notably swards of [Stipagrostis plumosa], [Stipagrostis obtusa], [Stipagrostis ciliata], geophytes, [Androcymbium spp.], [Asphodelus], and annuals, [Daucus spp.], [Ammodaucus spp.]; clay-rich sand covers may support shrub communites of the chenopod [Cornulaca monacantha] or the Resedaceae [Randonia africana].', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 71-72).');
    'Communities of water drainage channels transecting regs of hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, characteristic of the drier parts, where sand-filled gullies of bare regs support, notably in northeastern African pebble regs, sparse [Haloxylon salicornicum] stands on shallow deposits or formations with [Lasiurus hirsutus], [Panicum turgidum], [Zilla spinosa] on deeper sands.', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380).');
    'Sand-covered hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, covering more than one-third of the surface of the western Sahara, a somewhat smaller portion of the eastern Sahara, huge expanses of the Arabian Desert, in particular, in the Rub''l Khali and the Nafud-Dahna, and substantial surfaces in the northern part and in the intermountain valleys and plains of the Sinai peninsula and in the northern Neguev. They include desert dunes as well as sandy regs and may be unvegetated, especially in the hyperarid zone or carry vegetation of greatly variable development. The communities of the sandy floors of wadis are excluded and listed in unit 73.14.', '(Zohary, 1973: 442-457; White, 1983: 220; Danin, 1983; Shmida, 1985: 32-33; Orshan, 1986: 8, 18-20; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 118-124, 130-134; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 162, 164-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Rieley and Page, 1990: 52; Ozenda, 1991: 70-71).');
    'Large unvegetated regs of the Saharo-Arabian desert zone, characteristic of gravel deserts with a surface so compacted that roots cannot penetrate, prominent in areas where rainfall is very low, less than 20 mm per year, and episodic, with many consecutive rainless years, occupying extensive surfaces, in particular, in the eastern Sahara.', '(White, 1983: 221, 223-224).');
    'Stone- or pavement-covered plateau-tops and rocky slopes of hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, where all fine products of weathering are swept away by the wind; included are Cretaceous and Tertiary stone pavements, very extensive in the Sahara. Accumulations of salts or gypsum may form in the layer beneath the surface stones, which are often varnished with blackish deposits of iron or magnesium compounds.', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; White, 1983: 220-221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 72-75).');
    'Often exiguous, but relatively species-rich, communities occupying the tops, flanks and rock crevices of hamadas and rocky slopes of hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, usally able to survive only in moisture-retaining depressions or rock fissures, or on steep rocky slopes deeply incised by drainage channels. Characteristic species include, in particular, [Forsskalea tenacissima], [Asteriscus graveolens], [Salvia aegyptiaca], [Farsetia aegyptiaca], [Reseda villosa], [Fagaria latifolia], [Enneapogon scaber], [Enneapogon desvoxii] ([Enneapogon brachystachya]), [Anastatica hierochuntica] in the northern northwestern, western and central Sahara, [Moricandia arvensis], [Cymbopogon schoenanthus], [Fagonia microphylla], [Haloxylon scoparium] in the northern Sahara, [Limoniastrum feei], [Pituranthos battandieri] in the northwestern Sahara.', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; Herbauts, 1973: 323; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 72-75).');
    'Communities of the hamada floor of plateau tops of hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, in particular, northwestern Saharan communities of dense rounded cushions of [Fredolia aretioides] ([Anabasis aretioides]), up to 50 cm high, scattered alone across extensive plateau surfaces, or with, notably, [Limoniastrum feei], [Pituranthos battandieri].', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 72-75).');
    'Communities of the flanks and rock crevices of hamadas of hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula, in particular, perennial communities of the rock flanks of unvegetated hamadas of the central Sahara, with [Anabasis articulata], [Aerva persica] and grasses including [Aristida spp.], [Stipagrostis spp.], [Enneapogon spp.], or communities of chasmophytes, including [Erodium glaucophyllum], [Reaumuria hirtella], [Helianthemum kahiricum], [Fagonia mollis], growing in crevices of rocks, sometimes lichen-covered, of the otherwise usually unvegetated Egyptian Desert hamadas.', '(Zohary, 1973: 420-437; White, 1983: 221; Danin, 1983; Orshan, 1986: 13-17; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 116-123; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 72-75).');
    'Large hamada surfaces or rocky slopes of the Saharo-Arabian desert zone with no vascular plant life, in situations of insufficient moisture or relatively high salt content, prominent in areas where rainfall is very low.', '(White, 1983: 221, 223-224).');
    'Usually dry valleys or stream courses of the Saharo-Arabian region, carrying water only during rare heavy rainfall, often retaining groundwater near enough to be reached by plant species. Wadis are the only desert habitat, apart from oases, occupied by trees or large shrubs, including, in particular, [Tamarix spp.] communities (unit 44.815) and [Acacia spp.] communities (unit 4B.3).', '(Zohary, 1973: 437-441; White, 1983: 219-220; Danin, 1983; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 41-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 121-122; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 160-169; Shmida y al., 1986: 380; Ozenda, 1991: 76-78; Benabid and Fennane, 1999: 91).');
    'Diverse woodlands, grasslands, [Erica arborea] or dwarf-shrub communities of high mountains, above about 1800 metres, of the Saharo-Arabian region, with a higher rainfall than that of surrounding lowlands, species-rich and often harbouring endemic species. Except in the most favoured locations or during periods of good rainfall, communities are often restricted to wadis.', '(White, 1983: 221-222; Le Houérou, 1986: 122; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986: 164; Ozenda, 1991: 84-86).');
    'Communities colonizing saline and gypseous evaporation soils of the hot deserts and semideserts of North Africa, the Sinai peninsula, Southern Mesopotamia and the Arabian peninsula.', '(Zohary, 1973: 458-472; White, 1983: 222-223; Danin, 1983; Shmida, 1985; Orshan, 1986: 13, 20; Abd el Rahman, 1986: 42-47; Le Houérou, 1986: 117; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986; Ozenda, 1991: 36-37, 78-79, 511-512).');
    'Hot deserts and semideserts of the Near East and northern Mesopotamia, within the Irano-Turanian floristic domaine; they include the Syrian Desert and the Northern Mesopotamian Desert.', '(Zohary, 1973: Map 7, units 19 [p.], 20 [p.]; Danin, 1983; Evenari, 1985a, 1985b; Shmida, 1985; Orshan, 1986; Shmida y al., 1986; Rieley and Page, 1990; Huetz de Lemps, 1994; Archibold, 1995).');
    'Hot deserts and semideserts of the southern Sahara, the Red Sea coastlands, the southern Arabian peninsula, the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman coastlands, within the Sub-Sudanian and Sudanian floristic domaines. On the southern fringes of the Sahara, their northern limit, separating them from the deserts of unit 73.1, is most conveniently situated at the transition between hyperarid regions with episodal, prevailingly winter, rains and arid regions with prevailing summer rains; they are thus limited, within the Palaearctic region, as here defined, to southern Mauritania.', '(Zohary, 1973: Map 7, units 24, 25, 26, 27, 30; Walter, 1979: 96-97, 113-114, Fig. 5; White, 1983: 224; Danin, 1983; Evenari, 1985a, 1985b; Shmida, 1985; Orshan, 1986; Abd el Rahman, 1986; Ayyad and Ghabbour, 1986; Monod, 1986; Shmida y al., 1986; Rieley and Page, 1990; Ozenda, 1991; Huetz de Lemps, 1994; Archibold, 1995).');
    'Deserts of the west coasts of continents, under the influence of cold ocean currents, mostly within subtropical or tropical regions, almost without measurable rainfall but with high relative humidity in the form of fogs and mists. Within the Palaearctic region, communities of the extreme western Sahara, between Saguia el Hamra, at the southern limit of the mediterraneo-Saharan succulent shrublands of unit 32.89, and the northern limit of the Sahel, are referable to this unit.', '(Walter, 1979; White, 1983: 224; Shmida, 1985: 30-33; Rieley and Page, 1990: 52; Walter and Breckle, 1991b; Allan and Warren, 1993; Demangeot, 1994; Archibold 1995).');
